{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::29", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 29, "text": "Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/03/yamato_tokuda-400x400.png)\n\n### Yamato Tokuda\n\nPosition title: Wendt Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/02/casey_trousil-400x400.png)\n\n### Casey Trousil\n\nPosition title: ECB Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/10/prithvi-varma-400x400.png)\n\n### Prithvi Varma\n\nPosition title: Wendt Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/09/Sheryl-Wang-1-400x400.jpg)\n\n### Sheryl Wang\n\nPosition title: ECB Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/10/matthew-weinberger-400x400.jpg)\n\n### Matthew Weinberger\n\nPosition title: Wendt Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/09/Max-Willemsen-400x400.jpg)\n\n### Max Willemsen\n\nPosition title: ECB Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/10/andrew-wolf-400x400.png)\n\n### Andrew Wolf\n\nPosition title: Wendt Staff\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2026/02/audrey-zeller-400x400.png)\n\n### Audrey Zeller\n\nPosition title: Wendt Staff\n\nSee student staff alumni\n\n## Advisory Board\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/10/IMG_9042-scaled-e1696526934107-400x400.jpg)\n\n### Marina Bloomer\n\nPosition title: Stellar Tech Girls Founder & Program Director\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/10/IMG_9041-scaled-e1696527120849-400x400.jpg)\n\n### Daniel Rogge\n\nPosition title: CEO, Tormach Inc.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/10/IMG_5635-scaled-e1698245404633-400x400.jpg)\n\n### Josh Roth\n\nPosition title: Assistant Professor, Biomedical, Mechanical Engineering\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/11/thumbnail_image-e1701113880476.png)\n\n### Giri Venkataramanan\n\nPosition title: Professor of Electrical and Computer Engineering\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/10/Elizabeth-400x400.png)\n\n### Elizabeth Wohlers\n\nPosition title: Staff Engineer, Sub-Zero, Inc.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/directions-hours-parking\n\n### Design Innovation Lab @ Wendt", "char_len": 2261, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::30", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 30, "text": "and Computer Engineering\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/10/Elizabeth-400x400.png)\n\n### Elizabeth Wohlers\n\nPosition title: Staff Engineer, Sub-Zero, Inc.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/directions-hours-parking\n\n### Design Innovation Lab @ Wendt\n\nWendt Commons, floor 2 (main entrance)\n215 N Randall Ave\nMadison, WI 53706\n\n**Hours:**\n\n5/11-5/15 Closed\n\nSummer Hours (starting 5/18) Monday – Thursday 10-4\nWeekends and UW Holidays: Closed\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/06/215A7292-768x512.jpg)\n\n### Design Innovation Lab @ ECB\n\nEngineering Centers Building, Rm B1084\nECB Basement, at the end of Engineering Drive.\n1550 Engineering Dr.\nMadison, WI 53706\n\n**General Hours:** Monday – Thursday 8am-7pm; Friday 8am-4pm\n\n**Note:** Parts of the shop are open until 9pm on weekdays. Check out the calendar below for the most up-to-date schedule.\n\n2026 ECB Shops Calendar\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/06/Screen-Shot-2023-06-26-at-4.22.58-PM-768x399.png)\n\n## Parking\n\n**Option #1:** Union South Garage Lot 80 is the closest to our Wendt location *\\*This lot often fills up during the day.***Option #2:**Parking Garage 17 in the center of the engineering campus and closest to our ECB location.\n**Option #3:**Free 2-hour street parking on the side streets south of Dayton St.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/policies\n\nWe work hard to make the lab a safe, welcoming, and productive space for all users. The policies we have are meant to help us achieve that together, so please read through them carefully and reach out if you have questions. **Always follow staff members’ instructions**, as they are always looking to preserve the lab’s safety and productivity.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Access", "char_len": 1917, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::31", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 31, "text": "and reach out if you have questions. **Always follow staff members’ instructions**, as they are always looking to preserve the lab’s safety and productivity.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Access\n\nOur lab is open to everyone officially affiliated with the College of Engineering. This includes students enrolled in CoE classes, CoE faculty/staff, CoE RSO members, and all collaborators with those groups/individuals. We welcome entrepreneurial work as long as it does not detract from our work supporting research, courses, and RSOs. Please contact us to clarify if your project may fall into this category!\n\nIn some rare cases, we may need to suspend individuals from the lab for a period of time. This is to preserve the lab’s safety, productivity, and welcoming environment for all users.\n\nSee steps for access here.\n\n## Access Fee (CoE Grad Students Only)\n\nCoE Graduate Students must pay a fee for access (aka “Lab Membership”).\n\nRead about the fee for CoE grad students here.\n\n## General Policies\n\n1. Please keep food in clean, designated areas, and avoid eating or drinking in carpeted spaces or fabrication spaces, like the machine shop.\n2. During particularly busy times in the shop (you’ll know when all the reservations are booked!) we may temporarily ask lab users to refrain from working on personal projects. Please check with lab staff if you are unsure.\n3. Adjustments or repairs to machines (e.g. changing bandsaw blades) must be done by staff exclusively.\n4. If you see something broken/dull/otherwise defective, please let staff know! We can’t replace or repair something if we don’t know it’s missing or broken. Don’t attempt to use broken/defective tools or equipment.\n5. Cleanup is a critical part of lab usage, so always build in time for cleaning up. Never leave the lab without cleaning up after yourself. A good rule of thumb is that the next user shouldn’t be able to tell what material you were using.\n6. Ask questions if anything is ever unclear! Our staff are always willing to help.\n\n## Safety Policies", "char_len": 2128, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::32", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 32, "text": "so always build in time for cleaning up. Never leave the lab without cleaning up after yourself. A good rule of thumb is that the next user shouldn’t be able to tell what material you were using.\n6. Ask questions if anything is ever unclear! Our staff are always willing to help.\n\n## Safety Policies\n\n1. Always have at least one other lab user present when using any lab facility. Never work alone!\n2. Any injury, accident, or unsafe circumstances, no matter how minor, should be reported to lab staff right away.\n3. Come to the lab ready to work safely and effectively – ensure you are not too tired, distracted, or otherwise impaired. Headphones/earbuds are a distraction and are never allowed in fabrication spaces. Please do not distract other lab users.\n4. Phones are allowed in the shop, but never use one while operating a machine, and always ensure their usage does not distract others. Step outside of the lab to take calls!\n5. Our hands-on training sessions cover safe usage of each piece of equipment in the lab. If you haven’t been trained on a piece of equipment, check with staff before using it. You may need to complete a formal training session first.\n6. Never try to touch a moving object (like a lathe or a drill press) with your hands or a shop rag. Wait until your machine has come to a complete stop before touching anything or walking away from the machine.\n7. Machines may be operated by only one person at a time. If you’re working in pairs/teams, all non-operator members should keep their hands off of the machine.\n8. Preserve easy access to exits, safety equipment like fire extinguishers or eye wash stations, and other important safety-related equipment by keeping all aisles clear. Never block a walkway!\n9. To keep floors free from tripping or slipping hazards, keep tools, scrap material, and oil/grease/other liquids off of the floor. Spills should be cleaned up right away to keep others from slipping. Ask staff for help if you’re not sure how to do it properly.\n10. Check with staff before using compressed air in the lab. In general, it’s hazardous to use compressed air to clean off parts and equipment.\n11. If you notice blood or other hazardous fluids, notify staff.\n\n## Clothing and Personal Protective Equipment", "char_len": 2254, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::33", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 33, "text": "if you’re not sure how to do it properly.\n10. Check with staff before using compressed air in the lab. In general, it’s hazardous to use compressed air to clean off parts and equipment.\n11. If you notice blood or other hazardous fluids, notify staff.\n\n## Clothing and Personal Protective Equipment\n\n1. Be aware of the activities/hazards you’ll be near while you’re in the lab and make reasonable clothing choices. Always keep your torso and legs completely covered (preferably with cut-resistant fabrics!) while in the lab – and remember that certain activities (like welding) will have additional PPE requirements.\n2. Headphone cords, jewelry (rings/bracelets/necklaces/dangly earrings), watches, hoodie drawstrings, long sleeves, and other dangly items may pose an entanglement risk in the lab and thus are not allowed. Usually, these items can be either removed or tucked in when you come to the lab. Long sleeves must be rolled up. Items like medical bracelets that cannot be removed may be taped in place.\n3. Hearing protection (e.g. earplugs or earmuffs, provided in the lab) is required when the decibel level in the lab reaches 90 or more. You’re always welcome to use hearing protection, but never use headphones/earbuds as they can be a distraction and/or entanglement risk.\n4. Close-toed shoes are always required in the lab.\n5. Long hair, long facial hair, and head coverings may be entanglement risks. Tie hair back appropriately and check in with lab staff before using the equipment to ensure your safety.\n6. Do not wear gloves while operating equipment, as they pose an entanglement risk. Exceptions may be made in certain circumstances (e.g. welding or material handling), so check with lab staff.\n7. Safety glasses are provided and always required while in any fabrication area, regardless of what activity you’ll be doing. Prescription glasses do not qualify as safety glasses, and you’ll need to wear safety glasses over your regular pair. You’ll be glad for the added protection! You’re welcome to bring your own pair of glasses if they meet or exceed the ANSI Z87+ standard.\n\n## Material Safety", "char_len": 2116, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::34", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 34, "text": "you’ll be doing. Prescription glasses do not qualify as safety glasses, and you’ll need to wear safety glasses over your regular pair. You’ll be glad for the added protection! You’re welcome to bring your own pair of glasses if they meet or exceed the ANSI Z87+ standard.\n\n## Material Safety\n\nAt times, our lab users need to work with unusual materials for functional or investigative purposes. We have experience with a wide range of materials and are eager to help with these projects, but we only allow users to work with materials known to be safe for the people and machines in the lab.\n\nPlanning to use a new material? Do your research first by reading the MSDS and checking Machinery’s Handbook. Once you’ve done that and it looks promising, come talk to us to make sure it’s OK. Some materials require special tooling/training to machine or are otherwise dangerous and are not allowed in the lab, for the safety of our users and our equipment. Carcinogenic, toxic, hardened, glass-filled, abrasive, corrosive, flammable, aerosol-producing, or special-tool-requiring materials are not allowed. We would be happy to help you find a suitable alternative or connect you with the resources you need to complete your project.\n\nSome unapproved materials include:\n\n* Magnesium & Alloys (highly flammable)\n* Beryllium & Alloys (carcinogenic dust)\n* G10/Fiberglass (toxic, special tooling required, dusty)\n* Titanium (special tooling required)\n* Ceramics (special tooling required)\n* Phenolic (Toxic)\n* Graphite (dusty)\n* Hardened Steels (special tooling required)\n* Higher Alloys (e.g. Hastelloy/Niobium/Inconel, special tooling required)\n\n## Reservations\n\nSome equipment in our labs is first-come first-served, but some pieces of equipment – most commonly, the lathes, mills, and laser cutter – require reservations. Machine reservations (also called Bookings) help us organize staff around user needs and generally help the lab run more efficiently. Please review these basic policies and reach out with any questions.", "char_len": 2019, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::35", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 35, "text": "pieces of equipment – most commonly, the lathes, mills, and laser cutter – require reservations. Machine reservations (also called Bookings) help us organize staff around user needs and generally help the lab run more efficiently. Please review these basic policies and reach out with any questions.\n\n* Reservations can be made up to 14 days in advance.\n* If at all possible, cancel reservations you plan not to use at least 12 hours in advance so that others can sign up in your place.\n* If you’re more than 15 minutes late for your reservation, the rest of your reservations for that day will be canceled. When the shop is busy, it’s extremely disruptive to have machines sitting idle, and we need to minimize that time. We’ll send you a notification that this has occurred.\n* Don’t reserve a machine for your friend/teammate – the person who uses the machine must be the one with the reservation.\n* Reserve only one machine at a time. You can only physically be in one location at a time! When you check in for a machine, if you have multiple simultaneous reservations by mistake, you’ll be asked which you’d like to cancel.\n* Within reason, don’t reserve more time than you think you’ll need.\n* Remember to build cleanup time into your reservation! The next user shouldn’t be able to tell what material you were working with.\n\n## Personal Projects\n\nOur lab’s mission is to support project work by our CoE community, and this necessarily includes personal projects. Personal projects are opportunities to pursue passions, learn new skills, and build confidence and community. However, when personal projects begin to crowd out projects for research, classes, or CoE student organizations, we may need to limit lab use for personal projects. As always, please reach out to us if you’d like to discuss your project.\n\n## Tools and Hardware\n\n### **Who May Use Design Innovation Lab Tools?**\n\nAny CoE community member may use our tools – just check in with us at the window first. Some tools (like those covered in our Woodworking or Welding Training) may require users to complete further training before use; some more specialized tools may only be accessible upon request. If you don’t see what you need, please ask us.\n\n### **Where May I Use Them?**", "char_len": 2251, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::36", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 36, "text": "us at the window first. Some tools (like those covered in our Woodworking or Welding Training) may require users to complete further training before use; some more specialized tools may only be accessible upon request. If you don’t see what you need, please ask us.\n\n### **Where May I Use Them?**\n\nOur tools can only be used in our Lab (the basement of ECB/Wendt Commons). **No tools should leave our lab unless specific permission is granted by full-time staff.** We are much better able to assist users with tool usage and project completion if work is done in our space. The community benefits from project work being completed in a centralized area instead of in separate labs.\n\n### **When May I Use Them?**\n\nOur tools are available for use during our open lab hours, which are available on our website. We also have a limited set of tools available in the Discovery Area of ECB for use by any community member during our off hours. We expect that any tools used during off hours be used safely and responsibly. These tools should be returned to their proper location in good condition and, like all other tools, should not leave the basement work area.\n\n### **How Do I Find Hardware?**\n\nWe stock an extensive assortment of fasteners and other useful items in the lab. Any CoE community member can purchase hardware from us.\n\nThis is now self-serve! Go back to our tool & hardware room and select what you need, note the type and quantity, then bring it up to the front to pay for it.\n\n\\*ECB: Until our POS system is in place, purchases under $5 will not be charged. Anything over $5 can be handled easily with our web-based payment system.\n\n### **What is Available In the Tool and Hardware Room?**\n\nMost hardware is self-serve and available in the tool & hardware room. Many hand tools, power tools, and consumables (e.g. adhesives) are available for self-service. All items should be returned to the place where they were found – we will rely on our community to keep the space orderly for all users.", "char_len": 2006, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::37", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 37, "text": "hardware is self-serve and available in the tool & hardware room. Many hand tools, power tools, and consumables (e.g. adhesives) are available for self-service. All items should be returned to the place where they were found – we will rely on our community to keep the space orderly for all users.\n\nWhat is NOT available in the tool and hardware room: less common specialty tools, high-precision tools/equipment that need to be more closely monitored, CNC/Welding/Woodworking-specific equipment (which will be located in those areas), and any frequently-needed items for use in the machine shop.\n\nCommon machine shop tools – such as end mills, lathe cutting tools, collets, drill bits, edgefinders, and anything needed for training sessions – can now be found in the yellow toolbox located next to each individual machine. We hope this change increases users’ efficiency!\n\n### **What if My Lab/Class Depends on Your Tooling?**\n\nPlease reach out to us with your specific needs and we’ll see what we can work out. Our tools and equipment are intended for use under our guidance in our space, but we recognize that some classes and labs have historically depended on us for some equipment.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/tours\n\n### In-Person Tours\n\nAnyone connected to the UW community (which includes students, staff, faculty, collaborators, academic visitors, prospective students and/or their parents, alumni, industry representatives, etc.) is welcome to tour the Design Innovation Lab during open hours.\n\nTours typically take 15-20 minutes and cover our equipment, our collaborative work areas, and resources available to users. When you arrive, please check in with the front desk for service.\n\n***Please just drop in for your tour***, unless your group is larger than 10 people and/or you have a question – in which case please contact: maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu\n\n### Remote Tours\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1271/2021/03/Animated-GIF-downsized_large.gif)\n\n**Click on the Wendt Doors to start your 360° virtual tour!**\n\n## Videos\n\n* A quick look at the Design Innovation Lab in  action\n  More\n* Get to Know  Us!\n  More\n* An in-depth tour from our Director, Lennon  Rodgers\n  More", "char_len": 2225, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::38", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 38, "text": "on the Wendt Doors to start your 360° virtual tour!**\n\n## Videos\n\n* A quick look at the Design Innovation Lab in  action\n  More\n* Get to Know  Us!\n  More\n* An in-depth tour from our Director, Lennon  Rodgers\n  More\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2018/07/215A1537-600x400.jpg)\n\n### For more information and videos of the Makerspace and its affiliated programs, check out these resources:\n\n* UW Admissions' Campus Virtual  Tour\n  More\n* UW College of Engineering  Website\n  More\n* UW Makerspace Youtube  Channel\n  More\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2018/05/F6A3099-600x400.jpg)\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/jobs-at-the-di-labs\n\n## Technical Staff\n\n*Applications are now closed. Apply again in the fall! See below for how to submit an interest form so we email you when applications open.*\n\n### Undergraduate Students\n\nWe hire undergraduate hourly students in both our Wendt and ECB locations every semester. We’re looking for students with the following qualities:\n\n[-] Outgoing and ready to help others become better designers and fabricators. Our staff is a service-oriented community of makers with a wide variety of skills and backgrounds.\n\n[-] Have experience designing with any of our tools/equipment!\n\n[-] Able to provide a welcoming environment in a service-oriented position, helping users with fabrication and design. Staff must also be willing to learn! We train on machines and for equipment maintenance, and provide other opportunities for potential creative projects!\n\n*Want to work here in the future? Submit an interest form here and we’ll email you when applications open again.*\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/06/BrettAish.jpg)\n\n## Fab Fellow Program\n\n### Graduate Assistants\n\nWe hire graduate students each year to help oversee our shops. If you have experience with hands-on learning and fabrication, please contact us. We may also be able to combine this work with your research interests towards a thesis.\n\n**Indicate Your Interest Here!**\n\n*Please fill out the Interest Form, and we will reach out.*\n\n##\n\n## Operations Staff\n\n### **Undergraduate Students**", "char_len": 2193, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::39", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 39, "text": "with hands-on learning and fabrication, please contact us. We may also be able to combine this work with your research interests towards a thesis.\n\n**Indicate Your Interest Here!**\n\n*Please fill out the Interest Form, and we will reach out.*\n\n##\n\n## Operations Staff\n\n### **Undergraduate Students**\n\n[-]  Outgoing & enthusiastic in assisting with the day-to-day operations of the space.\n\n[-] Interested in applying their areas of interest and expertise to an expanding and engaging operational environment.\n\n[-] Looking to expand upon office management, finances, advertising, video and communications, and/or event management interests.\n\n*If this sounds like you, submit an interest form here and we’ll email you when applications open.*\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/composites\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Shop Tools Required training for *all users*\n\nComposites Lab Training Required for *all users.* Prerequisite: Intro to Shop Tools\n\nSafety is our top priority, and we will ensure that all students using the composites lab have all the training and personal protective equipment necessary to use the lab safely and effectively.\n\nContact di-composites@engr.wisc.edu with any questions.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/215A5867-768x512.jpg)\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Hours & Access\n\nThe composites lab is available for student use by reservation only, between 8am-9pm 7 days/week. Reservations are made in 1-day increments on our shop website.\n\nStudents must have completed Intro to Shop Tools before completing the Composites Lab Training on Canvas and attending our hands-on training before using the lab (see steps above).\n\n## Capabilities & Equipment", "char_len": 1836, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::40", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 40, "text": "8am-9pm 7 days/week. Reservations are made in 1-day increments on our shop website.\n\nStudents must have completed Intro to Shop Tools before completing the Composites Lab Training on Canvas and attending our hands-on training before using the lab (see steps above).\n\n## Capabilities & Equipment\n\nThis facility is set up for students to safely perform post-processing procedures on cured composites. Because composites, like cured carbon fiber, can produce very fine particulate matter when abrasive processes are performed, the safest way to perform these operations is to utilize an industrial downdraft table. The downdraft table uses a vacuum and filtration system to suction particulate matter away from the operator and leave very little particulate matter in the air. Efficacy is further improved by the use of a snorkel, which further aids in suctioning particulate matter away from the operator.\n\nEquipment & Tools available for use:\n\n* Diversitech Industrial Downdraft Table, fitted with snorkel\n* Explosion-proof vacuum\n* Wide variety of pneumatic shaping and cutting tools\n\n## Contact\n\nPlease contact us at di-composites@engr.wisc.edu and we’ll be happy to answer any questions you have.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/cnc-mills-lathes\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Machining Training Required for *all users*\n\nCNC Mill Training\n\nMastercam Resources\n\n* Requires Intro to Machining to complete CNC 1 training in main machine shop\n* Requires Intro to Machining to complete CNC Lathe training in CNC Lab.\n* Requires CNC 1 to complete CNC 2 & 3 training in CNC Lab.\n\n* If you are trying to reserve a machine for your CNC 2, CNC 3, or CNC Lathe training session and none are available, please contact the shop.\n* If you need assistance from full-time staff, please set up a Design Consultation. We can dig into your project details if we can plan ahead to set aside time for you.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/IMG_2367-1-768x512.jpg)\n\n## **CNC machining training available!**\n\n* 3-axis mill training: CNC Mill 2 (2OP) and CNC Mill 3 (TMC7)\n* Haas Lathe training: CNC Lathe 1\n* read our CNC Training page for detailed information", "char_len": 2210, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::41", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 41, "text": "for you.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/IMG_2367-1-768x512.jpg)\n\n## **CNC machining training available!**\n\n* 3-axis mill training: CNC Mill 2 (2OP) and CNC Mill 3 (TMC7)\n* Haas Lathe training: CNC Lathe 1\n* read our CNC Training page for detailed information\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n### Related Videos\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/TRAK-tmc7-400.png)\n\n## TRAK TMC7\n\nThe CNC Lab has a TRAK TMC7 Toolroom Machining Center.\n\nLearn more\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/trak-2op-400-sq.png)\n\n##\n\nThe CNC Lab has two 2OP Vertical Machining Centers.\n\nLearn more\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/haas-st-15-400.png)\n\n## Haas ST 15\n\nThe CNC Lab has three Haas ST 15 Lathes.\n\nLearn more\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/TRAM-DPM-400.png)\n\n##\n\nThe CNC Lab has two 3-axis TRAK DPM2 mills with ProtoTRAK SMX controllers.\n\nLearn more\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/m-pass\n\n* Is only for UW students enrolled in a degree program, and for current UW faculty/staff outside the College of Engineering (CoE).\n* Is for makers using the space for engineering, design, and/or innovation.\n* Costs $150 per semester, and is registered for the current semester no matter when you apply.\n\nSee semester schedules\n\n* You ***may not*** use ECB equipment or services with the M-pass.\n* This membership does not cover the cost of consumables.\n* M-Passes may not to be used for personal production for profit, or for furniture projects.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/10/Screenshot-2024-10-30-at-12.14.32 PM-768x525.png)\n\nhttps://wid.wisc.edu/genetic-symphonies-the-building-hox-of-life/\n\n**Step 1:**\n\nRequest an M-Pass\n\n\\*If you’re paying with a funding string, your PI must create a payment account first.\n\n**Step 2:**\n\nComplete Lab Orientation\n\n1. 1. Complete the Canvas module training\n\n**Optional:**\n\nObtain your Laser Training\n\n1. 1. Complete the Canvas module training\n   2. Attend in-person hands-on training session\n\n**Optional:**\n\nRequest the Makerspace Shop Training", "char_len": 2293, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::42", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 42, "text": "a payment account first.\n\n**Step 2:**\n\nComplete Lab Orientation\n\n1. 1. Complete the Canvas module training\n\n**Optional:**\n\nObtain your Laser Training\n\n1. 1. Complete the Canvas module training\n   2. Attend in-person hands-on training session\n\n**Optional:**\n\nRequest the Makerspace Shop Training\n\n##### **\\*Not available November-December/April-May**\n\nTo use the machine shop you will need to be trained in a 2 part series; bandsaws, drill press, and sanders, and then the panel saw, table saw, and miter saw.  Each training will take 1 hour. Email our Shop Manager to schedule an appointment. This option is by request and is not a guaranteed option through the M-Pass.\n\n**\\***To renew your M-Pass, please re-submit the request form above.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/lab-orientation\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Lab Orientation introduces students to the DI Lab and basic safety awareness. Completing this orientation grants users access to limited tools/equipment within the our labs and lays the foundation for further training (e.g. Intro to Shop Tools and Intro to Machining).\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use everything in the Wendt facility *except* equipment that requires extra training (shop machinery + laser cutters).\n* Use hand tools in the ECB facility Tool Room and Discovery Center.\n* Hardware and materials may be purchased at either location without completing the orientation.\n\n## Steps to Complete the Lab Orientation\n\n1. Complete the Lab Orientation videos and quizzes in Canvas\n2. *That’s it!*\n\n## Time to Complete\n\nThe Lab Orientation can be completed in as little as 15-20 minutes. We hope it’s time well spent getting oriented to our offerings!\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/intro-to-shop-tools", "char_len": 2094, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::43", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 43, "text": "Complete the Lab Orientation videos and quizzes in Canvas\n2. *That’s it!*\n\n## Time to Complete\n\nThe Lab Orientation can be completed in as little as 15-20 minutes. We hope it’s time well spent getting oriented to our offerings!\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/intro-to-shop-tools\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Overview\n\nOur Intro to Shop Tools module provides introductory training on machines like drill presses, sanders, and band saws. Students will understand safety considerations pertaining to basic machine tools and feel confident navigating projects using this equipment in our shops. This training only needs to be completed once – but we’re always happy to provide a quick refresher!\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use everything in the ECB shop *except* the lathes and mills (which require the Intro to Machining) or equipment that requires other specialty training\n* Use everything in the Wendt shop *except* equipment that requires specialty training\n\n## Steps to complete Intro to Shop Tools\n\n(*If you haven’t yet completed the Lab Orientation, do that first!*)\n\n1. Complete all the pre-lab quizzes in Canvas\n2. Enroll in and attend an Intro to Shop Tools session (see below for more information). The link to enroll will be provided after you complete step 1.\n3. (Optional, but *highly recommended!!*) Complete the post-lab in Canvas! This will solidify everything you learned in your hands-on session and best prepare you to make good use of the tools for your own projects in the future.\n\n## Time to Complete\n\n* The Intro to Shop Tools can usually completed within a day or two – one for taking the Canvas quizzes and another for the hands-on session and post-lab.\n\n## Hands-on Intro to Shop Tools Session", "char_len": 2057, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::44", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 44, "text": "prepare you to make good use of the tools for your own projects in the future.\n\n## Time to Complete\n\n* The Intro to Shop Tools can usually completed within a day or two – one for taking the Canvas quizzes and another for the hands-on session and post-lab.\n\n## Hands-on Intro to Shop Tools Session\n\nThis hands-on session introduces basic fabrication techniques and equipment including workholding techniques, vertical band saws, drill presses, and sanders, as well as how to tap (internally thread by hand) a part. Participants will make a fun test piece during the session to get hands-on experience with the tools.\n\n## Location\n\nThis hands-on session meets in the ECB Shop – just head downstairs and you’ll see someone who can check you in. For individuals completing this as part of a class (e.g. InterEGR 170, ME 201, etc…), you may meet in your classroom to begin the training. Follow your instructor’s instructions!\n\n## Duration\n\n~45 minutes\n\n## Before you arrive\n\n* Wear appropriate clothing as defined by the safety policy\n* Arrive on time. Individuals who show up more than 10 minutes late will be unable to participate.\n\n## How to Enroll\n\nOpen sessions are posted in Fusion. You’ll get the link to see available sessions once you’ve completed the Canvas quizzes.\n\nDuring Fall and Spring semester, we offer several sessions per week, but the demand is much lower over the summer and during academic breaks. Please reach out to us to set up a session if you don’t see any listed – we are usually able to accommodate within a week or so.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/intro-to-machining\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Overview", "char_len": 1981, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::45", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 45, "text": "More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Introduction to Machining module introduces students to basic machining techniques using a mill and a lathe. It’s intended as a foundation to be built on as students work on more ambitious, complex projects throughout their time here. Students will learn safe operation of a manual mill and a lathe and, in doing so, will produce a small test part to precise specifications.\n\n**Steps:**\n\n1. Make sure you’ve completed the Intro to Shop Tools! This is an important prerequisite for the material you’ll learn in Intro to Machining.\n2. Complete the Intro to Machining quizzes in Canvas, which includes watching the demonstration videos.\n3. Successfully complete the test piece (reserve machines through Fusion and actually use the machines to make the part in the shop)\n\n## Test Piece\n\nTo make the test piece, reserve a lathe and mill online and then come to the ECB Shop and make it. Individuals typically need **at least two hours on each machine (4 x 30-minute slots each)**, and the lathe should be reserved before the mill. The ECB Shop will provide you with the metal you will be machining when you arrive.\n\nAlpha Part Print\n\nMaking the Alpha part videos:  lathe and mill\n\nBeta Part Print\n\nMaking the Beta part videos:  lathe and mill\n\nGrading Sheet\n\n* When you have completed all quizzes, you will be able to reserve a lathe and a mill to do your test piece in Fusion\n* You will need to start with a two-hour reservation on a lathe, followed by a second, two-hour reservation on a mill. They do not have to be done on the same day!\n* We will supply all necessary tools, materials and safety glasses.  Please show up dressed appropriately at your reserved time and check in at the window.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/laser-cutter-training", "char_len": 2056, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::46", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 46, "text": "reservation on a mill. They do not have to be done on the same day!\n* We will supply all necessary tools, materials and safety glasses.  Please show up dressed appropriately at your reserved time and check in at the window.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/laser-cutter-training\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Intro to Laser Cutting\n\nThe laser cutter is one of the busiest tools in the labs. Available in the Design Innovation Lab @ Wendt, the laser cutter is simple to use after a brief training session. This training will cover file types, how to use the laser cutter software, basic operation of the laser cutter, logistics, and safety considerations.\n\n### Steps to Complete Laser Cutter Training\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete the Lab Orientation\n2. Complete the Laser Cutter Canvas module\n3. Use the link provided in Canvas to register for a 1-hour in-person training session at the Design Innovation Lab @ Wendt. \\*\\*\\**Over the summer we provide training sessions by request only. Shoot us an email!* \\*\\*\\*\n\nEmail maker-laser@engr.wisc.edu with any questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/welding-training\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Welding Training\n\nOur welding training introduces users to our MIG and TIG welding equipment. Welding is a skill built with hours of practice, so our sessions are designed to give you the tools you need to develop skills sufficient for your project work. Our expert staff are always willing to help!\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all", "char_len": 2276, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::47", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 47, "text": "hours of practice, so our sessions are designed to give you the tools you need to develop skills sufficient for your project work. Our expert staff are always willing to help!\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Intro to MIG Welding\n\n## Overview\n\nThe Intro to MIG Welding training teaches users how to safely set up and use MIG welders. Only after completing this training will users be allowed to use the MIG welders.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use MIG welders\n\n## Steps to complete Intro to MIG Welding\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Shop Intro\n2. Complete the MIG Welding quiz\n3. Enroll in and attend a MIG Welding session\n\n---\n\n## Intro to MIG Welding\n\nThis session will familiarize students with the safe operation and set-up of a MIG welder. Students will also practice fillet, lap, and butt joints.\n\n## Location\n\nECB shop (check in at the window)\n\n## Duration\n\n~2 hours\n\n## Before you arrive\n\n* Enroll in Intro to MIG Welding\n* Wear appropriate clothing as defined by the safety policy. This is where clothing choice really matters! It should not melt or burn easily.\n* Arrive on time. Individuals who arrive more than ten minutes late will be unable to participate.\n\n## How to Enroll\n\nOpen sessions are posted in Fusion. You’ll get the link to see available sessions once you’ve completed the Canvas quizzes.\n\n## Intro to TIG Welding\n\n## Overview\n\nIntro to TIG Welding teaches users how to safely setup and use a TIG welder. Using the TIG Welders is only allowed after completing this training.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use TIG welders\n\n## Steps to complete Intro to TIG Welding\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Intro to Shop Tools\n2. Complete Intro to MIG Welding\n3. Complete the TIG Welding quiz\n4. Enroll in the TIG Welding training session\n\n---\n\n## TIG Welding Training\n\nIndividuals will be taught the basics of TIG welding steel. This will include training in machine set-up, use of filler rod, and fusion welding beads, butt joints, lap joints, and T-welds. Individuals may ask about TIG Welding aluminum – a separate session may be necessary for individuals considering aluminum for substantial project work.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shop – check in at the window\n\n## Duration\n\n~3 hours", "char_len": 2291, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::48", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 48, "text": "filler rod, and fusion welding beads, butt joints, lap joints, and T-welds. Individuals may ask about TIG Welding aluminum – a separate session may be necessary for individuals considering aluminum for substantial project work.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shop – check in at the window\n\n## Duration\n\n~3 hours\n\n## Before you arrive\n\n* Enroll in Intro to TIG Welding (link available on Canvas)\n* Wear appropriate clothing as defined by the safety policy. This is where clothing choice really matters! Clothing must not melt or easily burn.\n* Arrive on time. Individuals who arrive more than ten minutes late will be unable to participate.\n\n## How to Enroll\n\nOpen sessions are posted in Fusion. You’ll get the link to see available sessions once you’ve completed the Canvas quizzes.\n\n## MIG Welding Aluminum\n\nIf you need to MIG weld Aluminum for your project, please contact the shop and we’ll be happy to help. This is no longer a formal training offering.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/woodworking\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## Woodworking\n\nStudents in the woodshop create anything from the highly practical (like shop cabinets) to the truly memorable (like a cheese-themed, Wisconsin-shaped guitar). The woodshop houses some of our most hazardous equipment, like the table saw, so our training focuses mostly on safety and practical tips for efficient usage of the space.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Woodshop Orientation\n\n## Overview\n\nThis orientation introduces students to the equipment in the ECB and Wendt woodshops, with a major focus on safety principles. Students will get brief hands-on experience with the miter saw and table saw and a variety of wood types. All participants will gain sufficient foundational safety knowledge to learn any piece of equipment from staff upon returning to the woodshop for project work.\n\n## Privileges", "char_len": 2281, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::49", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 49, "text": "safety principles. Students will get brief hands-on experience with the miter saw and table saw and a variety of wood types. All participants will gain sufficient foundational safety knowledge to learn any piece of equipment from staff upon returning to the woodshop for project work.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use the Wendt woodshop (including table saw, miter saw, sanders, router)\n* Use the ECB woodshop (including all of the above, plus jointers, planers, drum sander, and more)\n* **Note: further instruction is required before using any equipment for the first time – this is explained in detail in both the online training and in-person orientation**\n\n## Steps to complete\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Intro to Shop Tools (this gives you the foundation you need to learn these more specialized tools)\n2. Complete the Woodshop Canvas module\n3. Enroll in and attend the Woodshop Orientation\n\n---\n\n## Woodshop Orientation\n\nThis session will cover, among other things:\n\n* Access and policies\n* Equipment availability in each woodshop (Wendt and ECB)\n* Safety principles: general and equipment-specific\n* Miter saw and table saw practice\n\n## Location\n\nECB Woodshop\n\n## Duration\n\n~60-90 minutes\n\n## Before you arrive\n\n* Enroll in a Woodshop Orientation\n* Wear appropriate clothing as defined by the safety policy\n* Arrive on time. Individuals who show up more than ten minutes late will be unable to participate.\n\n## How to Enroll\n\nOpen sessions are posted in Fusion. Use the link at the end of the Canvas module to enroll. We’re adding new sessions throughout the semester, so check back or reach out if you don’t see one that works for you.\n\n## Wood Lathe\n\n## Overview\n\nAccess to the wood lathe is a little different from the other equipment because of its complexity. The training will cover how to safely use a wood lathe and chisels. Only individuals who have successfully demonstrated safety and proficiency will be allowed to use the wood lathe.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use the wood lathe\n\n## Steps to complete Wood Lathe training\n\n1. Complete the Woodshop Orientation.\n2. Wood lathe training is scheduled upon request! Stop by the shop or email us to arrange a session.\n\n---\n\n## Wood Lathe Training Session", "char_len": 2214, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::50", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 50, "text": "will be allowed to use the wood lathe.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use the wood lathe\n\n## Steps to complete Wood Lathe training\n\n1. Complete the Woodshop Orientation.\n2. Wood lathe training is scheduled upon request! Stop by the shop or email us to arrange a session.\n\n---\n\n## Wood Lathe Training Session\n\nThis session will familiarize students with the safe turning of spindles (horizontal grain) and face work (perpendicular grain) using spurs, face plates, screw drives, chucks and live centers with a focus on carbide tools.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Woodshop\n\n## Duration\n\n~1 hour\n\n## Before you arrive\n\n* Wear appropriate clothing as defined by the safety policy\n* Prepare to be flexible; the training timeline is entirely dependent on how many other students require assistance in the woodshop.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/cnc-machining-training\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\n## CNC Training\n\nWe offer Computer Numerical Control (CNC) Mills and Lathes in our CNC Lab – in addition to all our manual mills being outfitted with X/Y CNC capability. Our training is designed to progress users through a series of projects of increasing complexity to develop confidence and competence with CNC equipment and software.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## CNC 1: Conversational CNC Machining\n\n## Overview\n\nThis self-paced training will cover basic conversational programming along with the standard canned programs (circular, rectangular pockets, rectangular frames, and bolt hole patterns) on the ProtoTRAK EMX controllers (staff will be available to answer any questions). ProtoTRAK EMX controllers are available on all Eisen mills. Individuals will not be allowed to program or use advanced controller features on a CNC mill until they have completed CNC Mill 1 training.\nNote: All of the programming is done at the machine. CAD/CAM software is not used.\n\n## Privileges", "char_len": 2294, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::51", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 51, "text": "ProtoTRAK EMX controllers are available on all Eisen mills. Individuals will not be allowed to program or use advanced controller features on a CNC mill until they have completed CNC Mill 1 training.\nNote: All of the programming is done at the machine. CAD/CAM software is not used.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* Use conversational CNC machining on ProtoTRAK EMX equipped milling machines.  These are the same machines used during the Intro to Machining.\n\n## Time Frame\n\nApproximately 2 hours\n\nIf you’ve found your previous machining experiences to be challenging, consider reserving more time.\n\n## Steps to complete CNC Mill 1\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Intro to Machining\n2. Complete the CNC Mill 1 quiz\n3. Reserve any available Manual Mill in the ECB Shop\n4. Program and machine two parts following the CNC Mill 1 Lab Instructions.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shop\n\n## CNC 2: 3-axis CNC Machining\n\n## Overview\n\nThis self-paced training will introduce individuals to 3 axis machining using CAM software-generated G-code on an enclosed, CNC mill with an automatic tool changer and flood coolant.  (Staff will be available to answer any questions). Individuals will not be allowed to program or run this machine until they have completed CNC Mill 2 training.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* CNC Mill 2 – Trak 2-OP:\n  CAM programmed three axis CNC machining on a Trak 2-OP mill.\n\n## Time Frame\n\nApproximately 3 hours\n\nIf you’ve found your previous machining experiences to be challenging, consider reserving more time.\n\n## Steps to complete CNC Mill 2\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Intro to Machining\n2. Complete CNC Mill 1 training\n3. Reserve a 2-OP mill in Fusion\n4. Machine two parts following the CNC Mill 2 Lab Instructions.\n\nNote: Staff will provide the G-code you need to machine the parts when you arrive.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shops – CNC Lab\n\n## CAM Software", "char_len": 1856, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::52", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 52, "text": "Complete Intro to Machining\n2. Complete CNC Mill 1 training\n3. Reserve a 2-OP mill in Fusion\n4. Machine two parts following the CNC Mill 2 Lab Instructions.\n\nNote: Staff will provide the G-code you need to machine the parts when you arrive.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shops – CNC Lab\n\n## CAM Software\n\nThe College of Engineering currently supports MasterCAM which is the CAM software used to generate the G-code for this training. While not required to complete this training, it is recommend that individuals go through the “Learning MasterCAM” tutorial available for free through DoIT online training.\nMasterCAM is available on all CAE lab computers. MasterCAM HLE is available for individuals to download to their personal computers. It has identical functionality to the version of MasterCAM found on CAE lab computers. Work can be saved and transferred to TEAM Lab staff in order to generate G-code.\n\n## CNC 3: Advanced CNC Machining\n\n## Overview\n\nThis training introduces the TMC7 Machine and takes students through the full process of converting a model to toolpaths to a completed part on a fully-featured 3-axis CNC machine.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* CNC Mill 3 – TMC7: CAM programmed three axis CNC machining on the TMC7 mill.\n\n## Time Frame\n\nApproximately 3 hours\n\nIf you’ve found your previous machining experiences to be challenging, consider reserving more time.\n\n## Steps to complete CNC Mill 3\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Intro to Machining\n2. Complete CNC 1 training in the Main Shop\n3. Complete CNC 2 training in the CNC Lab\n4. Reserve the TMC7 in Fusion\n5. Machine two parts following the CNC Mill 3 Lab Instructions.\n\nNote: Staff will provide the G-code you need to machine the parts when you arrive.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shops – CNC Lab\n\n## CNC Lathe\n\n## Overview\n\nThis training introduces the Haas CNC Lathe and takes students through the process of loading and running pre-made toolpaths to complete a part on a fully-featured CNC lathe.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* CNC Lathe: CAM programmed CNC machining on the Haas CNC Lathes.\n\n## Time Frame\n\nApproximately 2 hours\n\nIf you’ve found your previous machining experiences to be challenging, consider reserving more time.\n\n## Steps to complete CNC Lathe Training\n\n(must be completed in order)", "char_len": 2248, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::53", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 53, "text": "lathe.\n\n## Privileges\n\n* CNC Lathe: CAM programmed CNC machining on the Haas CNC Lathes.\n\n## Time Frame\n\nApproximately 2 hours\n\nIf you’ve found your previous machining experiences to be challenging, consider reserving more time.\n\n## Steps to complete CNC Lathe Training\n\n(must be completed in order)\n\n1. Complete Intro to Machining\n2. Reserve the CNC Lathe in Fusion\n3. Machine parts A, B, and C following the CNC Lathe Lab Instructions.\n\nNote: Staff will provide the G-code you need to machine the parts when you arrive.\n\n## Location\n\nECB Shops – CNC Lab\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/training/frequently-asked-questions\n\n* Lab  Orientation\n  More\n* Intro to Shop  Tools\n  More\n* Intro to  Machining\n  More\n* Intro to Laser  Cutting\n  More\n* Welding  Training\n  More\n* Woodworking\n  More\n* CNC  Training\n  More\n* Composites  Post-Processing\n  More\n* Frequently Asked  Questions\n  More\n* Fusion  Troubleshooting\n  More\n* CAD  Support\n  More\n* Book a Machine  Reservation!\n  More\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## All the names changed! What happened?\n\nWe updated the names of our offerings to better reflect the intent and purpose behind each one.\n\n* A “Seminar” is now called a **training session**.\n* A “permit” is now called **training** to better communicate that these are foundations to be built upon, not terminal experiences.\n* “Red Permit” is now **Intro to Shop Tools** to better capture the intent and content of the session. The content has been completely revamped as well.\n* “Green Permit” is now **Intro to Machining** for the same reason. We hope to eliminate the confusion between the two colors previously offered!\n\n## I have my Red (or Green) Permit - Do I need to re-do my training after the name change?\n\nAbsolutely not, though of course you are welcome to get a refresher! The names have changed, but for the most part, the content remains exactly the same.\n\nAll students who have completed our training in the past still enjoy the same privileges and access that accompanied the training under the old names.\n\n## What training do I need?", "char_len": 2163, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::54", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 54, "text": "are welcome to get a refresher! The names have changed, but for the most part, the content remains exactly the same.\n\nAll students who have completed our training in the past still enjoy the same privileges and access that accompanied the training under the old names.\n\n## What training do I need?\n\nThis all depends on your project! Read through the information about the various training we offer using the links on the left hand side of this page and reach out if you have questions. We’re happy to help.\n\n## What is \"Fusion\" and how do I access it?\n\nFusion is the online system used to manage users’ training history, fee payment, equipment reservations, and training session signups/attendance. Access it here or click the link in the top right corner of this page where it says \"Fusion Login\".\n\n## How do I set up a CAE account to use the lab's computers?\n\nHere’s a link:\n\nCAE New Account Creation\n\n## I'm basically Hephaestus, do I still need to go through the permit process?\n\nYes, even Hephaestus himself would have to go through our training. All of our students, staff, and faculty, no matter how experienced, are part of our making community, and training together is an important shared experience.\n\nMany instructors like to take our training just to check in on what their students are learning. If you’re an advanced user, others in your hands-on session can certainly learn from you!\n\n## What if I don't have time for the training? I'm in a hurry!\n\nWe don’t make exceptions to our training requirements – it’s all about ensuring community safety and community standards.\n\nOur labs contain machines and tools that, when operated improperly, can cause serious harm to the operator and those nearby. In addition, when a machine is damaged, it can take that machine offline just when others need it most.", "char_len": 1815, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::55", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 55, "text": "– it’s all about ensuring community safety and community standards.\n\nOur labs contain machines and tools that, when operated improperly, can cause serious harm to the operator and those nearby. In addition, when a machine is damaged, it can take that machine offline just when others need it most.\n\nJust like any other lab that uses hazardous materials or equipment, we require potential users to prove they have basic knowledge of the equipment and its safe operation prior to its use; the training requirements are the simplest way of proving that these users have this knowledge at scale (we have thousands of users per year!). It also gives users the ability to complete quality work in a safe and efficient manner and the assurance that those working around them are working safely too.\n\n## I am in a class that meets in a fabrication lab. If I do not get trained in time can I come to the lab anyway and just watch?\n\nNo. Just like any other lab that uses hazardous materials or equipment; we require potential lab users to prove they have basic knowledge of equipment and its safe operation before being allowed to use it. All students enrolled in courses that use the lab have training requirements clearly communicated to them at the beginning of the semester. Please contact your instructor if you feel your course timeline was unreasonable.\n\n## Once I've completed training, what next?\n\nOur training is designed as ***a solid foundation on which you can build deeper competence*** through future experience. These are not intended as standalone courses! We hope we’ve given you what you need to both ask useful questions (which our staff can answer) and use the equipment & machines safely.\n\n## Do I ever have to renew my training?\n\nNope! Completing the training once is enough, but you’re always welcome to get a refresher.\n\n## Why are there hands-on training sessions, and do they have any prerequisites?\n\nMost machines require in-person demonstration and supervised practice beyond what you can get from a Canvas module, which is why we offer hands-on training sessions. These small-group sessions allow individuals to ask questions and learn by demonstration.", "char_len": 2173, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::56", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 56, "text": "and do they have any prerequisites?\n\nMost machines require in-person demonstration and supervised practice beyond what you can get from a Canvas module, which is why we offer hands-on training sessions. These small-group sessions allow individuals to ask questions and learn by demonstration.\n\nAll hands-on sessions have at least one (but usually more) prerequisites, which depends on the session. Some sessions build on prior knowledge. For example, taking our welding hands-on training requires some foundational knowledge of shop tools for the training to be effective. Use the links to the left to see the specific prerequisites for each session.\n\n## When are training sessions offered?\n\nEach session is handled a bit differently, but in general, our labs offer many training sessions every week. Full schedule information is available on our general shop calendar, and specific session information can be found using the Fusion link provided at the end of the prerequisite Canvas module.\n\n## How do I register for a training session?\n\nUse the link provided at the end of the prerequisite Canvas module to register for a session. If there are no sessions listed for your desired training session, please reach out to us. Depending on the time of year, we may be able to accommodate you.\n\n## I'm a professor/advisor. Can I arrange for a group of my students to all receive training at the same time through a special session?\n\nYes! We’d love to work with your class/group, so please reach out to us. We do require a fair bit of advanced notice – depending on the size of your group, we often need to close parts of the lab to accommodate this. We would like to understand more about your learning goals for your students/group and ensure our offerings will meet your needs.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/fusion-troubleshooting\n\nRead on to find solutions to the most common problems students have…\n\n### I’m trying to reserve a mill/lathe for Intro to Machining after completing my Canvas quizzes, but I can’t. Why not?", "char_len": 2030, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::57", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 57, "text": "ensure our offerings will meet your needs.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/fusion-troubleshooting\n\nRead on to find solutions to the most common problems students have…\n\n### I’m trying to reserve a mill/lathe for Intro to Machining after completing my Canvas quizzes, but I can’t. Why not?\n\n99% of the time, this is because you haven’t yet completed Intro to Shop Tools, which is a prerequisite for Intro to Machining. Completing the Intro to Shop Tools quizzes isn’t enough, you must also have completed the hands-on session where you make the robot head. Once your attendance at that session has processed, you’ll be able to make mill/lathe reservations for your Intro to Machining test piece.\n\nWe try to avoid this situation by asking before you take the Intro to Machining quiz in Canvas whether you’ve completed Intro to Shop Tools or not. Answering this question honestly helps us avoid these confusing situations!\n\n### I just completed the (Intro to Shop Tools, MIG Welding, Wood Saws, etc…) session and don’t see it in my profile on Fusion. Why not?\n\nThe process of updating a student’s training status often takes up to 24 hours, and in the case of large classes, up to 48 hours. If for some reason this timing isn’t fast enough for you, you can email or come into the lab and tell us when you took your training, and we can verify your attendance/manually grant you the training status.\n\n### How do I prove to my instructor/PI that I completed certain training?\n\nGo to shops.engr.wisc.edu and sign in at the upper right-hand corner of the page. From there, click on your name and select “Profile” from the menu. Providing a screenshot of the training listed in the “Memberships” section should suffice as evidence of completion. If there are any problems, please reach out to us.\n\nNote: we are no longer issuing physical permits upon completion of Intro to Shop Tools (f/k/a Red Permit) or Intro to Machining (f/k/a Green Permit). Because this is new as of Fall 2023, some instructors may have legacy instructions about deliverables if they require our training. Rest assured you’re not missing anything, the single source of truth about the training you’ve completed is in your Fusion profile.", "char_len": 2211, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::58", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 58, "text": "to Machining (f/k/a Green Permit). Because this is new as of Fall 2023, some instructors may have legacy instructions about deliverables if they require our training. Rest assured you’re not missing anything, the single source of truth about the training you’ve completed is in your Fusion profile.\n\n### I’m trying to sign up for a training session but don’t see any listed. Can you help?\n\nThis could be for one of two reasons:\n\n1. For any training session that requires the completion of Canvas quizzes ahead of time, the link to register for that training session is only available in Canvas at the end of the module. Do not attempt to register for any session directly from Fusion if the title includes “(Register in Canvas)” and the description indicates that no sessions will be listed there.\n2. It’s possible that none have been listed! We try to stay ahead of demand as best as we can, but you’ll often find that (especially for welding training) you may need to wait a bit. MIG and TIG welding both have interest forms linked from Canvas, and that’s the best way to let our team know you’re waiting for training. If you’re looking for a different kind of training and don’t see any sessions (or all sessions are full), please reach out to us and we’ll do our best to list new sessions. Note that we usually cannot accommodate scheduling requests for training sessions, as our instructors are also busy students with their own hectic schedules!\n\n### I’m looking at my profile and don’t see the (Red Permit/Green Permit), which I know I completed in the past. Where did it go?\n\nIt’s still there, it’s just under a different name. As of the 2023-24 academic year, the Red Permit is now Intro to Shop Tools, and the Green Permit is now Intro to Machining. If you’ve completed one or both of these in the past and don’t see it listed in your profile, please reach out to us and we’ll try to debug it. Our system should reflect exactly what EMU had in its records – we haven’t yet found an exception to this, but it’s always possible.\n\n### I can’t make a reservation for the machine I want, why not?\n\nThis can happen for a few reasons:", "char_len": 2137, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::59", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 59, "text": "your profile, please reach out to us and we’ll try to debug it. Our system should reflect exactly what EMU had in its records – we haven’t yet found an exception to this, but it’s always possible.\n\n### I can’t make a reservation for the machine I want, why not?\n\nThis can happen for a few reasons:\n\n* If you don’t see the machine listed at all in on the Bookings page, it means you don’t have the appropriate eligibility to reserve that machine or that the machine is down/unreservable for some reason. If you think that’s an error, please let us know.\n* The TIG welders and CNC machines in TEAM Lab do not currently have publicly available reservation slots, so you won’t see those show up on the Bookings page. TIG welders are generally available (first-come, first-served) and the CNC Lab’s schedule is managed by Jay.\n* If you see the machine listed and there are slots that all say “Unavailable”, it means that it’s been booked. Try another day/machine!\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/cad-support\n\n## Are you hoping to learn how to use a 3D modeling software or level up your skills?\n\nCAD is a critical engineering tool used to capture design intent, get ideas out of your head, and help make stuff.\n\n## Which Software Should I Use?\n\nWe primarily teach Onshape because it is a CAD program that is:\n\n* ***Free*** for university students, faculty and staff.\n* **Easy** to learn using Onshape’s tutorials.\n* **Browser- and cloud-based**. Works on any computer that has a browser (Mac, Windows, Linux…) and does not require extra software to be installed. Hardware requirements are significantly less for Onshape than for installed desktop CAD programs (e.g. memory, processor speed, graphics).\n* Great for **collaborating**. It’s often referred to as the “Google Docs of CAD” since files can be easy viewed and/or edited among teams.\n* A **real engineering tool**. Onshape was created by the founder of Solidworks (article), so this is not your typical freeware CAD software.\n\nCreate a Free Onshape Account\n\n**Other options at UW-Madison College of Engineering (Solidworks, Autodesk, NX, etc.):**\n\nCAE CAD Software List\n\nCAE Computer Labs\n\nCitrix Remote Use Through a Browser\n\n## CAD Help\n\nOur staff can help you get started with CAD or answer specific questions.\n\nBook a 1/2 hr session", "char_len": 2297, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::60", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 60, "text": "Onshape Account\n\n**Other options at UW-Madison College of Engineering (Solidworks, Autodesk, NX, etc.):**\n\nCAE CAD Software List\n\nCAE Computer Labs\n\nCitrix Remote Use Through a Browser\n\n## CAD Help\n\nOur staff can help you get started with CAD or answer specific questions.\n\nBook a 1/2 hr session\n\n## CAD Tutorials\n\nJust getting started with CAD or want to level up? Explore these tutorials:\n\n* CAD Fundamentals\n* CAD Best Practices\n* Onshape Training\n* Learn by Doing: Design and 3D Print a Keychain\n\n## CAD Fundamentals\n\n### CAD is slow\n\nCAD is used to develop an idea once hand sketching stops being useful. (Don’t shortchange the sketching phase. CAD is slow and once you start modeling you often reduce the number of options you are considering. Doing that too early may set you on the wrong path.)\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/headphones.png)\n\n### CAD is a means to an end\n\nThe CAD tool you choose is often interchangeable since the final output is something like a PDF (machining drawing or laser cutter) or an STL file (3D printer).\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/What-is-a-STL-File.gif)\n\n### CAD is Hierarchical\n\nThere are many hierarchical relationships you will encounter in CAD. You often need to create reference geometry before you create functional geometry. A few of the key hierarchies include:\n\nMake a **Plane** or **Surface** and then use it to draw a **Sketch**\n\nUse your **Sketch** to create a **Feature** (like a cut or an extrusion)\n\nCreate **Parts** and then put them together into an **Assembly**\n\nCreate and accurately dimension **Parts** or **Assembly** and then add them to a **Drawing**\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/Plane-1024x546.png)\n\n### CAD can capture Design Intent", "char_len": 1825, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::61", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 61, "text": "extrusion)\n\nCreate **Parts** and then put them together into an **Assembly**\n\nCreate and accurately dimension **Parts** or **Assembly** and then add them to a **Drawing**\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/Plane-1024x546.png)\n\n### CAD can capture Design Intent\n\nA good CAD model and drawing will properly convey design intent, “the intelligence built into the solid model to control the behavior of the part when subjected to changes or alteration” (such as changing a dimension). Here’s one example for how you create and dimension a hole in a block. The hole can be a certain distance from a corner or edge, or it can be in the middle of the face, for example. If the size of the block or the hole changes, the part rebuilds correctly if the design intent has been considered in the definition.\n\nParametric modelers (like SolidWorks and Onshape) capture the intent of a design, including relations, parameters, and model behavior. You can draw lines approximately, and later dimension them exactly. You can also change the sketch and feature dimensions at any time and rebuild the part.\n\nIn this example, one hole is fixed, one is driven by an equation, and the other two are mirrored. As the size of the hinge changes, the holes remain properly spaced along the length and width.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/Design-Intent-223x300.png)\n\n### How will it be made?\n\nAs you design a part and assembly, you can consider how it will be made and create relationships and dimensioning schemes that communicate the manufacturing approach.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/drawing-1024x686.png)\n\n### Initial Setup\n\n* Orient your part the way it makes sense in the world\n* Use the origin and the starting planes\n\nThis sewing machine sits on a table. Consider using the table surface as the Top plane. You typically approach the long side of the sewing machine, so the Front would go through the long dimension of the sewing machine\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/sewing-machine-1024x657.png)\n\n### Start from the ground up", "char_len": 2173, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::62", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 62, "text": "the table surface as the Top plane. You typically approach the long side of the sewing machine, so the Front would go through the long dimension of the sewing machine\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/sewing-machine-1024x657.png)\n\n### Start from the ground up\n\n* Build a strong foundation of reference geometry (Planes, surfaces, curves, axes and sketches)\n* Avoid referencing edges and features that will change frequently when dimensioning or adding relations. Use those initial planes, surfaces, curves and sketches to drive the rest of the design.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/planes.png)\n\n### Minimize Features\n\nUse symmetry and patterning whenever you can\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/mirror.jpg)\n\nRevolve instead of extrude round things\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/12/revolve.png)\n\n### Other stuff\n\n* Know when to start your model over. When you iterate over and over, your model tree gets full of junk. Now that your design is solidified, you should be able to quickly model it from scratch.\n* If you are designing an injection molded part, you will need drafts and rounds (fillets) to help with the molding process. Add these features at the end of your model tree to simplify the modeling.\n\n**Onshape has an amazing learning platform. Look there first to get unstuck or add to your skillset.**\n\nHere’s your OnRamp to OnShape:\n\nOnshape Learning: CAD Basics\n\nSheet metal modeling is awesome for anything you bend or fold including soft goods:\n\nOnshape Learning: Sheet Metal\n\nWant to level up? Surfacing gives you freedom and lets you model organic shapes like car bodies or computer mice:\n\nOnshape Learning: Surfacing\n\nVirtual simulation (FEA, CFD, etc) is one way to “prototype” your design.\n\nOnshape Learning: Simulation\n\nThe best way to learn CAD is by using it for your own project. At our workshops we use the Design Hub Bambu 3D printer to make keychains / backpack hangers you design. Come to a workshop or just design your own.\n\nOur criteria:", "char_len": 2123, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::63", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 63, "text": "is one way to “prototype” your design.\n\nOnshape Learning: Simulation\n\nThe best way to learn CAD is by using it for your own project. At our workshops we use the Design Hub Bambu 3D printer to make keychains / backpack hangers you design. Come to a workshop or just design your own.\n\nOur criteria:\n\n* Your design should have at least two parts so you can think about the relationship between two bodies, figure out how to provide the proper clearance and once you build it, see what is working and what isn’t so you can iterate.\n* Uses this steel cable key ring (provided). The cable is 2 mm in cross-section diameter.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/01/keychain-300x300.jpg)\n\n* Here are a couple examples (fidget and a detachable spork)\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/01/spork-and-fidget-300x132.jpg)\n\n* Once you have your design, download Bambu Studio here. Setup your plate, slice it, and export the plate to a \\*.gcode.3mf file.\n* Put that file on a mini SD card, insert it into the Bambu, go to files, select your file and hit print.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/teaching-a-class-at-the-design-innovation-lab\n\n### **We can support your course as long as it:**\n\n* *Is related to design, innovation, making, engineering;*\n* *Is offered within the UW-Madison College of Engineering. If not, contact us to discuss – we do host some non-engineering courses (maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu);*\n* *Does not conflict with an already scheduled event;*\n* *Does not exceed our capacity. In general about 20 to 25 students is the max at one time, though this varies depending on the activity and the specific space being used;*\n* *Has been scheduled with sufficient notice (one week or more depending on the details).*\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Can I have my class meet in the Wendt or ECB facilities?", "char_len": 1976, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::64", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 64, "text": "space being used;*\n* *Has been scheduled with sufficient notice (one week or more depending on the details).*\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Can I have my class meet in the Wendt or ECB facilities?\n\nYou’re welcome to use the space in Wendt or ECB for a few of your lab sessions subject to availability. However, neither space works well as a *regular* meeting space (e.g. every M-W-F from 1-2:30pm). It’s best to ask your students to use the space on their own time during regular hours (e.g. spread out the use throughout the week).\n\nLet us know your needs and we’ll do our best to help.\n\n***Please email us ahead of time to ensure space and equipment is available: maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu***\n\n## What are ways I could integrate your facilities into my course?\n\nThis depends on the equipment/spaces you’d like to use.\n\nThe Wendt space can handle more spontaneous work, while the equipment in ECB often requires pre-planning and reservations. Please reach out to us with your ideas well in advance so we can help realize your vision for your course.\n\nFor our Wendt space, we recommend the following:\n\n[1] Tailor your labs around our equipment. Provide students freedom and flexibility on particular lab assignments. Encourage them to collaborate with others and be creative using the space. Decrease the structure of the assignment so students may choose to deviate if motivated to do so.\n\n[2] Have your lab sections meet in Wendt once to introduce the students to the equipment. To prepare, we can train you and/or the TAs of your class so they can run the class with minor support from our staff.\n\n[3] Encourage students to come back on their own time to leverage the staff and equipment within the CoE shops. It’s difficult for Wendt to support groups >~ 25 on a regular schedule, though we can accommodate a very large number of students spread out over the entire day and week. If specialized or a significant amount of assistance is needed by your students, please have your TAs hold office hours in Wendt (for your students only). Our student staff can help train your TAs so they know how to use the Wendt equipment and can assist your students as needed.", "char_len": 2263, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::65", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 65, "text": "day and week. If specialized or a significant amount of assistance is needed by your students, please have your TAs hold office hours in Wendt (for your students only). Our student staff can help train your TAs so they know how to use the Wendt equipment and can assist your students as needed.\n\n[4] Leverage the workshops offered within Wendt: Each week we offer workshops on topics that might align directly with the learning objectives of your course (e.g. 3D printing, microcontrollers/electronics… and we’re always open to new ideas); feel free to advertise these events as supplemental instruction for your students. Events/workshops are posted here.\n\n## Does the Design Innovation Lab have instructional content I can use for my class?\n\nYes! We offer instructional content for most of the equipment in the space (e.g. 3D printers, laser cutter, electronics, etc.). These “Learning Modules” may be used by instructors and/or students freely without approval.  Click here for the Canvas page where all the content (except quizzes) is available. Please contact us if you have any questions and/or would like help migrating one or more of these Learning Modules to your Canvas page: maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu.\n\nYou could also encourage and/or require your students to attend our Workshops (link).\n\n## Will the Design Innovation Lab staff teach my lab?\n\n* In short, no; however, our staff will:\n  + Train you and/or your TAs beforehand on the equipment.\n  + Be available in a limited capacity during your lab to ensure you have the equipment needed + oversee safety.\n* You and/or your TA will need to:\n  + Generate the instructional content yourself or use our “Learning Modules” – see above.\n  + Teach the content to your students.\n\nThe instructor and/or TA team will need to come into our facility beforehand to be trained by our shop staff on the relevant equipment. This will allow the instructors/TAs to give demos and be the first source of support. Our staff is available to help, though it’s not possible to provide the complete instructional development and delivery for all of the classes using our space.", "char_len": 2119, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::66", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 66, "text": "trained by our shop staff on the relevant equipment. This will allow the instructors/TAs to give demos and be the first source of support. Our staff is available to help, though it’s not possible to provide the complete instructional development and delivery for all of the classes using our space.\n\n\\*While the instructor and/or TA must handle any instructional activities during set lab times, instructors are welcome to assign modules to their students and have their students come in during Project Support times (listed at the bottom of each equipment page) for assistance from the student staff.\n\n## Can my class reserve space or equipment for my class in the Design Innovation Lab?\n\n***Wendt***\n\nTo use the **laser cutter, waterjet, CNC router,**or to schedule a **tour,**you must make a reservation. All other equipment doesn’t require a reservation, therefore you can just walk in and get started, if the steps above have been completed.\n\nIf you anticipate a large number of your students using the Wendt lab, please contact us so we can coordinate: maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu\n\n***ECB Shops***\n\nPlease contact us well in advance if you need equipment (mills, lathes, welders) reserved for your class. This generally works best early in the semester when there are fewer students affected by the blocked reservations.\n\n## May the students in my class use the equipment in the Design Innovation Lab (without paying a fee and/or obtaining formal training)?\n\nIn Wendt, this is possible only during your lab session when you and/or your TAs are present and leading the instruction. As long as you and/or the TA are leading the instruction, no training or fees are required of your students. However, if your students will come back on their own outside class time, they must have the appropriate training described here.\n\n\\*You and/or your TA must receive prior training from our staff.\n\nIn ECB, students must always have proper training, even if they only plan to observe. Fees are not required if the students are not using the equipment, but if they plan to return on their own, they must have paid the Access fee.\n\n## Can my class have a tour of the Design Innovation Lab during class or lab time?", "char_len": 2206, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::67", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 67, "text": "must always have proper training, even if they only plan to observe. Fees are not required if the students are not using the equipment, but if they plan to return on their own, they must have paid the Access fee.\n\n## Can my class have a tour of the Design Innovation Lab during class or lab time?\n\nIn short, yes! We are happy to provide tours of our facilities. You’re welcome to see Wendt, ECB, or both, depending on your interests. Wendt and ECB are about a 5-minute outdoor walk from each other. Tours cover the equipment used in the space, our collaborative work areas, and resources available to users.\n\nTours of ECB or Wendt typically take 15-20 minutes. If your class is 10 people or fewer, no reservation is needed – just come to the front desk (Wendt) or check-in window (ECB) and ask for a tour – simple as that! If the desk worker has stepped away, please ring the doorbell mounted on the desk and wait for them to return.\n\nIf your class is larger than 10 people and/or you have a question regarding tours, please contact: maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu\n\nIf you want your students to experience more than a short tour, please see the options listed above: Project Support, Workshops, etc.\n\n**We look forward to seeing you at the DI Lab!**\n\nWant to host an event? See info here.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/your-event-at-the-di-lab\n\n#### We host events that are i*nnovation, design, engineering-related or are* *organized by someone affiliated with the College of Engineering.*\n\nThe *Makerspace Team* will ensure the space is ready for the *Organizer* (organizer of the event), but the Organizer must create, setup/tear down, and run their event.\n\nTo request an event, read through the information below and contact Maggie (Primary point of contact) with: your name, affiliation, agenda, catering plans, furniture needs, number of attendees and the date and time of the desired event.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Does the Makerspace provide activities for my event?\n\nThe **Makerspace Team** can help the **Organizer**(s) brainstorm ideas, but ultimately the activities must be created, finalized and run by the **Organizer**.\n\n## Can attendees use the Makerspace equipment?", "char_len": 2291, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::68", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 68, "text": "panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## Does the Makerspace provide activities for my event?\n\nThe **Makerspace Team** can help the **Organizer**(s) brainstorm ideas, but ultimately the activities must be created, finalized and run by the **Organizer**.\n\n## Can attendees use the Makerspace equipment?\n\nYes, if the attendees have the proper training and have paid their fees.\n\nIf the permit+fees are not possible for your attendees, then the Organizer’s team must obtain the proper training ahead of time to run the equipment for all attendees (“demo” the use of the machine for attendees).\n\n## Can Makerspace staff can help with my event?\n\nUsually *one* student staff from the Makerspace Team will be available to help *during* the event. Their primary responsibility is to make sure that the Organizer has what is needed to run their event. The Organizer will likely need to recruit others from within their own organization to help plan and run the event.\n\n## Who will order the materials for my activity / event?\n\nAll supplies and materials must be ordered / purchased by the Organizer. Many common items can be purchased in the Makerspace mini-mart.\n\n## Who will setup and clean-up from my event?\n\nThe Organizer is in charge of setting up and cleaning up after their event. They should work with the Makerspace Operations Manager to ensure specific arrangements are possible. The Makerspace Team will help with setup if staff is available though clean-up should be completely done by the Organizer and their team.\n\nFailure to return a space to its original state following an event may result in the denial of future requests for use of the event.\n\n## Is food allowed in the Makerspace?\n\nYes, in most areas. Though double check with the Operations Manager.\n\n## Who will order the event food?\n\nThe Organizer.\n\n## Can the Makerspace provide a tour at my event?\n\nYes – most likely a student staff can provide a tour during your event! Please book a tour on the tours page.\n\n## Can the organizer pay for materials and fees for attendees?", "char_len": 2033, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::69", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 69, "text": "Operations Manager.\n\n## Who will order the event food?\n\nThe Organizer.\n\n## Can the Makerspace provide a tour at my event?\n\nYes – most likely a student staff can provide a tour during your event! Please book a tour on the tours page.\n\n## Can the organizer pay for materials and fees for attendees?\n\nYes! Please create a payment account with your UW funding string, and a list of attendees (names and netIDs) whose fees you’ll be covering. During the event, attendees can purchase materials from the Makerspace mini-mart. \\*To cover a Lab Membership Fee, the users must be in CoE. If they’re not in CoE, they’ll need an M-Pass.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/virtual-reality\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nLearning Modules (Optional!) Join the course in Canvas.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/VRland-768x402.jpg)\n\nVR Headsets are available to faculty and staff who are part of the College of Engineering. If you are not affiliated with the College of Engineering you must have an M-Pass to reserve the headsets.\n\n* This is only for faculty/staff at UW and not for students or student orgs to check out.\n* Our student staff can provide basic technical support prior to the reservation **but will not be able to run, organize, teach lab lessons, and/or create educational content specific to a course.** Staff with VR expertise may not be present during all scheduled lab times so advanced planning is required. It’s recommended that each course has a lab TA that is fairly knowledgeable with frequent questions and issues with their lesson.\n* Due to construction, the Kohler Visualization Studio is not available this year.\n\nHeadset Request Form\n\n**You are responsible for:**", "char_len": 1727, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::70", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 70, "text": "so advanced planning is required. It’s recommended that each course has a lab TA that is fairly knowledgeable with frequent questions and issues with their lesson.\n* Due to construction, the Kohler Visualization Studio is not available this year.\n\nHeadset Request Form\n\n**You are responsible for:**\n\n* Installing software applications on the headsets before pick-up time. Expect at least 1 week prior to your reservation to load and test needed applications and internet connection in your reserved space. This can take 20+ minutes/headset.\n* Reserving a room for your class. Due to construction, we can not offer the Kohler Visualization Suite at this time. Instructors may reserve a room on campus through EMS. You may request a room on Floor 3 or 4 of Wendt Commons to minimize transport efforts of the headsets.\n* The safe transport and return of all headsets. We can provide suitcases that can accommodate approximately 15 headsets.\n\n***Our staff will:***\n\n* Coordinate schedules with instructors, including time instructors may need to load files to the headsets.\n* Provide technical support to instructors regarding VR headsets, including hardware and firmware updates prior to the reservation.\n* Troubleshoot headsets that are malfunctioning (based on staffing availability and may not occur on-demand).\n* Provide disposable headset covers at the request of instructors; requests must be made in a reasonable timeframe.\n\nWe will do our best to ensure the equipment is ready and working properly for each reservation; however, users must be prepared to use the equipment independently.\n\n## AR/VR Equipment List", "char_len": 1617, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::71", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 71, "text": "disposable headset covers at the request of instructors; requests must be made in a reasonable timeframe.\n\nWe will do our best to ensure the equipment is ready and working properly for each reservation; however, users must be prepared to use the equipment independently.\n\n## AR/VR Equipment List\n\n| Type of Equipment | Make + Model | Qty | Type | Training Requirement |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Microsoft | https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/hololens||Microsoft HoloLens | 2 | AR Headset | Lab Orientation |\n| Oculus | https://www.oculus.com/quest/?locale=en\\_US||Oculus Quest - Obsolete | 20 | all-in-one gaming system built for virtual reality | Lab Orientation |\n| Oculus | https://www.meta.com/quest/products/quest-2/?utm\\_content=a503a32f-da7b-4928-a6cb-0e0df84ca387&utm\\_placement=digitalstorebanner&utm\\_source=www.google.com&utm\\_medium=oculusredirect||Oculus Quest 2 | 10 | all-in-one gaming system built for virtual reality | Lab Orientation |\n| Samsung | https://www.samsung.com/uk/support/mobile-devices/what-is-samsung-gear-360-camera/||Samsung Gear 360 camera (2017) | 1 | 360 degree camera | Lab Orientation |\n\n**## Virtual + Augmented Reality Project Support\n\n| Support Staff | Date | Start Time | End Time |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| #N/A |  |  |  |**\n\n***Check-in during these hours for questions pertaining to design consultation, materials, and best practices.***\n\nE-mail maker-vr@engr.wisc.edu with questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/mills\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nRPM Calculator\n\nIntro to Machining Training\n\n(Required training for *all users*)\n\nIf you need assistance from full-time staff, please set up a Design Consultation. We can dig into your project details if we can plan ahead to set aside time for you.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/eisen-mill-emu-400.png)\n\nWe have several Eisen S-3AII vertical mills available for use. Each has been upgraded with a ProtoTRAK EMX, 2-axis CNC Controller.\n\nTwo additional Eisen S-3AB vertical mills (Mill 5 and Mill 6) are very similar to the S-3A11 but have a larger vertical capacity. If you’re not particularly tall, you might find the S-3A11 mills easier to operate (Mills 1-4, 7 and 8). Just ask us when you come in.", "char_len": 2273, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::72", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 72, "text": "EMX, 2-axis CNC Controller.\n\nTwo additional Eisen S-3AB vertical mills (Mill 5 and Mill 6) are very similar to the S-3A11 but have a larger vertical capacity. If you’re not particularly tall, you might find the S-3A11 mills easier to operate (Mills 1-4, 7 and 8). Just ask us when you come in.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n### Related Videos\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/manual-lathes\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nRPM Calculator\n\nIntro to Machining Training Join the course in Canvas.\n\nIf you need assistance from full-time staff, please set up a Design Consultation. We can dig into your project details if we can plan ahead to set aside time for you.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n### Related Videos\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2023/07/boringpic2-768x512.jpg)\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/Eisen-1740-lathe-400.png)\n\n## Eisen Engine Lathes\n\nWe have three Eisen engine lathes, models 1640G (Lathe 4) and 1740G (Lathes 2 and 3).\n\nLearn more\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/republic-1660-400-sq.png)\n\n## Republic Lagun lathes\n\nWe have two Republic lathes, an RL-16x40 (Lathe 9) and RL-16x60 (Lathe 5).\n\nLearn more\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/sharp-1640LV-400-sq.png)\n\n## sharp 1640LV\n\nWe have has one Sharp 1640 LV lathe (Lathe 8).\n\nLearn more\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/Eisen-collet-lathe-400-.png)\n\n## Eisen CTL-6-18DT\n\nWe have three Eisen Collet lathes available for turning smaller, precision parts (Lathes 1, 6 & 7).\n\nLearn more\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/welding\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nMIG Welding Module Join the course in Canvas. (Prerequisite: Intro to Shop Tools)\n\nTIG Welding Module Join the course in Canvas. (Prerequisite: MIG Welding)", "char_len": 2107, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::73", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 73, "text": "precision parts (Lathes 1, 6 & 7).\n\nLearn more\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/welding\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nMIG Welding Module Join the course in Canvas. (Prerequisite: Intro to Shop Tools)\n\nTIG Welding Module Join the course in Canvas. (Prerequisite: MIG Welding)\n\n* If you need to attend an Intro to Shop Tools, or Welding sessions and none are scheduled, please contact the shop.\n* If you need assistance from full-time staff, please set up Design Consultation. We can dig into your project details if we can plan ahead to set aside time for you.\n\nWe offer both MIG and TIG welding training and have multiple welders available through our Fusion reservation system. Information and technical specs on specific welders can be found below:\n\nMIG 3: Millermatic 252\n\nMIG 4:  Millermatic 350P\n\nMIG 6:  Millermatic 252\n\nMIG 7:  Millermatic 140\n\nMIG 8:  Millermatic 350P\n\nTIG 1:  Dynasty 210\n\nTIG 2: Dynasty 210\n\nTIG 3: Dynasty 210\n\nTIG 4:  Dynasty 200DX\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/IMG_8883-1365x2048-1-768x1152.jpg)\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/sheet-metal-equipment\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Shop Tools Training Required training for *all users*\n\n### Grizzly 48″ Brake (Max thickness):\n\n* 0.194 for aluminum (6 GA)\n* 0.105 for mild steel (12 GA)\n* 0.060 for stainless steel (16GA)\n\n### Grizzly 52″ Shear (Max thickness):\n\n* 0.063 for aluminum (16 GA)\n* 0.048 for mild steel (18 GA)\n* 0.031 for stainless steel (20 GA)\n\n### Pexto 24″ Brake (Max thickness):\n\n* 0.060 for aluminum (16 GA)\n* 0.032″ for steel (18 GA)\n* 0.024″ for stainless steel (24 GA)\n\n### Pexto 37″ Shear (max thickness):\n\n* 0.060″ for aluminum (16 GA)\n* 0.032″ for steel (18 GA)\n* 0.024″ for stainless steel (24 GA)\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/grizzly-brake-768x736.jpg)\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/woodworking-equipment\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Shop Tools Required training for *all users*.\n\nWoodworking Module Required training for *all users*. Prerequisite: Intro to Shop Tools", "char_len": 2149, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::74", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 74, "text": "[page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/woodworking-equipment\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Shop Tools Required training for *all users*.\n\nWoodworking Module Required training for *all users*. Prerequisite: Intro to Shop Tools\n\nWe provide extensive woodworking equipment in both of our locations  for users who have completed the woodshop orientation. See below for a sampling of the equipment available for use!\n\nIf you need to attend an Intro to Shop Tools, or Woodshop orientation session and none are scheduled, please contact the shop.\n\nIf you need assistance from full-time staff, please set up Design Consultation. We can dig into your project details if we can plan ahead to set aside time for you.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/IMG_9268-768x768.jpg)\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/sawstop-ts-400.png)\n\n##\n\nWe have a SawStop table saw with a 50\"+ rip capacity. The safety brake helps make it a workhorse of the shop.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/jet-12-jointer-planer-400sq-1.png)\n\n##\n\nThe ECB Woodshop has a 12\" jointer/planer combination machine with a carbide-insert, helical head.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/powermatic-20-hh-planer-400-sq-1.png)\n\n##\n\nIn addition to the 12\" jointer/planer is a 20\" Powermatic Planer, also with a carbide insert, helical head.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/powermatic-25-dds-1.png)\n\n##\n\nThe ECB Woodshop also has a 25\" Powermatic Drum Sander, with dual heads.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/bandsaws-1.png)\n\n##\n\nThere are a host of bandsaws dedicated to wood and plastic use; some in ECB are dedicated to resawing or detail work.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/delta-hd-shaper-1.png)\n\n##\n\nThe ECB Woodshop also has a Delta HD Shaper. It has both 1/2\" and 3/4\" spindles and a variety of cutters.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/routers-400-1.png)\n\n##", "char_len": 2149, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::75", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 75, "text": "ECB Woodshop also has a Delta HD Shaper. It has both 1/2\" and 3/4\" spindles and a variety of cutters.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/routers-400-1.png)\n\n##\n\nThe ECB + Wendt Woodshop have a number of routers: hand, trim and plunge, as well as a router table.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/PM-mortiser-400-sq-1.png)\n\n##\n\nThe ECB Woodshop is also home to a tilt-table mortiser.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/PM-66-TS-400.png)\n\n##\n\nThe TEAM Lab has more than one table saw, a Powermatic 66 with 500\"+ rip capacity, is used more for sheet goods and plastics.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/3d-scanners\n\n## Get Started:\n\n##\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/03/Artboard-7-copy-3.png)\n\n## **Ensure 3D Scanning the right method for your project!**\n\n* Reverse engineering, measuring, duplicating a part… Sometimes it’s easier and/or faster to just use calipers, make a mold, etc.\n* Parts with deep grooves, small overhangs, tight corners, or anything hard to shine a light on might not be good candidates for 3D scanning, but we will help assess!\n* Understand the resolution you need for your final output\n* Assess your timeline! Post-processing takes a good chunk of time.\n* If the scan file needs to be cleaned or merged, we can show you how to use VxElements, and then you can post-process independently.\n\n##\n\n## Not sure where to start, or need fee-for-service scanning?\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/03/Artboard-7-copy-4.png)Fill out a design consultation form\n\n\\*Staff may recommend this option\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/Scooterscan-2-768x768.jpg)\n\n##\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/03/Artboard-7-copy-3.png)\n\nSend us an email!  We will book the scanner of your choice based on availability.\n\n\\*Consider checking out this user guide if it’s your first time 3D scanning.\n\n##\n\n## Post-Processing + 3D Modeling", "char_len": 2106, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::76", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 76, "text": "us an email!  We will book the scanner of your choice based on availability.\n\n\\*Consider checking out this user guide if it’s your first time 3D scanning.\n\n##\n\n## Post-Processing + 3D Modeling\n\nHere’s a helpful video for post-processing. We can also help you at this point in your process.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2025/03/Artboard-7-copy-4.png)Sign up here for help\n\n## Equipment + Resources\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n### Creaform Handyscan 700\n\n***The Creaform Handyscan 700 is an amazing engineering tool and will give sub-millimeter resolution scans that are professional grade.***\n\n* The Creaform VX Elements software is the best tool for post-processing the mesh. It’s super powerful for analyzing the mesh and adding entities like surfaces, lines, planes, points that can be imported into CAD packages. However, the software is only on a couple powerful Makerspace laptops – you can borrow the laptops while in the Makerspace though you’ll need shop manager approval.\n  + 3D scanning has two parts:\n    - Part 1: Scan, which will likely take 1-2 hours for a small/simple part.\n    - Part 2: Post-processing the scan (mesh) using Creaform’s VX Elements software can take a while depending on your needs. Expect at least 1-2 hours for a simple part. While the VX Elements software for the Creaform scanners is user-friendly, it’s similar to a CAD or FEA package = training is required. We’re here to help train you on the software – it’s a super fun engineering tool to learn.\n  + Preparing your item takes a bit of time and may require spraying it with this powder (which we provide).\n  + You may need to put “target” stickers on your object if it’s large (e.g. larger than a basketball)\n\n### Creality RaptorX\n\nThe RaptorX is a wireless hybrid 3D scanner that combines blue laser and near-infrared (NIR) technology for high-precision scanning. With a range of 5mm to 4,000mm, it captures fine details and large objects with ease, making it ideal for a variety of applications. Its lightweight, portable design ensures versatility and convenience.", "char_len": 2189, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::77", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 77, "text": "scanner that combines blue laser and near-infrared (NIR) technology for high-precision scanning. With a range of 5mm to 4,000mm, it captures fine details and large objects with ease, making it ideal for a variety of applications. Its lightweight, portable design ensures versatility and convenience.\n\n### Additional Resources\n\nLearning Modules (Optional!) Join the course in Canvas.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/cnc-routers\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nMake a Reservation\n\nIntro to Shop Tools Required training for *all users*\n\nLearning Modules (Optional!) Join the course in Canvas.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n### Software\n\n## ***V-Carve***\n\nThe Laguna runs gCode created in V-carve (PC only).\n\nWe have a license that will let you create tool paths at home (before you come in), if you’d like. Otherwise booking your reservation ensures knowledgable staff will be available to help you.\n\nTo do this, access the invitation link (here) and add your email address.  If you already have a V&Co account, you should use the email address associated with your account.\n\nAfter signing up you will receive an email with an invitation lint that you must access in order to complete the membership signup process.\n\nOnce this is done, you will be able to sign into the VCarve Pro Trial software and create projects to cut on our router.\n\n\\*Our version of Vcarve does not post gCode. This is intentional, trained staff will check your tool paths before posting code to run on our machines.\n\n#### V-Carve Tutorials\n\nStart with this “Wing Spar” tutorial here to learn how to cut 2D profiles.\n\nVectric, the maker of Vcarve, provides very good tutorials here.\n\n#### Tool Library for V-Carve\n\nA tool database for V-Carve with preset feeds and speeds for common materials can be found here. Currently this database only has imperial end mills.\n\nTo use this database you will have to have V-Carve installed (see Software above).\n\n-In V-carve go to the Toolpaths panel and select Display Tool Database.\n\n-Delete all existing tools and import the new tool database.\n\n### Materials + Project Support", "char_len": 2202, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::78", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 78, "text": "this database only has imperial end mills.\n\nTo use this database you will have to have V-Carve installed (see Software above).\n\n-In V-carve go to the Toolpaths panel and select Display Tool Database.\n\n-Delete all existing tools and import the new tool database.\n\n### Materials + Project Support\n\nWe sell sheet goods in the Mini-Mart. You may also use your own materials on the CNC routers if approved by staff. If you have questions regarding the machinability of materials, please come to a Project Support Session (below) to contact our CNC router managers.\n\nwpDataTable with provided ID not found!\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/215A0422-768x1152.jpg)\n\n### Laguna CNC Router\n\nYou may create, modify, and cancel reservations in Fusion.\n\n* Laguna  Specs\n  More\n* Laguna  Manual\n  More\n* Reserve the  Laguna!\n  More\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/laguna-cnc.jpg)\n\n**## CNC Routers Project Support\n\n| Support Staff | Date | Start Time | End Time |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| #N/A | 6/10/2026 | 09:00 AM | 05:00 PM |\n| Ethan Dretzka | 6/12/2026 | 09:00 AM | 12:00 PM |**\n\n***Check-in during these hours for questions pertaining to design consultation, materials, and best practices.***\n\nE-mail maker-machineshop@engr.wisc.edu with questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/computers-cameras\n\n## Get Started:\n\n#### *We have lots of documentation equipment, computers, and cameras available for use for all of your photo & video project needs!*\n\nUse Requirements\n\nBeginners Guide (Optional!)\n\nCamera Basics (Optional!)\n\n* The tool/equipment is not to be taken out of the Design Innovation Lab (2nd floor of Wendt Commons).\n* The tool/equipment is for your use only; do not check something out for someone else.  If you need help using the tool feel free to ask our student staff for a quick lesson or refresher.\n* All of the tools/equipment must be returned by the end of the business day, unless otherwise agreed upon.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/computers-cameras-768x977.png)\n\n## Computers, Cameras, and More Equipment List", "char_len": 2168, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::79", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 79, "text": "staff for a quick lesson or refresher.\n* All of the tools/equipment must be returned by the end of the business day, unless otherwise agreed upon.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/computers-cameras-768x977.png)\n\n## Computers, Cameras, and More Equipment List\n\n| Type of Equipment | Make/Model | Qty | Type | Training Requirement |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Bose | Quiet Comfort 25 | 3 | Noise-canceling headphones, comes with case | Lab Orientation |\n| Canon | EOS 5D Mark IV | 1 | Lenses: EF 24-105mm, EF 40mm, EF-S 24mm f/2.8 STM, EF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS II | Lab Orientation |\n| Canon | EOS Rebel T6 | 1 | Lenses: EF 24-105mm, EF 40mm, EF-S 24mm f/2.8 STM, EF-S 18-55mm f/3.5-5.6 IS II | Lab Orientation |\n| FLIR | C2 | 1 | Pocket-sized thermal camera | Lab Orientation |\n| GoPro | Hero 5 Session | 1 | Small portable camera for video or timelapses | Lab Orientation |\n| Insta360 | Pro 2 | 2 | Camera capable of taking 360 degree photo or video for virtual environments | Lab Orientation |\n| VUZE | Plus 360 VR | 1 | Camera capable of taking 360 degree photo or video for virtual environments | Lab Orientation |\n| Zoom Audio Recorder | H5 | 1 | Audio Recorder capable of being mounted to a camera | Lab Orientation |\n| Documentation Station |  | 1 | Mobile set up with hues lighting, a microphone, and attachments for multiple cameras | Lab Orientation |\n| Lenovo |  | 1 | Lenovo Laptop (3d scanning) | Lab Orientation |\n| Alienware Desktop |  | 1 | Alienware Desktop available in room 106 | Lab Orientation |\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/electronics\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nJoin the course in Canvas for learning modules! (Optional)\n\nIf you want to learn more about Microcontrollers, Motors, and soldering check out our Workshops and Training calendar.\n\nReady to go? Head back into the electronics bays and grab what you need to get started. Check out the kits we have available in the Mini-Mart in-person, or listed below.\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/08/215A7249-scaled-1-300x200.jpg)\n\nElectronics in your Class\n\nSee details on using and reserving the electronics bays.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.", "char_len": 2297, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
