| Charlotte Andrews | 6/11/2026 | 02:30 PM | 04:00 PM |\n| Norbusamten Naftel | 6/12/2026 | 11:00 AM | 04:00 PM |**\n\n***Check-in during these hours for questions pertaining to design consultation, materials, and best practices.***\n\nE-mail maker-electronics@engr.wisc.edu with questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/laser-cutters\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Laser Cutting\n\nRequired training for *all users.*", "char_len": 2278, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::82", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 82, "text": "for questions pertaining to design consultation, materials, and best practices.***\n\nE-mail maker-electronics@engr.wisc.edu with questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/equipment/laser-cutters\n\n## Get Started:\n\nUse Requirements\n\nIntro to Laser Cutting\n\nRequired training for *all users.*\n\nReserve a Laser Cutter\n\n**\\***Maximum: 2 hours over a 1-week period\n\nYou may cancel your appointment easily through your Fusion account.\n\nLearning Modules (Optional!) Join the course in Canvas.\n\n* At your reservation time, check-in with staff to log into the laser cutter computer, and help you load the file and material. They will turn the light at the laser green for the duration of your reservation.\n* The user must monitor the cut until finished and press the pause or e-off if anything looks weird (large flames, etc.)\n* Let staff know when finished and staff will log out of the machine.\n* There is a desktop computer dedicated to prepping files for the Laser Cutter by the electronics area. No reservation required.\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n## File Setup Tutorial\n\n## Equipment Specs & Software\n\nUniversal Laser System\\_ ILS9.150 (free-standing platform with a materials processing envelope of 36″ x 24″, max material thickness of 1/2″, see approved materials below).\n\nUniversal Laser System\\_VLS4.75 (free-standing platform with a material processing envelope 18″ x 24″, max material thickness of 1/4″, see approved materials below).\n\n***Software***\n\nYou will need a 2D vector file, which can have the following file types: .dxf, .ai, .pdf\n\nThese files can be generated from multiple software packages including:\n\n* 3D (CAD): Solidworks, Onshape, Fusion 360\n* 2D: Illustrator, Gravit, Inkscape\n\nWe have a computer available for file prep – just look for the file prep station near the laser cutter. CAE login not required.\n\n## ULS Approved/Unapproved Materials\n\nIf you have material that is not listed in the approved or unapproved list, stop in to talk with the Shop Manager. Do not attempt to use materials on laser cutter without staff approval.\n\n## ULS Approved Materials", "char_len": 2183, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::83", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 83, "text": "near the laser cutter. CAE login not required.\n\n## ULS Approved/Unapproved Materials\n\nIf you have material that is not listed in the approved or unapproved list, stop in to talk with the Shop Manager. Do not attempt to use materials on laser cutter without staff approval.\n\n## ULS Approved Materials\n\n| Material | Vector Cut | Vector Engrave | Raster Engrave | | --- | --- | --- | --- | | Fabric - Canvas | OK | OK | OK | | HDF (High Density Fiberboard) | OK | OK | OK | | MDF (Maple veneer) | OK | OK | OK | | Masonite/Hardboard | OK | OK | OK | | Uncoated Paper | OK | OK | OK | | Cardboard/ Corrugated Cardboard | OK - Very flammable | OK | OK | | Chipboard | OK - Very flammable | OK | OK | | Matboard/Museum Board | OK - Leaves burn marks | OK | OK | | Veneered Plywood | OK | OK | OK | | Balsa Wood | OK - Works great | OK | OK | | Basswood | OK - Works great | OK | OK | | Hard Woods | OK - max 1/2\" - 1/4\" or thinner is recommended | OK | OK | | 100% Leather | OK | OK | OK | | Cork | OK - Edges may burn | OK | OK | | Fabric - Muslin | OK - Must be taped down | OK | OK | | Linoleum | OK | OK | OK | | Acrylic | OK | OK | OK | | Mirrored Acrylic (Must be upside down) | OK | OK | OK | | Rowmark Plastics | OK | OK | OK | | Duralar (polyester film) | OK | OK | OK | | Foam Core | OK - Melts the edges | OK | OK | | Foam - EVA | OK - Melts the edges | OK | OK | | Foam - Tool foam | OK - Melts the edges | OK | OK | | Fabric - Ballistic Nylon | OK | NOT OK | NOT OK | | Fabric - Denim | OK | OK | OK | | Fabric - 100% Silk | OK | OK | OK | | Fabric - 100% Wool | OK | OK | OK | | Fabric - 100% Cotton | OK | OK | OK | | Glass (Soda-lime / Lead Crystal) | NOT OK | OK | OK | | Marble | NOT OK | OK | OK | | Unglazed Porcelain Tile | NOT OK | OK | OK | | Ceramic - Laser tile | NOT OK | OK | OK | | Ceramic - Saltillo tile | NOT OK | OK | OK | | Ceramic - Glazed Tile | NOT OK | OK - Vector engraving removes the glaze | OK - Vector rastering removes the glaze | | Anodized Aluminum | NOT OK | OK - Vector engraving removes the anodization | OK - Vector engraving removes the anodization | | Powder Coated Metal | NOT OK | OK | OK | | General Acetal (Delrin) | OK | OK | OK | | Kapton tape | OK | OK | OK | | Tyvek | OK | OK | OK | | PET | OK | Need to Test | Need to test | | Polyurethan Foam |", "char_len": 2300, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::84", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 84, "text": "- Vector engraving removes the anodization | OK - Vector engraving removes the anodization | | Powder Coated Metal | NOT OK | OK | OK | | General Acetal (Delrin) | OK | OK | OK | | Kapton tape | OK | OK | OK | | Tyvek | OK | OK | OK | | PET | OK | Need to Test | Need to test | | Polyurethan Foam |\n\nOK - Melts the edges | OK | OK |\n\n## ULS Unapproved Materials\n\n| Material | Notes |\n| --- | --- |\n| PVC (artificial leather, vinyl) | Emits chlorine while cutting |\n| Rubbers | Tend to melt when laser cut, can catch fire, emits fumes |\n| Food | Any kind of food items are strictly prohibited on laser cutter |\n| Material with Sticky/ Gluey/ Oily/ Unknown coatings | Any material (even from the approved list) with sticky/gluey/oily/unknown coatings are not allowed to use on laser cutter. It can damage the machine parts/can catch fire/can emit fumes |\n| Carbon Fibres | Laser beam can burn the material with noxious gases |\n| Fiberglass | Emits fumes while cutting |\n| Epoxy | Laser beam can burn the material with noxious gases |\n| ABS | Emits cyanide gas and tends to melt while cutting |\n| Teflon (PTFE) | Emits fumes while cutting |\n| Polycarbonate/Lexan | Absorbs the laser, hence is very ineffective at cutting or engraving |\n| Unknown Grades of Plastics | Some plastic grades melt when laser cut, can catch fire, emits fume |\n| PolyPropylene | PolyPropylene Foam catches the fire and melts the material |\n| Delrin | Emits Benzene while cutting |\n| PETG | It is a dirty material to process, giving off white particulates that can damage the machine parts. |\n| HDPE/milk bottle plastic | It catches fire when used on laser cutter. |\n| Foam - Polystyrene Foam | OK - Melts the edges |\n| Epoxy | Epoxy is an aliphatic resin, strongly cross-linked carbon chains. A CO2 laser can't cut it, and the resulting burned mess creates toxic fumes (like cyanide!). Items coated in Epoxy, or cast Epoxy resins must not be used in the laser cutter (see Fiberglass). |\n| Any non-planar or warped materials | The laser carriage can crash into it, damaging the mechanicals of the laser cutter. For any exception to this rule see the shop manager. |\n\n## Useful Links and Guides", "char_len": 2165, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::85", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 85, "text": "in Epoxy, or cast Epoxy resins must not be used in the laser cutter (see Fiberglass). |\n| Any non-planar or warped materials | The laser carriage can crash into it, damaging the mechanicals of the laser cutter. For any exception to this rule see the shop manager. |\n\n## Useful Links and Guides\n\n* Universal Laser Guide\n* Make a Box on the Laser Cutter (here or here)\n  + Make sure to download files from this site as **.svg** files.\n* Making Laser cut designs\n* Accounting for the kerf of the laser\n* Solid Works to Universal Laser\n* Guide to use laser cutter rotary tool\n\n## Materials for the Laser Cutter for Sale\n\n| Material | Material Type | Thickness | Length & Width | Cost |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Hardboard (HDF) | Wood | 1/8 | 18 x 24 | 212,00 |\n| Hardboard (HDF) | Wood | 1/8 | 36 x 24 | 425,00 |\n| Hardboard (HDF) | Wood | 1/4 | 18 x 24 | 345,00 |\n| Hardboard (HDF) | Wood | 1/4 | 36 x 24 | 69,00 |\n| Veneered MDF | Wood | 1/4 | 18x24 | 39,00 |\n| Veneered MDF | Wood | 1/4 | 36x24 | 78,00 |\n| Plywood | Wood | 1/4 | 18 x 24 | 6,00 |\n| Plywood | Wood | 1/4 | 36 x 24 | 12,00 |\n| Foam Core |  | 3/16 | 30 x 20 | 3,00 |\n| Acrylic - Black | Plastic | 1/8 | 18 x 24 | 1.075,00 |\n| Acrylic - White | Plastic | 1/8 | 18 x 24 | 1.075,00 |\n| Acrylic - Clear | Plastic | 1/8 | 18 x 24 | 1.075,00 |\n| Acrylic - Black | Plastic | 1/8 | 36 x 24 | 215,00 |\n| Acrylic - White | Plastic | 1/8 | 36 x 24 | 215,00 |\n| Acrylic - Clear | Plastic | 1/8 | 36 x 24 | 215,00 |\n| Acrylic - Black | Plastic | 1/4 | 18 x 24 | 20,00 |\n| Acrylic - White | Plastic | 1/4 | 18 x 24 | 20,00 |\n| Acrylic - Clear | Plastic | 1/4 | 18 x24 | 1.825,00 |\n| Acrylic - Black | Plastic | 1/4 | 36 x 24 | 40,00 |\n| Acrylic - White | Plastic | 1/4 | 36 x 24 | 40,00 |\n| Acrylic - Clear | Plastic | 1/4 | 36 x 24 | 365,00 |\n| Acrylic - Various Colors | Plastic | 1/8 | 18 x 24 |  |\n| Corrugated Cardboard |  | 5/32 | 24 x 36 | 25,00 |\n\n**## Laser Cutters Project Support\n\n| Support Staff | Date | Start Time | End Time |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| #N/A |  |  |  |**\n\n***Check-in during these hours for questions pertaining to design consultation, materials, and best practices.***\n\nE-mail maker-laser@engr.wisc.edu with questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/storage", "char_len": 2257, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "grainger-design-innovation-lab::86", "doc_slug": "grainger-design-innovation-lab", "chunk_index": 86, "text": "Staff | Date | Start Time | End Time |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| #N/A |  |  |  |**\n\n***Check-in during these hours for questions pertaining to design consultation, materials, and best practices.***\n\nE-mail maker-laser@engr.wisc.edu with questions.\n\n## [page] https://making.engr.wisc.edu/storage\n\n## Head to the checkout window to check out a locker\n\nUse Requirements\n\n![](https://making.engr.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/1329/2024/10/new-lockers-picture-768x512.jpg)\n\n*Lockers may be checked out for the Spring, Summer or Fall terms, but must be cleaned out and returned at the end of each term.*\n\nTo lock your locker, enter a 4-digit combination of your choice, and turn the lock-knob handle to lock/unlock.\n\nOther storage options are very limited, but please reach out to us if you’re in need and we’ll do our best to help (maker-contact@engr.wisc.edu).", "char_len": 863, "id": 10, "source": "Grainger Engineering Design Innovation Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://making.engr.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::0", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram\n\nUW Crest\n\nBluesky\n\n## Cookie Notice\n\nWe use cookies to improve your experience on our website. You agree to the UW–Madison Privacy Notice by continuing to browse without changing your browser settings to block or delete cookies.\n\n**Accept**\n\nSkip to main content\n\n* **Law & Entrepreneurship\n  Clinic**\n\n* About Us\n* Clinic Services\n* Clinic Students\n* Contact Us\n\n# Clinic Services\n\nLearn more about the free legal advice that L&E provides to nascent entrepreneurs and early stage companies. We also offer additional services for established businesses, UW faculty & staff, UW athletes, and rural entrepreneurs.\n\n## Legal Advice for Entrepreneurs\n\n### Form your business.\n\nThe first step for most founders is to select and form a business entity.\n\nWe advise clients on the type of legal entity that best suits their goals by reviewing their funding strategies, ownership models, business plans and tax exposure.\n\nWe then follow up to be sure the correct legal documents are properly filed.\n\n### Shape your intellectual property portfolio.\n\nWe help entrepreneurs add value to their early-stage enterprise by providing a solid footing for their intellectual property (IP) portfolio.\n\nMany of our clients have bold new inventions, brands and content that they want to protect as they bring their ideas to market.  Our students and supervising attorneys routinely analyze the patentability of inventions, advise on trademark rights for brands and review content for copyright protection.\n\n### Set rules of the road for your online presence.\n\nSophisticated websites are at the heart of the business model for many of our clients.", "char_len": 1789, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::1", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "supervising attorneys routinely analyze the patentability of inventions, advise on trademark rights for brands and review content for copyright protection.\n\n### Set rules of the road for your online presence.\n\nSophisticated websites are at the heart of the business model for many of our clients.\n\nWe help our clients draft privacy policies that comply with legal requirements and effectively communicate how they protect sensitive data. We also build terms of service agreements designed to limit the liability of our clients and to ensure a great user experience for their customers and business partners.\n\n### Establish strong relationships with your employees and contractors.\n\nWell-drafted contracts are a great way to build business relationships from a solid foundation.\n\nWe draft employment contracts and independent contractor agreements that:\n\n* Protect the intellectual property and trade secrets of our clients\n* Establish a clear scope of work to be delivered and terms of payment\n* Specify what happens when a contract ends\n\n### Apply for Legal Advice »\n\n## Resources for Entrepreneurs\n\n![video thumbnail for trademarks and copyright](/uwle/resources/media/trademarks_copyright.png)\n\n1. Overview of Trademarks & Copyright\n\n![video thumbnail for entity types](/uwle/resources/media/entity_types.png)\n\n2. Overview of LLCs & Corporations\n\n![video thumbnail for creating a legal entity](/uwle/resources/media/legal_entity.png)\n\n3. Choosing a Lawyer for Your Small Business\n\n![worker classification video thumbnail](/uwle/resources/media/worker_classification.png)\n\n4. Understanding Worker Classifications\n\n### More Resources »\n\n## Additional Services\n\n### Office Hours\n\nWe hold regular office hours to provide general guidance and respond to questions.\n\n* Office Hours »\n\n![L&E Clinic students and staff around a table discussing clients](/uwle/services/media/office_hours.jpg)\n\n### Faculty Consulting\n\nWe provide a number of services free of charge to University of Wisconsin faculty and staff.\n\n* Faculty Consulting »\n\n![students and staff discussing around a table](/uwle/services/media/table_discussion.png)\n\n### Name, Image & Likeness\n\nWe represent University of Wisconsin student athletes to review name, image, and likeness (NIL) contracts free of charge.\n\n* NIL Contract Reviews »", "char_len": 2298, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::2", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "staff.\n\n* Faculty Consulting »\n\n![students and staff discussing around a table](/uwle/services/media/table_discussion.png)\n\n### Name, Image & Likeness\n\nWe represent University of Wisconsin student athletes to review name, image, and likeness (NIL) contracts free of charge.\n\n* NIL Contract Reviews »\n\n![clinical instructor Tami Patel meeting with clinic students at a table](/uwle/services/media/img_6133-2-2.jpg)\n\n### Rural Entrepreneurship Program\n\nThe Rural Entrepreneurship Program is our initiative intended to support entrepreneurship outside of the Madison and Milwaukee areas.\n\n* Rural Entrepreneurship Program »\n\n![clinical instructor Jeffrey Glazer and two clinic students enjoying a clinic meeting](/uwle/services/media/img_6007-2.jpg)\n\n## Follow us\n\nStay up-to-date on us and our clients by following us on social media.\n\n![linkedin logo](/uwle/services/media/linkedin_icon_2.png \"Follow Us on LinkedIn\")![twitter logo](/uwle/services/media/twitter_icon_square.png \"Follow Us on Twitter\")\n\n![Lock Icon](/lawcms/famfamfam/lock.png \"Log in to edit\")\n\n![pixel tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/apply\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram\n\nUW Crest\n\nBluesky\n\n## Cookie Notice\n\nWe use cookies to improve your experience on our website. You agree to the UW–Madison Privacy Notice by continuing to browse without changing your browser settings to block or delete cookies.\n\n**Accept**\n\nSkip to main content\n\n* **Law & Entrepreneurship\n  Clinic**\n\n* About Us\n* Clinic Services\n* Clinic Students\n* Contact Us\n\n# Apply for Legal Advice\n\n## Client Criteria\n\nThe Law & Entrepreneurship (L&E) Clinic is designed to help entrepreneurs develop businesses that create a positive economic impact for the state of Wisconsin.\n\nWe select applicants with a connection to Wisconsin who would otherwise be unlikely to obtain qualified legal advice. This usually means the applicant has not received a significant round of outside funding or financing from investors. We are also interested in whether the work requested presents an interesting educational opportunity for our students.", "char_len": 2287, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::3", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 3, "text": "would otherwise be unlikely to obtain qualified legal advice. This usually means the applicant has not received a significant round of outside funding or financing from investors. We are also interested in whether the work requested presents an interesting educational opportunity for our students.\n\n## Application Process\n\n1. Fill out the \"Request Legal Advice\" form.\n2. We will contact you to schedule an initial screening interview. Screening interviews typically occur weekly.\n3. After the screening interview, we will let you know whether our services are a good fit for your legal needs.\n\n## Request Legal Advice\n\n## Disclaimers\n\nSending an email to us or submitting this form does not create an attorney-client relationship, and any information you include will not necessarily be treated as privileged or confidential. You should not send sensitive or confidential information to this email address or using this form.\n\nThe information provided in your application and subsequent surveys and questionnaires may be used for quality improvement of the services provided by the Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic. We may use the information gathered from you in the course of your application and subsequent services to learn how we can be more effective. We will never publish any personally identifiable information, and we will take all reasonable efforts to ensure that your identity is not ascertainable from the information that may be published. In the course of gathering information, we will indicate information which is minimally required for providing services; you are under no obligation to provide additional information. We endeavor to provide the best services we can, and any information and feedback that you can provide will help to make us better.\n\n### Issues Not Handled by the L&E Clinic\n\n* Litigation/disputes (or situations where litigation appears likely)\n* Pure tax advice\n* International law\n\n![Lock Icon](/lawcms/famfamfam/lock.png \"Log in to edit\")\n\n![pixel tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/office-hours.html\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram", "char_len": 2291, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::4", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 4, "text": "for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/office-hours.html\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram\n\nUW Crest\n\nBluesky\n\n## Cookie Notice\n\nWe use cookies to improve your experience on our website. You agree to the UW–Madison Privacy Notice by continuing to browse without changing your browser settings to block or delete cookies.\n\n**Accept**\n\nSkip to main content\n\n* **Law & Entrepreneurship\n  Clinic**\n\n* About Us\n* Clinic Services\n* Clinic Students\n* Contact Us\n\n# L&E Office Hours\n\nIn addition to several other clinic services, the L&E Clinic holds office hours with organizations throughout the entrepreneurial community. Tell us a little bit about yourself and your business through our intake form to sign-up for Office Hours.\n\n## Sign Up for Office Hours\n\n## Rural Entrepreneurs\n\nIf you are outside of the Madison or Milwaukee areas, you can connect with us through our Rural Entrepreneurship Program's Clinic Connect Office Hours.\n\n### Rural Entrepreneurship Program »\n\n![Lock Icon](/lawcms/famfamfam/lock.png \"Log in to edit\")\n\n![pixel tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/faculty.html\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram\n\nUW Crest\n\nBluesky\n\n## Cookie Notice\n\nWe use cookies to improve your experience on our website. You agree to the UW–Madison Privacy Notice by continuing to browse without changing your browser settings to block or delete cookies.\n\n**Accept**\n\nSkip to main content\n\n* **Law & Entrepreneurship\n  Clinic**\n\n* About Us\n* Clinic Services\n* Clinic Students\n* Contact Us\n\n# Faculty Consulting\n\nThe L&E Clinic provides free legal services to UW faculty and staff, specifically with respect to participation in outside activities such as consulting, sitting on advisory boards, conducting seminars and classes, and even founding companies.\n\n## Outside Activities", "char_len": 2193, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::5", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 5, "text": "Us\n\n# Faculty Consulting\n\nThe L&E Clinic provides free legal services to UW faculty and staff, specifically with respect to participation in outside activities such as consulting, sitting on advisory boards, conducting seminars and classes, and even founding companies.\n\n## Outside Activities\n\nOutside activities often arise from Research and Sponsored Programs (RSP) and may originate from the Office of Industrial Partnerships (OIP). These outside activities are permitted by the University provided certain disclosures are made and procedures are followed to ensure that University resources are not being used and University rights are not being given away.\n\nWe can assist clients by analyzing proposed contracts to identify any issues.\n\n## Request Faculty Consulting Services\n\n![Lock Icon](/lawcms/famfamfam/lock.png \"Log in to edit\")\n\n![pixel tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/nil.html\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram\n\nUW Crest\n\nBluesky\n\n## Cookie Notice\n\nWe use cookies to improve your experience on our website. You agree to the UW–Madison Privacy Notice by continuing to browse without changing your browser settings to block or delete cookies.\n\n**Accept**\n\nSkip to main content\n\n* **Law & Entrepreneurship\n  Clinic**\n\n* About Us\n* Clinic Services\n* Clinic Students\n* Contact Us\n\n# Name, Image & Likeness Contracts\n\nThe Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic offers transactional legal services to both off-campus and on-campus entrepreneurs, including students and faculty. Subject to NCAA guidance, applicable NIL policies and state law, student athletes from anywhere in the state of Wisconsin can apply to the clinic for review of their Name, Image and Likeness (NIL) contracts.\n\n## Request NIL Services\n\n![Lock Icon](/lawcms/famfamfam/lock.png \"Log in to edit\")\n\n![pixel tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/rural.html\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram", "char_len": 2292, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::6", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 6, "text": "tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)\n\n## [page] https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/rural.html\n\nSite icons\n\nUniversity logo that links to main university website\n\nfacebook\n\ntwitter\n\nx\n\nyoutube\n\nlinkedin\n\ninstagram\n\nUW Crest\n\nBluesky\n\n## Cookie Notice\n\nWe use cookies to improve your experience on our website. You agree to the UW–Madison Privacy Notice by continuing to browse without changing your browser settings to block or delete cookies.\n\n**Accept**\n\nSkip to main content\n\n* **Law & Entrepreneurship\n  Clinic**\n\n* About Us\n* Clinic Services\n* Clinic Students\n* Contact Us\n\n# Rural Entrepreneurship Program\n\nThe Rural Entrepreneurship Program is an L&E Clinic intiative intended to support entrepreneurship outside of Madison and Milwaukee.\n\n## Program Goals\n\nThe goal of the program is two-fold:\n\n* first and foremost, to support entrepreneurs through direct action and support for policy initiatives that create opportunity for entrepreneurs in rural Wisconsin; and\n* second, to support law students interested in practicing in rural communities.\n\n## Entrepreneur Support\n\nOur program supports entrepreneurs by providing direct legal action and outreach. We do this in two ways: referrals to our services and Clinic Connect office hours. We also support policy initiatives in areas that directly affect rural entrepreneurs including broadband, cooperatives, and access to capital.\n\n### Service Referrals\n\nWe work with community partners to identify entrepreneurs that may need legal support and refer them to the L&E Clinic for free legal advice.\n\n### Apply for Free Legal Advice »\n\n![clinical professor jeffrey glazer and two clinic students enjoying a presentation by another clinic student](/uwle/services/media/img_5971-2.jpg)\n\n### Clinic Connect Office Hours\n\nWe also work with community partners to bring Clinic Connect Office Hours as an additional service to programming that is already occurring in the community.\n\n### Sign up for Clinic Connect Office Hours »\n\n![clinical instructorsand clinic students brainstorming at StartingBlock](/uwle/services/media/037.jpg)\n\n## Student Involvement\n\nFor law students, participating in the Rural Entrepreneurship Program is a unique opportunity.", "char_len": 2284, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic::7", "doc_slug": "law-entrepreneurship-clinic", "chunk_index": 7, "text": "occurring in the community.\n\n### Sign up for Clinic Connect Office Hours »\n\n![clinical instructorsand clinic students brainstorming at StartingBlock](/uwle/services/media/037.jpg)\n\n## Student Involvement\n\nFor law students, participating in the Rural Entrepreneurship Program is a unique opportunity.\n\nFor students interested in working outside of Madison or Milwaukee, working in the program can introduce them to community leaders, lawyers, and entrepreneurs in the communities where they want to practice. In turn, it lets the communities meet our students and see their high calibre work up close. For students interested in public policy, we offer the opportunity to dig in to meaningful issues that directly support rural entrepreneurship.\n\nWhen our students leave UW Law School and go out to practice, they will have a head start.\n\n### Prospective Clinic Students »\n\n![Lock Icon](/lawcms/famfamfam/lock.png \"Log in to edit\")\n\n![pixel tracker for ENGAGE](https://secure.adnxs.com/px?id=1624295&t=2)\n\n![pixel tracker](https://ib.adnxs.com/seg?add=31384504)", "char_len": 1060, "id": 7, "source": "Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic - Services", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://law.wisc.edu/uwle/services/"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::0", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "The founder forcus model is basically say like what if we became such a place an institution that explicitly recognized entrepreneurship as a career path as an objective that people have and we help them achieve that career path and we first start by inviting them to Wisconsin.\n\n>> Hey everyone and welcome back to the Startup Wisconsin podcast.\n\nA show where you can learn about Wisconsin's growing tech scene through stories of startups, founders, investors, and the talented people making it all happen.\n\nMy guest today is John Echart, the Pile Baskin Professor in Business Leadership at the Wisconsin School of Business and special adviser to the chancellor at WMadison for Entrepreneurship.\n\nHe's leading an effort to make the university more founder forward.\n\nJohn's path to this work started right out of high school when he served three years in the army.\n\nThat experience stuck with him.\n\nYou can take a group of individuals from different backgrounds, put them through training and development, and watch them achieve things that many thought were not possible.\n\nHe carried that mindset into academia, co-founding generator, serving as a founder and investor himself, and eventually asking the question, what would Google do if they were running this university and wanted to produce more entrepreneurs?\n\nFinding that answer required data.\n\nHis team surveyed the entire student body and found entrepreneurship happening everywhere, not just in the business school.\n\nHistory, political science, women's studies, engineering, medicine.\n\nThere were thousands of students with product or service ideas that the university didn't even know about.\n\nDid you know that tech transfer as a concept was literally invented at Wisconsin?\n\nBut the founder forward model goes beyond spinning out lab research.\n\nIt treats entrepreneurship as a career path the institution should actively cultivate the same way it does for law or medicine.", "char_len": 1934, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::1", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "even know about.\n\nDid you know that tech transfer as a concept was literally invented at Wisconsin?\n\nBut the founder forward model goes beyond spinning out lab research.\n\nIt treats entrepreneurship as a career path the institution should actively cultivate the same way it does for law or medicine.\n\nWe also talk about why capital constraints have collapsed in recent years due to technology and how the university plans to connect student founders with communities across the state.\n\nAll right, folks, let's get into it.\n\nSo, you've been teaching entrepreneurship at W for a while.\n\nWhat made you want to step into this new role and being a part of this new initiative and actually trying to change how WMadison and the entire institutional ecosystem that it's involved in supports founders?\n\nWhat does that look like?\n\nWell, I think I would say that, you know, to get to this moment and my willingness and actually excitement to jump into this role really is kind of based on several formative experiences.\n\nSo, one is that um right out of high school, I served in the army for three years on active duty.\n\nAnd uh there's many very amazing things about that experience.\n\nBut what I observed was an institution that had a process to take a group of individuals really from a variety of backgrounds and you actually have a bunch of of individuals that can really achieve amazing things on behalf of our off of our nation.\n\nAnd that always stuck with me through the rest of my career that it's really possible to start with a group of individuals that want to work together and achieve a objective.\n\nand you can really train them to do something that many thought wouldn't be possible.\n\nAnother you know experience was my own time uh as an academic studying entrepreneurship and learning how you can use the tools of science and statistics to not only just describe things that are already there but to also create new inventions and new processes to really improve different outcomes you might be pursuing.\n\nAnd really the the use of statistics like the first time you you start to dive through a giant pile of data and try and see what's there, what opportunities might be there.", "char_len": 2180, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::2", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "already there but to also create new inventions and new processes to really improve different outcomes you might be pursuing.\n\nAnd really the the use of statistics like the first time you you start to dive through a giant pile of data and try and see what's there, what opportunities might be there.\n\nWhen it works, it's almost a magical moment >> as to the outcomes that you can you can drive and the positive impact that you can have.\n\nAnd for sure like institutions like like Google have really put that to good force as far as building great businesses and and now it's it's novel idea that they really you can apply data science to business and really have outsized outcomes.\n\nanother is sort of my my time at generator co-founding uh a fantastic institution where really you know very similar to the my experiences in the army you're starting with with a program that's designed to help entrepreneurs achieve the best that they possibly can in the shortest period of time as possible >> really providing them with a very high energy environment concentrated training and support access to people that can help them uh and capital and I really got to go around to state of Wisconsin in the Midwest and start with a bunch of entrepreneurs, cohort after cohort that all they had at the time was was just a slide deck in the early days and watched and participated in and helped them build their businesses in the early stages and watching it happen again and again and again and realized this is not a random thing that just kind of happened >> or happens now and then.\n\nThis is a process that can be applied and developed just like uh my time in in the army.\n\nAnd then I've had my own entrepreneurial experiences as a founder, as an investor, as serving on company boards.\n\nSome companies went sideways, some companies did well, some didn't do so well.\n\nAnd uh really have always ran my professorship with staying one one leg in the applied in practice space to try and pull those two legs two legs together.\n\nPart of my inspiration there comes from the medical school here where we have these amazing physicians that both practice medicine and they're also basic scientists pushing the frontier of our understanding of medicine.", "char_len": 2233, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::3", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 3, "text": "applied in practice space to try and pull those two legs two legs together.\n\nPart of my inspiration there comes from the medical school here where we have these amazing physicians that both practice medicine and they're also basic scientists pushing the frontier of our understanding of medicine.\n\nAnd what makes the magic occur is you have people that are really doing both.\n\nAnd I've always found that as inspiration in my work.\n\nSo when the chancellor knocked on the door and asked me if I would uh take this on, what had happened before that is after my time at generator, I also been working on campus as an academic administrator in the center for entrepreneurship and I started to ask the question like what would Google do >> if they were running this university and they wanted to produce more entrepreneurs?\n\nHow do we get to more entrepreneurs?\n\nHow do we how do we drive positive outcomes?\n\nAnd we had very high demand for the entrepreneurship courses and the entrepreneurship center because we opened it to students from outside the business school.\n\nAnd I was sitting there and just wondering like well how big is this going to get?\n\nSo started systematically measuring entrepreneurship in the student body undergrads grads at all levels at our institution and really came up with some surprising statistics.\n\nThere's lots of economic activity that our university didn't know about, our center didn't know about, took transfer office didn't know about.\n\nSome of these entrepreneurs you knock on their door and you know they were just experimenting with things like students often do.\n\n>> Others you knock on their door and you realized >> this is somebody who's on their way.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\n>> This is their journey.\n\nSo you fast forward uh to the present.\n\nWe built a lab around that that data series and a bunch of other data series that was really focused on better understanding entrepreneurship in the student body and how you might produce more companies using data science and applying it.\n\nAnd uh we really had a lot of information that one could plug into the ask the chancellor came and asked uh of us to um to start think about other ways that our university might do better at at entrepreneurship.\n\nSo all those pieces came together.", "char_len": 2255, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::4", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 4, "text": "more companies using data science and applying it.\n\nAnd uh we really had a lot of information that one could plug into the ask the chancellor came and asked uh of us to um to start think about other ways that our university might do better at at entrepreneurship.\n\nSo all those pieces came together.\n\nAnd then the last thing I would say about this is there is this thing I observed year after year after year on our campus is there are these students that that start to pursue and go down the path of being entrepreneurs and many of them it's part of the learning process and and they get off that train and that's fine.\n\nBut far too many of them not that we shouldn't have lots of them.\n\nI'm saying like many meaning it's not a random thing.\n\nan accidental would pursue a career as an entrepreneur and have phenomenal outcomes become advisers to me help me better understand how to how to teach it better how to become a better entrepreneur investor myself it's not a random thing Jake but it's not concentrated in one place >> the history department it's in political science it's in women's studies it's in business it's in engineering it's in medicine it's everywhere and if you take those people from all those schools and you put them in a room all these entrepreneurs there is a commonality amongst those people camaraderie shared experiences bodies of expertise that I think universities really haven't fully recognized like we do law medicine these different occupations and careers and that's really the opportunity >> yeah that's awesome and I know you guys put together that report and you said so part of the data that you found was like wow there's There's a lot of entrepreneurship and economic activity happening right here within our student body that we just aren't like aren't aware of and supporting.\n\nWas there any other like sets of data that were that you found interesting beyond like hey every basically every department has entrepreneurship happening with students?\n\nWas there anything else that was kind of enlightening to you?\n\nI think another surprise to me and I'm not really quite sure how to think about it, but it's it's something like a fun thing to kind of mold the clay around a little bit is every year we like I mentioned we survey the entire student body.", "char_len": 2294, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::5", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 5, "text": "there anything else that was kind of enlightening to you?\n\nI think another surprise to me and I'm not really quite sure how to think about it, but it's it's something like a fun thing to kind of mold the clay around a little bit is every year we like I mentioned we survey the entire student body.\n\nWe ask them just uh several questions and one of them is like are you a founder?\n\nYes.\n\nNo, I don't know.\n\nAll these questions you can respond with those three choices.\n\nOne of the questions is do you have an idea for a product or service?\n\nIt's about 20% say they do.\n\nAnd sometimes I think about that number and I I think to myself, wow, that's really high.\n\nLike 20%, you know, on our campus that means there are thousands of people that have an idea for product or service.\n\nLike let's get on that, right?\n\nIt's very exciting.\n\n>> Another part of it to me, I'm like, okay, this is actually a differentiator because why doesn't everybody say yes to that question?\n\n>> Like for me, I couldn't imagine not I mean, you know, I'm on an airplane or something looking out the window.\n\nI'm like five ideas are popping in my head about what products or you know some ideas that might be there but there I guess people that aren't like that.\n\nSo already across this population of people there's some folks that are call it like a little maybe a little bit more entrepreneurial than others which is natural.\n\nIt makes sense.\n\nWe already kind of know that.\n\nBut that's a surprising number.\n\nAnd then it just kind of begs the question like there ought to be a system around that.\n\n>> Approach those people.\n\nYou know, some of those people for sure are in basic science labs and they have an idea and they're, you know, our university.\n\nOur labs are at the frontier >> and there's not many labs at the frontier on any given topic.\n\nIt's probably 10 teams in the world that understand what the what some of our labs know.\n\nWe've got somebody in there that just raised their hand and said, \"Yeah, I think I have an idea.\" >> Yeah.\n\nYeah.\n\n>> You know, it's a mind bender a little bit.\n\n>> Yeah.", "char_len": 2081, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::6", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 6, "text": "at the frontier on any given topic.\n\nIt's probably 10 teams in the world that understand what the what some of our labs know.\n\nWe've got somebody in there that just raised their hand and said, \"Yeah, I think I have an idea.\" >> Yeah.\n\nYeah.\n\n>> You know, it's a mind bender a little bit.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nOne thing that was fascinating to me was I I started to learn about some of the like studentled entrepreneurship that was happening just by searching around and I think I don't know if it was through just random Google searching or if it showed up in my LinkedIn feed at one point, but there was a student named Ben.\n\nI can't remember his last name off the top of my head, but he was running >> this probably.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nYep.\n\nThat's his name.\n\nYeah.\n\nHe was running ramp 100 and I just found that he had like the meetup that he'd set up.\n\nHe created like a Luma page and it was just monthly or or bimonthly.\n\nI can't remember the cadence, but I was like, \"This is cool.\n\nThis is what I love it when I can find people that are like so self motivated.\n\nThey're like no one else is doing it, so I'm going to do it.\" And that's like a huge signal of like it's just more evidence of what you guys already gathered in that report of like hey there's activity happening and it there's so much happening that students are just starting to create like their own efforts to like make it more fruitful like their experience there get more out of that experience connect with entrepreneurs and learn from each other and I think that's a beautiful thing and so like it's cool that like now this new initiative is happening you have like the right people in the in the room asking the questions like how would Google do this or how would some other entity do And that matters like the context of how you're framing the questions especially when you're in an institution that's been around for so long and knows a certain set of ways or other departments have done because in a certain way because those career paths are a little more clear and understood and there's the next phase is like hey you go to this institution after us or you go to this this you work for this company as an intern or or whatever that next level is.\n\nBut for entrepreneurship it's like you just let them fly.\n\nyou're like, \"Hey, go fly.", "char_len": 2299, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::7", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 7, "text": "are a little more clear and understood and there's the next phase is like hey you go to this institution after us or you go to this this you work for this company as an intern or or whatever that next level is.\n\nBut for entrepreneurship it's like you just let them fly.\n\nyou're like, \"Hey, go fly.\n\nLike, hopefully you can fly away from here.\" Because they're on their own.\n\nAnd so, it's just kind of a fascinating thing.\n\nBut the fact that that they're taking self initiative to start like a their own product or service idea is pretty cool.\n\nSo, yeah, I kind of want to go into um this next question about like uh the report.\n\nYou talk about this phrase founder forward and there's like tech transfer within university and commercialization with like the research you were talking about because some of those really complex like at the edge of research type stuff like how do you take that to market like what does that look like?\n\nThe researchers aren't entrepreneurs like they're in the weeds focused on like the latest and greatest and that's where they should stay and be but yeah like maybe talk about that that founder forward theme and why it's why you feel like it's different from what other universities may be doing.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nSo I it's a fabulous question and it really takes us back to the past when warfare was formed in 1925 and many people don't don't realize this they know that we have maybe a tech transfer office and that it's it's quite well known and prominent across the United States but technology transfer as a concept was literally invented at Wisconsin >> and I do not know that >> the idea what basically happened is there's a professor Harry Stebach that had come up with a technology technology to irdiate milk in other foods and by doing so increase the vitamin D content of food 