{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::8", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 8, "text": "transfer as a concept was literally invented at Wisconsin >> and I do not know that >> the idea what basically happened is there's a professor Harry Stebach that had come up with a technology technology to irdiate milk in other foods and by doing so increase the vitamin D content of food products.\n\nI think Quaker Oro had approached him and apologies if I don't get the story exactly right but I think this is the correct story an abbreviated one for sure is instead of patenting and profiting from himself directly at the time he decided he wanted university to benefit from the scientific from the profits from his scientific efforts and bounced around for a while and there really wasn't at the time a way to do this and and the university wasn't particularly excited about it and in the end formed Wisconsin alumni research foundation with some enterprising alumni and I think one or two deems and and some other leaders in the state and gave his patent to that institution and there were or the profits from it uh and then that basically became over time the tech transfer organization for the University of Wisconsin Madison and the mindset behind this the basic idea which is still very true today is that on our campus and others across the world and now text transfer is a thing it's an industry there is like tech transfer conference and everything else the basic idea is that in these labs and across these universities, there's amazing sciences being done at the frontier.\n\nAnd in most cases, what's driving what's discovered is scientific curiosity alone.\n\nThere's something we don't know.\n\nWe want to figure this out.\n\nAnd in sometimes what happens is they discover something that's economically valuable.\n\nAnd you disclose this idea as a professor, an inventor to your tech transfer office.\n\nIn our case, the Wisconsin Alumni Research Foundation and kind of the entrepreneurship version of the story is they secure a patent, a company is formed or licensed the patent back from university.\n\nThen you have entrepreneurship as an outcome where the other outcome is licensing.\n\nYou license it to an existing company.\n\nThe same idea which was Harry Sebach's story and we have there's phenomenal stories like at our university that and others where people's lives have been saved.", "char_len": 2291, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::9", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 9, "text": "university.\n\nThen you have entrepreneurship as an outcome where the other outcome is licensing.\n\nYou license it to an existing company.\n\nThe same idea which was Harry Sebach's story and we have there's phenomenal stories like at our university that and others where people's lives have been saved.\n\nyou millions of people have been treated with cancer from technology uh invented on on our campus and this process really starts with an invention in a lab.\n\nNow some labs it's a little different on our campus.\n\nThe inventor actually has an intention to do something commercial as part of their scientific effort but that's not always the case.\n\nIt's not core to the machine.\n\nWe're designed to kind of pick up the accidental and also the purposeful.\n\nOther universities have basically mimicked this.\n\nAnd if you look at how universities manage entrepreneurship at an institutional level today, it's around the research function that there's something discovered and we need to kind of manage this process of how we form companies around it and uh there are some universities that are particularly good at this and others that are that are that are you know like pretty good and so on but it's like a known thing.\n\n>> Okay.\n\nBut if you look at our campus and others, you'll see a tremendous amount amount of incredibly impactful entrepreneurship that isn't part of that story.\n\nThere's somebody that's on our campus and others.\n\nThey're learning things while they're here, computer science, they're learning about different fields, maybe in psychology, and their mind starts to go and they're entrepreneurial.\n\nAnd then they do something with that either as a student after they graduate, maybe 20 to 30 years after they graduate.\n\nBut there's this application of knowledge that leads to an entrepreneur endeavor.\n\nAnd some of these outcomes are tremendous.\n\nLike Epic Systems, for example.\n\nThere's no University of Wisconsin patent ever affiliated with Epic Systems.\n\nBut very much the story of that company's arrival, its creation.\n\nWMadison was part of that through Judy Faulner's experiences while she was here.", "char_len": 2115, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::10", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 10, "text": "some of these outcomes are tremendous.\n\nLike Epic Systems, for example.\n\nThere's no University of Wisconsin patent ever affiliated with Epic Systems.\n\nBut very much the story of that company's arrival, its creation.\n\nWMadison was part of that through Judy Faulner's experiences while she was here.\n\nI wouldn't say that like you know she didn't go through like a W accelerator or something like that but part of the knowledge she acquired while he was while she was here was created some of the seeds for that company and her story is not unique I mean she's a very unique story but like as far as other people starting companies on our campus that aren't using patented technology and if you look at how our universities and others treat that kind of entrepreneurship and kind of manage it so to speak what you'll see is across these institutions all kinds of different programs centers and everything else that are kind of taking a small bite off the apple, but there isn't like a like a a institutionwide approach towards how you would kind of cultivate, manage and approach entrepreneurship outside of the tech transfer kind of industry so to speak or model.\n\nAnd that's really what the report is about.\n\nsays is look if you really think about what's happening here is for this whole thing to work whether it's tech transfer or this other thing it's all about founders it's about enterprising people that want to go down a certain path they're empirically everywhere on the campus we just talked about that that earlier but what outcomes could you achieve if you started thinking about cultivating that population of individuals and helping them be successful just like we do with other occupations marketing professionals, journalists, and everything else.\n\nBut there's a there's a twist to it.\n\nYou can't build a silo.\n\nYou can't create like, you know, the school of entrepreneurship.\n\nYou know, that might be fun to start or something like that.\n\nI wouldn't criticize someone for doing that, but you'd be creating another silo in a system that really needs something that crosscuts everywhere.", "char_len": 2099, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::11", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 11, "text": "can't build a silo.\n\nYou can't create like, you know, the school of entrepreneurship.\n\nYou know, that might be fun to start or something like that.\n\nI wouldn't criticize someone for doing that, but you'd be creating another silo in a system that really needs something that crosscuts everywhere.\n\nAnd so the founder forcus model is basically say like what if we became such a place an institution that explicitly recognized entrepreneurship as a career path as an objective that people have and we help them achieve that career path and we first start by inviting them to Wisconsin that we are building a home for them here in our state and then we'll do everything we possibly can while they're here to help them develop themselves as founders as entrepreneurs and it's a little different than career placement but hey we help them launch whether it's now or later.\n\nAnd it's not just students.\n\nSame thing for faculty.\n\nWe have amazing faculty entrepreneurs on our campus and a strong history of that.\n\nBut we could become a place for those kinds of founders as well.\n\n>> That's the idea behind the founder forward philosophy and it's really a model being created on our campus by entrepreneurs.\n\nalmost everyone involved in this is a founder in in some way and for entrepreneurs for the next generation.\n\n>> Yeah, that's awesome.\n\nThe report kind of also digs into like you know they don't really sugarcoat it.\n\nThey go right into like gatekeeping, risk management, things like that as part of the past culture of the EW system and and I'm sure that's you know real at a lot of other institutions across the country.\n\nSo what does that look like, you know, from a people's perspective?\n\nLike if I'm in a different department on campus, I'm not in like the the business or school of business, but like how would I as a student like be exposed to the idea that I have an idea?\n\nI now know that I can start talking to someone else on campus about this and get support or get access to some kind of accelerator or get access to resources and etc.\n\nand feel like this is a place where I can build my my future through entrepreneurship even though I came for this one thing.\n\nThis is also of interest to me.\n\nWhat does that so what does that look like?", "char_len": 2249, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::12", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 12, "text": "and get support or get access to some kind of accelerator or get access to resources and etc.\n\nand feel like this is a place where I can build my my future through entrepreneurship even though I came for this one thing.\n\nThis is also of interest to me.\n\nWhat does that so what does that look like?\n\nWell, you could almost I think sometimes when people think about a university, they kind of think like this is just like a big company.\n\nThis is what this thing this is like maybe this is a way to like think about how to manage this kind of thing.\n\nAnd you know, rightfully so, companies are designed where there's almost like a like a queen or a king at the top.\n\nAnd there's everyone has to work for somebody in this society.\n\nLike if you're that king or queen, well, there's a board of directors on top of me.\n\nAnd then the share workers are voting for the board of directors.\n\nThere's a whole cycle, right?\n\n>> Yeah.\n\n>> But the idea is that you have a very focused organization around a particular purpose.\n\nAnd if it's right, it grows dramatically.\n\nAnd if it's wrong, like it the whole thing falls apart.\n\nAnd that's the idea of capitalism and and in and like kind of the Shuppeterian renewal that we have in the private sector.\n\nUniversity is a little bit different.\n\nIt's more like a city than it is like a company.\n\n>> It's designed to have that gale of destruction occurring all the time, you know, at the lowest kind of like we're at the frontier where the innovation is happening.\n\nSo in that kind of model like like your question like you know how do we like reach those people and everything else it's sort of more like the tools that you would use if you were engaged in trying to like like get a message across Madison Wisconsin >> or Green Bay or like the state of Wisconsin you're using like tools of like marketing and things like that.\n\nSee that's one one part of it.\n\n>> But we also we are like to some extent more like a corporation in the sense that we do have institutional relationships with with our students and faculty and so on.\n\nAnd you can imagine like embedding in different processes that people engage with when they're registered for classes or so or something.\n\nThere might be some some efforts made to make you know some of these pathways more available to them.", "char_len": 2299, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::13", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 13, "text": "with with our students and faculty and so on.\n\nAnd you can imagine like embedding in different processes that people engage with when they're registered for classes or so or something.\n\nThere might be some some efforts made to make you know some of these pathways more available to them.\n\nM >> and that's the thinking that the path we're going down is like what adjustments would you make to core systems in an institution to help people who want to pursue and go down the path of entrepreneurship in a way that's very compatible with the core ideas of an academic institution which is about exploration scientific discovery.\n\nNo one's really forced to go down a path.\n\nYou want them to kind of choose their own path in in their in their journey.\n\nThat's sort of how we're thinking about it now.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nIt makes me think about just even education before college.\n\nIt's I feel like I myself was never really exposed to entrepreneurship.\n\nMy my parents weren't I guess my my mom technically is kind of an entrepreneur as she did like an in-home daycare type stuff, you know, to pay for groceries and all that kind of stuff as we were kids.\n\nBut like, you know, my dad worked still works at a paper mill.\n\nMy uncle was a mechanic, opened up his own shop.\n\nBut a lot of people just don't really get exposed to, oh, unless their parent or grandparent was a business owner or someone close to them in their life, they don't really know like that's a path I can take or that I have the ability to do so or the permission to do it.\n\nSo I I feel like like you were saying like all these touch points as they first engage with our campus for a tour, they're registering for classes, orientation, whatever those things are.\n\nThere's all these different touch points.\n\nAnd it really makes me think about the state in general like how do we do that from age, you know, eight and up, like really like where people you can start teaching kids and teenagers like this mindset of like, hey, if you have an idea, here's how you should be thinking through that.\n\nAnd like it's actually something you could bring to life somehow.", "char_len": 2113, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
