xible growth capital designed specifically for Wisconsin companies in tech, advanced manufacturing, and aggra business that are ready to scale.\n\nWhat makes us different?\n\nWe're not looking for exits.\n\nWe offer funding structures like revenue-based financing and redeemable equity so you can grow with capital that fits your business model.\n\nAnd beyond the money, our team brings decades of experience in startups, including operations, financing, and more.\n\nWe're a true partner, not just a check.", "char_len": 2298, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::17", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 17, "text": "offer funding structures like revenue-based financing and redeemable equity so you can grow with capital that fits your business model.\n\nAnd beyond the money, our team brings decades of experience in startups, including operations, financing, and more.\n\nWe're a true partner, not just a check.\n\nIf your business has a solid revenue base, a clear growth plan, and Wisconsin roots, Veency Fund wants to hear from you.\n\nHead over to veencyfund.com to learn more and start our conversation today.\n\nVeency Fund, innovative capital for lasting growth.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nAre there strategies around like your alumni network and like as far as like if a student has a really solid idea and they just need like the distribution or the connections that to kind of find that those first customers is that something that you guys are leveraging or is it kind of like not quite that to that phase yet?\n\nIs that I'm just kind of curious if there's thoughts around that.\n\nYeah.\n\nWhat what I would say is when we wrote that report, we came across and when we wrote it, of course, we live here, so we we know some of this is happening already, like just like little bright stars of excellence.\n\n>> And what happens right now is that you'll have entrepreneurial faculty and staff that just have a reputation for being great connectors out in our alumni network and everything else.\n\nAnd amazing things come come from that.\n\nAnd we point to that and to your point we say this really ought to be systematized at a much broader level in a more kind of serious level and we could we know it's worth the effort because look at the outcomes we can point to today that have come from that and that's very much where we're headed.\n\nSo this effort is is regular coordination with the W Madison Foundation Alumni Association to kind of go down that path together.\n\nBut amongst our our alumni and friends of the university, there is just tremendous expertise.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\n>> And there is a real opportunity and a desire on all sides of this to kind of pull that expertise together.\n\nAnd that's for sure what we're going to be doing.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nThat's awesome.\n\nAre there other universities that you've looked at as you did your research of that you found insightful?", "char_len": 2229, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::18", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 18, "text": "And there is a real opportunity and a desire on all sides of this to kind of pull that expertise together.\n\nAnd that's for sure what we're going to be doing.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nThat's awesome.\n\nAre there other universities that you've looked at as you did your research of that you found insightful?\n\nLike, wow, I love the way that they're approaching their programming here or there.\n\nand if there's been case studies that you found and and if you're looking to maybe apply those locally as well.\n\n>> Absolutely.\n\nI there's there's a lot to copy at other places uh schools that are running different kind of programs and initiatives that are particularly exciting and effective.\n\nThere's certainly some in the Big 10, but I'm kind of competitive so I don't want to, >> you know, I get it.\n\n>> But um I'm only joking about that.\n\nBut um uh there are there are really things to copy.\n\nI would say that in some areas UW is by far ahead of other institutions and other areas we're maybe a little behind and we can kind of bring on board some of their their ideas and thinking.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nUm absolutely the report was both inward looking but also the work of the committee really did look across the United States.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nYeah.\n\nBecause, you know, even for me as I look at other other states and other cities, you know, I was in Michigan in December and trying to figure like I asked around at this event.\n\nI was like, \"How do you guys find out about what's going on across the state?\" Like some of you are from Ann Arbor, some of you from Grand Rapids, Traverse City, you know, wherever.", "char_len": 1580, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::19", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 19, "text": "and other cities, you know, I was in Michigan in December and trying to figure like I asked around at this event.\n\nI was like, \"How do you guys find out about what's going on across the state?\" Like some of you are from Ann Arbor, some of you from Grand Rapids, Traverse City, you know, wherever.\n\nAnd they were like, \"Yeah, well, there's this one newsletter, but this is only for the east side of the state, and then there's this other one that's only for Detroit.\" And so you kind of have to and and it made me realize like wow maybe what I'm doing with startup Wisconsin or what we're doing is a little more unique than I realized and and I've kind of been getting more of that feedback like there's not a lot of states that have like a good sense of what's all going on and I'm not perfect and there's a lot I'm probably still missing but we're doing our best to to get better visibility and awareness around what's happening and I think in regards to the things you're doing that's again it's a process like okay wow like we're realizing that people don't know about this or like this this database of people is actually something we could leverage.\n\nLet's figure out what that looks like without without abusing it, right?\n\nIt's like, hey, there's there's has to be intention to the way you approach it.\n\nBut I Yeah, but I think that that's incredible.\n\nYeah.\n\nAnd then as you think about going beyond Madison, like you know, the W system is larger than just Madison.\n\nAre there thoughts on shared learnings there to across different campuses across the state or is it hey right now we're just focused on the Madison efforts?\n\n>> Yeah, I mean so I I would just say in reaction to what you said before is I think I think what you're doing with the podcast is is incredibly important and helpful.", "char_len": 1800, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::20", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 20, "text": "learnings there to across different campuses across the state or is it hey right now we're just focused on the Madison efforts?\n\n>> Yeah, I mean so I I would just say in reaction to what you said before is I think I think what you're doing with the podcast is is incredibly important and helpful.\n\nI found the podcast just like online and look searching for Wisconsin and startups and like this looks interesting and it's given me an opportunity to learn more about other entrepreneurial efforts and endeavors in the state and even people who I know well to hear them talk about all the way through like like their thoughts on entrepreneurship was has been incredibly insightful certainly for me I think uh when you think about kind of the statewide impact this is very much core to what WMadison is supposed to be and one of the things that we it and is for sure one of the things that we we learned during our our process is we interviewed close to 200 individuals across the state, alumni, entrepreneurs, uh, leaders, administrators, faculty members all across the state.\n\nAnd we got the same story again and again and again from the founders that were tied to WMadison that they very much felt that their entrepreneurial efforts was an embodiment of the Wisconsin idea that they took what they learned while they're at the university and other experiences and they were having dramatic positive impact on the state of Wisconsin and in the communities that they live in outside of Wisconsin from their courageous acts of entrepreneurship and and leadership.\n\nAnd those experiences often help them become community leaders as well beyond their beyond their own companies.\n\nAnd we absolutely agree like that's really something that we we felt that this is entrepreneurship is very much closely tied to one of the core values of the institution in our state.\n\nAnd when it comes to like the practical impact of this, here's one of the things that I'll bend your mind with a little bit.\n\nWMadison attracts amazing students from across the world in our state to come to Madison for an education.\n\nAnd while they're here, we actually know like we know who they are.\n\nThere are students from Green Bay, Lacrosse, Oaklair, Rhinelander.", "char_len": 2229, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::21", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 21, "text": "the things that I'll bend your mind with a little bit.\n\nWMadison attracts amazing students from across the world in our state to come to Madison for an education.\n\nAnd while they're here, we actually know like we know who they are.\n\nThere are students from Green Bay, Lacrosse, Oaklair, Rhinelander.\n\nThey're on our campus and they'll tell us if you ask them, they're on our survey, I want to be a founder or I am a founder.\n\nAnd one of the things that we're after is building systems and connections with those business communities around these students to help these students start companies in those counties in Green Bay, in Lacrosse, Ryan Linder, Ashlin, Wisconsin, across the state.\n\nAnd this is not a fantasy.\n\nThis is something that's completely practical.\n\nWe've seen from the work of generator WDC has fantastic programs.\n\nOther like title town tech in Green Bay is a phenomenal platform very much in in like I'd love it if if one of my suits is financed or one of our suits is financed by Tel Tech that would just be phenomenal outcome.\n\nyou ask about metrics, you know, that that means you're definitely doing a good job there.\n\nAnd this is something that we're that we're pursuing and it's not, you know, right away where there's some systems to put in place before we get that going.\n\nBut we've already had conversations with people in different communities across the state that are kind of ready to receive and help build those connections to help foster company formation across the state from the work that we're doing here as part of this effort.\n\n>> That's awesome.\n\nAnd and there's other instit you know obviously there's like generator there's warf and and I'm thinking about even in in the Green Bay area there's other organizations involved with entrepreneurship or like the new manufacturing alliance things like that.\n\nHow do you guys think about collaborating with all of those entities or maybe new entities that you maybe haven't collaborated in the past?\n\nIs there like efforts there to figure out how do all the webs connect to make sure that we're lifting up our the volume of resources we have but also lifting up that network?", "char_len": 2160, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::22", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 22, "text": "think about collaborating with all of those entities or maybe new entities that you maybe haven't collaborated in the past?\n\nIs there like efforts there to figure out how do all the webs connect to make sure that we're lifting up our the volume of resources we have but also lifting up that network?\n\nHey, we have more contacts here, more contacts there, or is it right now you're just kind of focused on the alumni network that has like like you said naturally expanded over time and has been really really powerful.\n\nI guess how do you how do you think about that?\n\nSo at the core, I think there's tremendous opportunity and there's a lot happening already, which is really amazing.\n\nI'd say like that we're kind of putting together our plan now on how to implement, you know, the report that we put together.\n\nWe just hired our first associate vice chancellor for entrepreneurship at our institution, Los Sheets, and he's just going through now and trying to figure out what to prioritize and everything else as far as, you know, how to have the impact that we're talking about.\n\nthen you'll see like a systematic approach emerge from that that will capture some of these ideas and build these relationships.\n\nI would say between now and then the way I often think about this is very much focus on a particular entrepreneur and what they're trying to do and what they're trying to build to make sure that thing gets built.\n\nAnd what's probably going to be happening first is there'll be some students or faculty uh that are in our system that will benefit from the support of those organizations and that's when you're going to start seeing the first activity and it'll be around something that has a high probability of turning into something because there's that entrepreneur in the middle that's kind of driving it.\n\n>> That's probably the first things you'll see in addition to just like conversations happening, people thought thinking about like how how would we be working uh together.\n\nBut I'd say stay tuned because I' I'd say that the initial feedback we're getting from Lewis is just starting is that what's here to build with is really really amazing.\n\n>> Yeah.", "char_len": 2176, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::23", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 23, "text": "to just like conversations happening, people thought thinking about like how how would we be working uh together.\n\nBut I'd say stay tuned because I' I'd say that the initial feedback we're getting from Lewis is just starting is that what's here to build with is really really amazing.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nI do want to talk about the capital constraint stuff because that tends to be a theme in Wisconsin and a lot of states in the Midwest around there's not enough capital for founders to take their ideas to market and and there's also the narrative like well how do they bootstrap it when they don't really know how to bootstrap it?\n\nThey feel like they need this or that.\n\nHow do you guys think about solving the capital problem or finding other solutions to create capital as a resource outside of maybe the traditional venture models or just things like that?\n\nObviously, there's like, you know, pitch contests on campus where students can get, you know, cash and they can do do what they need to with that.\n\nBut yeah, how are how are you guys thinking about the capital problem and what can the university do about it?\n\nLet's talk about the context of the moment that we're in which around capital because we are sitting in like a fundamental change in human history.\n\nThis part of a trend line that you know you could pick whatever your starting point whether it's like coffee shops and the Lloyds of London and financing people taking boats around the world and hopefully the boats sink they come back with spices and we can you know make money from that and it's a very risky endeavor that people engaged in to this moment.\n\nAnd it used to be that if you had an idea and you wanted needed financing for it, you had to literally go to a king or a queen and ask them for their blessing and some resources from them and even a license to engage in whatever it is that you were trying to do like legal permission >> to engage in that activity.\n\nThat's what the world used to look like.\n\nBetween that time period and now we've had greater greater in access to capital.\n\nAnd what happened, you can pick your point, but around the age of the dawn of venture capital, the requirement that the novel idea also be embodied in a wealthy individual.", "char_len": 2237, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::24", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 24, "text": "what the world used to look like.\n\nBetween that time period and now we've had greater greater in access to capital.\n\nAnd what happened, you can pick your point, but around the age of the dawn of venture capital, the requirement that the novel idea also be embodied in a wealthy individual.\n\nSecondly, and we entered a world where you could be somebody without means and you could approach somebody with capital and you could finance that idea and get it off the ground.\n\nOkay.\n\nNow what's been happening since then based on technological change, information technology primarily and other things is that the costs of getting a business off the ground have been collapsing for many industries while the ability to reach national markets, global consumers and everything else at a lower and lower cost has been increasing and the need to raise capital for any particular idea or the amount of money that you need to raise has been dropping in an Alaskan four or five years has literally collapsed.\n\nThe floor has dropped and you know I say technology more broadly but you should think about like all the SAS services that are out there and software that you can use to do things that before you would be impossible to do so.\n\nOkay.\n\nAnd so uh it is very practical for people to think about entrepreneurship as a career path.\n\nAnd you might say, look, the first couple businesses I might start might be ones that don't require a lot of capital, >> but do have like the potential to have favorable economic returns.\n\nAnd then maybe the next one would be something that I would pursue.\n\nAnd there are some very impressive entrepreneurs in Madison and around that have in our state that have bootstrapped themselves into like quite an impressive outcome without raising capital.\n\nAnd >> I just wanted to to bring that up because the practicality of what we're talking about >> about people building, you know, starting stepping into the economy as as a founder, it is much more feasible today or this week than it was last week and that trend continues.\n\n>> Capital is much less of a constraint than it used to be.\n\nHaving said that, I agree with you 100%.\n\nThere are many great entrepreneurs in Wisconsin that are struggling to raise.", "char_len": 2229, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::25", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 25, "text": "economy as as a founder, it is much more feasible today or this week than it was last week and that trend continues.\n\n>> Capital is much less of a constraint than it used to be.\n\nHaving said that, I agree with you 100%.\n\nThere are many great entrepreneurs in Wisconsin that are struggling to raise.\n\nAnd when I look at what they've accomplished, what they've pulled off, they've done the work.\n\nThey've produced the thing, the object, the widget, or whatever that in another environment would secure the capital to get it to the next stage, and then they're struggling here.\n\nAnd we really need to to find ways to help finance these companies and also get them in some cases higher valuations because that lets them bring in more capital to then be able to finance the next stage.\n\nAnd this is not really like a university thing on its own.\n\nAlthough we do have strategies that we're going to be working on as far as spinning up different forms of act working to get broader access to capital for founders.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\n>> But at a core, I'm not disagreeing with it all.\n\nI'm 100% agreeing with you and there are companies I know quite well that are kind of in that very spot at this moment.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\n>> The theory of the report though is is kind of more like this is that if we increase the quality and the quantity of companies coming off of our campus, we're going to create a situation where if you're an investor in the United States and you're not in Madison, you're missing out.\n\nAnd if we're doing that, then we're going to be bringing investors into the state that then will look at other top opportunities as well.\n\nAnd so the idea is to kind of use this amazing institution that we have, activate itself at another level than it is today.\n\nIt's very high level for entrepreneurship, have increased volume of activity, and if you're an investor, you'd want to be here.\n\nThat's what we're after.\n\nAnd of course that would you know spill over to the rest of this the state as well.\n\nThat's one way this work can help in addition to explicitly like raising funds for veter funds of different forms in and of.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nYeah.", "char_len": 2132, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::26", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 26, "text": "if you're an investor, you'd want to be here.\n\nThat's what we're after.\n\nAnd of course that would you know spill over to the rest of this the state as well.\n\nThat's one way this work can help in addition to explicitly like raising funds for veter funds of different forms in and of.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nYeah.\n\nAnd something I do always think about too with the challenge of getting the funding you need to like or that you think you need to get to the next phase of your business to do whatever it is you're achieve looking to achieve is that the friction of not getting the funding is almost intentional so that you keep working on like hey maybe the business model needs to be adjusted still.\n\nLike that's why like the numbers just don't work yet.\n\nLike you think you know what you're doing but you're not quite there.\n\nAnd so like that friction from not being able to get the capital you're looking for is actually a good thing.\n\nAnd it's just slowly chipping away at this, you know, this thing that you're trying to build and like carve carve away basically.\n\nAnd it's like it helps you kind of just refine your pitch, refine your pitch, refine your model, refine the thing that you're actually offering over over time.\n\nAnd and I and a lot of things too for so many entrepreneurs like the timing of a business going to market can be so relevant for certain technologies where it's like hey at the time when that thing was created like it was incredible but the market wasn't ready for it or whatever that looks like.\n\nLike there were certain pieces that had to be in place before that could be true.\n\nSo while like hey I wish there was more capital all the time.\n\nYeah, that'd be great.\n\nBut at the same time, there's like whether it's the universe or whatever, it's like no, like this isn't right now.\n\nThis isn't it.\n\nAnd you need to like really think through that, reflect on that as a founder and ask why, you know, kind of thing.\n\nSo, >> you raised an important point, which is if you're bootstrapping or you don't have a lot of money available, it's harder to lie to yourself.\n\nYou have to make it work.", "char_len": 2105, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::27", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 27, "text": "it.\n\nAnd you need to like really think through that, reflect on that as a founder and ask why, you know, kind of thing.\n\nSo, >> you raised an important point, which is if you're bootstrapping or you don't have a lot of money available, it's harder to lie to yourself.\n\nYou have to make it work.\n\nIf instead you raised like $20 million for some idea that, you know, well, we'll figure it out along the way, it's quite easy to lie to yourself for a long time that you have a business there when you basically don't, you know, you look and you've got plenty of foosball tables and people are doing stuff and everything else and like, but is there really a strong economic foundation there or not?\n\nVersus the business and you open it up and it's like there's no foosball tables.\n\nthere's a couch with some holes in it and like they're, you know, they're doing what they can to build what they can like they're if they've got revenue and they've got costs and like there's some alignment emerging there towards profitability.\n\nIt's real and they almost have to do that.\n\nAnd I'm very much a fan of when possible.\n\nIt's not always possible, but to really starve a business when it's searching for product market fit, like suffer and until you find it and when you when you find it, if you can, again, not all businesses are able to do that based on the technological requirements and the fundamental costs.\n\nBut if you can, if you go out to raise and you have that, you can show those economics, you'll have a much easier easier time of it than than if you don't have that.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nYeah.", "char_len": 1585, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::28", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 28, "text": "again, not all businesses are able to do that based on the technological requirements and the fundamental costs.\n\nBut if you can, if you go out to raise and you have that, you can show those economics, you'll have a much easier easier time of it than than if you don't have that.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\nYeah.\n\nI'm actually curious for you on a personal level there's like a there is like a bigger why behind you know like the Wisconsin idea and how the university serves the state you know the bigger picture there so for you like what is success look like you know in this role like obviously you have a lot of expertise that you can share and you could be a mentor obviously those numbers can shift but for you like what would that look and feel like for this thing to be successful and why does that matter to you >> I mean there's a couple different ways to think about it but uh one is uh in grad school that I really came to admire the machine we have in our economy kind of our free market system where at the core is a concept called prito optimal exchange and what this is is that when there is a prito optimal exchange the idea is that at least one person gains from the exchange and nobody is worse off >> it's often described as like both parties gain from the exchange But in an extreme, you know, sense of definition is at least one person is better off and and and nobody's worse off.\n\nAnd if you think about what entrepreneurship is fundamentally about, it's about human progress, societal change, improvement in standard of living, improvement in lifespans without forcing people to do something.\n\nInstead, it's all driven by paro optimal exchange.\n\nI come up with an idea and I try and convince you to give me cash for it and in return I give you something you're happier to have than the cash that you just had.\n\nWhether it be like a milkshake, a life-saving drug or whatever.\n\nAnd when an entrepreneur does that with something new, you look at it, you're like, \"Oh, shiny object.\" But I didn't even have that choice before.\n\n>> And now I I can have this thing, that medicine, that computer I use in love or that microphone.\n\nLike now I have this thing like I'm better off than I was before.\n\nWe know you're better off because nobody forced you to do it.", "char_len": 2261, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::29", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 29, "text": "like, \"Oh, shiny object.\" But I didn't even have that choice before.\n\n>> And now I I can have this thing, that medicine, that computer I use in love or that microphone.\n\nLike now I have this thing like I'm better off than I was before.\n\nWe know you're better off because nobody forced you to do it.\n\n>> That's if you think about improving the human condition without conflict and strife at the core, that's what that's about.\n\nThat's what entrepreneurship is about.\n\nIt's also about people overcoming challenges and the fulfillment they get from that and serving others and having employees and and this kind of community aspect of it.\n\nFor sure.\n\nI got caught with that notion as a PhD student kind of starting to fully understand how that works and also looking at the world around me and just seeing that like so many of the things that I enjoy in a daily basis come from the efforts of an entrepreneur.\n\nAlmost every single thing on my body whether it's like my shirt, my pants, my glasses, like they're all coming from companies that like made this stuff for me.\n\n>> That's often, you know, somewhere along the way maybe there was some academic research that came up with some polymer or some like thing as part of it that kind of made that possible.\n\nBut again, like you need the actor, the entrepreneur.\n\nAnd for some reason, I got caught by that bug.\n\nYou can't really explain >> the importance of that.\n\nAnd it's really driven almost every aspect of what I'm what I'm doing, whether it's when I'm in the field myself working on as an entrepreneur or, you know, helping you start generator or something like that or in the classroom.\n\nAnd for me in the end, like I'm I cannot wait till like I'm somewhere up in northern Wisconsin and I stop and open a door and there's the founder of a company that came from this process >> for me that like I cannot wait for that moment.\n\nI know it's going to happen like we're down that path.\n\nThat's when it'll be and also just like you you'll see all these stories and in more and more quality and in in more companies.", "char_len": 2065, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::30", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 30, "text": "there's the founder of a company that came from this process >> for me that like I cannot wait for that moment.\n\nI know it's going to happen like we're down that path.\n\nThat's when it'll be and also just like you you'll see all these stories and in more and more quality and in in more companies.\n\nI think it really is about this tie between what a university is in its connection to the community that it serves and it's very much part of and it has really helped incubate it like when you got to grow up in Wisconsin and I can't believe what the spa state created >> with it institution and how close it is to the citizens of of the state and and kind of the core ideals of of what it's supposed to be and what it can be and what it is.\n\nThat's what drives me and I can't really explain why but that's what I want to see.\n\n>> Yeah, that's beautiful.\n\nI love it.\n\nI love it.\n\nYou know, as we wrap things up here, what is the next, you know, 6 12 months look like for for you in this in this effort and like a I guess a practical sense or a daily, weekly, monthly sense, however you want to talk about it.\n\n>> Well, I would say the most exciting thing has happened as far as like accelerating this work has been the arrival of our new associate vice chancellor for entrepreneurship.\n\nAnd my role in the next 12 months is to support his effort as he learns about our community and our resources that we have available to us and starts to put together like the action plan around the report.\n\nBut very much like as you as we kind of got from this conversation, there are two fundamental pieces that have to both happen.\n\nWe have to have this data science effort continue to help us discover and invent and see things that we'd otherwise be blind to around how we can improve entrepreneurship across the state of Wisconsin.", "char_len": 1820, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::31", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 31, "text": "kind of got from this conversation, there are two fundamental pieces that have to both happen.\n\nWe have to have this data science effort continue to help us discover and invent and see things that we'd otherwise be blind to around how we can improve entrepreneurship across the state of Wisconsin.\n\nand as WMadison in this case as the driver of the focus of this work and you need to have initiatives and programs and systems put in place so that we have more startups in the way that you would with like a business accelerator not so much a scientific effort but like we're going to look across the institution find gaps points of falloff find opportunities to kind of increase the flow of entrepreneurs in the front end and then experiences for them and that's very much the area that Lewis is going to be focusing on as he uh helps expand the impact of entrepreneurship with within W after 12 months.\n\nI'm not sure like I like to go >> Yeah.\n\nI mean totally totally makes sense.\n\nYeah.\n\nRetrospective.\n\nHow'd the year go?\n\nWhere do we want to go from here?\n\nWhere do we continue?\n\nWhere do we stop?\n\netc.\n\nYeah.\n\n>> That's right.\n\nThat's right.\n\nAnd the other part of it is that this work has ebbed and flowed where >> when we did the when the working group was working quite actively there was really broad engagement with many people outside the university.\n\nThen there was about a 9 12-month period where like we kind of had to think about what we were going to do with all this.\n\nThe university had to And then we weren't very then outward focused and engaged at that time as we were kind of letting ourselves come, you know, stew on it in figure out like how what how are we going to go forward?\n\nHow are we going to organize ourselves?\n\nThat all happened.\n\nSounds passive.\n\nIt was a lot of work, but like that we now know where we're going to go.\n\nAnd in the next phase is bringing the outside back in again because key of the work that we're doing is an awareness that entrepreneurship is a rapidly changing field.\n\nhow you do it, how you practice it, who knows what they're doing, who doesn't know what they're doing, like who's got dry powder, who doesn't have dry powder.\n\nThat is like by the month kind of thing.\n\nOkay.\n\n>> Yeah.", "char_len": 2243, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::32", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 32, "text": "we're doing is an awareness that entrepreneurship is a rapidly changing field.\n\nhow you do it, how you practice it, who knows what they're doing, who doesn't know what they're doing, like who's got dry powder, who doesn't have dry powder.\n\nThat is like by the month kind of thing.\n\nOkay.\n\n>> Yeah.\n\n>> And so you need people helping to shape what the university is doing that are in the flow 247.\n\nThey have to be part of what we're what we're creating.\n\nAnd so you'll see much more outward engagement.\n\nIt's already happening uh now that we're in this next phase of the work.\n\nAnd the other part of it is that the the work that we're doing has got to be of the people it's meant to serve >> within the university that has been constant.\n\nSo entrepreneurs within the university have been part of this work all along the way as we're working with with deans and and everything else.\n\nYou'll see that as well, but you will see kind of much more community engagement outside the university like we were doing before.\n\n>> Awesome.\n\nAwesome.\n\nWell, as we wrap things up, you know, just want to thank you for your time and and sharing all the information, sharing your personal thoughts and feelings around this whole effort.\n\nIt was awesome, too.\n\nAnd I'll definitely be sharing in the show notes a link to the report and other other press releases around the efforts here, so uh people don't have to worry about trying trying to dig it up on their own.\n\nBut yeah, I think it's incredible.\n\nIt's great that you're trying to lead with this versus like just trying to It's not a side thing anymore.\n\nlike this is like everything now.\n\nLike this needs to be like in the the front the front of uh what we're doing and uh I think that's that's awesome.\n\nSo for folks that are curious, are they able to reach out to you if they have questions or if they're curious on how to get involved whether they're a founder and would love to mentor with students or are just curious around the programming?\n\nUh what's the best way to get a hold of you like LinkedIn or you know go to the website?\n\nI'm just kind of curious.\n\n>> Well, you can drop my email in the show notes.\n\nThat's completely fine.\n\nyou have that email address.", "char_len": 2208, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin::33", "doc_slug": "podcast-transcripts-jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin", "chunk_index": 33, "text": "love to mentor with students or are just curious around the programming?\n\nUh what's the best way to get a hold of you like LinkedIn or you know go to the website?\n\nI'm just kind of curious.\n\n>> Well, you can drop my email in the show notes.\n\nThat's completely fine.\n\nyou have that email address.\n\nUm, if you also go to entrepreneurship.wist.edu, you can download the report and there's also like I think a contact us box.\n\nUm, we do read those.\n\nUh, so feel free to send us any feedback that you have and we are very much open to different ideas, criticism, reactions.\n\nis like we're trying to get to the right place and the mind of the scientist is that you never really have all the right answers and you're trying to figure out what the answer might be and you're trying to get there as as quickly as you possibly can.\n\nSo, um both cheering us on and also pointing out things where it might be on the wrong path, we're we're certainly all ears.\n\n>> Yeah, it would be awesome to circle back like in a year and just kind of hear how things are going.\n\nSo, hopefully you'd be up for that.\n\nBut yeah, absolutely.\n\nAwesome.\n\nWell, thank you so much.\n\nIt's been an awesome conversation and uh best of luck with everything.\n\n>> All right.\n\nThank you, Jake.\n\n>> Thanks for joining us on the Startup Wisconsin podcast.\n\nWant to support the show?\n\nDon't forget to subscribe and get updates.\n\nIf you're feeling generous, you can share, rate, and review our podcast to help others find us.\n\nAll right, folks.\n\nUntil next time, let's keep moving Wisconsin forward.", "char_len": 1554, "id": 23, "source": "Student founder podcast transcripts", "type": "transcript", "category": "transcript", "url": "file://jon-eckhardt-startup-wisconsin.txt"}
{"chunk_id": "sbdc-uw-madison::0", "doc_slug": "sbdc-uw-madison", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://sbdc.wisc.edu\n\n## **Learning for the Life of Your Business with the Wisconsin SBDC at UW-Madison**\n\nThe Wisconsin Small Business Development Center (SBDC) at UW-Madison provides no-cost consulting and non-credit courses to help businesses from startup through growth. The nationwide SBDCs were established by the Small Business Administration in 1980 with legislation written by WI Senator Gaylord Nelson. We offer affordable training opportunities as you start, manage, and grow your business and no-cost small business consulting by appointment. View the Business Consulting and Classes & Training pages to learn more.\n\n##\n\n## For information about business resources, upcoming programs, and more Join our mailing list\n\n![](https://sbdc.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/399/2023/07/Course-Flow-Road-Map_V3-2-768x994.jpg)\n\nWhether you are thinking about your business idea with First Steps to Starting a Business, brushing up your skills with Introduction to or Intermediate Financial Management, needing a sounding board when you’re stuck on an important decision, or growing your teams’ leadership skills, we have classes and consulting support across the board.\n\nIn our training courses, **START** classes support you during the earliest stages of starting a business, from ideation to business basics and creating a feasible business plan.\n\n**MANAGE** classes help you navigate the changes that arise when you begin to operationalize your work, generally within years 1-4 of operating. These classes include topics like financial management, marketing, and human resources.\n\n**GROW** classes help your aspiring and emerging leaders build practical skills to support your team. Whether you are hiring your own employees or transitioning to a leadership role in a larger organization, these classes help you build your leadership toolbox.\n\nClasses & Training Opportunities\n\n## The SBDC at UW-Madison Helps you START, MANAGE & GROW Your Business!\n\n### Starting a New Business?", "char_len": 1997, "id": 8, "source": "SBDC UW-Madison", "type": "static_html", "category": "business-support", "url": "https://sbdc.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "sbdc-uw-madison::1", "doc_slug": "sbdc-uw-madison", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "Whether you are hiring your own employees or transitioning to a leadership role in a larger organization, these classes help you build your leadership toolbox.\n\nClasses & Training Opportunities\n\n## The SBDC at UW-Madison Helps you START, MANAGE & GROW Your Business!\n\n### Starting a New Business?\n\nSTART classes focus on helping you through the earliest stages of starting a business, from early ideation to business basics and creating a feasible business plan.\n\n* See upcoming  classes\n  More\n\n![](https://sbdc.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/399/2023/01/pexels-rodnae-productions-7309317-600x400.jpg)\n\n### Operationalizing Your Business?\n\nMANAGE classes help you navigate the changes that arise when you begin to operationalize, generally within years 1-4 of starting. Topics include financial management, marketing, and HR.\n\n* See upcoming  classes\n  More\n\n![](https://sbdc.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/399/2023/01/pexels-mikael-blomkvist-6476259-scaled-e1679601606868-600x400.jpg)\n\n### Building Leadership?\n\nWhether you are hiring your own team or transitioning to a leadership role, GROW classes help aspiring and emerging leaders build practical skills for success.\n\n* See upcoming  classes\n  More\n\n![](https://sbdc.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/399/2023/01/25900705292_45da7ea588_c-600x400.jpg)\n\n### In 2025, our team\n\n...worked directly with 680 consulting clients\n...helped clients obtain over $20.2 million in capital\n...helped 29 new businesses start\n...hosted 55 training events, serving over 1,600 participants\n\nHow can we help you grow?\n\n![](https://sbdc.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/399/2024/04/SBDC-Group-Photo_112023_Z72_1101-600x400.jpg)\n\n## Success Stories\n\n> [My consultant] Amy has been amazing. [When I was building our space], she helped me get insight into the banker’s mind. I made the phone calls, but she was there as a sounding board and my cheerleader... On one phone call, I said, it’s been so hard, I literally just need to plan the next seven days, and she helped me set an achievable goal when I couldn’t see the end in sight.\n>\n> —- Brittany Ballweg, Dolphin Swim Academy\n\n![](https://sbdc.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/399/2025/07/20240619_200255-600x400.jpg)\n\n## Wisconsin Art Hub\n\nWisconsin Art Hub supports creativity in Cambridge", "char_len": 2289, "id": 8, "source": "SBDC UW-Madison", "type": "static_html", "category": "business-support", "url": "https://sbdc.wisc.edu/"}
