://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/SV_red-frame-400x400.png)\n\n### Vallabh Sambamurthy\n\nPosition title: Dean, School of Business\n\n![A mature black man with a recessive hairline and mustache](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/EW_red-frame-400x400.png)\n\n### Eric Wilcots\n\nPosition title: Dean, College of Letters and Science\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/nsf-i-corps\n\n## Entrepreneurship Starts Here", "char_len": 2259, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::4", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 4, "text": "mature black man with a recessive hairline and mustache](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/EW_red-frame-400x400.png)\n\n### Eric Wilcots\n\nPosition title: Dean, College of Letters and Science\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/nsf-i-corps\n\n## Entrepreneurship Starts Here\n\nYou don’t have to be a seasoned entrepreneur to engage with the U.S. National Science Foundation Innovation Corps (NSF I-Corps™): all it takes is an idea. Beginning a commercial endeavor may seem daunting, but NSF I-Corps gives you the tools to translate ideas into impact, teaching you the skills you need to find—and then reach—the right customers with a technology they truly want. Developed to complement the NSF I-Corps Great Lakes Regional hub, the regional UW-Madison NSF I-Corps program is designed to help your team develop the skillset and eligibility for success in the National NSF I-Corps program.\n\nI-CORPS Training Opportunities\n\n![NSF I-CORPS HUB GREAT LAKES REGION Logo](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/05/logo-nsf-icorps-new-2025.png)\n\n## BENEFITS OF THE NSF I-CORPS PROGRAM\n\n***Research suggests the number one reason startups fail is because they create a product no one wants.*** NSF I-Corp™ programs help you circumvent this issue. Starting at the regional level, you will gain valuable insights into your target market while learning how to augment your technology to meet customer needs, networking with experienced industrial mentors, and developing a strong foundation, all while establishing credibility for future funding opportunities. Completing the regional or regional I-Corps program is the easiest way to gain the know-how needed to compete for the $50,000 I-Corps Team award, which helps cover expenses related to exploring and understanding your market.\n\n![Silhouette of face with a gear and dotted lines, labeled 'Iterative Development' on the right](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/I-Corps-101_column_iterative-development-900x600.png)", "char_len": 2015, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::5", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 5, "text": "award, which helps cover expenses related to exploring and understanding your market.\n\n![Silhouette of face with a gear and dotted lines, labeled 'Iterative Development' on the right](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/I-Corps-101_column_iterative-development-900x600.png)\n\nBy starting your entrepreneurial journey with I-Corps, you will be able to make improvements to your research-inspired innovation alongside the customers who want it. We call this agile learning. Refining your technology with the end-user in mind helps develop a better and more successful product.\n\n![Illustration of two hands shaking with the words relationship building underneath](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/I-Corps-101_column_relationship-building-900x600.png)\n\nThe I-Corps Program uses Customer Discovery Interviews to gain valuable information about the people who will use your technology. Through exploration, curiosity, and real conversations, these interviews will give you fresh, useful insight into your market.\n\n![Two face silhouettes facing sideways forming a lightbulb, labeled 'Market Insights' on the left](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/I-Corps-101_column_market-insights-900x600.png)\n\nUsing the Lean Startup Method, a strategy created by experienced entrepreneurs, you will be able to develop a customer-oriented perspective to avoid common mistakes made by researchers in early-stage entrepreneurial ventures. This technique helps refocus your perspective, using thorough research to inform your decision-making.\n\n## THE AVENUES TO ENTREPRENEURSHIP\n\nThe National I-Corps Program is designed to help you establish a strong entrepreneurial framework: first, through the initial application and selection process, then, through the Team Award, which grants ***$50,000*** over six months. To become eligible, participants either need to have received NSF funding within the last five years or participate in a local or regional I-Corps program. ***UW’s regional I-Corps program is a great place to begin exploring entrepreneurship: the earlier you engage, the stronger your application will be when you’re ready to compete for the national team award.***\n\n*Want to get involved? To participate in I-Corps:*", "char_len": 2281, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::6", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 6, "text": "a local or regional I-Corps program. ***UW’s regional I-Corps program is a great place to begin exploring entrepreneurship: the earlier you engage, the stronger your application will be when you’re ready to compete for the national team award.***\n\n*Want to get involved? To participate in I-Corps:*\n\n**YOU DON’T NEED:** experience in entrepreneurship, established investors, previous NSF funding, third-party verification, or a fully developed prototype.\n\n**YOU DO NEED:** an idea for a potentially marketable technology, an open mind, a readiness to learn, and, eventually, a team comprised of a technological lead, an entrepreneurial lead, and a mentor (Need help with this? Schedule a meeting with Bonnie!)\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/I-Corps-Pathways-Graphic.png)\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/activate-fellowship\n\nPursuing entrepreneurship can seem daunting, but the Activate Fellowship gives early career researchers with big ideas the tools they need to make it possible. This two-year fellowship supports early stage scientists who are eager to turn their innovative research into viable, market-ready technologies by providing comprehensive financial and professional support and essential resources. Plus, with Activate Anywhere, fellows do not need to relocate to complete fellowship requirements. The Activate Fellowship supports scientists at the outset of their entrepreneurial pursuits to increase the accessibility of these ventures and to turn groundbreaking ideas into reality. Learn how to apply here!\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/ActivateLogoBlackSM2.png)\n\nLearn more on the Activate Website\n\n## THE BENEFITS", "char_len": 1701, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::7", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 7, "text": "of their entrepreneurial pursuits to increase the accessibility of these ventures and to turn groundbreaking ideas into reality. Learn how to apply here!\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/ActivateLogoBlackSM2.png)\n\nLearn more on the Activate Website\n\n## THE BENEFITS\n\nBy providing access to financial resources, a network of mentors and colleagues, and entrepreneurial coaching, the Activate Fellowship is able to achieve their mission to “empower scientists to reinvent the world by bringing their research to market.” As part of the Activate Fellowship, the Activate Anywhere program allows fellows to complete the fellowship requirements wherever they live, so whether fellows are looking to relocate or hoping to stay where they are, Activate can accommodate an array of needs. Plus, Activate Fellows retain all intellectual property rights created throughout the fellowship. Additional fellowship benefits include:\n\n## A Generous Funding Package\n\nActivate Fellows receive a yearly stipend of 100K, plus travel allowance, health insurance, and relocation (if applicable). Additional to the yearly stipend, each project receives $100K in R&D funding and can access $75K+ in flexible capital. By providing funding to fellows, Activate opens the door to pursuing big ideas and makes entrepreneurship accessible.\n\n## Supportive Connections and Coaching\n\nThe Activate Fellowship provides unparalleled access to entrepreneurial education to help fellows develop key skills necessary for startup success. Additionally, they receive custom-built, regular mentorship and have access to a wide network of professionals, helping them develop priorities and make lasting connections.\n\n## Cutting-Edge Research Facilities\n\nFellows gain access to essential research tools, state-of-the-art equipment, advanced facilities, and specialized expertise by collaborating with a dedicated host laboratory. While Activate Anywhere Fellows tap into their established local facilities, they still benefit from Activate's community and unrivaled support.", "char_len": 2063, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::8", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 8, "text": "to essential research tools, state-of-the-art equipment, advanced facilities, and specialized expertise by collaborating with a dedicated host laboratory. While Activate Anywhere Fellows tap into their established local facilities, they still benefit from Activate's community and unrivaled support.\n\n> The Activate Fellowship has been instrumental in my growth as an entrepreneur and the continued progress of my company, SixLine Semiconductor. The fellowship has provided the financial support necessary to focus solely on my company’s development, along with training and classes that have set me up for success. Additionally, the Activate network and community of entrepreneurs, technical experts, and mentors is unparalleled, offering invaluable guidance and support. I highly recommend the Activate Fellowship to anyone interested in transforming their innovative ideas into commercialized products.\n>\n> —Katy Jinkins, Activate Fellow and CEO & Co-Founder of SixLine Semiconductor\n\n## APPLICATION DETAILS\n\nActivate prioritizes candidates who are leaders, have a dedication to diversity and inclusion, and possess deep technical expertise for this fellowship. Exceptional candidates will propose feasible projects to meaningfully affect their field and the world.\n\n**To be eligible, applicants must:**\n\n* Have bachelor’s degree + 4 years post-bachelor’s scientific research, engineering, or technology development experience\n* Be leading the commercial development of a hardware-based technology innovation for the first time, BUT still be in the development at the time of deadline\n* Not have raised more than $2M in debt or equity funding from non-governmental sources\n* Be able to diligently commit 2 years full-time to their proposed project\n* Be legally able to work in the United States and speak English\n\n##\n\n## Applications for the 2025 cohort are due on October 23rd, 2024, at 7pm CT\n\nApply on the Activate Website", "char_len": 1928, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::9", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 9, "text": "equity funding from non-governmental sources\n* Be able to diligently commit 2 years full-time to their proposed project\n* Be legally able to work in the United States and speak English\n\n##\n\n## Applications for the 2025 cohort are due on October 23rd, 2024, at 7pm CT\n\nApply on the Activate Website\n\n![The activate sectors of \"verticals\" include advanced robotics and manufacturing, built environment, carbon management, chemistry and materials, climate, computing, earth resources, electronics and connectivity, energy generation and delivery, energy storage and batteries, food and agriculture, industrial biotechnologies, life sciences, space and aeronautics, transportation and mobility, and water.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/Activate-Verticals-01.png)\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/mentorship\n\n## **Supporting the journey from bold ideas to market-ready solutions.**\n\nThe path from research to a finished product is rarely straightforward. That’s why we connect successful startup leaders with STEM student innovators—to help navigate the twists and turns of commercialization.\n\nAs a mentor, you’ll guide future founders through critical stages of the startup journey—from securing funding and conducting market research to refining their pitch and preparing for launch. Your experience can make the difference between a promising idea and a successful venture.\n\n![Collage of icons representing mentorship](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/hero-mentor-illustration-768x531.png)\n\n## Are you an experienced entrepreneur or researcher with a passion for innovation?\n\nTEO mentors play a pivotal role in nurturing the next generation of innovators by helping them overcome the challenges of commercializing their research. As a mentor, you’ll:\n\n* **Empower emerging entrepreneurs** by applying your professional expertise to help STEM students secure funding, craft market strategies, and shape their product development journey.\n* **Shape the future of STEM innovation** by exploring and influencing cutting-edge technologies.\n* **Expand your network** by connecting with leading researchers, entrepreneurs, and industry experts.\n* **Inspire real-world change** by helping bring transformative ideas to market.", "char_len": 2271, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::10", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 10, "text": "journey.\n* **Shape the future of STEM innovation** by exploring and influencing cutting-edge technologies.\n* **Expand your network** by connecting with leading researchers, entrepreneurs, and industry experts.\n* **Inspire real-world change** by helping bring transformative ideas to market.\n\n![Group of start-up colleagues meeting virtually with their mentor](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/10/iStock-1853096652.jpg)\n\n## About the NSF I-Corps™ Mentor Program\n\nThe NSF I-Corps™ program equips mentors with tools and training to actively support student teams as they explore commercialization pathways.\n\n![Be hands on](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/teo-mentorship-role-graphics_HandsOn-768x512.png)\n\nParticipate in training sessions and mentoring meetings. Use the Socratic method to help teams refine ideas, guide customer interviews, and develop viable strategies.\n\n![teach through experience](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/teo-mentorship-role-graphics_Experience-768x512.png)\n\nShare your professional background and insights to build trust, foster collaboration, and empower teams to navigate challenges with confidence.\n\n![Actively communicate](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/08/teo-mentorship-role-graphics_Communicate-768x512.png)\n\nCommunicate regularly via Slack, video calls, and shared documentation to provide timely and actionable feedback, keeping teams on track.\n\n## Mentor on ***your*** time\n\nChoose the level of involvement in the NSF I-Corps™ mentor program that fits your schedule and experience.\n\n**Local Mentors (3-4 hours/week)**\nSupport teams with business insights, customer discovery, and refining value propositions and ecosystem maps.\n\n**National Mentors (15 hours/week)**Guide teams through the transition from lab to market. Help them understand industry dynamics, manage confirmation bias, and connect with key stakeholders.\n\n## Become a TEO Mentor Today\n\nContribute directly to the growth of future entrepreneurs and help shape the innovation system at UW-Madison and beyond. Fill out the form below to start your mentorship journey.\n\nQuestions? Contact us at teo-director@engr.wisc.edu.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/clean-energy-tech-transfer", "char_len": 2282, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::11", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 11, "text": "Today\n\nContribute directly to the growth of future entrepreneurs and help shape the innovation system at UW-Madison and beyond. Fill out the form below to start your mentorship journey.\n\nQuestions? Contact us at teo-director@engr.wisc.edu.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/clean-energy-tech-transfer\n\n### Funding to Commercialize Clean Energy Technologies\n\nThe U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) is on a mission to curb carbon emissions, implement strategic solutions for environmental stewardship, reduce carbon footprints, and advance a low-carbon, sustainable future. Because technology transfer is critical to achieving this mission, funding opportunities from the DOE Office of Technology Transitions (OTT) are seeking cutting-edge solutions to advance transformative technologies in clean energy.\n\nFind Funding Opportunities\n\n![U.S. Department of Energy Logo](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/logo-assetArtboard-1@2x.png)\n\n![Office of Technology Transitions logo](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/logo-assetArtboard-2@2x.png)\n\n## THE PROGRAMS\n\n#### *“In the history of the Department of Energy (DOE), there has never been a more exciting time for commercialization than now.”*\n\n-Vanessa Z. Chan, Chief Commercialization Officer and Director, Office of Technology Transitions, U.S. Department of Energy\n\n![DOE Technology Commercialization Fund Logo](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/DOE-clean-energy-tech_Artboard-1@2x-900x600.png)\n\n## Commercialize energy and climate resilience technologies\n\nDo you have a promising clean energy or decarbonization solution? The Technology Commercialization Fund, with funding allocated from the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law, supports the demonstration, scaling, and technology transfer of innovative projects.\n\n![DOE American Made Logo](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/02/DOE-clean-energy-tech_Artboard-2@2x-900x600.png)\n\n## Make your innovation part of a sustainable energy future\n\nCompete for technology development prizes and access training, teaming, and mentoring. Designed to accelerate transformative clean energy advancements, the American Made program aims to create connections among entrepreneurs, national, labs, and industry.", "char_len": 2278, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::12", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 12, "text": "part of a sustainable energy future\n\nCompete for technology development prizes and access training, teaming, and mentoring. Designed to accelerate transformative clean energy advancements, the American Made program aims to create connections among entrepreneurs, national, labs, and industry.\n\n## PAST OPPORTUNITIES\n\n### **Re-X Before Recycling Prize**\n\nIndividuals and teams can compete to identify opportunities and advance supply chain innovations in the U.S. that make end-of-use products more valuable by reusing, repairing, refurbishing, remanufacturing, and/or repurposing them.\n\n> Phase 1 entries close March 12, 2024.\n\nLearn More\n\n### **The SOLVE IT Prize**\n\nCommunity change makers can compete to implement innovative clean energy solutions in a way that works best to address their unique needs and challenges through the Solutions for Lasting, Viable Energy Infrastructure Technologies (SOLVE IT) Prize.\n\n> Phase 1 entries close April 12, 2024.\n\nLearn More\n\n### **Power at Sea Prize**\n\nIndividuals can compete to develop a new system, subsystem, or component—powered in part by wave, tidal, ocean current, river, salinity gradients, or thermal gradients—from original conception, to teaming, to a testable stage of initial development.\n\n> Phase 1 entries close July 26, 2024.\n\nLearn More\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/news\n\n# 2025 I-Corps Year in Review\n\n![Young middle eastern man wearing glasses and smiling while looking at a computer someone is holding](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-32-1024x683.png)\n\nBuilding national success in the entrepreneurship space doesn’t happen overnight, but the Technology Entrepreneurship Office’s (TEO’s) steady investment in NSF I-Corps™ program participation has certainly yielded results in 2025. I-Corps is an immersive program that aims to train entrepreneurs, translate technologies, enable positive economic impact, and nurture an innovative ecosystem.\n\nIn the UW System, UW–Madison and TEO have facilitated a rise in overall I-Corps participation in 2025, serving over 500 participants across 16 events, three cohorts, and five National Teams.\n\nRead More\n\n## Innovation Highlights", "char_len": 2195, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::13", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 13, "text": "enable positive economic impact, and nurture an innovative ecosystem.\n\nIn the UW System, UW–Madison and TEO have facilitated a rise in overall I-Corps participation in 2025, serving over 500 participants across 16 events, three cohorts, and five National Teams.\n\nRead More\n\n## Innovation Highlights\n\n* ![Asian woman with long brown hair standing next to an Asian man with short black hair.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/DSC07997-150x150.jpg)\n\n### I-Corps Alum Dr. Jiajie Sui is the Next-Gen Entrepreneur for Next-Gen Batteries\n\nMarch 5, 2026\n* ![white man with a buzz cut and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/oliver-wiener-150x150.png)\n\n### Leadership Spotlight: Oliver Wiener\n\nMarch 2, 2026\n* ![three women pose with the Wisconsin W hand symbol](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/Final_Team_Photo-150x150.jpeg)\n\n### Forget the Superbowl—NFLPA Case Competition Winner Deeksha Singh Talks Success in Entrepreneurship (and Life)\n\nFebruary 12, 2026\n* ![Collage of images showing the close-up of an eye looking at computer code, a plant growing in the soil, 3D printer with metal dust, and two images of computerized cell images](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-33-150x150.png)\n\n### Meet the 2025 UW-Madison NSF I-Corps Teams Awardees\n\nJanuary 30, 2026\n* ![Transcend logo with a photo of two men talking to another person](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/transcend-imageArtboard-1-150x150.png)\n\n### Call for Applications & Sponsors – Transcend UW Pitch Competition 2026\n\nJanuary 28, 2026\n* View all\n  More\n\n## Upcoming Events\n\nFree Virtual Workshop: 2026 UW-Madison NSF I-Corps™ Summer Cohort\n\nJune 25, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - July 30, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\nVirtual\n\nTransform Your Research into Real-World Impact Are you ready to bring your research to life and make a real-world impact? Join our free, six-week virtual workshop, led by the UW-Madison regional NSF I-Corps™ program, and take the …\n\nTake Control of Your Career with a Personalized Roadmap\n\nJuly 20, 2026 @ 5:00 pm - July 22, 2026 @ 7:30 pm", "char_len": 2161, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::14", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 14, "text": "Impact Are you ready to bring your research to life and make a real-world impact? Join our free, six-week virtual workshop, led by the UW-Madison regional NSF I-Corps™ program, and take the …\n\nTake Control of Your Career with a Personalized Roadmap\n\nJuly 20, 2026 @ 5:00 pm - July 22, 2026 @ 7:30 pm\n\nReady to navigate your career path more confidently? Join us for an interactive, in-person workshop led by Andrew L. Shafer, a strategist, business builder, and author of Strategic ROADMAP: An Intentional and Memorable Approach to …\n\nFall 2026 NSF I-Corps™: Materials, Manufacturing & Energy in the Age of AI\n\nOctober 1, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - November 12, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\nVirtual\n\nTranslating Deep Tech Discovery into Economic Benefit A Specialized Virtual NSF I-Corps Cohort | Fall 2026 | Oct 01-Nov 12 | Space is Limited The research landscape is moving into an era that turns frontier …\n\nView all upcoming events\nMore\n\n## Newsletter Archives - The Startup Stream\n\nThis is an accordion element with a series of buttons that open and close related content panels.\n\nExpand allCollapse all\n\n### Startup Steam – Issue #5: Spring 2026\n\n**![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/04/Untitled-1.png)2025 I-Corps Year in Review**\nSee how I-Corps empowers researchers to test ideas in the real world, turning innovation into viable startups through customer discovery and mentorship.\n\n**Ferro MX Innovation Spotlight**\nLearn how Ferro MX is advancing materials innovation, translating cutting-edge research into scalable solutions with real industry impact.\n\n**Deeksha Singh Wins NFLPA Analytics Competition**\nExplore how Singh and her team tackle real-world data challenges, building analytical skills and delivering actionable insights through hands-on competitions.\n\nRead More\n\n### Startup Stream – Issue #4: Fall 2025\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/11/StartupStream-1-300x300.png)\n\n**Director Dan Olszewski’s Business Model Canvas**\nTurn tech ideas into ventures using Dan Olszewski’s nine-part framework from the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship.\n\n**Innovation Stories**\nExplore how Badger entrepreneurs transform bold ideas into lasting impact.", "char_len": 2191, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::15", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 15, "text": "Dan Olszewski’s Business Model Canvas**\nTurn tech ideas into ventures using Dan Olszewski’s nine-part framework from the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship.\n\n**Innovation Stories**\nExplore how Badger entrepreneurs transform bold ideas into lasting impact.\n\n**Transcend UW Launches Strong**\nDiscover a new student-led entrepreneurship organization and learn how they help drive startup success.\n\nRead More\n\n### Startup Stream – Issue #3: Summer 2025\n\n**![person at a whiteboard writing](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/07/Screenshot-2025-07-17-at-10.08.48 AM-300x300.png)Emily Bick’s Entomological Entrepreneurial Journey**\nDiscover how spy movies and a guitar tuner inspired one UW–Madison researcher’s global network of industry interest in insect behavior.\n\n**Startup Successes**\nExplore multiple perspectives on how the university’s vibrant entrepreneurial ecosystem can empower Badgers to turn bold ideas into lasting impact.\n\n**Think Like an Entrepreneur**\nLearn how to identify impact, communicate beyond academia, and move ideas forward with purpose.\n\nRead More\n\n### Startup Stream – Issue #2: Spring 2025\n\n**![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-27-at-2.34.30 PM-300x295.png)Startup Teams Earn National Spotlight**\nExplore how UW researchers gained national recognition through NSF I-Corps training.\n\n**Brand Strategy Tips**\nDiscover smart strategies to shape your startup’s identity and stand out in the market.\n\n**Innovation Meets Investment**\nLearn how startups attract funding by aligning research with real-world impact.\n\nRead More\n\n### Startup Stream – Issue #1: Fall 2024\n\n**![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/Screenshot-2025-03-27-at-2.34.35 PM-300x295.png)Ethical AI in Focus**\nExplore how facial data is used to audit and de-bias recognition systems for safer tech.\n\n**Next-Gen Battery Breakthrough**\nDiscover how a new membrane boosts performance in future energy storage.\n\n**From Idea to Impact**\nMeet TEO founders turning bold ideas into real-world ventures.\n\nRead More\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/contact-us", "char_len": 2130, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::16", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 16, "text": "and de-bias recognition systems for safer tech.\n\n**Next-Gen Battery Breakthrough**\nDiscover how a new membrane boosts performance in future energy storage.\n\n**From Idea to Impact**\nMeet TEO founders turning bold ideas into real-world ventures.\n\nRead More\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/contact-us\n\n![A mature white woman with dark hair and brown eyes](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/BB_red-frameAsset-3-300x300.png)\n\n### Bonnie Bachman\n\nPosition title: TEO Director and I-Corps Program Director\n\nEmail:\nbjbachman@wisc.edu\n\nPhone: (608) 265-4083\n\n## Join our mailing list!\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/free-virtual-workshop-2026-uw-madison-nsf-i-corps-summer-cohort\n\n# Free Virtual Workshop: 2026 UW-Madison NSF I-Corps™ Summer Cohort\n\nVirtual\n June 25, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - July 30, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\n## Transform Your Research into Real-World Impact\n\nAre you ready to bring your research to life and make a real-world impact? Join our **free, six-week virtual workshop,** led by the UW-Madison regional NSF I-Corps™ program, and take the first step toward achieving your entrepreneurial goals. Participants can **earn a micro-grant** and become eligible for larger programs, including the **NSF National I-Corps™ Program ($50k)** and **I-Corps Boost**. Open to eligible members from all higher-education institutes.\n\n### Why Join?\n\nThis non-credit, hands-on course will equip you with essential entrepreneurial tools and insights, including:\n\n* **Lean LaunchPad Methodology**: Master customer discovery, ecosystem mapping, and the Value Proposition Canvas.\n* **Customer-Centric Thinking**: Understand your customers’ pain points from their perspectives.\n* **Strategic Mapping**: Identify customer roles, requirements, and decision-making processes.\n* **Real-World Connections**: Engage with customers, suppliers, and funders to accelerate your innovation journey.\n\n### Who Should Attend?\n\n* **Researchers & Innovators**: Faculty, staff, and students ready to explore the commercial potential of their research.\n* **Aspiring Entrepreneurs**: Individuals seeking entrepreneurial skills and access to a supportive network of mentors and investors.\n\n### Workshop Schedule", "char_len": 2200, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::17", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 17, "text": "Who Should Attend?\n\n* **Researchers & Innovators**: Faculty, staff, and students ready to explore the commercial potential of their research.\n* **Aspiring Entrepreneurs**: Individuals seeking entrepreneurial skills and access to a supportive network of mentors and investors.\n\n### Workshop Schedule\n\n* **Session 1:** June 25 from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* **Session 2:** July 02 from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* **Session 3:** July 09 from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* **Session 4:** July 16 from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* **Catch Up Week (Q&A):** July 23 from 5:00 pm to 6:00 pm (Central Time)\n* **Final Session:** July 30 from 4:45 pm to 7:30 pm (Central Time)\n\n### Don’t Miss Out!\n\nKickstart your entrepreneurial journey with the support of the **local NSF I-Corps program** and the **UW–Madison Technology Entrepreneurship Office**. This is your chance to turn ideas into action.\n\nApply Now\n\n*Applications must be received by midnight on June 10th, 2026. *Questions can be directed to Fadhel Alrabiah,**falrabiah@wisc.edu**.**\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/take-control-of-your-career-with-a-personalized-roadmap\n\n# Take Control of Your Career with a Personalized Roadmap\n\nJuly 20, 2026 @ 5:00 pm - July 22, 2026 @ 7:30 pm\n\n##\n\n## **Ready to navigate your career path more confidently?**\n\nJoin us for an interactive, in-person workshop led by Andrew L. Shafer, a strategist, business builder, and author of *Strategic ROADMAP: An Intentional and Memorable Approach to Achieving Success.* Through engaging discussions and hands-on exercises, you’ll gain the tools to map out your career path and long-term goals confidently.\n\n### **Why Attend?**\n\n* **Identify your strengths** and key areas for growth.\n* **Apply the Strategic ROADMAP framework** to create a career plan tailored to you.\n* **Gain expert insights** from a leader who has advised Fortune 100 executives and startups.\n* **Receive personalized feedback** to refine your career strategy.\n\n### **Session Dates & Times**\n\nMonday to Wednesday, July 20-22 | 5:00 PM – 7:30 PM\n\nFood will be provided during the event.\n\n**Location:**\n\nKurt F. Wendt Commons, Room# 410B (4th floor).\n\n215 N Randall Ave, Madison, WI 53715\n\nParking is available at:\n\nUW-Madison Union South Garage Lot 80", "char_len": 2285, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::18", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 18, "text": "strategy.\n\n### **Session Dates & Times**\n\nMonday to Wednesday, July 20-22 | 5:00 PM – 7:30 PM\n\nFood will be provided during the event.\n\n**Location:**\n\nKurt F. Wendt Commons, Room# 410B (4th floor).\n\n215 N Randall Ave, Madison, WI 53715\n\nParking is available at:\n\nUW-Madison Union South Garage Lot 80\n\n1308-1398 W Dayton St, Madison, WI 53715\n\nDon’t miss this opportunity to gain clarity and direction for your professional future!\n\nRegister Now\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/free-virtual-workshop-2026-uw-madison-nsf-i-corps-fall-cohort\n\n# Fall 2026 NSF I-Corps™: Materials, Manufacturing & Energy in the Age of AI\n\nVirtual\n October 1, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - November 12, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\n## **Translating Deep Tech Discovery into Economic Benefit**\n\n#### **A Specialized Virtual NSF I-Corps Cohort | Fall 2026 | Oct 01-Nov 12 | Space is Limited**\n\nThe research landscape is moving into an era that turns frontier science into economic impact and stronger industrial supply chains. Funding now prioritizes applied, mission‑driven work, rapid commercialization, and market viability. Innovation is the heart of I-Corps: I-Corps courses will help drive your research into innovative solutions and products that improve the world.\n\nIf you’re faculty, a postdoc, or a graduate student ready to commercialize your technology, register for this short course. Accelerate your tech transfer, access translation‑focused funding, and turn your academic insights into market‑ready solutions.\n\n#### **THE CHALLENGE: Pure Lab Research is No Longer Enough**\n\nFederal agencies are systematically restructuring funding frameworks to prioritize **applied, mission-driven outcomes**, speed-to-market, and domestic supply chain integration.\n\nWhether you are a faculty principal investigator (PI) looking to solidify future federal grant competitiveness or a postdoc/PhD student aiming to maximize the real-world impact of your discovery, this elite program can drive your research into broad adoption.\n\n#### **WHAT YOU WILL GAIN**", "char_len": 2012, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::19", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 19, "text": "you are a faculty principal investigator (PI) looking to solidify future federal grant competitiveness or a postdoc/PhD student aiming to maximize the real-world impact of your discovery, this elite program can drive your research into broad adoption.\n\n#### **WHAT YOU WILL GAIN**\n\n* **7 Weeks of Relentlessly Direct Mentorship:** Work directly with deep-tech commercialization experts who cut through bureaucratic red tape and push you to pressure-test your technology against volatile real-world markets.\n* **Up to $3,000 in Micro-Grant Funding:** Immediate non-dilutive capital dedicated strictly to getting out of the lab to conduct real-world customer discovery with industrial buyers, infrastructure developers, grid operators, and supply chain managers\n* **Eligibility for NSF National I-Corps™ (up to $50K) and I-Corps™ Boost.**\n\n#### **ARE YOU ELIGIBLE?**\n\nWe are recruiting teams (comprising faculty, postdocs, graduate students, and/or alumni) leveraging **artificial intelligence****as an enabler** or innovating within physical bottlenecks to solve macro-infrastructure problems. If your research touches any of the following fields, you belong in this cohort:\n\n* **Advanced Materials & Metallurgy:** Novel structural composites, extreme-environment materials, and accelerating the discovery-to-insertion timeline using AI frameworks.\n* **Supply Chain & Manufacturing Resilience:** Automated or advanced manufacturing systems, domestic processing/refining, and mitigating foreign dependencies or critical mineral bottlenecks.\n* **Energy & Power Innovation:** Advanced energy storage, next-generation nuclear tech, grid modernization, and tackling the massive power infrastructure demands of AI data centers, manufacturing, and transportation.\n* **AI-Enabled Hardware & Process Controls:** Any application of AI that advances manufacturing, materials, or energy and power.\n\n#### **WORKSHOP SCHEDULE:**", "char_len": 1913, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::20", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 20, "text": "tech, grid modernization, and tackling the massive power infrastructure demands of AI data centers, manufacturing, and transportation.\n* **AI-Enabled Hardware & Process Controls:** Any application of AI that advances manufacturing, materials, or energy and power.\n\n#### **WORKSHOP SCHEDULE:**\n\n* Session 1 (Orientation): Oct 01,  from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* Self-paced coursework and fundamentals: Oct 2-14\n* Session 2: Oct 15, from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* Session 3: Oct 22, from 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* Session 4: Oct 29, 4:45 pm to 7:00 pm (Central Time)\n* Catch Up Week (Q&A): Nov 5, from 5:00 pm to 6:00 pm (Central Time)\n* Final Session: Nov 12, from 4:45 pm to 7:30 pm (Central Time)\n\n#### **Apply to the Upcoming Cohort—Secure Your Team’s Spot:**\n\nRgister your Interest\n\nApply by September 16th, 2026\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/events\n\n« Previous events Today\n\nVirtual June 25, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - July 30, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\nTransform Your Research into Real-World Impact Are you ready to bring your research to life and make a real-world impact? Join our free, six-week virtual workshop, led by the UW-Madison regional NSF I-Corps™ program, and take the …\n\nJuly 20, 2026 @ 5:00 pm - July 22, 2026 @ 7:30 pm\n\nReady to navigate your career path more confidently? Join us for an interactive, in-person workshop led by Andrew L. Shafer, a strategist, business builder, and author of Strategic ROADMAP: An Intentional and Memorable Approach to …\n\nVirtual October 1, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - November 12, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\nTranslating Deep Tech Discovery into Economic Benefit A Specialized Virtual NSF I-Corps Cohort | Fall 2026 | Oct 01-Nov 12 | Space is Limited The research landscape is moving into an era that turns frontier …\n\n« Previous events\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/03/05/jiajie-sui-feature\n\n![Asian woman with long brown hair standing next to an Asian man with short black hair.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/DSC07997-1200x800.jpg)\n\nUW–Madison is preparing the next generation—of entrepreneurs, and of batteries. “Next-gen” batteries are on the horizon, and NSF I-Corps™ alumna and Early Career Entrepreneur-in-Residence Jiajie Sui is helping to commercialize them.", "char_len": 2248, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::21", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 21, "text": "is preparing the next generation—of entrepreneurs, and of batteries. “Next-gen” batteries are on the horizon, and NSF I-Corps™ alumna and Early Career Entrepreneur-in-Residence Jiajie Sui is helping to commercialize them.\n\nAll rechargeable batteries use anodes and cathodes to facilitate the transfer of power when charging (taking in power) or discharging (putting out power). The anodes in current batteries are made from graphite, which is a cheap and effective material, but higher-capacity, quicker-charging, and even lower-cost batteries use metal anodes instead. Metal also makes the entire battery faster and safer in the long term.\n\nThese metal anodes work best when they are smooth. However, as the battery is used, the energy transfer can cause metallic branches called dendrites to form. Dendrites make the surface of the anode rough and can reduce energy storage and battery lifespan, or even short them out altogether, resulting in inefficiency and risk.\n\nEnter Sui and her PI Xudong Wang, a Grainger Institute for Engineering Professor in the Department of Materials Science and Engineering (MSE). They have developed a porous ferroelectric separator membrane made from a polymer called P(VDF-TrFE). This separator limits dendrite growth—a process the team calls “active dendrite suppression”—and protects rechargeable batteries from the issues such defects cause.\n\nIn suppressing dendrites, the separator reduces battery failure, extends lifespan, prevents short circuits and overheating, and enhances efficiency by over 20%—overall improving longevity, performance, safety, and cost-effectiveness in manufacturing. It also offers a universal, scalable solution for sustainable futures through EVs, renewable energy, and portable devices.\n\n![scientific graphic illustrating anodes on the left side, cathodes on the right, and electrolytes in the middle](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/Dendrite-Illustration_horizontal-e1773161326345.png)\n\n***The diagram above demonstrates the inside of a battery and where the separator membrane sits.***", "char_len": 2082, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::22", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 22, "text": "anodes on the left side, cathodes on the right, and electrolytes in the middle](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/Dendrite-Illustration_horizontal-e1773161326345.png)\n\n***The diagram above demonstrates the inside of a battery and where the separator membrane sits.***\n\nAlthough Sui does not have direct experience with batteries, she knows ferroelectricity and polymers and was able to apply that knowledge to the battery separator. Through her research in amino acid-based functional materials, she explored different applications such as piezoelectricity, proton conductivity, and carbon absorption. Learning about these areas introduced her to many real-world materials challenges that she wanted to help solve. After receiving her master’s degree from University of Washington, Sui was able to embody the Wisconsin Idea and pursue those real-world solutions during her MSE PhD right here at UW–Madison.\n\n“I realized bringing research innovations to the real world was something I really wanted to do, which led me to explore tech transfer and entrepreneurship opportunities on campus,” she said.\n\nShe signed up for the Morgridge Entrepreneurial Bootcamp (MEB) program, investigated practical options, and designed her plan for entrepreneurship after her doctoral studies. Her PI Wang was instrumental in this process.\n\n“Wang is fully supportive and shared his experience of co-founding a tech startup,” Sui said. “He has many patents and the passion to commercialize his technology, but he lacks the right person and time to do it by himself. That’s when we decided to team up and to do something.”\n\nBattery and energy related innovations have substantial market potential, and the separator solves a key problem in advancing that market. After carefully considering patents, commercialization potential, technology readiness level, and their personal research expertise, Sui and Wang landed on the ferroelectric battery separator with the startup FerroMX.", "char_len": 1985, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::23", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 23, "text": "potential, and the separator solves a key problem in advancing that market. After carefully considering patents, commercialization potential, technology readiness level, and their personal research expertise, Sui and Wang landed on the ferroelectric battery separator with the startup FerroMX.\n\nSui and Wang then participated in 2024’s I-Corps cohort with industry mentor Nasser Kutkut. The I-Corps program allowed Sui, now serving as FerroMX’s Entrepreneurial Lead, opportunities to interact with real people and validate the market. She honed product-market fit, explored potential improvements based on customer feedback, and developed communication skills she wouldn’t have in solely a research setting.\n\n“I-Corps is beneficial for both product development and for personal professional growth,” she said.\n\nSince completing the I-Corps program, Sui has been selected as an Early Career Entrepreneur-in-Residence (EEIR) through TEO’s partner office, the newly established Badger Tech Foundry. EEIR is one option for UW–Madison PhDs to forge a pathway from entrepreneurial education like MEB and I-Corps into the commercial market. The program selects promising technologies to provide training and hands-on development for strategic launch.\n\n“I started as an EEIR in November 2025 to continue commercializing FerroMX, including conducting more research to improve the technical readiness for market, more market research and customer interviews, and getting more training as an entrepreneur,” Sui said.\n\nNext steps for Sui and FerroMX include developing a minimum viable product (MVP) and fundraising, with the goal to generate revenue in 2027.\n\n“The dendrite growth problem our technology aims to solve is critical in the market, and it’s one of the reasons holding back advancing next gen batteries. We have demonstrated its impact and performance improvement in real battery systems, and we have the technical expertise to move forward and pivot the technology if needed,” she said.", "char_len": 1988, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::24", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 24, "text": "aims to solve is critical in the market, and it’s one of the reasons holding back advancing next gen batteries. We have demonstrated its impact and performance improvement in real battery systems, and we have the technical expertise to move forward and pivot the technology if needed,” she said.\n\nSui encourages others to sign up for opportunities like MEB and I-Corps. “It’s a great start to explore entrepreneurial journeys or just industrial jobs in general,” she said. Sui is a perfect example of how entrepreneurial training at UW–Madison equips the next generation of founders with the next generation of technologies that can solve real-world issues—just like she aspired to.\n\n• • •\n\nFeatured image: Jiajie Sui (standing), entrepreneurial lead for FerroMX, and professor Xudong Wang (seated), PI and technical lead for the project.\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/03/02/wiener-spotlight\n\n![white man with a buzz cut and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/oliver-wiener.png)\n\nOliver Wiener is an entrepreneur and financier with expertise in the digital realm. He is the Founder and Managing Partner of Kensington Merchant Partners, an investment firm in the evolving financial and technological ecosystem. He was formerly a Portfolio Manager at Standard Investments and a founding partner at BTIG, and is the founder of The Association of Digital Asset Markets. He graduated from UW–Madison with a dual major BA in International Relations and Political Science. He now sits on the Technology Entrepreneurship (TEO) Advisory Board and the College of Letters & Science Board of Visitors.\n\nWe asked Wiener five questions to learn about his career journey and get his advice for entrepreneurs who also want to be leaders.\n\n### What is your personal journey through entrepreneurship and where are you today?", "char_len": 1869, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::25", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 25, "text": "(TEO) Advisory Board and the College of Letters & Science Board of Visitors.\n\nWe asked Wiener five questions to learn about his career journey and get his advice for entrepreneurs who also want to be leaders.\n\n### What is your personal journey through entrepreneurship and where are you today?\n\nI started my first company on campus in the summer before my sophomore year, in the mid-90s, called Wiz Kidz. There were a bunch of older kids in my social circle that were running small businesses. One was doing laundry, one was doing Culligan water bottles. I loved the idea of having a small business, and they inspired me, but my friend and I were more technologically inclined. At that period of time, students had just started to bring personal computers to campus, and they were really expensive. Kids would move in with a multi-thousand dollar-Dell computer in boxes. Nobody really knew how to use them, but we did. And so we would set up people’s computers when they moved in.\n\nThe school also had a CD-ROM that you would buy called WiscWorld which had the TCP/IP packet to install. It was like $20 or $25 at the bookstore. But the license said that once you had it, you could install it for free multiple times. We would charge people for our install services and give them WiscWorld for free. There’s nothing like buying something for $25 and charging $20 to install it. At a similar time, there were a couple of other college campuses where similar businesses were born: one was called Geek Squad, which eventually sold to Best Buy, and one was called Firedog, which sold to Circuit City. We did not have such luck. We could never figure out how to scale. And that was the end of that entrepreneurial journey, but it was innate in me to start that entrepreneurial experience in Madison and go through trials and tribulations.\n\nToday I run a small business that is not in that same ecosystem. But the reason I ended up here—and a lot of my career experience—has been about taking the entrepreneurial operator step, about walking off the edge of a cliff, about having the risk and taking that desire to not just have a job, but to be building a company while I’m building a career.\n\n### What drew you specifically to being involved in leadership of TEO at UW-Madison?", "char_len": 2272, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::26", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 26, "text": "about taking the entrepreneurial operator step, about walking off the edge of a cliff, about having the risk and taking that desire to not just have a job, but to be building a company while I’m building a career.\n\n### What drew you specifically to being involved in leadership of TEO at UW-Madison?\n\nThe inspiration from Tom Erickson, former founding director of the School of Computer, Data & Information Sciences, and Ian Robertson, the former Dean of the College of Engineering (CoE), who both helped create TEO as part of the drive to bring NSF funding and other programming to campus. I saw that as the gateway to supporting a larger entrepreneurial environment—as we’ve now birthed, as Dean Ranjan has come in, and the staffing of TEO with Bonnie and team. There’s a lot that we produce at WARF and in the research university, but there’s also an entire ecosystem of undergrad entrepreneurialism that exists. And it’s the matching of the two in support of those journeys, which was reflective of my own journey that I saw echoes of, that I was excited to support and be a part of. No corollary story is the same. History doesn’t repeat, but it sure does rhyme.\n\n### As an advisory board member, what is your role? What do you enjoy most about your involvement with TEO?\n\nThe board has evolved, the program has evolved, our experience and responsibilities have evolved. The evolution continues because Dean Ranjan is new, the School of Computer, Data & Information Sciences (CDIS) launching is new. Those movements are changing our roles in a number of ways. Regardless, I enjoy working with TEO’s programming team, the support staff, and the other colleagues for sure. The people.\n\n### From your own experience, what was the most valuable lesson you learned that you now bring to your leadership?\n\nIn entrepreneurialism and leadership, in my opinion, it’s about passion. You can’t teach somebody the desire to be entrepreneurial. It’s not necessarily an innate trait—and maybe it has to do with some level of *un*intelligence because you crave the danger of it, the excitement. I tell people I have lots of days that are twos and lots that are eights. You can’t convince somebody to want to live like that.", "char_len": 2213, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::27", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 27, "text": "to be entrepreneurial. It’s not necessarily an innate trait—and maybe it has to do with some level of *un*intelligence because you crave the danger of it, the excitement. I tell people I have lots of days that are twos and lots that are eights. You can’t convince somebody to want to live like that.\n\nWith leadership specifically, my father used to say that sometimes—or many times—it is actually the person who speaks the quietest that gets the room to listen. I’m a fairly large personality who speaks with a big booming voice, and he used to remind me that sometimes you just have to speak quietly so that people around you get quiet to listen to hear you speak. But it’s not just about getting people to hear you, but getting them to *listen*to you. That is how you become a leader. There are many other traits that it takes to be a great leader, but that is one that resonates with me right now that I will pass on.\n\n### If you could give one piece of advice to aspiring entrepreneurs starting their journey, what would it be?\n\nDon’t be afraid to hit the floor and get up. It’s all about how you rebound. That’s generally just a life thing, but in an entrepreneurial life more so than anything else, you will get hit and you will hit the ground and you do need to stand up and dust yourself off.\n\nThere are also a lot of amazing entrepreneurial resources across campus in different ways. As Dean Eric Wilcots (L&S, now interim Chancellor) has recently said, “There are a lot of doors on campus. You just need to start opening some of them.” It’s a big place, and it’s daunting for people, but know that you can just start walking in places and opening doors.\n\n• • •\n\nFeatured image: Oliver Wiener, Founder and Managing Partner of Kensington Merchant Partners and TEO Advisory Board member.\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/?post_type=post\n\n“Next-gen” batteries are on the horizon, and NSF I-Corps alumna and Early Career Entrepreneur-in-Residence Jiajie Sui is helping to commercialize them.\n\nOliver Wiener is an entrepreneur and financier with expertise in the digital realm. He is the Founder and Managing Partner of Kensington Merchant Partners, an investment firm in the evolving financial and technological ecosystem. He was formerly a Portfolio …", "char_len": 2279, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::28", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 28, "text": "is helping to commercialize them.\n\nOliver Wiener is an entrepreneur and financier with expertise in the digital realm. He is the Founder and Managing Partner of Kensington Merchant Partners, an investment firm in the evolving financial and technological ecosystem. He was formerly a Portfolio …\n\nTEO student assistant Deeksha Singh’s team was announced as the graduate winner of the 2025-26 NFLPA Case Competition February 5, 2026. She shares about the competition and her best advice for finding the conditions you need to thrive—in entrepreneurship, in career, and in life.\n\nMeet the 2025 UW-Madison NSF National I-Corps teams awardees and learn more about their groundbreaking work. Each team has a unique project aimed at addressing pressing societal challenges.\n\nTranscend UW, a premier student-led entrepreneurship & startup organization, is calling for participants and sponsors for their 11th-annual Pitch Competition on April 16th and 17th, 2026. Apply by February 16th to secure your eligibility.\n\nTEO’s steady investment in NSF I-Corps™ program participation has yielded results in 2025: larger cohorts, substantial economic impact, and inspiring innovation.\n\nDays/Times: Wednesdays 1-3pm, starting January 21 Instructor: Anne Lynn Gillian-Daniel Location: 3545 Engineering Hall Credit: 1 credit (InterEGR 797) Certificate in Higher Education Teaching and Learning: Course Description Improv requires the ability to listen carefully, think quickly, and communicate …\n\nThe NSF I-Corps Hub: Great Lakes Region has released its 2025 Impact Report, highlighting more than a decade of outcomes from research-driven entrepreneurship across the Midwest and beyond. Since 2012, I-Corps–trained teams affiliated with Great …\n\nThe NSF I-Corps™ Great Lakes Hub has circulated a new solicitation for National Teams that introduces several notable changes to program structure, funding, and participation rules. These updates affect timelines, team capacity, travel, and prototyping …", "char_len": 1982, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::29", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 29, "text": "teams affiliated with Great …\n\nThe NSF I-Corps™ Great Lakes Hub has circulated a new solicitation for National Teams that introduces several notable changes to program structure, funding, and participation rules. These updates affect timelines, team capacity, travel, and prototyping …\n\nLaboratory testing delays and inconsistencies aren’t usually a good thing. But sometimes, those very frustrations can cause innovation to spark. UW–Madison Mechanical Engineering PhD graduate and 3D Powder Tech startup co-founder Luis Izet Escaño Vólquez talks startup formation, product development, and how to shift between being a researcher and an entrepreneur.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/bachman-bonnie\n\n# Bonnie Bachman\n\nPosition title: TEO Director and I-Corps Program Director\n\nEmail: bjbachman@wisc.edu\n\nPhone: (608) 265-4083\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Bonnie Bachman\n\n![A mature white woman with dark hair and brown eyes](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/BB_red-frameAsset-3-300x300.png)\n\nBonnie Bachman is an experienced leader, researcher, and entrepreneur developing and leading the Technology Entrepreneurship Office at the University of Wisconsin-Madison. Bachman is a Professor Emeriti from the Missouri University of Science and Technology and also led research and development (R&D) departments for several Fortune 100 and 500 firms. She holds a bachelor’s degree in physics from Benedictine University, a master’s degree in mechanics and materials science, and a doctoral degree in materials science and engineering from Rutgers University.\n\nBachman brings a unique *lifecycle* approach to building entrepreneurial capacity for faculty and teams in STEM research.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/shi-xiaolei\n\n# Xiaolei (Shelley) Shi\n\nPosition title: Program Specialist for Translational Research\n\nEmail: xshi257@wisc.edu\n\nPhone: 608-890-1562\n\nAddress:\nEngineering Centers Building M1036E\n1550 Engineering Dr., Madison, WI 53706\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Xiaolei (Shelley) Shi\n\n![Headshot of Asian woman with medium length red-brown hair, wearing a dark brown t-shirt and a gold necklace](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/shelley-headshot-300x300.png)", "char_len": 2220, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::30", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 30, "text": "M1036E\n1550 Engineering Dr., Madison, WI 53706\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Xiaolei (Shelley) Shi\n\n![Headshot of Asian woman with medium length red-brown hair, wearing a dark brown t-shirt and a gold necklace](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/shelley-headshot-300x300.png)\n\nDr. Xiaolei (Shelley) Shi serves as a Program Specialist for Translational Research in both the Early Entrepreneurship in Residence (EEIR) Program and the Technological Entrepreneurship Office at UW-Madison. She is also a senior scientist in the Chemical &Biological Engineering Department, focusing on dairy-related research. With a passion for entrepreneurial research, she brings more than 15 years of experience in applied research in broader STEM fields, as well as a strong background in patent disclosure and startup company foundations. She leverages her expertise in STEM research and federal regulations, along with established connections with hospitals, government agencies, companies, and universities, in her role as a liaison for UW-Madison’s entrepreneurial teams and the NSF Great Lakes Hub I-Corps Tech Scouting Program. She also co-founded a UW-Madison spin-out company, Ninjas Printing. She has supported the Dairy Research and Engineering/Manufacturing teams at UW in seeking I-Corps and SBIR/STTR funding from federal agencies such as NASA, NSF, and USDA.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/alrabiah-fadhel\n\n# Fadhel Alrabiah\n\nPosition title: Startup Associate\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Fadhel Alrabiah\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/01/Fadhel_Headshot-300x300.png)\n\nFadhel Alrabiah, a PhD candidate in Civil and Environmental Engineering at UW-Madison, brings his entrepreneurial mindset and startup experience to the Technology Entrepreneurship Office. As TEO’s graduate student, he fosters innovation and empowers peers to explore entrepreneurial opportunities, bridging the gap between academia and industry.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/apfelbach-eric\n\n# Eric Apfelbach\n\nPosition title: Technology Executive and Director\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Eric Apfelbach\n\n![A mature white male with short gray hair and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/eric_red-frame-300x300.png)", "char_len": 2265, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::31", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 31, "text": "https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/apfelbach-eric\n\n# Eric Apfelbach\n\nPosition title: Technology Executive and Director\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Eric Apfelbach\n\n![A mature white male with short gray hair and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/eric_red-frame-300x300.png)\n\nEric Apfelbach seamlessly blends entrepreneurial flair with corporate prowess. With recent CEO roles at PEGEX and EnSync Energy, he’s navigated complex markets adeptly. Eric’s journey includes founding innovative ventures like Virent and Alfalight, alongside impactful roles at Planar Systems and Applied Materials. Armed with a BS in Chemical Engineering from the University of Wisconsin, he continues to shape the tech landscape through board positions at the Wisconsin Technology Council, and Orbital Materials.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/closmore-elizabeth\n\n# Elizabeth Closmore\n\nPosition title: Co-Founder and President of Commotion\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Elizabeth Closmore\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/02/Elizabeth_Headshot-300x300.png)\n\nElizabeth is the Co-Founder and President of Commotion, an AI tech startup transforming customer experience. With experience at Target, Hearst, and startups, she has a track record of scaling businesses and driving innovation. Previously, she was a key early leader at Sprinklr, shaping its core product and partnerships, contributing to its successful IPO. She also advises and invests in early-stage tech companies. Elizabeth holds a degree in Political Science and International Studies from the College of Letters and Science, graduating in 2005.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/kaczmarczyk-christian\n\n# Christian Kaczmarczyk\n\nPosition title: Principal, Third Prime\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Christian Kaczmarczyk\n\n![A white man with short dark hair and brown eyes](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/christian_red-frame-300x300.png)", "char_len": 1949, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::32", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 32, "text": "Christian Kaczmarczyk\n\nPosition title: Principal, Third Prime\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Christian Kaczmarczyk\n\n![A white man with short dark hair and brown eyes](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/christian_red-frame-300x300.png)\n\nChristian Kaczmarczyk, a standout Economics graduate, is currently a Principal at Third Prime, a leading venture capital firm focusing on fintech, proptech, industrial tech, and crypto. With a track record spanning startups like BlockFi, Bison Trails (acquired by Coinbase), and FalconX, Christian’s expertise in business development and strategy is unmatched. Previously, he excelled as an investor at firms like Alumni Ventures Group and Bascom Ventures.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/tamchin-craig\n\n# Craig Tamchin\n\nPosition title: CEO and Co-Founder of Empowered Buildings\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Craig Tamchin\n\n![White man with short brown hair and brown eyes](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/07/ctamchin_red-frame-300x300.png)\n\nCraig is the Co-Founder and CEO of Empowered Buildings, a technology company specializing in building automation systems, energy management, and smart building solutions. Craig has over 20 years of experience in energy, software, and data analytics. He is considered a leading expert in the field of building automation and energy efficiency.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/wiener-oliver\n\n# Oliver Wiener\n\nPosition title: Founder, Kensington Merchant Partners\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Oliver Wiener\n\n![A bald white man with glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/oliver_red-frame-300x300.png)\n\nMr. Wiener, the esteemed Founding Partner of Kensington Merchant Partners (KMP), boasts a distinguished background in financial services, including notable roles at Standard Investments and BTIG. As a former Board President of The Association of Digital Asset Markets, his expertise extends to the digital realm. Graduating from the University of Wisconsin in 2000, he initiated his entrepreneurial journey with Wiz Kidz in 1997 while still at UW.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/arpaci-dusseau-remzi\n\n# Remzi Arpaci-Dusseau\n\nPosition title: Director, School of Computer, Data & Information Sciences", "char_len": 2253, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::33", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 33, "text": "realm. Graduating from the University of Wisconsin in 2000, he initiated his entrepreneurial journey with Wiz Kidz in 1997 while still at UW.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/arpaci-dusseau-remzi\n\n# Remzi Arpaci-Dusseau\n\nPosition title: Director, School of Computer, Data & Information Sciences\n\n* LinkedIn profile for Remzi Arpaci-Dusseau\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/02/Rezmi_Headshot-300x300.png)\n\nRemzi Arpaci-Dusseau is the Director of the School of Computer, Data & Information Sciences (CDIS) and Special Advisor to the Provost on Computing at UW-Madison. A leading researcher in storage and distributed systems, he co-leads a research group with Professor Andrea Arpaci-Dusseau, whose innovations are widely adopted in commercial systems.\n\nPreviously, Remzi served as Chair of the Computer Sciences Department, playing a key role in advancing the school’s mission. His contributions have earned him numerous accolades, including the ACM-SIGOPS Mark Weiser Award and fellowships from both the ACM and AAAS. An award-winning educator, he has received UW-Madison’s Professor-of-the-Year honor seven times. His widely used operating systems textbook (OSTEP) is downloaded millions of times annually.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/sambamurthy-vallabh\n\n# Vallabh Sambamurthy\n\nPosition title: Dean, School of Business\n\n![A mature Asian Indian man a recessive hairline and mustache wearing glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/SV_red-frame-300x300.png)\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/staff/wilcots-eric\n\n# Eric Wilcots\n\nPosition title: Dean, College of Letters and Science\n\n![A mature black man with a recessive hairline and mustache](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2024/03/EW_red-frame-300x300.png)\n\n“Our leading scientists are demanding more support to commercialize their innovations. The lifecycle support through TEO will be transformational in its impact on society.”\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/03/02/2025-i-corps-year-in-review\n\n![Young middle eastern man wearing glasses and smiling while looking at a computer someone is holding](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-32.png)", "char_len": 2240, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::34", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 34, "text": "in its impact on society.”\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/03/02/2025-i-corps-year-in-review\n\n![Young middle eastern man wearing glasses and smiling while looking at a computer someone is holding](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-32.png)\n\nBuilding national success in the entrepreneurship space doesn’t happen overnight, but the Technology Entrepreneurship Office’s (TEO’s) steady investment in NSF I-Corps™ program participation has certainly yielded results in 2025. I-Corps is an immersive program that aims to train entrepreneurs, translate technologies, enable positive economic impact, and nurture an innovative ecosystem.\n\n![Visual highlighting the 2025 facts that are included in the paragraph text](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-33-1.png)\n\nIn the UW System, UW–Madison and TEO have facilitated a rise in overall I-Corps participation in 2025, serving over 500 participants across 16 events, three cohorts, and five National Teams. Participation throughout the UW System also increased in 2025, with the first two cohorts alone supporting 36 teams and 97 participants from seven campuses—up from 24 teams, 58 individuals, and just two campuses in 2024. These seven UW campuses joined an additional six universities within the Great Lakes Region for participation in 2025.\n\nTwo of the UW–Madison National I-Corps ELs have been selected for the Early Entrepreneur in Residence (EEIR) program in the newly established Badger Tech Foundry. This complementary program provides training and hands-on development for the strategic development of serial entrepreneurs. It caps participants’ startup experiences, training, and commercialization preparation at UW–Madison before they fully enter the market as newcos.\n\nThe Plan Your Impact program was created as another follow-on option for National I-Corps Teams, which covers 12 weeks of advanced entrepreneurial topics. It focuses on the knowledge and skills needed to thrive in tough tech commercialization, including business fundamentals, intellectual property & licensing, company formation, fundraising, team building & governance, and pitching. The first PYI cohort convened in January and will meet until April.", "char_len": 2286, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::35", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 35, "text": "It focuses on the knowledge and skills needed to thrive in tough tech commercialization, including business fundamentals, intellectual property & licensing, company formation, fundraising, team building & governance, and pitching. The first PYI cohort convened in January and will meet until April.\n\nThe I-Corps mentorship network grew and improved along with participation. TEO developed a mentor video, guide, and process for orientation and development that streamlines effective support. The network now includes mentors from the Great Lakes and other National Hubs, and UW–Madison I-Corps instructors teach for other Hub members and Great Lakes programs. Progress was also made on the Badger Intel-JIT Mentor Matching Platform—the team produced a whitepaper, completed alpha testing, and applied for funding. An AI coaching platform for lagging teams was assessed as an option moving forward.\n\nMarket success for I-Corps participants continued in 2025. Startup companies led by past UW I-Corps ELs saw significant funding, totaling more than $12m. Ubicept, specializing in single-photon imaging and perception, was co-led through UW–Madison I-Corps by Andreas Velten in 2019 and received $8m in funding in 2025. Galasys, featured in last season’s TEO newsletter, is a product of the 2023 I-Corps cohort and received $185k in funding in 2025. SixLine, Alithic, Flux XII, Ninjas Printing, and Dirac Labs are other notable mentions as successfully funded startups from 2025.\n\nOverall, the UW System and UW–Madison specifically have had a fruitful year of I-Corps with the help of TEO. If you are interested in outreach events or joining the next cohort, keep an eye out for announcements on how to get involved in 2026—we’d love to see you there!\n\n• • •\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/02/12/singh-interview\n\n![three women pose with the Wisconsin W hand symbol](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/Final_Team_Photo-1200x800.jpeg)", "char_len": 1982, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::36", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 36, "text": "how to get involved in 2026—we’d love to see you there!\n\n• • •\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/02/12/singh-interview\n\n![three women pose with the Wisconsin W hand symbol](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/Final_Team_Photo-1200x800.jpeg)\n\nIn its second annual Analytics Case Competition, the National Football League Players Association (NFLPA) offered $30,000 in prizes to undergraduate and graduate students to address the following challenge: how do the cumulative effects of workload throughout the season impact key metrics such as player performance, injury risk, earnings, or team wins and losses?\n\nWisconsin School of Business MBA Student Ambassador and TEO student assistant Deeksha Singh Vijay Singh‘s team was selected not only as one of five finalists, but was announced as the graduate winner on February 5, 2026.\n\nPotential focus areas were broad, including topics like addition of a second bye, compressed game schedule, field surface type, international travel, length of season, player workload and performance, position of the bye week, and relationship between earnings and playtime. Singh and her team, Kasey Morris and Mai Nguyen, won $12,000 analyzing red flag games (short rest of less than six days combined with travel through more than two timezones) and their effect on stress and player performance.\n\nWe asked Singh about the competition, her team’s strategy, and her best advice for finding the conditions you need to thrive—in entrepreneurship, in career, and in life.\n\n### How did you find this competition and why did you choose to compete?\n\nBefore this competition, I did not know anything about American football, because for me, football is soccer—and the funny thing is, I don’t even know a lot about that! I’m a first year MBA student and I have a goal of participating in ten competitions over this academic year. From my undergrad days, everything I know about business and entrepreneurship stemmed from doing these competitions. It’s a discrete, high-pressure period with a team. It’s project-based and everything needs to be well thought out.", "char_len": 2135, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::37", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 37, "text": "goal of participating in ten competitions over this academic year. From my undergrad days, everything I know about business and entrepreneurship stemmed from doing these competitions. It’s a discrete, high-pressure period with a team. It’s project-based and everything needs to be well thought out.\n\nI wanted to keep putting myself in situations and seeing how I managed to get out of them. This NFLPA one wasn’t really advertised, but my teammate Mai is an MS Business Analytics student and she thought it was relevant for her specifically. I wanted to do more analysis. We got Kasey from the finance specialization in the MBA program and the rest was history.\n\n### How did you approach your topic of red flag games? How did you arrive at that focus area with your team?\n\nThe original prompt was open-ended—which to us meant we didn’t know where to start, so we started researching the problem space more. I spoke to a footballer on the UW–Madison team who is also an MBA student to try to get an understanding of his pain points. He helped provide a lot of initial direction about short rest, because then you don’t have time to recover. We took that as a data point and then we triangulated it against the current industry trends.\n\nWe created a whiteboard to understand how travel and short rest affect performance and injury risk on the individual player level. However, two weeks into our work, my analysis showed that short rest actually *improves*performance and *reduces*risk of injury. I thought I had to be doing something wrong. But my work was validated by the industry. It made sense—it was just bad news for us. We were very despondent, but I tried to rally the team—because this is where the best innovation comes from.\n\nI then noticed that there was not enough data for certain teams and players. Doesn’t this mean that certain players are just not encountering certain risk conditions? There were different types of risks that each position group was absorbing. Let’s look at frequency, exposure, and fairness at the team level, the position group level, and the player level. I started mapping it out in a matrix.", "char_len": 2131, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::38", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 38, "text": "certain players are just not encountering certain risk conditions? There were different types of risks that each position group was absorbing. Let’s look at frequency, exposure, and fairness at the team level, the position group level, and the player level. I started mapping it out in a matrix.\n\nWe found out that West Coast teams are unfairly disadvantaged. They are encountering a red flag game four times more than the league average, while East Coast teams are encountering it zero percent of the time. That’s not fair. And whenever they were exposed, their performance degraded quite significantly compared to the baseline.\n\nNow, how do we put it in like a narrative that has impact? I think the reason we differentiated ourselves as a team and as a project was because we created a new metric, and we were experts in our insight and our solution, and that made it applicable to the NFL Players union. Our analysis could be scaled up, and we had an answer prepared for any question.\n\n![Red Flag Games: Peak Performance or Survival of the Resilient?](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/1-TITLE.png)\n\nThe team’s title slide, showcasing their analytic lens.\n\n### How did your involvement with TEO and your School of Business training prepare you for this opportunity?\n\nThe road would not have been as clear or as easy or as supported if I didn’t have either of those two support networks. We had to prepare a 45-minute presentation for stakeholders, and I didn’t want them to be nodding off—I wanted them to be nodding *along*. In the Wisconsin School of Business, I reached out to Anita Mukherjee. She had me come to her professional MBA class to present. Douglas McLeod and Sameer Deshpande also gave us their thoughts on our work. That feedback was invaluable, not only on a personal and professional level, but also in that this is how the support system should be. And that’s to say nothing of the silent support from all the members of my MBA cohort and my professors.", "char_len": 2001, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::39", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 39, "text": "Deshpande also gave us their thoughts on our work. That feedback was invaluable, not only on a personal and professional level, but also in that this is how the support system should be. And that’s to say nothing of the silent support from all the members of my MBA cohort and my professors.\n\nTEO was also a great support system. In my student assistant role, I’m working on the NSF I-Corps program. One of the co-foundations is customer discovery. I made sure I did my customer and stakeholder discovery in this competition. We reached out to last year’s winners and asked them what kind of questions do they ask in Round 2. We had not even gotten through Round 1, but it’s good to be prepared. I-Corps is also a great program because it’s not in a silo. It exists in a larger ecosystem—there are a lot of different alternative paths you can take from the program. You have access to a large mentor network, which I took advantage of. I mapped out my solution space and looked at support system allies I could leverage to reach my goals. I think every person going into NSF I-Corps should also be thinking, how can NSF I-Corps or TEO help me get to where I want to go next?\n\n### How did it feel when you were announced as a finalist and then as a winner?\n\nFor Round 1, my team was across multiple time zones—we were in a red flag game ourselves! For Round 2, I was in class. I had just received a job offer for my summer internship, which I sent to my family group chat, and everyone was congratulating me. Then ten minutes later, I refreshed my email and got the NFL announcement. I was vibrating, and the class was not even close to being done. My teammates Casey and Mai were also in class, and no one was responding to my texts because they’re good students, unlike me. After class I apologized to the professor and ran through the Wisconsin School of Business second floor to find my teammates so I could high-five them. And then we went to hotpot.\n\n### The quote on your bio says, “Find the conditions you need to thrive.” How did you find those conditions for yourself and what is your best advice for other entrepreneurs on how to find theirs?", "char_len": 2152, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::40", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 40, "text": "of Business second floor to find my teammates so I could high-five them. And then we went to hotpot.\n\n### The quote on your bio says, “Find the conditions you need to thrive.” How did you find those conditions for yourself and what is your best advice for other entrepreneurs on how to find theirs?\n\nIn computer science, we often say that certain systems are optimized for the average use case. That makes sense for a lot of systems. However, when it comes to your professional trajectory, your decision making, and your life, you can’t be optimizing for the average use case. General advice won’t necessarily apply to you, the stage you are in your life, and what you need to do to get to where you want to go next.\n\nWhen I started the MBA as an international student, I knew that I didn’t want to do the same things as everyone else because I didn’t want what everyone else was getting. I wanted something that made sense for me. I needed access to certain networks, mentorship, and practice, which I could get through competitions. I know what my gaps are and how I can leverage my strengths to make up for them. It might not make sense for your use case, but it makes sense for mine. I’m okay with making sacrifices to hit my goal and because I’m able to do it ruthlessly and with precision. I’m not sitting at home stressing about things outside my control—I’m keeping myself busy and showing my work.\n\n• • •\n\nFeature image: Winning NFLPA Case Competition team Kasey Morris, Mai Nguyen, and Deeksha Singh.\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/01/30/2025i-corps-teams\n\n![Collage of images showing the close-up of an eye looking at computer code, a plant growing in the soil, 3D printer with metal dust, and two images of computerized cell images](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-33.png)", "char_len": 1868, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::41", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 41, "text": "of images showing the close-up of an eye looking at computer code, a plant growing in the soil, 3D printer with metal dust, and two images of computerized cell images](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-33.png)\n\nThe National Science Foundation (NSF) I-Corps™ Teams program is an immersive, innovative program that facilitates the transformation of invention all the way to impact. This seven-week experiential training program prepares scientists and engineers to extend their focus beyond the university laboratory—accelerating the economic and societal benefits of NSF-funded and other basic research projects that are ready to move toward commercialization.\n\nWidely recognized as an effective training program in the U.S. and internationally, I-Corps addresses four urgent national needs:\n\n1. Training an entrepreneurial workforce\n2. Translating technologies\n3. Enabling positive economic impact\n4. Nurturing an innovation ecosystem\n\nResearch indicates that the primary reason startups fail is the development of products that lack market demand. I-Corps helps entrepreneurs avoid pitfalls by identifying the problem that customers need to solve. Through this program, participants have the opportunity to network with experienced industry mentors, build a solid foundation for their venture, and enhance their credibility for future funding opportunities. Additionally, completing the local or regional program is the most straightforward path to applying for the I-Corps Team award, which helps cover expenses related to customer discovery up to $50,000.\n\nThe UW–Madison local I-Corps program prepares teams to have the skillset and eligibility for success in the regional or national I-Corps Teams program. This free six-week, non-credit virtual workshop uses evidence-based strategies for achieving entrepreneurial success and is open to research faculty, staff, and students at any higher education institution.\n\nThe 2025 cohort of UW-Madison National I-Corps teams comprised a diverse group of researchers, each with a unique project aimed at addressing pressing societal challenges. Here, we meet the teams and learn more about their groundbreaking work.", "char_len": 2216, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::42", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 42, "text": "and students at any higher education institution.\n\nThe 2025 cohort of UW-Madison National I-Corps teams comprised a diverse group of researchers, each with a unique project aimed at addressing pressing societal challenges. Here, we meet the teams and learn more about their groundbreaking work.\n\n## Statistical Framework for Language Model Outputs\n\nThis project translates a new method for validating artificial intelligence (AI) outputs, helping industries adopt trustworthy and reliable AI technologies. The solution generates calibrated confidence scores, indicating when decision-makers can rely on AI outputs. This solution seeks to address how to ensure AI produces trustworthy responses when used in industry applications, making it safer and more practical to use AI systems across different industries and when time is critical—such as healthcare and finance.\n\n![headshot of a white person with blond hair and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/1742834484801.jpg)\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Auden Krauska\n\n![headshot of a white man with brown hair, a beard, and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/rohe-karl.jpg)\n**Technical Lead:** Karl Rohe\n\n**Industry Mentor:** Ray Mendez\n\n**How it works:**\n\n* Couples experiential learning with first-hand investigation\n* Utilizes an advanced statistical framework for validating Large Language Models outputs\n* Individualizes analysis patterns to each output, which improves accuracy\n\n## Soil Electrochemical Sensing\n\nThis project is advancing agricultural sensors which are capable of directly measuring plant-available nitrate at the plant root zone in real-time throughout the growing season. This ability allows real-time decisions to be made regarding fertilization rates, including using spatially and temporally varying rates.\n\n![headshot of an asian man with short black hair and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/andrewsLab_002-768x960-1-300x300.jpg)\n\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Kuan-Yu Chen\n\n![headshot of a white man with short brown hair and a beard](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/andrews_joseph-jandrews4-1x1-transparent-1024x1024-1-300x300.png)\n\n**T****echnical Lead:** Joseph Andrews", "char_len": 2272, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::43", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 43, "text": "Lead:** Kuan-Yu Chen\n\n![headshot of a white man with short brown hair and a beard](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/andrews_joseph-jandrews4-1x1-transparent-1024x1024-1-300x300.png)\n\n**T****echnical Lead:** Joseph Andrews\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/CB_IMG_2214d-388x400-1-291x300.jpeg)\n\n**Industry Mentor:** Cecily Brose\n\n**How it works:**\n\n* Electrochemical, in-situ sensors capable of operating in soil environments\n* Sensors use a nanoporous hydrophilic membrane that filters out soil particulates and minimizes interference from soil components\n\n## Non-invasive Cell Imaging\n\nThis non-invasive imaging solution is designed to improve how therapeutic cells are evaluated in biomedical research. Cell therapies are becoming a critical tool in the treatment of diseases such as cancer, but current evaluation methods are slow, costly, invasive, and incomplete. With this non-invasive technology, researchers can assess behavior of therapeutic cells inside the body over time—critical for advancements in healthcare and public health.\n\n![headshot of a man with brown skin and short black hair with a beard](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/victorPic-300x300.jpg)\n\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Victor Fernandes\n\n![headshot of a bald man with light skin and a gray goatee](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/hernandez-300x300.jpg)\n\n**Technical Lead:** Reinier Hernandez\n\n**Industry Mentor:** Rafael Diaz\n\n**How it works:**\n\n* Radiolabeling platform enables direct, quantitative imaging of living therapeutic cells\n* Blend of chemical oxidation, modified metal-binding agent, and positron-emitting isotope means labeled cells maintain viability and function over time\n\n## Powder Spreadability Testing\n\n![headshot of a man with brown skin, short black hair, and a goatee](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/Luis-Escano.jpg)\n\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Luis Izet Escaño Vólquez\n\n![headshot of an asian man with short black hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/lianyi-chen16-9-jpg-webp-copy-300x300.jpg)\n\n**Technical Lead:** Lianyi Chen\n\n**Industry Mentor:** Xiujuan Jane Zhang", "char_len": 2232, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::44", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 44, "text": "Lead:** Luis Izet Escaño Vólquez\n\n![headshot of an asian man with short black hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/lianyi-chen16-9-jpg-webp-copy-300x300.jpg)\n\n**Technical Lead:** Lianyi Chen\n\n**Industry Mentor:** Xiujuan Jane Zhang\n\nThis project pioneers advancements in metal 3D printing through an accurate and precise quality control testing device. Powder-based additive manufacturing depends on the quality of powders that feed into the AM machine. The testing device ensures safety and repeatability in industries that require precision, such as aerospace, medical, and automotive. Read more about the innovation in more detail here.\n\n**How it works:**\n\n* Assesses metal powders at a detailed, particle-by-particle scale\n* Qualification happens under real manufacturing conditions rather than in a thin layer, saving time and money\n\n## Chronic Pain Diagnostics\n\n![headshot of an asian woman with medium black hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/02/Shinye-KIM-square-1-300x300.jpg)\n\n**Technical Lead:** ShinYe Kim\n\nThis digital tool can help better diagnose chronic pain, which affects over 100 million adults in the United States and contributes to an estimated $560–$635 billion annually in lost productivity and healthcare costs. Such advancements can change the game in many ways, but particularly in more accurately communicating pain, reducing misdiagnosis, and preventing opioid dependence or addiction.\n\n**How it works:**\n\n* A digital phenotyping platform combines linguistic and metabolic analysis with machine learning algorithms to identify patterns in chronic pain expression\n* The platform provides real-time, individualized insights that can better treat patients—both in short- and long-term care\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/01/28/transcend-call-2026\n\n![Transcend logo with a photo of two men talking to another person](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/transcend-imageArtboard-1.png)\n\n## Incubate your startup with Transcend UW!\n\nTranscend is UW–Madison’s premier student-led entrepreneurship & startup organization, and they are calling for participants and sponsors for their 11th-annual Pitch Competition on April 16th and 17th, 2026.", "char_len": 2246, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::45", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 45, "text": "Incubate your startup with Transcend UW!\n\nTranscend is UW–Madison’s premier student-led entrepreneurship & startup organization, and they are calling for participants and sponsors for their 11th-annual Pitch Competition on April 16th and 17th, 2026.\n\n**Read more details on eligibility here and apply at this link by February 16th to secure your spot.**\n\nTranscend is the perfect place to grow your skills and work on exciting projects that can make a difference in the real world. The org helps undergraduate and graduate students develop their startup ideas by providing mentorship, funding opportunities, and access to a community of like-minded individuals. They encourage cross-disciplinary collaboration, so members can find the perfect team to bring their vision to life.\n\nFor their 2026 Pitch Competition, Transcend is looking for talented individuals or teams of up to five who have an idea they are ready to fund. Competitors have access to up to $50k in prize money from a growing entrepreneurial ecosystem across Wisconsin. They are particularly interested in startups that have a social or environmental mission, but they encourage all applicants to think about the positive broader impact their ventures can have.\n\nThe competition structure allows participants to build and adjust their pitches over weeks of events, including mandatory attendance to an Intellectual Property Seminar and Project Review Session and optional but recommended attendance to a training on Business Models (which we reviewed in our last TEO newsletter!). The competition itself is hosted over two days in which all teams participate in a poster session and pitch placement round, and then placed based on performance for the second day’s general, advanced, or top five tracks.", "char_len": 1768, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::46", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 46, "text": "on Business Models (which we reviewed in our last TEO newsletter!). The competition itself is hosted over two days in which all teams participate in a poster session and pitch placement round, and then placed based on performance for the second day’s general, advanced, or top five tracks.\n\n**Transcend is also looking for sponsors for 2026.** Sponsoring this event is a unique opportunity for existing organizations to support early-stage entrepreneurs while also advertising their organization and networking amongst some of the best up-and-coming, collaborative innovators across the university. Click this link to invest in the next generation of founders (via Innovation Days Fund – 112340033), or reach out to Transcend leadership at transcenduw@gmail.com with questions.\n\nWe hope to see you there!\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/news/untitled-1\n\n�PNG\n\u001a\n���\nIHDR��\u0001,��\u0001,\b\u0006���y}�u��� pHYs��\n\u0012��\n\u0012\u0001��~��� �IDATx��Y�mY�\n�1�Z��sn\u0013�FFdf%U�r5���\b�DI\u0018$ސ�\nH~�\u0005��\u0011� �\u0017X�\u0004\u0012\u0002�dld �\n�\u0007�4E�LY�reU����22�۝f�5�\u0018<�fε� �/�)V�Ĺg7k�f4�h'���\\*�B@�\u0013�\u0004\"g\u0010\u0011���\u001f�\b�0zo�O\u0013\u0014��4>H�-R�~�\n�V\\\\_?\u0001�PU0��T��N���w����\u0011��\\_���ݿB��C��Pі\u00020\u0001� \"\u0014b\\\n\u000e�Z@� &0\u0017\u001b�j\u000e���:FL\n\u0010)Hm���\\_���M|���\u0007� \"x��k�Z�����\u001a�`�\u0010\u0011�\n�o�}w���[\u0017���~\u001f?���(��Xeß�z�\n�qS\u001b�\u0016\u0002��d��;�7�u\u0016(�R�UF�H�����\u0010�k�\n��.���QF�\n�\u0010\\*3�}��1��AT��\nT\u0006\u0014\u0002fB\u0017`k�Z�&��a\u0010H\u0015T�UB�N�\u0010T\u0004\n\u0002�T�\u0010,�`��\u0013 j-I\u001f���\u0005`\u0016pa�\bJ)�\u0014�\u0001\u0011����L��\u0005�s\u0003�6�J��ѺͭT�.", "char_len": 1360, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
