{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::125", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 125, "text": "startup st newest NSF I-Corps™M cohort\nmentor advic about how to go against the flow\nindividual goals.\n\nAbove all, I hope this issue inspires you to keep seeking the\nmany pathways to entrepreneurial development that this\ncampus provides.\n\nWishing you a season of renewed ideas and energy.\n\nBompie\n2025 NSF I-Corps™ year in review\n$12M+ 500+\nraised by UW I-Corps participants engaged\nalumni startups across 16 events\nfrom\n5 national teams 13\nsupported\nuniversities\nOur I-Corps program just\nwrapped its biggest year\nyet!\n\nWe set a ipation, established\non pathways, and had\nhuge startup successes, topping $12M.\n\nSee\nhow the program expanded across the UW\nSystem\nidea to impact\nRead more\nMeet the 2025 National I-Corps™ Teams\nThe NSF I-Corps Teams program helps researchers turn\ninnovations into real-world solutions through hands-on\ntraining and industry mentorship.\n\nFacilitated -Cord s participants with the skills\nnetwork ideas.\n\nWe are proud that our 2025 cohort brings\nforward bold innovations across Al, agriculture, healthcare, manufacturing, and digital diagnostics\nteam remendous strides toward translating research into\nStatistical Framework for Language\nModel Outputs (Rohe, Krauska,\nMendez)\nA new statistical method that assigns\ncalibrated confidence scores to Al-generated\noutputs-advancing safer, more trustworthy\nAl for high-stakes fields like healthcare and\nfinance.\n\nSoil Electrochemical Sensing\n(Andrews, Chen, Huang)\nReal-time, in-soil sensors that measure\nplant-available nitrate at the root zone,\nempowering farmmeerrs to optimize fertilization\nwith precision.\n\nNon-invasive Cell Imaging\n(Hernandez, Fernandes, Diaz)\nA radiolabeling platform that enables direct,\nquantitative imaging of therapeutic\naccelerating progress in cell-based\ntreatments for diseases like cancer.\n\nPowder Spreadability Testing\n(Chen, Escano Volquez, Zhang)\nA particle-level quality control device for\nmetal 3D printing, improving safety and\nrepeatability for aerospace, medical, and\nautomotive manufacturing.", "char_len": 2002, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::126", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 126, "text": "of therapeutic\naccelerating progress in cell-based\ntreatments for diseases like cancer.\n\nPowder Spreadability Testing\n(Chen, Escano Volquez, Zhang)\nA particle-level quality control device for\nmetal 3D printing, improving safety and\nrepeatability for aerospace, medical, and\nautomotive manufacturing.\n\nChronic Pain Diagnostics (Kim)\nA digital phenotyping tool using linguistic and\nmetabolic analysis plus machine learning to\nidentify chronic pain patterns-improving\ndiagnosis and reducing risks surrounding\nmiscommunication and opioid dependence\nMore about the 2025 National Teams\nFerroMx is powering next-gen batteries\nI-Corps Alum Dr.\n\nJiajie Sui is the Next Gen Entrepreneur for\nNext Gen Batteries\n-I-Corps alum and Early Career Entrepreneur-in-Residence Dr.\n\nJiajie Sui is helping accelerate\nthe future of \"next-gen\" batteries through her startup FerroMX.\n\nAlongside PI Xudong Wang (MSE), Sui\nis commercializing a ferroelectric separator membrane that suppresses dendrites-metallic growths\nthat can cause battery failure.\n\nThe technology boosts efficiency by 20%, improves safety,a nd extends\nbattery life for applications from EVs to renewable energy storage.\n\nSui's entrepreneurial path began during her MSE PhD at UW-Madison and was shaped by MЕВ,\nI-Corps the Badger Tech Foundry.\n\nToday she's advancing FerroMX\nsing, and preparing for market launch.\n\nHer journey s UW-Madis\nempowers researchers to turn high-impact materials innovations into real-world solutions.\n\nMore about FerroMx\nPictured from left sey Morris, Mai Nguyen, and Deeksha Singh\nDeeksha Singh Wins NFLPA Analytics Competition\nTEO student assistant and Wisconsin School of Business MBA Ambassador Deeksha Singh and I\nteam took home the graduate division win and $12,000 prize in the NFLPA's 2025-26 Analytics Case\nCompetition.\n\nTheir project analyzed how \"red flag games\"-short rest paired with long-distance travel\nect player stress and performance.\n\nSingh shared insights on tackling an open-ended challenge,\nbuilding a cross-disciplinary team, and finding the conditions to thrive in entrepreneurship and life.", "char_len": 2085, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
