nnovation competition, offering mentorship, funding, and\nexposure.\n\nIt's a launchpad for bold ideas-perfect for students\neager to build, pitch, and make an impact.", "char_len": 1985, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::128", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 128, "text": "events\nApril 16-17, 2026\nTranscend Pitch Competition\nTRANSCEND\nStudent organization, Transcend, is UW's largest student-run\ninnovation competition, offering mentorship, funding, and\nexposure.\n\nIt's a launchpad for bold ideas-perfect for students\neager to build, pitch, and make an impact.\n\nApril 21, 2026 | 12:00 PM - 1:00 PM\nGGRREEAATT NSF I-Corps™M Spring Cohort Learning Session\nL RE A G K I E O S N Join TEO and the Great Lakes NSF I-Corps Hub for a virtual\ninformation session about the full spectrum of NSF I-Corps\nopportunities and how they support students translating\nresearch discoveries into market-ready solution\nMay 11, 2026 | 5:00 PM -7:30 PM\nFREE Workshop: From Research to Action:\nUnderstanding Your Market Workshop\nfrom RESEARCH This hands-on training, led by the Marketing Leadership\nInstitute and UW-Madison Business Library expert Pegg\nSmith, wille quip you with the tools to understand market\ndynamics, conduct B2B or B2C research, and develop data-\ndriven market strategies.\n\nAll designed\nRegl\nJune 25 - July 30, 2026 | 4:45 PM -7:00 PM (on Thursdays)\nFREE Virtual Workshop: NSF I-Corps™ Summe\nCohort\nTRANSFORM by the UW-Madison local NSF I-Corps™ program, this 6-\nyour RESEARO week workshop will help you take the first step toward achieving\nyour entrepreneurial goals.\n\nParticipants can earn am ic\nnd become eligible for larger programs, includin\nthe NSF National I-Corps™M Program ($50k) and I-Corps Boost.\n\nApply\nJune 1-3, 2026 | 5:15 PM -7:30 PM\nFREE Workshop: Take control of your career with\nPersonalized Road\nThrough engaging discuss exer\nAndrew L.\n\nShafer, a strategist, business builder, and auth\nof Strategic ROAD Intentional and Memora\nApproach to Achieving Success.\n\nYou'llg ain the tools to\nconfidently map out your career path and long-term goals.\n\nRegister\nSpring forward with help from TEO\nWhether you're a student, faculty member, or campus partner,\nTEO connects you with eurship trainings,\nmentorship.", "char_len": 1942, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::129", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 129, "text": "Intentional and Memora\nApproach to Achieving Success.\n\nYou'llg ain the tools to\nconfidently map out your career path and long-term goals.\n\nRegister\nSpring forward with help from TEO\nWhether you're a student, faculty member, or campus partner,\nTEO connects you with eurship trainings,\nmentorship.\n\nand\nopportunities to help bring your ideas to life\nMeet Oliver Wiener\nTEO Advisor\nOliver\nand Managing Partner he evolving financia\nand technological merly a Portfolio Manager at Standard sand\nundin f Digital As\ngraduated from UW-Madison with a dual major BA in International Relations and Political Science\nHe now sits on the Technology (TEO) Advisory Board and the College of Letters &\nScience Board of Visitors.\n\nWe asked Wiener five questions to learn about his career\njourney and get his advice for entrepreneurs who also want to\nbe leaders.\n\nWhat did your personal journey through entrepreneurship look like, and where\neyou today?\n\nbefore my sophomo\nts had just started bringing personal computers to campus.\n\nNobody really kne\nple's co\nnem the TCP/IP packet and WiscWorld for free.\n\nIt was innate in me to\nnand go s and tribulations.\n\nToday, I run a\nnot in ecosystem.\n\nBut the reason I ended up here has b\ntaking that desire not just to have a job, but to build a company while I'm building a career.\n\n2.W hat drew you specifically to being involved in the leadership of TEO at UW-\nMadison?\n\ncreate TE ve to bring NSF funding\nand other programming t at as the gateway to supporting a larger entrepreneurial\nThere WARF an , but there's also an\nentire ecosystem of undergraduate entrepreneurialism.\n\nAnd matching of the two in support of\nthose journeys, which reflected my own journey and excited me to support and be a part of it\n3.\n\nAs an advisory board member, what is your role, and what do you enjoy most\nabout your involvement with TEO?\n\ne TEO experience and responsibilities are ever-evolving.\n\nand these changes affect o several ways.\n\nRegardless, I enjoy working with TEO's\nprogramming team, suppor d other colleagues, for sure\n4.\n\nWhat was the most valuable lesson you learned from your own experience\nthat you now bring to your leadership style?\n\nEntrepreneurialism and leadership, in my opinion, are about passion.\n\nYou can't teach somebody the\ndesire to be an entrepreneur.", "char_len": 2287, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::130", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 130, "text": "team, suppor d other colleagues, for sure\n4.\n\nWhat was the most valuable lesson you learned from your own experience\nthat you now bring to your leadership style?\n\nEntrepreneurialism and leadership, in my opinion, are about passion.\n\nYou can't teach somebody the\ndesire to be an entrepreneur.\n\nIn terms of my leadership style, my father used to say that, sometimes\n-or many times-it is actually the person who speaks the quietest who gets the room to listen.\n\nYou\nneed people not just to hear you, but to listen to you.\n\nThat is how you become an effective leader.\n\n5.\n\nIf you could give one piece of advice to aspiring entrepreneurs starting their\njourney, what would it be?\n\nDon't be afraid to hit the floor and get up.\n\nIt's all about how you rebound.\n\nThere are also many\namazing entrepreneurial resources across campus in various forms.\n\nUW-Madison is a big place, and\nit can be daunting, but know that you can just start walking around and opening doors.\n\nMore about Oliver\nAre you a UW-Madison alum or Wisconsin-based\nentrepreneur?\n\nWe want to hear your story.\n\nHelp us celebrate our community of innovation by sharing your high-tech small business\ncommercialization or research journey.\n\nSelected stories will be featured on the website and in our\nnewsletter to inspire the next generation of changemakers.\n\nShare you story with Bonnie\nJoin the Startup Stream community!\n\nWe invite you to join our network of\nUW-Madison innovators and\nentrepreneurs\nUse the button below to be added to our content list.\n\nWe\npromise to only send you the latest activities, insights,\nopportunities, and stories from our office.\n\nfollow us on\nLINKEDIN\nSubscribe Now\nTechnology\nEntrepreneurship Office\nUNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN-MADISON\nTechnology Entrepreneurship Office\nUNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN-MADISON\n1550 Engineering Drive |