elerators, …\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/icorps_boost-3-768x432-1.png)\n\n« Previous events\n\nNext events »\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/03/04/2024-nsf-i-corps-teams-awardees\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/Featured-Image.png)", "char_len": 2152, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::133", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 133, "text": "…\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/icorps_boost-3-768x432-1.png)\n\n« Previous events\n\nNext events »\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/03/04/2024-nsf-i-corps-teams-awardees\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/Featured-Image.png)\n\nThe National Science Foundation (NSF) I-Corps™ Teams program is an immersive, innovative program that facilitates the transformation of invention all the way to impact. This seven-week experiential training program prepares scientists and engineers to extend their focus beyond the university laboratory — accelerating the economic and societal benefits of NSF-funded and other basic research projects that are ready to move toward commercialization.\n\nWidely recognized as an effective training program in the U.S. and internationally, NSF I-Corps addresses four urgent national needs:\n\n1. Training an entrepreneurial workforce\n2. Translating technologies\n3. Enabling positive economic impact\n4. Nurturing an innovation ecosystem\n\nThe UW-Madison local NSF I-Corps program prepares teams to have the skillset and eligibility for success in the NSF I-Corps program. This free, six-week, non-credit, virtual workshop uses evidence-based strategies for achieving entrepreneurial success and is open to research faculty, staff, and students at any higher education institution.\n\nResearch indicates that the primary reason startups fail is the development of products that lack market demand. NSF I-Corps helps entrepreneurs avoid pitfalls by identifying the problem that your customers need to solve. Through this program, participants have the opportunity to network with experienced industry mentors, build a solid foundation for their venture, and enhance their credibility for future funding opportunities. Additionally, completing the local or regional program is the most straightforward path to applying for the NSF I-Corps Team award, which helps cover expenses related to customer discovery up to $50,000.\n\n## **Meet the 2024 UW-Madison NSF I-Corps Teams**", "char_len": 2050, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::134", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 134, "text": "for future funding opportunities. Additionally, completing the local or regional program is the most straightforward path to applying for the NSF I-Corps Team award, which helps cover expenses related to customer discovery up to $50,000.\n\n## **Meet the 2024 UW-Madison NSF I-Corps Teams**\n\nThe 2024 cohort of UW-Madison NSF I-Corps teams comprised a diverse group of researchers, each with a unique project aimed at addressing pressing societal challenges. Here, we meet some of the standout teams and learn more about their groundbreaking work:\n\n## **Biosensor Diagnostics**\n\n![Photo of a young white person with blond hair and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-07-1.png)\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Nathan Novy\n\n![Photo of an Asian Indian man with short black hair and glasses](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-08.png)\n**Technical Lead:** Vatsan Raman\n\n![Photo of a white woman with shoulder length brown hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-09.png)\n**Industry Mentor:** Jennifer Gagne\n\n**Department:** CALS Biochemistry\n\n**Innovation Focus:**\n\nBiosensor Diagnostics is transforming drug testing with a rapid, point-of-care solution designed to prevent overdoses and improve treatment. Their technology:\n\n* Delivers quick, accurate results for immediate clinical action.\n\n* Reduces emergency room stays, lowering healthcare costs.\n\n* Supports critical care settings, including ERs, pain clinics, and maternal-fetal medicine.\n\n**How It Works:**\n\n* Uses protein-based sensors to detect small molecules.\n\n* Employs high-throughput sequencing for enhanced sensitivity.\n\n* Aims to create affordable, paper-based drug tests for widespread use.\n\nThis breakthrough technology ensures faster diagnosis and better patient outcomes—a game-changer for modern healthcare.\n\n## **Face Recognition**\n\n![Photo of a young white male with short, curly blond hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-04.png)\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Harrison Rosenberg", "char_len": 2140, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::135", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 135, "text": "diagnosis and better patient outcomes—a game-changer for modern healthcare.\n\n## **Face Recognition**\n\n![Photo of a young white male with short, curly blond hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-04.png)\n**Entrepreneurial Lead:** Harrison Rosenberg\n\n**![Photo of an Arabic man with short dark hair.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-01.png)****Technical Lead:** Kassem Fawaz\n\n![Photo of an Asian woman with shoulder length black hair.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-05-1.png)\n**Industry Mentor:** Stella Chan\n\n**Department:** COE Electrical & Computer Engineering\n\n**Innovation Focus:**\nThis team is redefining face recognition technology with a system designed for security, fairness, and transparency. Their innovation:\n\n* Creates synthetic facial data to audit and improve AI models.\n\n* Reduces bias in face recognition across diverse demographics.\n\n* Increases accuracy and trust in biometric identification.\n\n**How It Works:**\n\n* Leverages AI-generated face datasets to fine-tune recognition models.\n\n* Helps companies test, validate, and enhance security systems.\n\n* Ensures ethical AI development by making systems auditable and fair.\n\nTheir work is shaping the future of secure and responsible AI-powered identification.\n\n## **Battery Membrane**\n\n**![Photo of a young Asian woman with long brown hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-02.png)****Entrepreneurial Lead:** Jiajie Sui\n\n**![Photo of an older asian man with gray hair](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-03.png)****Technical Lead:** Xudong Wang\n\n**![Photo of an older Arabic man with gray hair and short beard.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/03/2024-Icorps-Team-Photos-06.png)****Industry Mentor:** Nasser Kutkut\n\n**Department:** COE Materials Science & Engineering\n\n**Innovation Focus:**\nBattery Membrane is revolutionizing energy storage with a new ferroelectric battery separator that improves:\n\n* Stability & longevity – Reduces battery failure and extends lifespan.\n\n* Performance – Enhances efficiency by over 20%.", "char_len": 2265, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::136", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 136, "text": "COE Materials Science & Engineering\n\n**Innovation Focus:**\nBattery Membrane is revolutionizing energy storage with a new ferroelectric battery separator that improves:\n\n* Stability & longevity – Reduces battery failure and extends lifespan.\n\n* Performance – Enhances efficiency by over 20%.\n\n* Safety & cost-effectiveness – Prevents short circuits and overheating.\n\n**How It Works:**\n\n* Uses ferroelectric membranes to counteract battery degradation.\n\n* Addresses dendrite growth, a major cause of capacity loss.\n\n* Offers a universal, scalable solution for EVs, renewable energy, and portable devices.\n\nThis breakthrough makes next-generation batteries safer, longer-lasting, and more efficient for a sustainable energy future.\n\n## **Partner with TEO to Advance Your Technology**\n\nJoin the next wave of innovators by engaging with TEO and participating in upcoming NSF I-Corps programs, workshops, and events. Whether you’re at the idea stage or ready to scale, there are plenty of opportunities to bring your vision to life.\n\nWritten By: Madison Sveum\nEdited By: Emma Uren\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2026/01/24/2025-i-corps-year-in-review\n\n![Young middle eastern man wearing glasses and smiling while looking at a computer someone is holding](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-32.png)\n\nBuilding national success in the entrepreneurship space doesn’t happen overnight, but the Technology Entrepreneurship Office’s (TEO’s) steady investment in NSF I-Corps™ program participation has certainly yielded results in 2025. I-Corps is an immersive program that aims to train entrepreneurs, translate technologies, enable positive economic impact, and nurture an innovative ecosystem.\n\n![Visual highlighting the 2025 facts that are included in the paragraph text](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-33-1.png)", "char_len": 1911, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::137", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 137, "text": "aims to train entrepreneurs, translate technologies, enable positive economic impact, and nurture an innovative ecosystem.\n\n![Visual highlighting the 2025 facts that are included in the paragraph text](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/2026-TEO-Spring-NL-Graphics-33-1.png)\n\nIn the UW System, UW–Madison and TEO have facilitated a rise in overall I-Corps participation in 2025, serving over 500 participants across 16 events, three cohorts, and five National Teams. Participation throughout the UW System also increased in 2025, with the first two cohorts alone supporting 36 teams and 97 participants from seven campuses—up from 24 teams, 58 individuals, and just two campuses in 2024. These seven UW campuses joined an additional six universities within the Great Lakes Region for participation in 2025.\n\nTwo of the UW–Madison National I-Corps ELs have been selected for the Early Entrepreneur in Residence (EEIR) program in the newly established Badger Tech Foundry. This complementary program provides training and hands-on development for the strategic development of serial entrepreneurs. It caps participants’ startup experiences, training, and commercialization preparation at UW–Madison before they fully enter the market as newcos.\n\nThe Plan Your Impact program was created as another follow-on option for National I-Corps Teams, which covers 12 weeks of advanced entrepreneurial topics. It focuses on the knowledge and skills needed to thrive in tough tech commercialization, including business fundamentals, intellectual property & licensing, company formation, fundraising, team building & governance, and pitching. The first PYI cohort convened in January and will meet until April.", "char_len": 1721, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::138", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 138, "text": "It focuses on the knowledge and skills needed to thrive in tough tech commercialization, including business fundamentals, intellectual property & licensing, company formation, fundraising, team building & governance, and pitching. The first PYI cohort convened in January and will meet until April.\n\nThe I-Corps mentorship network grew and improved along with participation. TEO developed a mentor video, guide, and process for orientation and development that streamlines effective support. The network now includes mentors from the Great Lakes and other National Hubs, and UW–Madison I-Corps instructors teach for other Hub members and Great Lakes programs. Progress was also made on the Badger Intel-JIT Mentor Matching Platform—the team produced a whitepaper, completed alpha testing, and applied for funding. An AI coaching platform for lagging teams was assessed as an option moving forward.\n\nMarket success for I-Corps participants continued in 2025. Startup companies led by past UW I-Corps ELs saw significant funding, totaling more than $12m. Ubicept, specializing in single-photon imaging and perception, was co-led through UW–Madison I-Corps by Andreas Velten in 2019 and received $8m in funding in 2025. Galasys, featured in last season’s TEO newsletter, is a product of the 2023 I-Corps cohort and received $185k in funding in 2025. SixLine, Alithic, Flux XII, Ninjas Printing, and Dirac Labs are other notable mentions as successfully funded startups from 2025.\n\nOverall, the UW System and UW–Madison specifically have had a fruitful year of I-Corps with the help of TEO. If you are interested in outreach events or joining the next cohort, keep an eye out for announcements on how to get involved in 2026—we’d love to see you there!\n\n• • •\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/12/10/improv-to-improve-science-communication-and-teaching\n\n![Delta Program logo](https://grad.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/329/2023/07/DELTPROGGR_color-flush-1024x372.png)**Days/Times:**Wednesdays 1-3pm, starting January 21 **Instructor:**Anne Lynn Gillian-Daniel **Location:**3545 Engineering Hall\n**Credit:** 1 credit (InterEGR 797)\n**Certificate in Higher Education Teaching and Learning**:\n\n## Course Description", "char_len": 2238, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::139", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 139, "text": "1-3pm, starting January 21 **Instructor:**Anne Lynn Gillian-Daniel **Location:**3545 Engineering Hall\n**Credit:** 1 credit (InterEGR 797)\n**Certificate in Higher Education Teaching and Learning**:\n\n## Course Description\n\nImprov requires the ability to listen carefully, think quickly, and communicate clearly — and so do science communication and teaching.\n\nUsing the storytelling and character-development techniques of theatrical improvisation, participants will build confidence, teamwork, leadership, listening and decision-making skills through the performance of short games and scenes. Participants will be able to better think on their feet, manage a constructivist classroom, and communicate science more effectively to both technical and non-technical audiences. Each session will be comprehensive, diverse, and dynamic (in addition to being a lot of fun), and will build on the skills from the week before. Due to the sequential nature of the class and the necessity of building a supportive learning community, please defer taking the course if you know in advance that your schedule will require you to miss more than two classes.\n\n## What do past participants say?\n\n*“My comfort level speaking/teaching in front of a group has really increased.”*\n\n*“This course helped me build confidence in speaking off the cuff, answering unexpected questions, and responding in the moment to difficult situations. Each week was a new, but welcome, challenge. The instructor created an environment where it felt safe to try new things, make mistakes, and then try again. I never imagined I would take an improv class, but I’m sure glad I did. One of the most enjoyable and rewarding classes I’ve taken!”*\n\n## Want to learn more about this course?\n\nCheck out this podcast episode from Sustainable Nano, where you hear how this course had a lasting impact on two Delta participants.\n\nOr read the article “Using Improvisation to Increase Graduate Students’ Communication Self-Efficacy” from instructor Anne Lynn Gillian-Daniel, which was published in *Change: The Magazine of Higher Learning*.\n\n## Questions?\n\nContact info@delta.wisc.edu\n\nLearn More & Register", "char_len": 2157, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::140", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 140, "text": "Delta participants.\n\nOr read the article “Using Improvisation to Increase Graduate Students’ Communication Self-Efficacy” from instructor Anne Lynn Gillian-Daniel, which was published in *Change: The Magazine of Higher Learning*.\n\n## Questions?\n\nContact info@delta.wisc.edu\n\nLearn More & Register\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/12/10/nsf-i-corps-great-lakes-region-impact-report-december-2025\n\nThe NSF I-Corps Hub: Great Lakes Region has released its **2025 Impact Report**, highlighting more than a decade of outcomes from research-driven entrepreneurship across the Midwest and beyond.\n\nSince 2012, I-Corps–trained teams affiliated with Great Lakes region universities have generated **$1.42 billion in total economic impact**, launched **437 companies**, supported **1,430 jobs**, and evaluated more than **2,400 breakthrough technologies**. These efforts span critical sectors, including healthcare, energy, advanced manufacturing, artificial intelligence, agriculture, and semiconductors.\n\nThe report also features team highlights from each state in the region, showcasing how academic innovations are translated into real-world solutions through customer discovery, commercialization support, and strong connections to the entrepreneurial ecosystem.\n\nThis impact reflects the strength of collaboration among universities, researchers, startups, funders, and industry partners committed to transforming research into societal and economic value.\n\n**Download the full Impact Report** to explore the data, regional insights, and startup stories shaping innovation in the Great Lakes region.\n\nRead Report\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/11/25/new-national-team-solicitation\n\nThe NSF I-Corps™ Great Lakes Hub has circulated a new solicitation for National Teams that introduces several notable changes to program structure, funding, and participation rules. These updates affect timelines, team capacity, travel, and prototyping policies.\n\n**What changed**", "char_len": 1968, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::141", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 141, "text": "NSF I-Corps™ Great Lakes Hub has circulated a new solicitation for National Teams that introduces several notable changes to program structure, funding, and participation rules. These updates affect timelines, team capacity, travel, and prototyping policies.\n\n**What changed**\n\n* **Longer period of performance:** The program period increases to **12 months** from the previous 6 months, giving teams more runway for planning and execution.\n* **Mentor support:** The solicitation **allows $3,000** to support an Industry Mentor (IM) role, signaling a stronger emphasis on industry guidance.\n* **Registration administration:** Allows a registration fee for administration (VentureWell).\n* **More teams:** The total number of teams accepted rises from **200 to 240**, expanding access and competition.\n* **Travel and prototyping restrictions:** International travel is prohibited, and prototyping is no longer allowed, shifting the program toward local, design-focused, or virtual deliverables.\n\nThese changes collectively move the program toward longer, more mentor-supported, and more widely accessible participation while tightening safety, travel, and prototyping constraints. Teams should review the updated solicitation carefully and adjust proposals, budgets, and timelines accordingly.\n\nContact TEO Director Bonnie Bachman with any questions regarding these changes.\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/10/13/3d-powder-tech\n\n![two men stand and talk in a lab with scientific equipment.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/Luis-6-2.jpg)\n\nLaboratory testing delays and inconsistencies aren’t usually a good thing. But sometimes, those very frustrations can cause innovation to spark.\n\nCollege of Engineering Early Entrepreneur in Residence postdoc Dr. Luis Izet Escaño Vólquez and Mechanical Engineering professor Dr. Lianyi Chen, co-founders of 3D Powder Tech  startup, have spent years studying the delicate process of turning powdered metal into customized parts using layers and layers of laser-melted material. To create defect-free parts for aerospace, biomedical, and automotive industries, this printing process requires metal powder to spread easily and evenly.", "char_len": 2199, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::142", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 142, "text": "have spent years studying the delicate process of turning powdered metal into customized parts using layers and layers of laser-melted material. To create defect-free parts for aerospace, biomedical, and automotive industries, this printing process requires metal powder to spread easily and evenly.\n\nEscaño is from the Dominican Republic, where he earned his bachelor’s degree in mechatronics engineering (a multidisciplinary field integrating mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, computer science, and software engineering to develop automated systems) at the Instituto Tecnológico de Santo Domingo. After graduating, he spent a year working as a production line supervisor.\n\nAs he realized his interest in developing technologies, he moved to the U.S. to pursue a Master’s degree—and later enter the PhD program—in manufacturing engineering at the Missouri University of Science and Technology as a student of Chen. He researched powder dynamics and processes in laser powder bed fusion, developing the first device compatible with X-ray imaging to study powder spreading in additive manufacturing. This device is the base for what would become 3D Powder Tech.\n\nWith two years left in his PhD program, Escaño transferred to UW–Madison with Chen. They continued to test new and existing metal alloys for implementation in additive manufacturing. The team quickly found that the process was challenging and unpredictable, as there were no existing powder qualifications standards to ensure the proper melt needed for defect-free parts. This not only resulted in waste, but in delayed lab research.\n\n![a metal bin with silver-gray powder piled on one side](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/10/POWDER-SPREADING-ALSI10MG-2-1.jpg)\n\nAnalysis of alluminum alloy (AlSi10Mg) powder using 3D Powder Tech’s qualification system. Photo by Escaño.", "char_len": 1870, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::143", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 143, "text": "in waste, but in delayed lab research.\n\n![a metal bin with silver-gray powder piled on one side](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/10/POWDER-SPREADING-ALSI10MG-2-1.jpg)\n\nAnalysis of alluminum alloy (AlSi10Mg) powder using 3D Powder Tech’s qualification system. Photo by Escaño.\n\nSo, the team set to work reenvisioning powder dynamics to better predict the spreading process in 3D printing conditions. Their innovative method utilizes in-situ X-ray imaging to analyze the spreading process at a particulate scale, utilizing the first-ever X-ray compatible powder spreading additive manufacturing machine that they designed. They then extended into more ambitious additive technologies under more complex conditions, such as those found in space. This resulted in a unique, first of its kind, X-ray compatible Electron Beam Melting system that completed their innovation path.\n\n“The study provided new understandings of powder behavior, which led us to create and patent a novel method to test the powder’s usability and performance for metal 3D printing,” said Escaño.\n\nOnce their device prototype was up and running, the team realized its many applications in commercial or real-world processes: incorporating novel materials in the production lines, accelerating production through quicker material testing and qualification, increasing printing success rate across 3D metal manufacturing, and enhancing powder recycling.\n\nEscaño and Chen then decided to bring their testing technology to the metal additive manufacturing market. By the end of Escaño’s PhD program in 2023, he and Chen received a WARF patent titled “Powder Deposition Apparatuses and Methods,” which legally protects their innovative powder testing method. During Escaño’s subsequent postdoc at UW, his team took the first steps toward commercialization and pursued campus resources to learn about entrepreneurship, such as Igniter from D2P and NSF I-Corps from TEO. The team also attended the Additive Manufacturing Users Group (AMUG) conference.\n\n![wheel shapes made from silver metal](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/titanium-parts-printed-from-powder-and-a-laser-provide-59d928.jpg)", "char_len": 2203, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::144", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 144, "text": "such as Igniter from D2P and NSF I-Corps from TEO. The team also attended the Additive Manufacturing Users Group (AMUG) conference.\n\n![wheel shapes made from silver metal](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/titanium-parts-printed-from-powder-and-a-laser-provide-59d928.jpg)\n\nTitanium parts printed from powder and a laser are high-strength and heat-resistant. Photo by David McNally/US Army.\n\nI-Corps™ was critical in the entrepreneurial process. The program provided the team early entrepreneurship education, including processes, terms, and practices to take innovation to the marketplace. It also offered additional training on how to interview customers, gather data, and analyze feedback when exploring marketing venues. In summer 2025, Xiujuan Jane Zhang, director of the Advanced Materials Industrial Consortium, mentored Escaño and his team throughout the National Program. This 7-week intensive course awards increased funding and more detailed evaluation.\n\n“I-Corps greatly helped us to organize and establish a better approach in our business. It is a highly recommended experience for those seeking to be entrepreneurs and to acquire the proper skillset and mentality to be successful,” said Escaño.\n\nThe biggest challenge Escaño notes from his startup journey has been shifting from a research-oriented mindset to a commercial one. “The skillset and mentality required to bring technology into market are very different from those required at a laboratory. The ability to create a network and pull individuals to believe in your vision is an art in itself,” he said.\n\nHe has also learned many valuable lessons from the entrepreneurial experience that he would not have learned in the lab alone. The most essential of these? Being open-minded and a good listener. “Your solution, despite being of your own creation, is not perfect and is full of flaws that only customers can bring up,” he continued. “You must constantly be able to change and adapt to the market and the customer’s desires. New technology cannot translate into a business if it’s not tailored for the users.”", "char_len": 2112, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::145", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 145, "text": "despite being of your own creation, is not perfect and is full of flaws that only customers can bring up,” he continued. “You must constantly be able to change and adapt to the market and the customer’s desires. New technology cannot translate into a business if it’s not tailored for the users.”\n\nEscaño and Chen anticipate a bright entrepreneurial future. As their business grows, they are continuously analyzing their business model and asking how other technologies might be implemented. They expect to be leaders of powder qualification in the 3D printing industry—in fact, a new generation of printers might leverage 3D Powder Tech’s understanding of the manufacturing process. Sometimes, short-term lab delays can result in long-term progress.\n\n• • •\n\n*Feature image: Drs. Luis Izet Escaño Vólquez (right) and Lianyi Chen (left) discussing 3D Powder Tech in their lab at UW–Madison. Photo from Escaño Vólquez.*\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/pyi-program\n\n# TEO – Plan Your Impact Program\n\n![Plan Your Impact](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/08/teo-plan-your-impact.png)\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nFirst Session:\n January 21, 2026 @ 10:00 am - 12:00 pm\n\n## Find your pathway to tough tech startup success.\n\nApply by **January 16, 2026** to take part in the Technology Entrepreneurship Office – Plan Your Impact program!\n\nThe Plan Your Impact program is a 12-week training series for entrepreneurial- and commercially-minded postdocs and grad students. The program focuses on the knowledge and skills needed to thrive in tough tech commercialization. It culminates in a pitch event with feedback from experienced investors and entrepreneurs.\n\nLimited capacity is available. Submit your application below.\n\n### PROGRAM HIGHLIGHTS\n\n* Business fundamentals\n* Intellectual property & licensing\n* Company formation\n* Fundraising\n* Building teams, advisory boards, & governance\n* Pitch workshop & presentation\n\n### WHEN\n\nWednesdays\nJanuary 21 – April 15, 2026\n10:00am – 12:00pm\n\n### WHERE (IN-PERSON)\n\nEngineering Centers Building\nRoom 1045\n1550 Engineering Drive\n\n## Apply to PYI\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/10/01/business-model-canvases", "char_len": 2202, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::146", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 146, "text": "advisory boards, & governance\n* Pitch workshop & presentation\n\n### WHEN\n\nWednesdays\nJanuary 21 – April 15, 2026\n10:00am – 12:00pm\n\n### WHERE (IN-PERSON)\n\nEngineering Centers Building\nRoom 1045\n1550 Engineering Drive\n\n## Apply to PYI\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/2025/10/01/business-model-canvases\n\n![A closeup of a white man with short gray hair and glasses speaking to an audience](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/Dan-2400x1600-1-1536x1024-1-1200x800.jpg)\n\nThe Technology Entrepreneurship Office (TEO) is one of many entrepreneurship resources on campus. Dan Olszewski is a skilled entrepreneur and the director of the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship, which is part of the Wisconsin School of Business but assists students across majors with entrepreneurial education, activities, competitions, and programming.\n\nProfessor Olszewski received his undergraduate degree in economics and computer science at UW–Madison, then went on to earn an MBA from Harvard and become a McKinsey consultant. He gained direct entrepreneurial and acquisitions experience with a $450m company. Realizing his interest in teaching, Professor Olszewski joined the UW–Madison faculty and has been part of the business school for the last 20 years. He is also the co-founder of the Morgridge Entrepreneurship Bootcamp, which is a one-week intensive training program in technology entrepreneurship of particular interest for College of Engineering graduate students who might already be involved with TEO.\n\nBut what is Professor Olszewski’s advice for what comes after training, when you have an idea that you’re ready to bring to the market? We asked him about the Business Model Canvas (BMC) and how correctly applying it can help you ask the right questions about your innovation and deliver not only valuable tech, but a sound startup ready for success.\n\n### How is the Business Model Canvas different from a business model, and why might that understanding be important to aspiring entrepreneurs?\n\n**Prof. Olszewski:** The term “business model” actually has a lot of different meanings, and that was probably one of the issues. If someone asked an entrepreneur to show their business model, they might wonder what exactly they wanted—a spreadsheet? Profits and losses?", "char_len": 2282, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::147", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 147, "text": "to aspiring entrepreneurs?\n\n**Prof. Olszewski:** The term “business model” actually has a lot of different meanings, and that was probably one of the issues. If someone asked an entrepreneur to show their business model, they might wonder what exactly they wanted—a spreadsheet? Profits and losses?\n\nThe BMC was a collaborative innovation to determine what is really important in a business model. It created a nine box canvas with numerous iterations, which has become the industry standard in entrepreneurship. Now, when someone asks for your business model, you can actually go through these nine boxes or even put up the canvas—I’ve been at various startups and they’ll actually have their business model printed out on their wall with post-it notes explaining it.\n\nThe BMC has nine different boxes with hypotheses about what your business is. If you’ve validated or invalidated those hypotheses, then you’ll have a pretty good idea of what your business model is and what your business entails. And more importantly, you can efficiently communicate it to someone when you’re explaining your business idea.\n\n### **What are the key elements of the BMC that work well? Are there any pitfalls to avoid if you apply it incorrectly?**\n\n**Prof. Olszewski:** I would say the most important aspects of the BMC, especially for an early-stage entrepreneur, are the target customer segment and the value proposition for that target customer segment. That’s the crux of the BMC and where you want to start to iterate on it, because if you don’t get that right, I’d say the rest of the business model is going to be built on a very weak foundation.\n\n![Chart with nine boxes titled \"Business Mode l Canvas\"](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/Business_Model_Canvas.jpg)\n\nA Business Model Canvas template, where aspiring entrepreneurs can flesh out details about their business. Image by Business Model Foundry.\n\nThat is quickly followed by the revenue stream of how you get paid. Because there are lots of ideas where there’s a customer and value, and it could be very beneficial, but at the end of the day, a company needs to get paid. Figuring out how that’s going to take place is another one of the real critical questions to answer in your business model.", "char_len": 2274, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::148", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 148, "text": "how you get paid. Because there are lots of ideas where there’s a customer and value, and it could be very beneficial, but at the end of the day, a company needs to get paid. Figuring out how that’s going to take place is another one of the real critical questions to answer in your business model.\n\nIt’s also very important that the entrepreneur realizes this is intended to be a living, flexible document. You don’t have to put these things down and set them in concrete, or think, “I’m sure I’m right.” It’s quite the opposite. As you gain new learning, new information, you have to be willing to pivot and change. That is one of the reasons that they often say you want to use post-it notes so that it’s very easy to change when you learn something new and you realize, for example, that value proposition doesn’t actually resonate with that target customer. I’ve discovered a different value proposition that they do care about. It is very much intended to follow a scientific approach to experimentation.\n\n### **How does understanding the BMC ultimately create a better startup or business?**\n\n**Prof. Olszewski:** Firstly, a canvas allows you to communicate what your business is. Numerous times, I’ve met with students who want to tell me about their idea, and at the end of 30 minutes, I still really don’t know what their idea is. They would be talking all about the technology, they’d be showing a website, they’d have all kinds of information that they were imparting, but it wasn’t giving me an understanding of: what *is* your business?\n\nI tell them to fill out the canvas and *then* we’ll meet, and at that point we’ll have a much more productive conversation on what the business is. You can get better feedback that way.\n\n![A large piece of paper with colorful sticky notes placed in chart boxes.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/25542796944_ae5464d29b_o-scaled.jpg)\n\nA canvas with sticky notes in each box. Photo by US Embassy Madrid.", "char_len": 1979, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::149", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 149, "text": "the business is. You can get better feedback that way.\n\n![A large piece of paper with colorful sticky notes placed in chart boxes.](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/25542796944_ae5464d29b_o-scaled.jpg)\n\nA canvas with sticky notes in each box. Photo by US Embassy Madrid.\n\nA BMC is also more flexible. We used to have students write a 50-page business plan that they’ve spent all kinds of time on. These were actually very difficult to make changes to, because when you realized you didn’t have the right target customer, you can’t just do a global replace on it; you have to go through the 50 pages and rethink the logic and all of the references. Students would fight making changes—even though they should—just because it was difficult. Whereas the BMC makes it very easy for people to pivot, to make those changes as they learn something. They then write a business plan later in the process once they feel enough confidence, versus having it be one of the initial steps.\n\n### **What are your top tips for entrepreneurs in TEO looking to learn more about applying the BMC to their tech innovations?**\n\n**Prof. Olszewski:** My first tip would be: don’t view all nine boxes as equally important for every idea. I would say that the three I mentioned—**value proposition, target customer, and revenue stream**—are universally the most important ones. Then, depending on your idea, some of the other boxes may be more or less important. Adjust your effort accordingly.\n\nSecond, the foundation is built on the customer. We call it “**product-market fit**,” which is how your value proposition aligns with your target customer. That foundation is really important, so you’ll want to have a high degree of confidence in it before you spend a lot of time building out your financials and other components.\n\nThird, be very **willing to pivot** and use this as a starting point for your idea, but don’t expect your initial idea to be your ending point. You’re almost assuredly going to learn as you go through the process by talking to customers, running experiments, and you’ll have pivots along the way. Embrace those. Don’t view them as failures—view them as learning opportunities to get you closer to the right answer.\n\n• • •", "char_len": 2249, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::150", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 150, "text": "be your ending point. You’re almost assuredly going to learn as you go through the process by talking to customers, running experiments, and you’ll have pivots along the way. Embrace those. Don’t view them as failures—view them as learning opportunities to get you closer to the right answer.\n\n• • •\n\nFeature image: Dan Olszewski at the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship 25-year celebration in November 2024. Photo by Paul Newby II.\n\nWritten by: Bri Meyer\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/events?past_events=false\n\n« Previous events Today\n\nVirtual June 25, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - July 30, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\nTransform Your Research into Real-World Impact Are you ready to bring your research to life and make a real-world impact? Join our free, six-week virtual workshop, led by the UW-Madison regional NSF I-Corps™ program, and take the …\n\nJuly 20, 2026 @ 5:00 pm - July 22, 2026 @ 7:30 pm\n\nReady to navigate your career path more confidently? Join us for an interactive, in-person workshop led by Andrew L. Shafer, a strategist, business builder, and author of Strategic ROADMAP: An Intentional and Memorable Approach to …\n\nVirtual October 1, 2026 @ 4:45 pm - November 12, 2026 @ 7:00 pm\n\nTranslating Deep Tech Discovery into Economic Benefit A Specialized Virtual NSF I-Corps Cohort | Fall 2026 | Oct 01-Nov 12 | Space is Limited The research landscape is moving into an era that turns frontier …\n\n« Previous events\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/the-activate-fellowship\n\n# The Activate Fellowship\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nJune 1, 2026 @ 9:00 am\n\n![Activate Announces Cohort 2025 Fellowship Applications Are Open, Expecting Another Record Year of Applicants](https://climateinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/activate-1024x576.jpg)\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/Screenshot-2025-09-24-105422.png)\n\n# **Ready to** **Change** **the World?**\n\n### **Start With the Activate Fellowship**\n\nApplications are now open. Complete the applicant interest form to receive the 2026 application.\n\n### **To be** **eligible****, you:**", "char_len": 2061, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::151", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 151, "text": "**Ready to** **Change** **the World?**\n\n### **Start With the Activate Fellowship**\n\nApplications are now open. Complete the applicant interest form to receive the 2026 application.\n\n### **To be** **eligible****, you:**\n\n* Must have a bachelor’s degree and 4+ years of post-baccalaureate scientific research, engineering, or technology development experience.\n* Must be leading the commercial development of a hardware-based technology innovation for the first time if awarded the fellowship, i.e., not a repeat hard tech founder.\n* Must be committed full-time to the proposed project or company if awarded the fellowship.\n* Must be legally able to work in the U.S. for the duration of the fellowship.\n* Must be able to communicate proficiently in English.\n\n### **To be eligible, your proposed project or company…**\n\n* Must be based in the physical or biological sciences or related engineering disciplines.\n* Must still be in development and not yet ready for full-scale product sales at the time of the application deadline.\n* Must not have raised more than $2M in debt or equity funding from non-governmental sources at the time of the application deadline.\n\n### **What we look for**\n\n**Technical Excellence**\n\nAre you deeply knowledgeable in the field of your proposed project to independently and safely lead the technical work involved? Can you communicate complicated, technical concepts to a general audience?\n\n**Leadership**\n\nAre you motivated to grow professionally through the leadership training the fellowship provides? Can you manage conflict and act with integrity through ambiguity to mobilize the resources needed to advance your proposed project?\n\n**Participation**\n\nWill you contribute to a respectful environment where people of all backgrounds feel valued—within the fellowship community and the wider innovation ecosystem?\n\n**Feasibility**\n\nIs your proposed project rooted in sound scientific principles? Does it present a credible path to scale, including viable entry markets or the potential to pivot? Is it reasonably differentiated from existing solutions and commercial efforts?\n\n**Impact Potential**", "char_len": 2127, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::152", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 152, "text": "ecosystem?\n\n**Feasibility**\n\nIs your proposed project rooted in sound scientific principles? Does it present a credible path to scale, including viable entry markets or the potential to pivot? Is it reasonably differentiated from existing solutions and commercial efforts?\n\n**Impact Potential**\n\nIs your project aligned with Activate’s mission of science for good? Will the fellowship meaningfully alter the trajectory of your professional development and your proposed project?\n\nLearn More\n\nReceive Application Link\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/activate-1024x576-1.png)\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/from-research-to-action-understanding-your-market-workshop\n\n# From Research to Action: Understanding Your Market Workshop\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nMay 13, 2026 @ 5:00 pm - 7:30 pm\n\nJoin us for a **free workshop** to help you analyze market trends, uncover customer insights, and refine your business strategy. This hands-on training, led by the Marketing Leadership Institute and UW Business Library expert Peggy Smith, will equip you with the tools to understand market dynamics, conduct B2B or B2C research, and develop data-driven market strategies.\n\n## Who Should Attend?\n\n* **Entrepreneurs & Startup Teams:** Validate your business idea and find new ways to prepare for and improve your pitch.\n* **Students & Researchers:** Gain or expand your understanding of industry trends.\n* **I-Corps Participants & Alumni:** Learn how to use traditional market research methods to elevate your customer discovery skills.\n\n## Workshop Details\n\n### May 13 | 5:00 PM – 7:30 PM (This is one-day session)\n\n**The Fundamentals of Market Research (Presented by Giustina Parisi):** This session will explore key market forces, customer discovery, and research methodologies.\n\n**B2B and B2C Sessions (Instructed by Peggy Smith)****:** Learn industry-specific tools and resources to size and analyze B2B markets, and discover consumer-focused research techniques and strategies to understand your customer base.\n\n### **Location:**\n\nEngineering Centers Building\nRoom 1045\n1550 Engineering Drive\n\n### **About the Instructors:**\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/Giustina-300x300.jpg)", "char_len": 2243, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::153", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 153, "text": "and discover consumer-focused research techniques and strategies to understand your customer base.\n\n### **Location:**\n\nEngineering Centers Building\nRoom 1045\n1550 Engineering Drive\n\n### **About the Instructors:**\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/03/Giustina-300x300.jpg)\n\nGiustina Parisi is a Teaching Faculty III in Marketing at the University of Wisconsin–Madison’s Wisconsin School of Business. She specializes in marketing and consumer insights, with prior industry experience at companies such as Procter & Gamble, Kraft Heinz, and American Family Insurance.\n\n### **Photo of Peggy Smith, a white woman with curly dark hair who is wearing glasses.**\n\nPeggy Smith is a Senior Academic Librarian at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, specializing in business research and data management. She supports students and faculty with their research needs and is a key contributor to the Marketing Leadership Institute, with particular expertise in B2B and B2C market research. Peggy is passionate about empowering others through knowledge and is dedicated to fostering a collaborative learning environment while advancing the field of market research at UW-Madison.\n\nDon’t miss this amazing FREE professional development opportunity!\n\nRegister Now\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/2026-spring-nsf-i-corps-learning-session\n\n# 2026 Spring NSF I-Corps Learning Session\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nVirtual\n April 21, 2026 @ 12:00 pm - 1:00 pm\n\n## Transform Your STEM Discoveries into Impact\n\nJoin us for a dynamic session designed to help you explore entrepreneurship and determine whether the **NSF I-Corps™ program** is the right fit for your goals.\n\nHosted by the **Technology Entrepreneurship Office (TEO)**, this session will introduce the full spectrum of I-Corps opportunities—local, regional, and national—and how they support researchers in translating discoveries into market-ready solutions.\n\nYou’ll also get a first look at other high-impact programs that support early-stage innovation, including:\n\n* **Engine Blueprint**\n* **Activate Fellowship**\n* **Boost** (new program)\n\nThese programs are designed to help you evaluate the commercial potential of your STEM research and connect with resources to move your ideas forward.", "char_len": 2266, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::154", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 154, "text": "high-impact programs that support early-stage innovation, including:\n\n* **Engine Blueprint**\n* **Activate Fellowship**\n* **Boost** (new program)\n\nThese programs are designed to help you evaluate the commercial potential of your STEM research and connect with resources to move your ideas forward.\n\nThis session is brought to you in collaboration with the **Great Lakes NSF I-Corps Hub**.\n\n### **Spring 2026 NSF I-Corps Cohort Info Session**\n\n**Tuesday, April 21st** | 12:00–1:00 PM CT | *Virtual*\n\nRegister Here!\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/trandscend-comp-2026\n\n# 11th Annual Transcend UW Pitch Competition\n\n![Transcend logo with a photo of two men talking to another person](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/transcend-imageArtboard-1.png)\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nApril 16, 2026 @ 9:00 am - April 17, 2026\n\nTranscend UW is campus’s premier student-led entrepreneurship & startup organization, and they are hosting their 11th-annual **Pitch Competition**. For students interested in participating, read more details on eligibility here and apply at this link by February 16th to secure your spot.\n\nThe Pitch Competition is Transcend’s main event in which participants compete for up to $50k in prize money and network with a growing entrepreneurial ecosystem across Wisconsin. Transcend encourages cross-disciplinary collaboration on ventures that have a social or environmental impacts. Students from all majors are welcome to apply or attend.\n\nParticipating members attend weeks of events to build and adjust their pitches, including an Intellectual Property Seminar, Project Review Session, and Business Model Training. Attendance to the competition itself is open, with two days of poster sessions and pitch placement rounds. Winners of top three and general prizes are announced after pitches on the second day.\n\nIf you are interested in sponsorship or have questions, please reach out to Transcend leadership at transcenduw@gmail.com. We hope to see you there!\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/cs-nest-spring-2026\n\n# CS NEST Spring 2026\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nFebruary 6, 2026 @ 9:00 am\n\n### Program Overview", "char_len": 2166, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::155", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 155, "text": "interested in sponsorship or have questions, please reach out to Transcend leadership at transcenduw@gmail.com. We hope to see you there!\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/cs-nest-spring-2026\n\n# CS NEST Spring 2026\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nFebruary 6, 2026 @ 9:00 am\n\n### Program Overview\n\nCS NEST is a free, ten-week venture-creation workshop designed to help entrepreneurially minded students and technologists create high-growth startups. Get product ideas, mentorship, and one-on-one coaching to develop a high-growth startup company. CS NEST is a program of a nationally ranked startup accelerator, gener8tor.\n\n**CS NEST program looks like:**\n\n* **Product Development:** Ideate, validate and build minimum viable products (MVPs).\n* **Culture:** Experience first-hand the challenges, but also tremendous benefit, of iterating quickly with minimal resources in solving business problems.\n* **Methodology:** Come away with a roadmap for testing new ideas through the design of an MVP.\n* **Next Steps:** Understand what you need to do to continue growing your company, and access other resources within gener8tor’s network to help.\n\n### Eligibility Criteria for CS NEST:\n\n1- **Location:** CS NEST is a venture-creation workshop for University of Wisconsin students and technologists in Madison, Wisconsin.\n\n2- **You’re Committed:** CS NEST provides product ideas, mentorship, and coaching, then works with each team one-on-one for 10 weeks to help develop ideas.\n\n3- **Entrepreneurial Mindset:** We’re seeking entrepreneurially minded individuals or teams who are ready to dive in and learn more about startups.\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| **Application Deadline** | February 6th, 2026 |\n| **Program Kickoff** | February 6th, 2026 |\n| **Program End** | April 22nd, 2026 |\n\nLearn More and Apply\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2026/01/Screenshot-2026-01-15-171033.png)\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/pyi-virtual\n\n# TEO – Plan Your Impact Program Virtual Cohort\n\n![Plan Your Impact Virtual Cohort](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/11/TEO-Event-Web-Graphic-2.png)\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nFirst session:\n January 21, 2026 @ 10:00 am - 12:00 pm\n\n## Find your pathway to tough tech startup success, with the ease of virtual attendance.", "char_len": 2294, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::156", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 156, "text": "Your Impact Virtual Cohort](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/11/TEO-Event-Web-Graphic-2.png)\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nFirst session:\n January 21, 2026 @ 10:00 am - 12:00 pm\n\n## Find your pathway to tough tech startup success, with the ease of virtual attendance.\n\n**Now open to all UW System schools**, apply by **December 19, 2025** to take part in the remote Technology Entrepreneurship Office – Plan Your Impact program!\n\nThe Plan Your Impact program is a 12-week training series for entrepreneurial- and commercially-minded postdocs and grad students. The program focuses on the knowledge and skills needed to thrive in tough tech commercialization. It culminates in a pitch event with feedback from experienced investors and entrepreneurs.\n\nLimited capacity is available. Submit your application below.\n\n**If you are affiliated with UW–Madison, please use this link to apply for the in-person cohort.**\n\n### PROGRAM HIGHLIGHTS\n\n* Business fundamentals\n* Intellectual property & licensing\n* Company formation\n* Fundraising\n* Building teams, advisory boards, & governance\n* Pitch workshop & presentation\n\n### WHEN\n\nWednesdays\nJanuary 21 – April 15, 2026\n10:00am – 12:00pm\n\n### WHERE (VIRTUAL)\n\nZoom attendance link to be sent\n\n## Apply to PYI - Virtual\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/fall-2025-nsf-i-corps-learning-session\n\n# Learning Session for the 2025 Spring NSF I-Corps Cohort\n\n![Photo of a white man with a beard wearing glasses looking at code on a computer](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/07/2025-TEO-Fall-Learning-Session-4-graphic-for-event-page.png)\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\nVirtual Event\n November 6, 2025 @ 12:00 pm - 1:00 pm\n\n## Transform Your STEM Discoveries into Impact\n\nJoin us for a dynamic session designed to help you explore entrepreneurship and determine whether the **NSF I-Corps™ program** is the right fit for your goals.\n\nHosted by the **Technology Entrepreneurship Office (TEO)**, this session will introduce the full spectrum of I-Corps opportunities—local, regional, and national—and how they support researchers in translating discoveries into market-ready solutions.\n\nYou’ll also get a first look at other high-impact programs that support early-stage innovation, including:", "char_len": 2272, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-entrepreneurship-office::157", "doc_slug": "tech-entrepreneurship-office", "chunk_index": 157, "text": "this session will introduce the full spectrum of I-Corps opportunities—local, regional, and national—and how they support researchers in translating discoveries into market-ready solutions.\n\nYou’ll also get a first look at other high-impact programs that support early-stage innovation, including:\n\n* **Engine Blueprint**\n* **Activate Fellowship**\n* **Boost** (new for this year!)\n\nThese programs are designed to help you evaluate the commercial potential of your STEM research and connect with resources to move your ideas forward.\n\nThis session is brought to you in collaboration with the **Great Lakes NSF I-Corps Hub**.\n\n### **Spring 2026 NSF I-Corps Cohort Info Session**\n\n**Thursday, November 6** | 12:00–1:00 PM CT | *Virtual*\n\nRegister Here!\n\n## [page] https://teo.wisc.edu/event/1770\n\n# 2025 Early Stage Symposium\n\n**This event has passed.**\n\n1 John Nolen Drive, Madison, Wisconsin\n November 5, 2025 @ 9:00 am - November 6, 2025 @ 5:00 pm\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/2025-ESS-CVENT-770X2952.png)\n\nCalling all entrepreneurs! Applications are now being accepted for the **Wisconsin Technology Council’s** 2025 Early Stage Symposium, taking place Nov. 5-6 at the Monona Terrace in Madison.\n\nThis year’s conference theme is “The spark starts here: Igniting Wisconsin’s next hot ventures” and features four unique opportunities for founders to get in front of investors:\n\n🎤 Open Mic Quick Pitches – 2-minute founder stories, no Q&A.\n\n💡 Tech Council Investor Networks Track – 5-minute presentations from 20+ startups\n\n🏆 Elevator Pitch Olympics – 90-second pitches scored live by investors\n\n🤝 Investor Intros – pre-scheduled, one-on-one meetings with angels & VCs from Wisconsin and beyond\n\nApply Now\n\nApplicants can register at a steeply discounted $79 rate, which includes four meals, networking, your company profile in the investor-only booklet and much more. Bonus: Entrepreneurs who register and fill out their application can also reserve free table space during networking sessions (limited availability).\n\n🗓 Deadline to apply: Friday, Oct. 3 at 5 p.m. Don’t miss this chance to be seen, heard and make connections that could spark your next\n\n![](https://teo.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2156/2025/09/2025-ESS-CVENT-770X2952.png)", "char_len": 2280, "id": 3, "source": "Tech Entrepreneurship Office", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://teo.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::0", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu\n\n## The Tech Exploration Lab\n\n**Where emerging technologies meet real-world problems.**\n\nWe activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison — connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n---\n\n### What We Do\n\nWe’re a front-end venture engine and campus-wide activation resource — not a classroom, an accelerator, or a consulting shop. We specialize in early-stage: the messy, high-potential space where curiosity becomes evidence and ideas become ventures worth backing.\n\nWe work in two directions: students bring ideas and we help them find out if they’re worth building. Industry partners, researchers, and faculty bring real problems and early-stage technologies and we activate student teams to explore, prototype, and assess what’s possible.\n\nEverything culminates at Demo Night — our bi-annual showcase of student ventures, industry innovation, and research translation.\n\n---\n\n### Who It’s For\n\n**Students** Explore emerging technology, build an early venture, or work on real industry and research challenges. From Open Labs and Build Nights to the Venture Pathway and Applied Industry and Research Innovation projects — there’s a place for you here.\n**[Start Here →]**\n\n**Industry Partners** Bring a real problem, anchor a challenge or hackathon, or sponsor innovation. A low-risk way to explore what’s possible with AI and emerging technologies — with the student talent who will build what’s next.\n**[Work With Us →]**\n\n**Researchers & Faculty** Surface challenges in your domain and activate student teams to build toward solutions. Or bring early-stage research with commercial potential and let us help you explore whether it can go somewhere.\n**[Explore Research Translation →]**", "char_len": 1830, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::1", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "what’s next.\n**[Work With Us →]**\n\n**Researchers & Faculty** Surface challenges in your domain and activate student teams to build toward solutions. Or bring early-stage research with commercial potential and let us help you explore whether it can go somewhere.\n**[Explore Research Translation →]**\n\n**Alumni** Mentor teams, bring a venture, join the Technology & Innovation Circle, or give to the Lab. Stay connected to what’s being built — and help shape what comes next.\n**[Get Involved →]**\n\n---\n\n### What People Are Saying\n\n*“Working on DermaVision through the Tech Exploration Lab has been one of my most meaningful experiences at UW–Madison. The Lab connected me with peers passionate about AI and healthcare, provided access to advanced tools and mentorship, and helped me turn an early idea into real progress. It’s more than a lab — it’s a launchpad.”* — UW–Madison Student Innovator\n\n*“The Lab is unique in that it connects students from across campus with advanced tools and industry mentorship to rapidly prototype and gain essential skills for an increasingly AI-driven world. It’s exciting to watch entrepreneurial ideas develop, and there is significant value in bringing the best of Google’s AI to support students’ exploration.”* — Kristin Storhoff, Google\n\n*“I came to the UW Tech Exploration Lab to mentor, but left with momentum. The Lab gave me the space — and the spark — to test a wellness idea I’d been quietly incubating. Working with sharp, driven students helped turn that early vision into a viable concept. It was a powerful reminder that innovation thrives on curiosity, collaboration, and a little Badger grit.”* — UW Alum and Lab Mentor\n\n[**See more testimonials**]\n\n---\n\n### About the UW Tech Exploration Lab\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab, led by the Wisconsin School of Business in collaboration with the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery, is where ideas and emerging technologies become real-world innovations and ventures.\n\n## See What's Happening in the Lab\n\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/LEL-springboard-150x150.jpg)\n\n### The UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/09/20250912_190648-150x150.jpg)", "char_len": 2268, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::2", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "Happening in the Lab\n\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/LEL-springboard-150x150.jpg)\n\n### The UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/09/20250912_190648-150x150.jpg)\n\n### The Lab’s Summer Kickoff: Get Plugged In\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/2c0118c6-c89b-4cae-b142-88736748a3fa-400-150x150.jpg)\n\n### UW Tech Exploration Lab in San Francisco: Founder Lab Networking\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/networking-150x150.jpeg)\n\n### How Fundable Is Your Startup?\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/ally-2-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Founder Lab Feedback Panel\n* More News\n  More\n\n## Hear What People Are Saying About the Lab\n\n## Contact Us\n\n## Sign up for Lab News and Updates\n\nJoin our email list for occasional news from the Lab.\n\n![UW Tech Exploration Lab Subscribe](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/04/subscribe-tel-150x150.png)![LinkedIn](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/03/li-150x150.png) ![discord](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/03/discord-150x150.png)\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/for-students\n\n## **Build something real.**\n\nThe Lab is for students who want to do more than study emerging technology — they want to activate it. Whether you’re launching a venture, experimenting with AI and emerging technologies on real industry and research problems, or just starting to explore, there’s a place for you here.\n\nMost of our formal programs have applications at the start of each semester. But you don’t need to be in a program to build with us. Show up, get involved, and let the work tell you where you belong.\n\n## Find Your Path\n\n### I have an idea I want to build into a venture. **→ TEL Venture Pathway**\n\nThe Lab’s structured track for student founders. Move from early concept to early-stage venture through three stages — Explore & Discover, Venture Build, and Founder Lab — with industry mentors, alumni advisors, and real-world interactdion at every step.", "char_len": 2265, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::3", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 3, "text": "into a venture. **→ TEL Venture Pathway**\n\nThe Lab’s structured track for student founders. Move from early concept to early-stage venture through three stages — Explore & Discover, Venture Build, and Founder Lab — with industry mentors, alumni advisors, and real-world interactdion at every step.\n\n[**Learn more about the Venture Pathway** →]\n\n### I want to work on real industry and research problems and build hands-on experience. **→ Applied Innovation & Commercialization Lab Fellows**\n\nNot every student wants to launch a startup. Students who join our Applied Innovation & Commercialization projects work on real problems brought by industry partners and campus researchers, applying AI and emerging technologies to challenges that don’t have easy answers yet. You’ll build proof of output, develop applied skills, and gain hands-on experience working at the frontier of emerging technology in a real-world context.\n\nWe’re early-stage by design — helping companies experiment with emerging technologies in a low-risk environment, and helping researchers get early signal on whether their work has commercial potential. It’s specific, valuable work, and students who thrive here tend to be the ones who want to go deep on a real problem and come out with something to show for it.\n\nStudents selected for these projects are designated as Applied Innovation & Commercialization Lab Fellows, earned through real project work with industry and research partners.\n\n![Tyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0662-300x225.jpg)\n\nTyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.\n\n### I want to work inside the Lab and help other students build. **→ TEL Lab Fellows**\n\nTEL Lab Fellows are the Lab’s undergraduate student hires — paid positions for students who want to work at the frontier of emerging technology, contribute to real Lab experiments, and help other students find their footing across all tracks.", "char_len": 2043, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::4", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 4, "text": "and help other students build. **→ TEL Lab Fellows**\n\nTEL Lab Fellows are the Lab’s undergraduate student hires — paid positions for students who want to work at the frontier of emerging technology, contribute to real Lab experiments, and help other students find their footing across all tracks.\n\nAs a Lab Fellow you’ll run experiments with AI and frontier tools, support Lab operations, and serve as a peer mentor embedded in the work — connecting students to resources, programs, and each other. It’s the kind of role that builds a resume and a reputation.\n\nTEL Lab Fellows work inside the Lab on frontier technology experiments and peer mentorship. Applied Innovation & Commercialization project students earn the same Lab Fellow designation through project-based work with industry and research partners.\n\nLab Fellow positions are part of a two-tier fellowship structure alongside our graduate-level Leadership Fellows. Applications open each semester.\n\n[**Learn more Lab Fellows** →]\n\n### You Don’t Need an Application to Start\n\nSome of our programs have applications at the beginning of each semester. But here’s the important part — you don’t need to be in a formal program to build with us.\n\nStarting the first week of September, everyone can plug into:\n\n* **Weekly Open Labs** — Mondays & Wednesdays\n* **Friday Build Nights** — Check the calendar and let us know you’re coming\n* **Workshops & skill-building sessions**\n* **Challenges and Hackathons**\n* **Volunteer opportunities**\n* **Monthly networking events** — alumni, mentor, and industry pop-ups (check the calendar)\n\nWhether you’re startup-curious, building your first prototype, or deep into applied AI — there’s a place for you here. Most events are on the main level of 1403 University Ave. unless stated otherwise.\n\nThe best way to stay plugged in: subscribe to our email list, join Discord, and follow our calendar.\n\n**Let’s build what’s next.**\n\n## Find Us\n\n**1403 University Ave., Madison, WI**\n\nLook for the tan building marked 1403 on University Ave. (the same location as the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub)", "char_len": 2084, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::5", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 5, "text": "best way to stay plugged in: subscribe to our email list, join Discord, and follow our calendar.\n\n**Let’s build what’s next.**\n\n## Find Us\n\n**1403 University Ave., Madison, WI**\n\nLook for the tan building marked 1403 on University Ave. (the same location as the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub)\n\n* **Main level events** — enter through the double glass doors facing University Ave.\n* **Second floor events** — walk to the west side of the building (Lorch Street side), enter through the double glass doors facing the loading zone, then head upstairs.\n\n**About the UW Tech Exploration Lab**\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/tel-venture-pathway\n\n## The TEL Venture Pathway\n\n**Your idea. Sharpened by the real world.**\n\nThe Venture Pathway is the Lab’s structured track for students ready to activate an idea at the frontier of emerging technology. What makes it different: you’re never working in a vacuum. At every stage, your idea is pressure-tested against real industry context — through mentors who’ve built companies, alumni who’ve navigated the problems you’re facing, and industry partners who can turn a promising concept into a live pilot.\n\nWe specialize in early-stage. The messy, uncertain, high-potential space before a venture is fully formed. We help you move from curiosity to evidence, and from evidence to a venture worth pursuing.\n\nYou can move through the stages in sequence, or enter at the stage that matches where you are. Teams with equivalent experience can participate in Venture Build or Founder Lab.\n\nAll pathway teams present at **Demo Night**, the Lab’s bi-annual showcase of student ventures, industry innovation, and research-to-market projects.\n\n### Stage 1: Explore & Discover – Fall 2026\n\n**Activate your idea. Test it against what’s real.**", "char_len": 2086, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::6", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 6, "text": "can participate in Venture Build or Founder Lab.\n\nAll pathway teams present at **Demo Night**, the Lab’s bi-annual showcase of student ventures, industry innovation, and research-to-market projects.\n\n### Stage 1: Explore & Discover – Fall 2026\n\n**Activate your idea. Test it against what’s real.**\n\nThis is where the work begins — and where most founders discover whether their idea holds up outside their own head. You bring the concept. We bring the context: industry mentors who surface relevant challenges, alumni who’ve built in your space, and a community of other students working at the frontier of emerging technology and real-world problems.\n\nTrack participants get access to mentors, structured frameworks, build resources, team members, and direct engagement with industry and alumni advisors. The goal isn’t a finished product — it’s clarity on whether your idea is worth pursuing and what the next step should be.\n\nAnyone can attend Build Nights, hackathons, and Lab events. But track support is limited — cohort size is capped, so apply early.\n\n**→ Applications for Explore & Discover** will be available in mid-September.\n\n### Stage 2: Venture Build – Fall 2026\n\n**From discovery to development.**\n\nVenture Build is where ideas and early prototypes evolve into credible venture opportunities. Teams enter with a clear problem and a validated idea or functional demo — and leave with market traction, proof points, and a compelling business case.\n\nThe real-world thread runs through every part of this program. Industry-connected mentors and alumni advisors bring live market context to your validation work. Wisconsin School of Business MBA collaborators — specialists in new product innovation — work over the semester to translate technical momentum into strategy.\n\nTogether, teams deepen market framing, strengthen value propositions, shape go-to-market strategy, and prepare for early adoption — culminating in a **Final Pitch Night** with investors and VCs focused on early-stage tech innovation.", "char_len": 2017, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::7", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 7, "text": "over the semester to translate technical momentum into strategy.\n\nTogether, teams deepen market framing, strengthen value propositions, shape go-to-market strategy, and prepare for early adoption — culminating in a **Final Pitch Night** with investors and VCs focused on early-stage tech innovation.\n\n**Who’s eligible:** Teams should have a prototype or proof-of-concept — even if early. Strong candidates come from Explore & Discovery, UW sandbox or hackathon projects, or independent work with a technical prototype already underway. Not sure if you’re ready? Apply anyway — we’ll help determine the best entry point.\n\n**Applications open August 28, 2026. Kickoff September 2026.**\n\n### Stage 3: Founder Lab – Spring 2027\n\n**Invitation-only. Pilot your venture in the real world.**\n\nFounder Lab is the Lab’s most advanced pathway — a venture launchpad for founders ready to move beyond validation into live market testing. Here, industry partners don’t just advise — they provide authentic test beds where you pilot your idea against real constraints, real users, and real feedback. This is not a class. It’s a test-and-learn build environment.\n\nFounder Lab teams receive dedicated mentors and technical advisors, applied AI and emerging technology resources, and structured sprints focused on piloting solutions, product-market fit, and go-to-market readiness.\n\nTeams operate on a light founder cadence — peer feedback sessions and milestone check-ins throughout the semester — culminating in a **trip to San Francisco** in the summer for ecosystem immersion, feedback from alumni founders, venture partners, and innovation leaders, and exposure to what comes next on the startup journey.\n\n**Who it’s for:** Founders who have already built something — a prototype, MVP, or working concept — validated with real users and ready to test in live market conditions. Prior Lab participation or equivalent entrepreneurial experience required.\n\nFounder Lab is invitation or referral only. Questions or want to refer a team? **Contact Sandra Bradley, Executive Director → sandra.bradley@wisc.edu**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/applied-innovation-commercialization\n\n## **Work at the frontier. Build real skills.**", "char_len": 2225, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::8", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 8, "text": "required.\n\nFounder Lab is invitation or referral only. Questions or want to refer a team? **Contact Sandra Bradley, Executive Director → sandra.bradley@wisc.edu**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/applied-innovation-commercialization\n\n## **Work at the frontier. Build real skills.**\n\nLab Fellows are undergraduate and graduate students who do real work at the UW Tech Exploration Lab at the frontier of emerging technology, on problems that matter. There are two paths into a Lab Fellowship.\n\n## Applied Innovation & Commercialization Lab Fellows\n\n**Go deep on real problems. Build proof of work.**\n\nApplied Innovation & Commercialization Lab Fellows work on project-based engagements with industry partners and campus researchers exploring what’s possible with AI and emerging technologies. We’re early-stage by design — structured experimentation, not production development. Low-risk for partners, high-learning for students.\n\nProjects draw from computer science, engineering, design, business, data science, AR/VR, and more. Students commit approximately 8–10 hours per week and are paid a stipend or hourly rate based on effort and project length.\n\n**Industry Innovation** — industry partners bring real problems and genuine curiosity. Student teams explore use cases, build early prototypes, and generate insight that helps companies decide whether and how to move forward.\n\n**Research & Translational Innovation** — researchers bring early-stage ideas with commercial potential. Student teams help answer the question: is there a use case here, and what would it take to get there?\n\nProjects come in on a rolling basis and teams are built based on project needs — not a semester calendar. The students we match most often are the ones we already know from Build Nights and other events and Lab programs. A form tells us your skills. Showing up tells us who you are.\n\n## TEL Lab Fellows\n\n**Work inside the Lab. Help others build.**\n\nTEL Lab Fellows are the Lab’s internal student hires — paid hourly positions for students who want to run experiments with AI and frontier tools, support Lab operations, and serve as peer mentors across all tracks.", "char_len": 2166, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::9", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 9, "text": "us who you are.\n\n## TEL Lab Fellows\n\n**Work inside the Lab. Help others build.**\n\nTEL Lab Fellows are the Lab’s internal student hires — paid hourly positions for students who want to run experiments with AI and frontier tools, support Lab operations, and serve as peer mentors across all tracks.\n\nYou’ll know what’s happening in the Lab before anyone else, and you’ll help shape how it happens. TEL Lab Fellows are part of a two-tier fellowship structure alongside our graduate-level Leadership Fellows.\n\n**Who it’s for:** Students already plugged into the Lab — showing up, curious about how it operates, and ready to contribute beyond their own projects.\n\n**→ We are working on updating our Lab Fellow Interest Form for both Applied Innovation & Commercialization and TEL roles. Check back soon.**\n\nMeanwhile, come to Open Labs, join a Build Night, participate in Challenges and Hackathons, and attend industry and alumni events. These aren’t just ways to pass the time — they’re how you become someone we think of first.\n\n**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar. You can also email us with questions.**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/for-researchers-faculty\n\n## **You see the big problems. We help activate the solutions.**\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab connects researchers and faculty with cross-disciplinary student teams ready to tackle hard, meaningful challenges — building early prototypes, assessing market potential, and developing go-to-market strategies using AI and emerging technologies.\n\nWe work in two ways: activating student teams around challenges in your domain, and helping translate early-stage research into commercially viable opportunities. Either way, the work is real, the students are builders, and the output is something you can actually use.\n\n### Two Ways to Work With Us\n\n#### Surface a Challenge — Activate a Solution\n\nYou know your field. You see the problems that aren’t being solved, the inefficiencies that persist, the gaps that matter. We help you bring those challenges to student teams who will ideate, prototype, and build toward real solutions using AI and emerging technologies.", "char_len": 2256, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::10", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 10, "text": "— Activate a Solution\n\nYou know your field. You see the problems that aren’t being solved, the inefficiencies that persist, the gaps that matter. We help you bring those challenges to student teams who will ideate, prototype, and build toward real solutions using AI and emerging technologies.\n\nThis is fast, hands-on, and grounded in your domain expertise. We work with you to surface and frame the challenge, then activate students through hackathons, build sprints, and focused project engagements to develop early-stage solutions.\n\n**Example — UW School of Veterinary Medicine** A Vet Med researcher identified a critical communication gap in the dairy industry: veterinarians and farm workers — many of whom are ESL speakers — struggle to communicate effectively in high-stakes environments. The Lab activated a student team that is now prototyping a real-time AI translation tool designed specifically for veterinary and agricultural contexts. A real-world problem, a practical solution, built by students with the tools to make it work.\n\n#### Translate Research Into Commercial Opportunity\n\nHave early-stage technology or research with commercial potential that hasn’t been tested against a market yet? The Lab helps you find out whether it can go somewhere — and what it would take to get there.\n\nStudent teams help answer the questions that matter most at this stage:\n\n* Is there a real use case here?\n* Who would buy this, and why?\n* What would an early MVP look like?\n* What’s the path to commercial application?\n\nTeams combine technical building capability — prototyping with AI and emerging technologies — with business intelligence, market analysis, and go-to-market strategy. The output is real evidence about your technology’s commercial potential and a clearer sense of next steps.\n\n### What You Get\n\nAcross both engagement models, researcher and faculty partners get access to:", "char_len": 1895, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::11", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 11, "text": "technologies — with business intelligence, market analysis, and go-to-market strategy. The output is real evidence about your technology’s commercial potential and a clearer sense of next steps.\n\n### What You Get\n\nAcross both engagement models, researcher and faculty partners get access to:\n\n* **Technical students** who build early prototypes and MVPs using AI and emerging technologies\n* **Business students** who assess market potential, develop business models, and shape go-to-market strategy\n* **Structured experimentation** designed to generate insight quickly without committing significant internal resources\n* **Early signal** on whether a challenge has a viable solution or a technology has commercial legs\n\n### Some Examples of Campus & Research Translation\n\nA growing area of Lab work involves bridging the gap between university research and real-world application — helping faculty and researchers assess the venture potential of promising work and find pathways to bring it to market.\n\n* **School of Veterinary Medicine Translation Tool** — A real-time AI translation tool improving communication between English-speaking veterinarians and Spanish-speaking dairy farm workers, developed in direct partnership with the UW School of Veterinary Medicine.\n* **ARHat+** — Built on UW-Madison research, a smartphone-based LiDAR and AR tool that rapidly identifies home safety risks and aging-in-place modifications, streamlining documentation for care professionals and integrating with EHR and insurance systems.\n* **RAAS (Robotics-as-a-Service)** — A commercialization enablement platform that gives university robotics researchers a structured path from lab to market readiness, reducing technical fragmentation and accelerating development timelines.\n* **AI Research Assistant** — An AI model designed to streamline workflows and improve outcomes for academic researchers across synthesis, analysis, and discovery.\n* **Chatbot for Entrepreneurs** — A conversational AI tool helping small business owners and entrepreneurs navigate uncertainty and make more confident planning decisions.\n\n### How It Works", "char_len": 2119, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::12", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 12, "text": "streamline workflows and improve outcomes for academic researchers across synthesis, analysis, and discovery.\n* **Chatbot for Entrepreneurs** — A conversational AI tool helping small business owners and entrepreneurs navigate uncertainty and make more confident planning decisions.\n\n### How It Works\n\nEngagements are scoped based on your project’s requirements and stage — from focused hackathons and build sprints to semester-long project engagements. Students commit approximately 8–10 hours per week and are paid through a project stipend or hourly arrangement funded by the researcher or faculty partner.\n\nIf you have a challenge worth solving or a technology worth translating, the first step is a conversation.\n\n**Contact us to learn more**\n\n---\n\n### About the UW Tech Exploration Lab\n\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/for-companies\n\n**![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/20250709_120338-hackathon-1024x576.jpg)Build and test what’s next. With the people who will build it.**\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab connects industry partners with cross-disciplinary student teams to explore real problems, prototype solutions, and surface new use cases and venture opportunities using AI and emerging technologies.\n\nWe’re early-stage by design. This isn’t advisory or theoretical work — teams are building, testing, and advancing ideas in real time. You don’t have to have it all figured out. We’ll help you shape and guide the process.\n\n### Start Here: Join the Technology & Innovation Circle\n\nThe Technology & Innovation Circle is the easiest way to plug into the Lab. It’s a warm, on-demand network of industry leaders, founders, and innovation practitioners who stay connected to what the Lab is building and learning.", "char_len": 2070, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::13", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 13, "text": "the process.\n\n### Start Here: Join the Technology & Innovation Circle\n\nThe Technology & Innovation Circle is the easiest way to plug into the Lab. It’s a warm, on-demand network of industry leaders, founders, and innovation practitioners who stay connected to what the Lab is building and learning.\n\nAs a Circle member you’ll hear about Lab programs, emerging needs, and student ventures as they develop. We’ll reach out when there’s something worth sharing or a need you might be able to help fill — a student team that could use your perspective, a challenge in your space, an event worth attending. You choose how and when to engage.\n\nParticipation is free, flexible, and designed to fit around your schedule.\n\n**→ Complete this form if you are interested in joining the Circle to hear about alumni and industry engagement opportunities**\n\n## Ways to Engage\n\n### Bring a Problem\n\nPartner with a student team to explore a real challenge in your organization — a use case you want to test, a technology you want to understand, or a question you want answered. Student teams apply AI and emerging technologies to generate insight, early prototypes, and evidence that helps you decide whether and how to move forward.\n\nThis is structured experimentation — low-risk for your organization, high-learning for the student team. Engagements are scoped and priced based on your requirements and interests.\n\n**→ See some of our work and contact us to bring a problem**\n\n### Anchor a Challenge or Hackathon\n\nFrom real-world challenges to innovation and ventures — the Lab partners with industry to translate meaningful problems into hands-on experimentation, deployable innovation, and new venture opportunities.\n\nThrough challenges, hackathons, and focused sprints, we create structured environments where cross-disciplinary student teams work on real problems using applied AI and emerging technologies — generating fresh ideas, testing solutions, and building momentum. For industry partners, this is a low-risk way to explore what’s possible while building a pipeline of talent and ideas.\n\n**How it works:**", "char_len": 2102, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::14", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 14, "text": "student teams work on real problems using applied AI and emerging technologies — generating fresh ideas, testing solutions, and building momentum. For industry partners, this is a low-risk way to explore what’s possible while building a pipeline of talent and ideas.\n\n**How it works:**\n\n* **Start with a real challenge** — bring a problem, opportunity space, or area of interest\n* **Activate student teams** — cross-disciplinary teams explore, build, and prototype solutions\n* **Test ideas quickly** — through short, focused engagements designed for speed and creativity\n* **Surface outcomes** — including early-stage solutions, new use cases, and venture opportunities\n\nSponsorship levels range from general event support to proposing a specific problem statement for teams to work on. Some example industry projects have included:\n\n* **Health & Wellness** — How to deliver personalized experiences using AI\n* **Manufacturing** — Using AI to optimize trade programs and improve retailer partnerships\n* **Retail** — Engaging audiences inundated with choices to improve online and in-store experience with AI\n* **AgTech** — Improving producer productivity in horticulture with AI\n* **Real Estate** — Using AR and AI to improve trust and safety in short-term rentals\n* **Consumer Goods** — Creating seamless AI-powered customer experiences to build brand engagement and loyalty\n* **Education & Training** — Leveraging VR and AI to lower cost and increase access to enterprise training\n\nAnd some examples of challenges that have been sponsored by industry partners:", "char_len": 1562, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::15", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 15, "text": "**Consumer Goods** — Creating seamless AI-powered customer experiences to build brand engagement and loyalty\n* **Education & Training** — Leveraging VR and AI to lower cost and increase access to enterprise training\n\nAnd some examples of challenges that have been sponsored by industry partners:\n\n* **Digital Health Challenge — Spring 2026** Focused on brain health, this challenge brought students together to explore how AI and digital technologies can improve quality of life for patients and caregivers. Teams developed solutions ranging from neurological monitoring tools to emotionally intelligent AI companions, with top teams advancing toward continued development and real-world application.\n* **Xorbix Hackathon — Spring 2026** In partnership with Xorbix, this hands-on hackathon gave students access to real-world data and industry context, challenging them to develop practical solutions using modern tools and platforms. The result: high-quality prototypes, new use cases, and direct exposure for students to real industry problems and expectations.\n* **Google AI Startup School – Summer 2025** This past summer, Google sponsored an AI Startup School for nearly 60 students — combining live online training, in-lab workshops, and a culminating hackathon with Google representatives on the judging panel. Events like this give students exposure to real startup frameworks and frontier tools while giving sponsors meaningful visibility with some of UW–Madison’s most motivated emerging talent.\n* **BuildFest — Fall 2025** Sponsored by Cursor, this Lab-led build sprint moved students from early ideas into tangible prototypes. Teams worked across sectors to build AI and blockchain solutions, exploring new concepts and shaping venture opportunities in a fast-paced, collaborative environment.\n\n### Sponsor Innovation\n\nSupport student-led experimentation through funding, tools, or data access. Sponsorship opportunities include Demo Night, Lab programs, and specific initiatives. Sponsorships are scoped based on your interests and the Lab’s current priorities.\n\n**→ Contact us about sponsorship and industry projects**\n\n### Who We Work With", "char_len": 2153, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::16", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 16, "text": "through funding, tools, or data access. Sponsorship opportunities include Demo Night, Lab programs, and specific initiatives. Sponsorships are scoped based on your interests and the Lab’s current priorities.\n\n**→ Contact us about sponsorship and industry projects**\n\n### Who We Work With\n\nWe work with companies of all sizes and sectors — from startups to enterprise. If you’re curious about whether the Lab is the right fit for your organization, reach out. We’re happy to have a conversation before you commit to anything.\n\n### About the Tech Exploration Lab\n\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/alumni\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/innovation-center.jpg)\n\n**The Lab doesn’t end at graduation.**\n\nWhether you’re a recent grad or a seasoned professional, the Tech Exploration Lab is a place to stay connected, give back, and keep building. You’re welcome here — at events, in the space, and in the work.\n\n### Start Here: Join the Technology & Innovation Circle\n\nThe Technology & Innovation Circle is the easiest way to stay plugged into the Lab. It’s a warm, on-demand network of alumni, industry leaders, and innovation practitioners who stay connected to what the Lab is building and learning.\n\nThe most direct way to give back is to share what you know. Work with student teams as a mentor, hold office hours, advise a specific cohort, or take a deeper role as an Executive-in-Residence. If you want to come in and work alongside students in the space, you’re welcome to do that too — the Lab is open and alumni are always part of the community.\n\nHave a look at some of the Lab’s recent **student ventures and innovation projects** to see what sparks interest.\n\nGuest speaker at a Build Night? Office hours for a venture team? We’ll find the right fit for your time and expertise.\n\n**→ Complete this form if you are interested in joining the Circle to hear about alumni and industry engagement opportunities**", "char_len": 2272, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::17", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 17, "text": "innovation projects** to see what sparks interest.\n\nGuest speaker at a Build Night? Office hours for a venture team? We’ll find the right fit for your time and expertise.\n\n**→ Complete this form if you are interested in joining the Circle to hear about alumni and industry engagement opportunities**\n\n#### Bring a Project or Venture\n\nHave a problem you want to explore or a venture you’re working on? Alumni can engage with the Lab the same way industry partners do — bringing a real challenge to a student team to explore, prototype, and pressure-test using AI and emerging technologies. Engagements are scoped and priced based on your requirements and interests.\n\n**→ Contact us to bring a project**\n\n#### Give to the Lab\n\nYour gift directly fuels student innovation — supporting venture programs, industry-defined projects, Build Nights, hackathons, and the tools students need to move ideas into action.\n\n**→ Make a gift online** *(specify the Tech Exploration Lab Fund – 112170239)*\n\nTo discuss gifting options, contact Caitlin Gates, Managing Sr. Director with the Wisconsin Foundation and Alumni Association, or Sandra Bradley, Executive Director of the Lab.\n\n### Come Find Us\n\nThe Lab is open. Alumni are always welcome to drop in, attend events, work in the space, or just see what students are building. Build Nights, Open Labs, Fourth Wednesday mixers, Demo Night — all of it is open to you.\n\n**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list and subscribe to our calendar. You can also email us with questions.**\n\n### About the Tech Exploration Lab\n\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/our-work\n\n## Applied Innovation and Ventures: From Real Problems to Market", "char_len": 2047, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::18", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 18, "text": "early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/our-work\n\n## Applied Innovation and Ventures: From Real Problems to Market\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab is where real-world problems meet emerging technology — and where the work of solving them leads somewhere. For industry partners, that means applied innovation that drives growth using frontier technology. For researchers and faculty, it means support in assessing the venture potential of promising research and finding pathways to bring it to market. For students, it means the resources, networks, and experience to build early-stage ventures.\n\n### How Ideas Get Activated\n\nThe Lab brings ideas to life through a range of programs, sprints, and events — each designed to connect students with real problems, industry partners, alumni, and emerging technologies. Below are examples of how that activation happens, from recurring semester programs to industry sponsored events.\n\n**Recurring Programs**\n\n* **Four-Week Problem to Demo Sprint** — The Lab’s signature program pairs multidisciplinary student teams with real industry and campus challenges. Over four weeks, teams move from problem framing to working prototype and then continue work through the semester, presenting their solutions to sponsors, mentors, and the broader Lab community at a culminating Demo Night.\n* **Badger Build Fest** — The Lab’s annual venture-building hackathon challenges students to go beyond building and think like founders — defining markets, validating assumptions, and articulating credible paths forward. Teams compete across AI, venture and sector-focused tracks, with sponsors, mentors, and judges drawn from the broader innovation ecosystem.\n\n**Industry & Partner Events**", "char_len": 1892, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::19", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 19, "text": "go beyond building and think like founders — defining markets, validating assumptions, and articulating credible paths forward. Teams compete across AI, venture and sector-focused tracks, with sponsors, mentors, and judges drawn from the broader innovation ecosystem.\n\n**Industry & Partner Events**\n\n* **Xorbix Technologies Hackathon (March 2026)** — Xorbix sponsored a fast-paced innovation challenge where student teams tackled a real-world AI and data problem, generating fresh ideas and early prototypes in just a few hours.\n* **Douglas D. Bradley Digital Health Challenge (annual)** — A focused challenge reimagining technology for brain health, bringing together students, clinicians, and innovators to develop solutions at the intersection of AI and healthcare.\n* **Google AI Startup School (Summer 2025)** — In partnership with Google, the Lab brought Google’s AI Startup School to UW–Madison students through live online training on cutting-edge agentic tools, in-lab workshops, and a culminating hackathon judged by Google representatives.\n\n### What We’re Building: Applied Innovation in Motion\n\nWhat you see below is a snapshot of that work in motion — multidisciplinary teams tackling meaningful problems across health, security, productivity, sustainability, and more, in collaboration with industry partners, alumni, and campus researchers.\n\n---\n\n### Health & Care\n\nStudent teams have consistently tackled some of the most pressing challenges in healthcare — from clinical training and caregiver burnout to neurological monitoring and patient communication.", "char_len": 1571, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::20", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 20, "text": "and more, in collaboration with industry partners, alumni, and campus researchers.\n\n---\n\n### Health & Care\n\nStudent teams have consistently tackled some of the most pressing challenges in healthcare — from clinical training and caregiver burnout to neurological monitoring and patient communication.\n\n* **PersonaXR** — A browser-based medical training platform using AI and immersive technology to simulate clinical exams, helping medical students improve readiness and pass rates.\n* **The Invisible Patient** — An AI companion for caregivers of Alzheimer’s and dementia patients that detects early signs of burnout through natural, empathetic conversation.\n* **NeuroTrack** — A mobile system that monitors subtle neurological changes in MS patients using daily tests and passive data, enabling earlier and more informed care.\n* **Ally AI** — An emotionally intelligent AI companion that adapts to users over time to reduce loneliness and support emotional well-being.\n* **Hatti for Alzheimer’s** — An AI-powered care companion that tracks routines, monitors wandering risks, and coordinates communication across home care, assisted living, and memory-care settings.\n* **Prescription Scanning App** — An AI tool that helps ESL patients and older adults understand medications in plain language, with reminders and caregiver updates.\n* **MadGlow** — An AI-powered skincare assistant that delivers personalized routines, progress tracking, and evidence-based product recommendations.\n* **GuideMyPlate** — A nutrition app that fights obesity through actionable steps rather than overwhelming data, helping users build sustainable healthy habits.\n* **MedCheck** — An AI tool that provides transparency around medication perceptions, helping patients make more informed decisions.\n\n---\n\n### Environment, Safety & Public Infrastructure\n\nSome of the Lab’s most consequential work addresses problems with broad societal stakes — from wildfire prediction and mitigation to real-time situational awareness in public and institutional settings.", "char_len": 2033, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::21", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 21, "text": "patients make more informed decisions.\n\n---\n\n### Environment, Safety & Public Infrastructure\n\nSome of the Lab’s most consequential work addresses problems with broad societal stakes — from wildfire prediction and mitigation to real-time situational awareness in public and institutional settings.\n\n* **EmberAI** — An autonomous aerial sensing and prediction platform for wildfire management that streams real-time perimeter data and near-term spread forecasts to agencies, utilities, landowners, and insurers — combining edge AI, calibrated sensors, and night-flight capabilities to protect people, property, and critical infrastructure.\n* **EverOS** — A real-time AI orchestration platform for venue operators and security teams that integrates video, audio, and sensor data to detect and respond to incidents before they escalate — currently exploring pilots in defense and with police departments.\n* **Ares** — Gives air traffic controllers AI-driven predictive awareness to identify conflicts and prevent incidents before they occur.\n\n---\n\n### AI Infrastructure, Security & Developer Tools\n\nSome of the Lab’s most technically ambitious work lives at the infrastructure layer — building the reliability, observability, and fairness tools that make AI systems trustworthy at scale.\n\n* **Cortexa** — An AI memory observability layer that reduces hallucinations and improves reliability in agentic workflows by tracking how agents store and use information.\n* **Fairlytics** — Real-time bias monitoring for machine learning models, surfacing fairness issues as predictions are made.\n* **Gantry** — An agent orchestration tool within the IDE, enabling developers to structure and manage AI workflows more effectively.\n* **ProTecht** — An AI compliance automation platform that helps federal cloud providers identify gaps in security documentation, reducing audit costs and accelerating FedRAMP authorization.\n* **TruChain** — Uses blockchain to verify the authenticity of video content from elected officials, creating immutable provenance and stopping deepfakes at the source.\n\n---\n\n### Productivity & Business Tools\n\nFrom inbox management to legal document analysis, teams have built practical tools that reduce friction in everyday work — many with clear paths to commercial application.", "char_len": 2289, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::22", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 22, "text": "elected officials, creating immutable provenance and stopping deepfakes at the source.\n\n---\n\n### Productivity & Business Tools\n\nFrom inbox management to legal document analysis, teams have built practical tools that reduce friction in everyday work — many with clear paths to commercial application.\n\n* **MottoNote** — An AI memory and recall layer that captures decision-making context across meetings, documents, and conversations, turning scattered inputs into structured insights.\n* **Lyntra** — An AI academic planner that breaks assignments into step-by-step sessions and schedules them around real student commitments.\n* **ScribeAI** — Transforms raw notes and prompts into structured, high-quality written content for professionals and teams.\n* **BeaverAI** — A Chrome extension that summarizes emails, identifies key tasks, and manages recurring themes to reduce inbox overload.\n* **Cosma** — An on-device AI file management platform that organizes and retrieves files by context rather than filename, maintaining privacy while reducing clutter.\n* **Clear Cause** — An AI tool that analyzes legal documents, highlights risk areas, and explains contract language in plain terms for individuals and small businesses.\n* **Inventory Automate** — A mobile-first AR/AI inventory system that reduces counting time by approximately 70% and improves accuracy for bars, restaurants, and small operators.\n* **AI Trend Radar** — A trend discovery platform that identifies early signals across social platforms and delivers predictive trend models and personalized recommendations for creators and agencies.\n* **Carmonic** — Makes drivers proactive rather than reactive about vehicle maintenance by surfacing early warnings and actionable insights.\n* **BadgerFlix** — Transforms long lecture content into short, bingeable, personalized episodes to improve comprehension and engagement.\n\n---\n\n### Social, Community & Experience\n\nSeveral teams have taken on the challenge of how people connect, discover, and engage in the real world — building platforms that use emerging technology to drive genuine human interaction.", "char_len": 2113, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::23", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 23, "text": "personalized episodes to improve comprehension and engagement.\n\n---\n\n### Social, Community & Experience\n\nSeveral teams have taken on the challenge of how people connect, discover, and engage in the real world — building platforms that use emerging technology to drive genuine human interaction.\n\n* **BluWorld** — A social platform that helps users discover local events and rewards real-world participation through gamified experiences and local business partnerships.\n* **StyleSwap** — Lets college students digitally share closets with friends to borrow clothes, reduce waste, and save money.\n* **UniBud** — An AI-powered student guide that personalizes milestones, surfaces relevant events and resources, and gives advisors real-time engagement insights.\n* **ClearMove** — Protects renters by turning leases, checklists, and move-in photos into organized, shareable evidence for dispute resolution.\n* **TimeMyGate** — A smart pre-flight planner that tells travelers exactly when to leave for the airport based on real-time conditions.\n* **SeaPay** — A blockchain payment platform enabling hotels and lodging providers to accept cryptocurrency, reducing transaction fees and expanding options for global travelers.\n* **Grow Together** — An app that finds when friends are free, suggests places to go, and grows a virtual garden when users spend real time together — making it easier to turn digital connection into real-world plans.\n\n---\n\n### Blockchain & Decentralized Technology\n\nA growing cluster of Lab projects is exploring how blockchain and decentralized infrastructure can bring trust, transparency, and new models of exchange to everyday problems.", "char_len": 1658, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::24", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 24, "text": "— making it easier to turn digital connection into real-world plans.\n\n---\n\n### Blockchain & Decentralized Technology\n\nA growing cluster of Lab projects is exploring how blockchain and decentralized infrastructure can bring trust, transparency, and new models of exchange to everyday problems.\n\n* **CredentialHub** — A decentralized professional verification platform powered by Solana blockchain, making credentials tamper-proof and instantly verifiable.\n* **Phanta** — AI-powered, blockchain-native portfolio management with real-time on-chain insights and decentralized group investment tools.\n* **UniMarket** — A blockchain-powered marketplace exclusively for verified students to trade textbooks, gear, and services with trust and minimal fees.\n* **BadgerTutor** — A peer tutoring platform that uses blockchain to establish trust and transparency between tutors and students.\n* **BadgerBadges** — A blockchain-based achievement system that turns real UW–Madison experiences into verifiable, tamper-proof digital badges.\n* **Cool Router** — A decentralized oracle network that brings real-time AI directly to Solana smart contracts with no polling or complexity.\n\n---\n\n### Campus & Research Translation\n\nA growing area of Lab work involves bridging the gap between university research and real-world application — helping faculty and researchers assess the venture potential of promising work and find pathways to bring it to market.", "char_len": 1436, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::25", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 25, "text": "no polling or complexity.\n\n---\n\n### Campus & Research Translation\n\nA growing area of Lab work involves bridging the gap between university research and real-world application — helping faculty and researchers assess the venture potential of promising work and find pathways to bring it to market.\n\n* **School of Veterinary Medicine Translation Tool** — A real-time AI translation tool improving communication between English-speaking veterinarians and Spanish-speaking dairy farm workers, developed in direct partnership with the UW School of Veterinary Medicine.\n* **ARHat+** — Built on UW-Madison research, a smartphone-based LiDAR and AR tool that rapidly identifies home safety risks and aging-in-place modifications, streamlining documentation for care professionals and integrating with EHR and insurance systems.\n* **RAAS (Robotics-as-a-Service)** — A commercialization enablement platform that gives university robotics researchers a structured path from lab to market readiness, reducing technical fragmentation and accelerating development timelines.\n* **AI Research Assistant** — An AI model designed to streamline workflows and improve outcomes for academic researchers across synthesis, analysis, and discovery.\n* **Chatbot for Entrepreneurs** — A conversational AI tool helping small business owners and entrepreneurs navigate uncertainty and make more confident planning decisions.\n\n---\n\n### Industry-Driven Innovation Sprints + Challenges\n\nIn addition to student-initiated projects, the Lab runs structured innovation challenges in partnership with industry sponsors — giving companies access to fresh thinking on frontier problems while giving students experience working on real business challenges.\n\nRecent challenge areas and projects have included:", "char_len": 1769, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::26", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 26, "text": "student-initiated projects, the Lab runs structured innovation challenges in partnership with industry sponsors — giving companies access to fresh thinking on frontier problems while giving students experience working on real business challenges.\n\nRecent challenge areas and projects have included:\n\n* **Health & Wellness** — How to deliver personalized experiences using AI\n* **Manufacturing** — Using AI to optimize trade programs and improve retailer partnerships\n* **Retail** — Engaging audiences inundated with choices to improve online and in-store experience with AI\n* **AgTech** — Improving producer productivity in horticulture with AI\n* **Real Estate** — Using AR and AI to improve trust and safety in short-term rentals\n* **Consumer Goods** — Creating seamless AI-powered customer experiences to build brand engagement and loyalty\n* **Education & Training** — Leveraging VR and AI to lower cost and increase access to enterprise training\n\n---\n\n*Interested in bringing a challenge to the Lab, exploring a research translation opportunity, or supporting student innovation? Contact us.*\n\n**About the UW Tech Exploration Lab**\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/news-and-events-2\n\n## See What People Are Saying About the Lab\n\nSee testimonials on how the Lab sparks innovation, builds connections, and turns possibility into action for students, industry partners, and alumni.\n\n## Read Press Coverage on the Lab\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab is building something new at the intersection of emerging technology and early-stage venture - see the press coverage and media contact information\n\n## News\n\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/LEL-springboard-150x150.jpg)\n\n### The UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/IMG_0808-150x150.jpg)", "char_len": 2179, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::27", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 27, "text": "contact information\n\n## News\n\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/LEL-springboard-150x150.jpg)\n\n### The UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/IMG_0808-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Winners from the Lab’s Digital Health Challenge + Demo Night Spring 2026\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/demo-1225-150x150.jpg)\n\n### All Spring 2026 Demo Night Teams\n* ![Tyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0662-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Fresh Ideas and Emerging Talent: Highlights from the Xorbix Hackathon\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/open-house-0126-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Open House Momentum\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/FL-3-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Join us at the Tech Exploration Lab this Fall\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/demo-1225-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Cap Times Feature: Students Building What’s Next with AI, Blockchain, and Emerging Tech\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/industry-0-150x150.jpg)\n\n### How AI, Robotics & Quantum Are Reshaping Business: Insights from the Tech Exploration Lab Industry Forum\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/demo-1-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Building What’s Next: Highlights from the Tech Exploration Lab Student Demo Night\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/venture-build-1225-150x150.jpeg)\n\n### Celebrating an Incredible Venture Build Pitch Night\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/11/Alka-Lakadia-Dermavision-600-x-600-150x150.png)\n\n### From Curiosity to Startup: How the Tech Exploration Lab Helped a Student Tech Entrepreneur Turn Ideas into Impact\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/networking-150x150.jpeg)", "char_len": 2165, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::28", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 28, "text": "From Curiosity to Startup: How the Tech Exploration Lab Helped a Student Tech Entrepreneur Turn Ideas into Impact\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/networking-150x150.jpeg)\n\n### Founder Stories Social: Conversations that Spark What’s Next\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/IMG_1750-150x150.png)\n\n### Build Nights – Fridays at 1403 This Fall\n* ![Mike Grall, CEO with Fulcrum Solutions watches a demo of a Quest headset with UW-Madison student Mason Baloun.](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/04/TechLab_Industry_main_2400_1600-1536x1024-1-150x150.jpg)\n\n### UW Tech Exploration Lab Featured in On Wisconsin Magazine: Inventing the Future\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/20250709_120338-hackathon-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Ways to Get Involved – Fall 2025\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/0819-1-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Congratulations to Our Summer Innovation & Venture Fellows!\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/parker-vd-150x150.jpg)\n\n### AI Venture Discovery Program: A Summer of Student Innovation\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/20250709_120338-hackathon-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Post-Event Recap: AI Startup Mixer and Hackathon Spark Real-Time Innovation\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/VE-Hero-Banner-DeNoise-150x150.png)\n\n### Jump In Anytime: What’s Happening at the UW Tech Exploration Lab This Summer & Fall\n* ![Hackathon](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/Hackathon-02-150x150.png)\n\n### AI Startup Hackathon – July 9-10\n* More Posts\n  More\n\n**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar. You can also email us with questions.**\n\n## Events\n\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/09/20250912_190648-150x150.jpg)", "char_len": 2155, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::29", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 29, "text": "plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar. You can also email us with questions.**\n\n## Events\n\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/09/20250912_190648-150x150.jpg)\n\n### The Lab’s Summer Kickoff: Get Plugged In\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/2c0118c6-c89b-4cae-b142-88736748a3fa-400-150x150.jpg)\n\n### UW Tech Exploration Lab in San Francisco: Founder Lab Networking\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/FL-3-150x150.jpg)\n\n### Join us at the Tech Exploration Lab this Fall\n* ![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/IMG_1750-150x150.png)\n\n### Build Nights – Fridays at 1403 This Fall\n\n## Past Events\n\n* ### How Fundable Is Your Startup?\n* ### Founder Lab Feedback Panel\n* ### Digital Health Challenge Finalists: Student Teams Present What’s Next in Health Innovation\n* ### Fresh Ideas and Emerging Talent: Highlights from the Xorbix Hackathon\n* ### Build an Idea. Test It. Demo It. In Four Weeks.\n* ### From Factory Data to AI: A Hands-On Workshop + Hackathon with Xorbix\n* ### Fourth Wednesday – March\n* ### 4 Weeks to Demo: Join the Sprint. Defining the Problem\n* More *Past Events* posts\n  More\n\n**About the Tech Exploration Lab**\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/support-the-lab\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/DSC00016-300x200.jpg)The Tech Exploration Lab is a cross-campus launchpad where students turn emerging technologies into real-world solutions. Led by the Wisconsin School of Business, the Lab gives multidisciplinary students hands-on experience with applied AI and frontier technologies while tackling real business and societal challenges.", "char_len": 2176, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::30", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 30, "text": "Lab is a cross-campus launchpad where students turn emerging technologies into real-world solutions. Led by the Wisconsin School of Business, the Lab gives multidisciplinary students hands-on experience with applied AI and frontier technologies while tackling real business and societal challenges.\n\nYour gift directly fuels student innovation — supporting venture programs, industry-defined projects, build nights, hackathons, and the tools students need to move ideas into action.\n\nBy donating, you help prepare the next generation of technology leaders, founders, and problem-solvers at UW–Madison.\n\nIf you wish to make a donation to the Lab, you can **make a gift online** (make sure to specify the Tech Exploration Lab Fund – 112170239) **.**\n\nYou can also set a time to discuss gifting options by contacting Caitlin Gates, Managing Sr. Director with the Wisconsin Foundation and Alumni Association, or Sandra Bradley, Executive Director of the Lab.\n\n**About the UW Tech Exploration Lab**\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/about-the-tech-exploration-lab-2\n\n![UW Tech Exploration Lab Open House at UW Madison](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2019/09/mindi.jpeg)\n\n## **Innovation starts here.**\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab is where emerging technologies meet real-world problems — and where curiosity gets activated into something worth building.\n\nWe help shape the next generation of startups coming out of UW–Madison by bringing students, alumni, industry partners, and researchers together around applied exploration. Turning curiosity into evidence, and ideas into ventures that are ready to move.\n\nThe Lab, led by the Wisconsin School of Business in collaboration with the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery, serves as a campus-wide activation resource for turning ideas and emerging technologies into real-world innovation and venture opportunities.", "char_len": 2204, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::31", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 31, "text": "ideas into ventures that are ready to move.\n\nThe Lab, led by the Wisconsin School of Business in collaboration with the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery, serves as a campus-wide activation resource for turning ideas and emerging technologies into real-world innovation and venture opportunities.\n\nIt is not a classroom, an accelerator, or a consulting shop. It is a front-end venture engine designed for early-stage discovery, rapid experimentation, and disciplined learning. Here, students don’t just learn about innovation — they practice it.\n\n### How the Lab Works\n\nThe Lab operates at the intersection of emerging technology and real-world problems. We work in two directions simultaneously:\n\n**Student ventures** — students bring ideas and curiosity, and the Lab provides the structure, mentorship, industry connections, and resources to help them find out whether those ideas are worth pursuing. The best ones move through the Venture Pathway toward real market opportunities.\n\n**Industry and research challenges** — companies, researchers, and faculty bring real problems and early-stage technologies to the Lab. Student teams apply AI and emerging technologies to prototype solutions, assess commercial potential, and develop go-to-market strategies. Fast, structured, and grounded in real-world context.\n\nEverything culminates at **Demo Night** — the Lab’s bi-annual showcase where student ventures, industry innovation projects, and research translation work come together in one room.\n\n### Who It’s For\n\n**Students** Whether you’re exploring emerging technology, building an early venture, or looking to work on real-world industry and research challenges, the Lab gives you a place to experiment, collaborate, and grow. Participation can be light or deep — from Open Labs and Build Nights to the Venture Pathway and Applied Innovation & Commercialization projects.\n\n**Industry Partners** Engage with student teams around applied problems, explore new ideas before they become expensive, and build early relationships with tomorrow’s talent. The Lab offers a low-risk environment for structured experimentation — testing assumptions, surfacing use cases, and anchoring challenges and hackathons that generate real insight.", "char_len": 2234, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::32", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 32, "text": "problems, explore new ideas before they become expensive, and build early relationships with tomorrow’s talent. The Lab offers a low-risk environment for structured experimentation — testing assumptions, surfacing use cases, and anchoring challenges and hackathons that generate real insight.\n\n**Researchers & Faculty** Surface the big challenges in your domain and activate student teams to ideate and build toward solutions. Or bring early-stage research with commercial potential and let the Lab help you explore whether it can go somewhere — and what it would take to get there. Either way, you get technical and business students working on real problems with real emerging technologies.\n\n**Alumni & Innovation Leaders** Reconnect with UW–Madison in a way that is practical and hands-on. Mentor teams, hold office hours, bring a challenge or venture, give to the Lab, or join the Technology & Innovation Circle to stay connected to what’s being built. Grounded in building, not theory.\n\n---\n\n*The UW Tech Exploration Lab is where exploration becomes action — and where the next generation of ventures begins.*\n\n## Hear What People Are Saying About the Lab\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/Bradley_Sandra_SQ_102022_Z72_6555_512x512-300x300.jpg)\n\nSandra Bradley\nTech Exploration Lab Executive Director and Wisconsin School of Business.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/01/ponto-300x300.jpeg)\n\nKevin Ponto\nTech Exploration Lab Faculty Co-Director, WID Associate and UW faculty.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/page-moreau-300x300.jpg)\n\nPage Moreau\nTech Exploration Lab Faculty Co-Director and Associate Dean Research and PhD Programs in the Wisconsin School of Business.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/contact\n\nThank you for your interest in the Tech Exploration Lab.\n\n**Students**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar. You can also email us with questions.", "char_len": 2130, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::33", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 33, "text": "you for your interest in the Tech Exploration Lab.\n\n**Students**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar. You can also email us with questions.\n\n**Industry and Alumni**Help shape the future of your industry while gaining access to fresh perspectives and ideas. The Lab offers options for industry and alumni to join our Technology and Innovation Circle, share your problems to solve, mentor or test new ideas in a low risk environment with innovative and entrepreneurial students. Contact sandra.bradley@wisc.edu to learn more.\n\n**Media**\nSee our media page or contact sandra.bradley@wisc.edu.\n\n**About the Tech Exploration Lab**\nThe Lab is a collaboration between the Wisconsin School of Business and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery. We activate early-stage innovation and ventures at UW–Madison, connecting students, industry partners, researchers, and alumni around real problems, applied AI, and emerging technologies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/12/demo-night-2026-celebrating-innovation-and-venture-momentum\n\n## Celebrating Innovation and Venture Momentum\n\nLast week’s Tech Exploration Lab Demo Night brought together a mix of students, industry partners, alumni, and the broader innovation community for an evening of showcasing applied innovation.\n\nStudent teams presented their work across the room demonstrating deployable solutions and early-stage venture concepts built through hands-on experimentation with AI and emerging technologies.\n\nWe were incredibly impressed by the quality of work and the progress teams have made this semester. (**See a list of all student teams**)\n\n# **Demo Night Award Winners**\n\n## **Most Innovative**\n\n### **First Place ($1,000) – PersonaXR**\n\n**Team:** Aayush Agrawal, Pouya Mirzaei, Anurag Janaswamy, Mathom Johnson\nA medical training platform using AI and immersive technologies to simulate clinical interactions, helping students better prepare for real-world patient scenarios.\n\n### **Second Place ($750) – The Invisible Patient**", "char_len": 2128, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::34", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 34, "text": "Aayush Agrawal, Pouya Mirzaei, Anurag Janaswamy, Mathom Johnson\nA medical training platform using AI and immersive technologies to simulate clinical interactions, helping students better prepare for real-world patient scenarios.\n\n### **Second Place ($750) – The Invisible Patient**\n\n**Team:** Shreya Lakhera & Shiv Akash\nA conversational AI companion designed to support caregivers of Alzheimer’s and dementia patients by identifying early signs of burnout through natural, empathetic interaction.\n\n## **Most Impact / Best Venture**\n\n### **First Place ($1,000) – Cortexa**\n\n**Team:** Arunjay Agrawal, Ishaan Kharbanda, Prateek Rao\nAn AI infrastructure layer focused on improving reliability in agentic workflows by reducing hallucinations and increasing determinism in how systems process and retain information.\n\n### **Second Place ($750) – MottoNote**\n\n**Team:** Slava Iudenko, Siddharth Singh\nAn AI-native memory and recall layer that captures and organizes decision-making context across meetings, documents, and tools—turning scattered inputs into structured, actionable insights.\n\n## **Judge’s Choice Awards ($500)**\n\n### **BluWorld**\n\n**Team:** David Skadron\nA social platform designed to drive real-world engagement by helping users discover local events and rewarding participation through gamified experiences and partnerships with local businesses.\n\n### **Everos**\n\n**Team:** Bryson Turner\nA real-time intelligence platform that integrates data from distributed sensors into a unified system, enabling faster decision-making in complex and high-stakes environments.\n\n# **Thank You to Our Judges**\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/judges-300x225.jpg)A special thank you to our Demo Night judges for their time, expertise, and thoughtful engagement:\n\n* Frank Hansen, Kinetic Solutions\n* Tyler Waite, Holos\n* Grant Watkins, gener8tor\n* Kevin Ponto, University of Wisconsin–Madison\n\nTheir feedback plays a critical role in helping these teams refine and advance their work.\n\n# **Douglas D. Bradley Digital Health Challenge Winners**\n\nWe also recognized the winners of this year’s Digital Health Challenge, focused on reimagining technology for brain health.\n\nThank you to our judges:", "char_len": 2236, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::35", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 35, "text": "feedback plays a critical role in helping these teams refine and advance their work.\n\n# **Douglas D. Bradley Digital Health Challenge Winners**\n\nWe also recognized the winners of this year’s Digital Health Challenge, focused on reimagining technology for brain health.\n\nThank you to our judges:\n\n* Adhira Sunkara, I/O Innovative\n* Debra Hermsmeir, Legacy of Health and Wellness\n* Michael Szewczyk, Okkanti\n\n### **NeuroTrack ($1,000)**\n\n**![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/neurotrack-3-300x179.jpg)Team:** Alexander Kubiak & Luray He\nA mobile system that monitors subtle neurological changes in individuals with Multiple Sclerosis using daily tests and passive data, helping detect deviations from a personal baseline for earlier, more informed care.\n\n### **Ally AI ($750)**\n\n**Team:** Adnan Fazulbhoy & Sanjit Saji\nAn emotionally intelligent AI companion that adapts to users over time, offering consistent and personalized support to help reduce loneliness and improve emotional well-being.\n\n# **What We’re** Seeing\n\nWhat stood out most wasn’t just the ideas, it was the progression:\n\n* From concepts to working prototypes\n* From exploration to deployable innovation\n* From projects to venture opportunities\n\nThis is exactly what the Lab is designed to do: Turn real-world problems into innovation and ventures.\n\n# **What’s Next**\n\nWe’re just getting started. This summer, we’ll continue building momentum through:\n\n* Hackathons\n* Open Labs\n* Industry-driven experiments\n\nWe’ll also be taking a group of **Founder Lab teams to San Francisco in June**, connecting them with alumni, investors, and the broader innovation ecosystem as they continue to shape and pressure-test their ideas.\n\nAnd this fall, the Lab we will be welcoming the next wave of teams ready to explore, build, and push ideas forward.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/industry\n\n## **From Real-World Challenges to Innovation and Ventures**\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab partners with industry to translate real-world challenges into hands-on experimentation, deployable innovation, and new venture opportunities.", "char_len": 2134, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::36", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 36, "text": "forward.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/industry\n\n## **From Real-World Challenges to Innovation and Ventures**\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab partners with industry to translate real-world challenges into hands-on experimentation, deployable innovation, and new venture opportunities.\n\nThrough challenges, hackathons, and focused sprints, we create structured environments where student teams work on meaningful problems using applied AI and emerging technologies—generating fresh ideas, testing solutions, and building momentum.\n\nFor industry partners, this is a low-risk way to explore what’s possible—while building a pipeline of talent and ideas.\n\n## **How It Works**\n\n* **Start with a real challenge**\n  Partners bring forward a problem, opportunity space, or area of interest\n* **Activate student teams**\n  Cross-disciplinary teams explore, build, and prototype solutions\n* **Test ideas quickly**\n  Through short, focused engagements designed for speed and creativity\n* **Surface outcomes**\n  Including early-stage solutions, new use cases, and venture opportunities\n\n## **Why It Matters**\n\n* Explore new ideas without committing significant internal resources\n* Gain fresh perspectives from emerging talent\n* Identify high-potential opportunities early\n* Build relationships with students who are actively shaping what’s next\n\n> **This is not theoretical work—teams are building, testing, and advancing ideas in real time.**\n\n# **Examples from the Lab**\n\n## **Digital Health Challenge (Spring 2026)**\n\n![NeuroTrack, a novel solution for MS patients, presents at the Lab's Digital Health Challenge in Spring 2026](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/neurotrack-3-300x179.jpg)\n\nNeuroTrack, a novel solution for MS patients, presents at the Lab’s Digital Health Challenge in Spring 2026\n\nFocused on brain health, this challenge brought together students to explore how AI and digital technologies can improve quality of life for patients and caregivers.\n\nTeams developed solutions ranging from neurological monitoring tools to emotionally intelligent AI companions, with top teams advancing toward continued development and real-world application.\n\n---", "char_len": 2205, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::37", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 37, "text": "to explore how AI and digital technologies can improve quality of life for patients and caregivers.\n\nTeams developed solutions ranging from neurological monitoring tools to emotionally intelligent AI companions, with top teams advancing toward continued development and real-world application.\n\n---\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2016/08/amfam-300x200.jpg)\n\nTeams working in a 24-hour hackathon format to build out novel solutions.\n\n## **BuildFest (Fall 2025)**\n\nSponsored by Cursor, a Lab-led build sprint designed to move students from early ideas into tangible prototypes.\n\nTeams worked across a range of sectors to build out AI and blockchain solutions, exploring new concepts and shaping venture opportunities in a fast-paced, collaborative environment.\n\n---\n\n![Tyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0662-300x225.jpg)\n\nTyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.\n\n## **Xorbix Hackathon (Spring 2026)**\n\nIn partnership with Xorbix, this hands-on hackathon gave students access to real-world data and industry context, challenging them to develop practical solutions using modern tools and platforms.\n\nThe result: high-quality prototypes, new use cases, and direct exposure for students to real industry problems and expectations.\n\n---\n\n# **Engage with the Lab**\n\nWhether through a focused challenge, hackathon, or ongoing collaboration, the Tech Exploration Lab provides a way to:\n\n* Test ideas quickly\n* Explore emerging technologies in context\n* Build a pipeline of talent and innovation\n\n## **Let’s Build What’s Next**\n\nIf you’re interested in bringing a challenge to the Lab or exploring ways to engage, we’d love to connect.\n\n**[Contact Us]**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/testimonials\n\nAt the UW Tech Exploration Lab, impact is best measured through the people who experience it firsthand. Students gain the confidence to test bold ideas, companies discover fresh solutions and future talent, and alumni mentors find meaning in giving back to the next generation. Together, their perspectives highlight how the Lab sparks innovation, builds connections, and turns possibility into action.", "char_len": 2298, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::38", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 38, "text": "Students gain the confidence to test bold ideas, companies discover fresh solutions and future talent, and alumni mentors find meaning in giving back to the next generation. Together, their perspectives highlight how the Lab sparks innovation, builds connections, and turns possibility into action.\n\n## **What students have to say:**\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/DSC01777.JPG.jpg)\n\n“Being able to talk to innovators in industry, who have years of experience with AI and VR systems, helps me learn what is actually valuable and what I want to pursue in my career.” – Spring 2025 Student\n\n“I would highly recommend any student to participate in a hackathon like this one. You don’t need to have a Computer Science background to perform in a hackathon. Just a will to learn and persevere is more than enough.” – Summer 2025 Hackathon\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/DSC_0019-scaled.jpg)\n\n“Working on DermaVision through the Tech Exploration Lab has been one of my most meaningful experiences at UW–Madison. The Lab connected me with peers passionate about AI and healthcare, provided access to advanced tools and mentorship, and helped me turn an early idea into real progress. It’s more than a lab—it’s a launchpad.” – 2025 Venture Discovery Student\n\n“It was an incredible experience where we not only got to build something meaningful but also learned a lot by collaborating under time pressure. You don’t need to be perfect or have everything figured out; just show up, stay curious, and keep building!” – Summer 2025 Hackathon\n\n## **What Mentors and Industry Partners have to say:**\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/DSC_0022-scaled.jpg)\n\n“I came into the Tech Exploration Lab to mentor students, but I walked away with something I didn’t expect: momentum. The lab’s interdisciplinary, experimental spirit gave me the space—and the spark—to test an idea I’d been quietly incubating in the wellness space. Sometimes, the best breakthroughs happen when curiosity, collaboration, and a little Badger grit collide.” – Kurt Kober, WSB alum (MBA ‘07)", "char_len": 2187, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::39", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 39, "text": "momentum. The lab’s interdisciplinary, experimental spirit gave me the space—and the spark—to test an idea I’d been quietly incubating in the wellness space. Sometimes, the best breakthroughs happen when curiosity, collaboration, and a little Badger grit collide.” – Kurt Kober, WSB alum (MBA ‘07)\n\n“The lab is unique in that it connects students from across campus with advanced tools and industry mentorship to rapidly prototype and gain essential skills for an increasingly AI-driven world. It’s exciting to watch entrepreneurial ideas develop, and there is significant value in bringing the best of Google’s AI to support students’ exploration.”  – Kristin Storhoff, Google\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/DSC01697.JPG.jpg)\n\n“The Tech Exploration Lab has been a great resource for us to explore how AI can benefit our business—without the high risk that usually comes with early experimentation. Through our engagement with the lab, we’ve been able to surface fresh ideas from talented students, test potential applications in a low-stakes environment, and get clearer insights into where AI could drive real value for our operations.” – Luke Anderson, Cub Foods CIO\n\n“As a small company navigating the challenges of innovation, especially around AI, the UW Tech Exploration Lab offered us something incredibly rare: a risk-free space to experiment, learn, and move forward. Through our partnership with the lab, we were able to test real use cases, collaborate with sharp student minds, and gain hands-on experience that translated into tangible insights that we could apply to our business. The learnings we gained here accelerated our AI journey; it was the spark we needed to look at our business differently through the use of AI.” -Tim Bratland, president of Crystal Farms\n\n**Want to get involved?\nContact us to learn more.**\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/DSC01624.JPG.jpg)\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/06/03/the-uw-tech-exploration-lab-is-hiring-for-2026-27\n\n**![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/03/LEL-springboard-300x200.jpg)The UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27.**", "char_len": 2249, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::40", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 40, "text": "[page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/06/03/the-uw-tech-exploration-lab-is-hiring-for-2026-27\n\n**![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/03/LEL-springboard-300x200.jpg)The UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27.**\n\nWe’re expanding our student team to work on applied AI and emerging technology — real projects, real industry partners, real outcomes.\n\nThese positions are for the academic year 2026-27 and a minimum of a one-year academic year commitment is preferred.\n\n**Open positions:**\n\n**Graduate students & post-docs:** Leadership Fellows in industry projects, research translation, venture development, and industry & alumni engagement.\n\n**Undergraduates:** Technical Builders working on AI, blockchain, XR, and frontier tech prototypes — plus roles in events & operations, student engagement, and communications.\n\nThis is hands-on work alongside Lab leadership, industry partners, and alumni. Not a classroom exercise.\n\n**Learn more and apply. Applications due August 14, 2026.**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/05/10/the-labs-summer-kickoff-get-plugged-in\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/09/20250912_190648-300x169.jpg)The UW Tech Exploration Lab is heading into summer with momentum — and we’re kicking things off with an open, informal gathering at the Lab.\n\nCome meet the community, grab some pizza, and hear what’s ahead. We’ll share what’s on tap for the summer and fall, including Open Labs, events, and opportunities to build, explore, and collaborate around applied AI and emerging technologies. Whether you’re continuing a project from the spring, considering getting involved for the first time, or just curious about what the Lab is doing — this is a great place to start.\n\n**When:** June 15 at 5:00 PM **Where:** 1403 University Ave, Madison, WI — Second floor. Enter the double glass doors on the west side of the building facing Lorch Street and head upstairs.\n\nPizza and drinks provided.\n\nRegister on Luma →\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/22/uw-tech-exploration-lab-in-san-francisco-founder-lab-networking", "char_len": 2168, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::41", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 41, "text": "Madison, WI — Second floor. Enter the double glass doors on the west side of the building facing Lorch Street and head upstairs.\n\nPizza and drinks provided.\n\nRegister on Luma →\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/22/uw-tech-exploration-lab-in-san-francisco-founder-lab-networking\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/2c0118c6-c89b-4cae-b142-88736748a3fa-400.jpg)The UW Tech Exploration Lab will be in San Francisco on June 25, bringing a select group of Founder Lab teams to engage with the broader Bay Area innovation ecosystem.\n\nFollowing a focused feedback session with founders, investors, and industry leaders, we’re opening the doors for a networking reception from 4:00–6:00 PM at Third Coast Foundry (625 2nd Street, SoMa).\n\nWe welcome:\n\n* UW alumni (“Bay Area Badgers”) interested in tech and entrepreneurship\n* Early-stage investors and founders\n* Industry professionals working in AI, startups, and innovation\n\nThis is an opportunity to:\n\n* Connect with others in the UW and Midwest network in San Francisco\n* Meet student teams building real-world applications of AI\n* Be part of the early momentum around Third Coast Foundry—a new space bringing Midwest innovation into the heart of the SF venture ecosystem\n\nLight snacks and non-alcoholic beverages will be provided.\n\n**[RSVP here]**\n\nIf you’re in the Bay Area, we’d love to have you join us.\n\n**About the Tech Exploration Lab**\nThe Lab, led by the **Wisconsin School of Business** in collaboration with the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery, is part of the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub, serving as a campus-wide activation layer for turning ideas and emerging technologies into real-world innovation and venture opportunities.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/15/how-fundable-is-your-startup\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/networking.jpeg)Thinking about raising money but not sure if you should?\n\nOr how ready you really are?\n\nJoin us for a candid, student-focused networking session where you can:\n\n* Get real feedback on your idea or startup\n* Understand when (and if) fundraising makes sense\n* Ask questions directly to experienced founders and advisors", "char_len": 2254, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::42", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 42, "text": "money but not sure if you should?\n\nOr how ready you really are?\n\nJoin us for a candid, student-focused networking session where you can:\n\n* Get real feedback on your idea or startup\n* Understand when (and if) fundraising makes sense\n* Ask questions directly to experienced founders and advisors\n\nThis is a low-pressure, informal networking event designed to help you think more clearly about your next step.\n\nCome with questions. Leave with clarity.\n\nSponsored by the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship and Tech Exploration Lab.\n\n**[RSVP]**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/13/founder-lab-feedback-panel\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/ally-2-1024x583.jpg)As part of the Tech Exploration Lab’s Venture Pathway, Founder Lab brings together teams that are moving beyond exploration and into shaping real-world innovation and venture opportunities.\n\nOn April 23 at 3:30 PM, Founder Lab teams will participate in a focused feedback session designed to push their ideas further.\n\nThis session brings in a panel of industry and ecosystem voices to provide direct, candid feedback on each team’s direction, positioning, and presentation. It’s an opportunity for teams to refine how they communicate their work, pressure-test assumptions, and sharpen their thinking as they move toward real-world engagement.\n\nMore than a checkpoint, this session serves as a rehearsal for what’s ahead.\n[**Join us and hear the teams on April 23]**\n\n## **Looking Ahead: Founder Lab in San Francisco**\n\nIn June, some of the Founder Lab teams will travel to San Francisco, where they will engage directly with alumni, investors, and operators across the broader innovation ecosystem.\n\nA key moment of the trip will take place on June 25 at the Third Coast Foundry, a new San Francisco-based hub bringing together leading Midwest universities including UW–Madison to support venture engagement and cross-institutional collaboration.\n\nFor Founder Lab teams, this is an opportunity to present their work in a real-world setting, gather feedback from experienced founders and investors and build relationships that extend beyond campus.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/media", "char_len": 2228, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::43", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 43, "text": "and cross-institutional collaboration.\n\nFor Founder Lab teams, this is an opportunity to present their work in a real-world setting, gather feedback from experienced founders and investors and build relationships that extend beyond campus.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/media\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/DSC_0027-scaled.jpg)\n\nCurious about the UW Tech Exploration Lab? We’re proud to be a **multidisciplinary launchpad** where students, alumni, industry, and campus partners experiment with emerging tech, especially AI, and test bold ideas that push Wisconsin innovation forward.\n\nFor **press inquiries, interviews, or more information**, please reach out to:\n\n* **Sandra Bradley** — Executive Director (email)\n\n**Recent Press Releases:**\n\n* **PRESS RELEASE – UW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab Hosts First-Ever Badger Build Fest, Showcasing Student Innovation in AI, Blockchain, and Venture Building (PDF)**\n\n**Featured Coverage:**\n\n* Cap Times Feature: Students Building What’s Next with AI, Blockchain, and Emerging Tech\n* UW–Madison’s Tech Exploration Lab Connects Students, Industry, and Emerging Technologies to Tackle Real-World Challenges\n* UW–Madison’s Tech Exploration Lab Attracts Partnership With Google, Mentors from SalesForce, Nike, and More\n* Spring Student Projects Highlight Innovation in Action\n\n**Want to learn more?** We’re always open to telling our story — and sharing what’s next.\n\n**About the Lab\nArtificial intelligence is reshaping nearly every industry, and higher education is racing to keep pace. At the University of Wisconsin–Madison, the Tech Exploration Lab is emerging as a national model for how universities and companies can collaborate to experiment, learn, and develop future talent in an era of rapid technological change. More info can be found on our about page.**", "char_len": 1873, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::44", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 44, "text": "to keep pace. At the University of Wisconsin–Madison, the Tech Exploration Lab is emerging as a national model for how universities and companies can collaborate to experiment, learn, and develop future talent in an era of rapid technological change. More info can be found on our about page.**\n\n**A Launchpad for Innovation and Discovery**\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab is where forward-looking ideas take shape. A collaboration between the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery and the Wisconsin School of Business, the Lab invites industry leaders, alumni, and students to explore bold ideas at the edge of emerging technology. From AI to AR/VR and beyond, multidisciplinary teams experiment, prototype, and reimagine what’s possible—turning industry challenges into entrepreneurial opportunities and real-world learning.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/07/spring-2026-demo-night-projects\n\n## See a map for the April 10 Demo Night\n\n## Health, Wellness & Human Performance\n\n**NeuroTrack**\nMobile-based system designed to monitor subtle changes in neurological function for individuals with Multiple Sclerosis, using daily tests and passive data to track deviations from a personal baseline.\n\n**PersonaXR (Medical Training Simulation Platform)**\nProvides customizable, browser-based clinical exam simulations to help medical students prepare for oral exams (OSCEs) and improve readiness and pass rates.\n\n**Prescription Scanning App**\nAI-powered app that uses prescription scanning and simple language to help ESL patients and older adults understand medications, with reminders and caregiver updates.\n\n**The Invisible Patient**\nAI-powered mental health companion designed for caregivers, detecting early signs of burnout through conversation and providing ongoing emotional support.\n\n**Luminary**\nLuminary is a weekly skincare and skin concern tracker and journal where the user is able to input their weekly skincare schedule and monitors how their skin responds over time. The main goal is to take the guesswork and the marketing noise out of skincare.\n\n**Ally**\nEmotionally intelligent AI companion designed to support meaningful conversations, recognize emotional context, and provide encouragement.\n\n## AI Platforms, Infrastructure & Developer Tools", "char_len": 2272, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::45", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 45, "text": "responds over time. The main goal is to take the guesswork and the marketing noise out of skincare.\n\n**Ally**\nEmotionally intelligent AI companion designed to support meaningful conversations, recognize emotional context, and provide encouragement.\n\n## AI Platforms, Infrastructure & Developer Tools\n\n**Precursr**\nAn AI-powered memory layer that aggregates user feedback across tools and turns it into structured, execution-ready specs and PRDs, helping product managers move from scattered inputs to clear, evidence-based decisions.\n\n**gantry**\nA “n8n for agent orchestration” within the IDE, enabling developers to structure and manage AI agent workflows more effectively.\n\n**Cortexa**\nBuilds a memory observability layer for AI agents to reduce hallucinations and improve reliability by tracking how agents store and use information.\n\n**Fairlytics**\nReal-time bias mitigation for machine learning models, focused on identifying and reducing bias as predictions are made.\n\n## Business, Productivity & Vertical Applications\n\n**MottoNote**\nAn AI-native memory and recall layer designed to capture and organize decision-making context across meetings, documents, and conversations, helping users retrieve insights and generate structured outputs.\n\n**Retention Engine**\nRetention engine for independent barbers that integrates with booking platforms to analyze visit patterns, predict churn, and trigger personalized retention actions.\n\n**Tourrec (AI Travel Distribution Platform)**\nAI-powered B2B platform helping small travel agencies digitize operations, convert products into listings, and scale customer acquisition.\n\n**Lyntra**\nHelps students plan and prioritize assignments by breaking work into step-by-step sessions, scheduling around real commitments, and guiding focus.\n\n**Swift Recall**\nExplores how students can improve study habits through a custom iOS app that supports user-created flashcards and persistent learning data.\n\n**Everos**\nDelivers automated situational awareness by integrating data from unknown and distributed sensors into a unified, real-time intelligence layer. Designed for contested environments, it enables fast, autonomous decision-making in defense and other high-stakes settings.", "char_len": 2216, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::46", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 46, "text": "learning data.\n\n**Everos**\nDelivers automated situational awareness by integrating data from unknown and distributed sensors into a unified, real-time intelligence layer. Designed for contested environments, it enables fast, autonomous decision-making in defense and other high-stakes settings.\n\n**AI in Research**\nExplores how AI can support and accelerate research by helping researchers synthesize information, generate insights, and streamline workflows across review, analysis, and discovery.\n\n## Communication, Content & Experience\n\n**School of Veterinary Medicine – Translation Tool**\nAn AI translation tool to improve communication between English-speaking veterinarians and Spanish-speaking dairy farm workers in real time.\n\n**KLYP**\nAn AI-powered video editor that turns raw footage into polished, social-ready content in one step, automatically adding edits, captions, and short-form clips so creators can move faster.\n\n**BluWorld**\nA social platform designed to get people off their phones and into real-world experiences by helping users discover what’s happening in their city. Through gamified rewards and local business partnerships, BluWorld makes going out feel engaging while connecting users with events and new places.\n\n## Entrepreneurship, Ecosystem & Innovation\n\n**Chatbot for Entrepreneurs**\nConversational AI tool to help entrepreneurs and small business owners navigate uncertainty and make planning decisions in a more personalized and dynamic way.\n\n**Tech Exploration Lab**\nA front door to venture discovery at UW–Madison, where students work with industry and alumni to apply AI and emerging technologies to real-world challenges and develop ideas that can evolve into industry innovations and startups.\n\n**[RSVP to attend the Lab’s April 10 Demo Night]**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/16/fresh-ideas-and-emerging-talent-highlights-from-the-xorbix-hackathon", "char_len": 1911, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::47", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 47, "text": "emerging technologies to real-world challenges and develop ideas that can evolve into industry innovations and startups.\n\n**[RSVP to attend the Lab’s April 10 Demo Night]**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/16/fresh-ideas-and-emerging-talent-highlights-from-the-xorbix-hackathon\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0665-1024x768.jpg)This past weekend, Xorbix Technologies partnered with the Lab to run a hackathon, where student teams tackled a real-world AI and data challenge. In just a few hours, students generated a wide range of creative ideas and early prototypes—showing how quickly fresh thinking can emerge when talented students engage with meaningful problems.\n\n**Congratulations to our winning teams:**\n\n**First Place**\nSahar Arora and Smyan Vinu\n\n**Second Place**\nSahana Ganesh, Niyati Balu, and Shana Desai\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0662-1024x768.jpg)\n\nEvents like this highlight the value of industry-sponsored innovation challenges. Companies gain fresh ideas, visibility with top students, and a potential internship and hiring pipeline, while students get hands-on experience working on real industry problems.![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0670-1024x768.jpg)\n\nIf you’d like to connect with the Lab community, join us for our upcoming **Fourth Wednesday** gathering on March 25.\n\nWe open the doors to alumni and professionals for pizza, conversation, and student networking, a great way to see what students are building and meet the next generation of innovators.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/01/31/open-house-momentum\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/open-house-0126-1024x768.jpg)\n\nLab Faculty Director, Kevin Ponto, talks to students about their virtual reality project at the Open House.\n\nOur January 30 Open House was packed and not just with people, but with ideas.\n\nStudents explored demos, learned about the Lab and campus ecosystem, and stayed to connect.", "char_len": 2128, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::48", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 48, "text": "Faculty Director, Kevin Ponto, talks to students about their virtual reality project at the Open House.\n\nOur January 30 Open House was packed and not just with people, but with ideas.\n\nStudents explored demos, learned about the Lab and campus ecosystem, and stayed to connect.\n\nHuge thanks to student orgs TECH, Strato VC, Women in Entrepreneurship, Badger Future Founders, Transcend, and Badger Blockchain for showing up and demonstrating connectivity in the ecosystem.\n\nThe semester is ramping fast for the Lab across Open Innovation, Industry Innovation, and Venture pathways.\n\nIf this is how we’re starting, we’re in for something big.\n\nLet’s build.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/01/29/kicking-off-spring-at-the-uw-tech-exploration-lab\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/FL-3-1024x683.jpg)Some of our programs have applications at the beginning of the semester. But here’s the important part.\n\n**You don’t need to be in a formal program to build with us.**\n\nStarting in the first week of September, e*veryone* can plug into:\n\n* Weekly Open Labs — Mondays & Wednesdays, 3:00–6:00 PM\n* Friday Build Nights — 6:00–10:00 PM (check the Lab’s calendar to let us know you are coming)\n* Workshops & skill-building sessions\n* Workshops, Challenges and Hackathons\n* Volunteer opportunities\n* Monthly “Fourth Wednesday” alumni, mentor, and Industry events and pop-ups (check the Lab’s  calendar for these events)\n\nWhether you’re startup-curious, building your first prototype, or deep into applied AI — there’s a place for you here. Most events are in the main level of 1403 University Ave. unless stated otherwise.\n\n**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar.**\n\nLet’s build what’s next.", "char_len": 1863, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::49", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 49, "text": "a place for you here. Most events are in the main level of 1403 University Ave. unless stated otherwise.\n\n**The best way to stay plugged into events and other things happening in the Lab is to subscribe to our email list, join discord and subscribe to our calendar.**\n\nLet’s build what’s next.\n\n**Our Location:** We are located at 1403 University Ave. Look for the tan building marked **1403** on University Ave. **For events on the main level**, enter the double glass doors facing University Ave. **For events on the second floor**, walk to the west side of the building which is Lorch Street. Enter through the double glass doors facing the loading zone on Lorch, then head straight upstairs to the second level.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/12/23/from-ai-hotel-booking-to-blockchain-payments-students-building-whats-next\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/demo-1225-scaled.jpg)In our first year, 400+ students have built 90+ ventures using AI, blockchain, and emerging tech—and many are moving toward commercialization.\n\nStudents have created blockchain technology that processes bank payments in under a second. AI-powered compliance platforms that reduce government audit costs. Tools that help small businesses navigate challenges using generative AI. Carpooling apps reshaping student commutes. Skin-care platforms replacing influencer marketing with peer trust.\n\nThe Cap Times recently came to our Demo Night to see these projects in action and explore partnerships like our work with the Wisconsin Small Business Development Center, where students transformed a pandemic resource guide into an AI adviser now helping entrepreneurs statewide.\n\nAs Executive Director Sandra Bradley told The Cap Times: “Our biggest problem today is we can’t meet the demand.”\n\nThis work is made possible by alumni support and industry partnerships. Interested in helping us scale to meet student demand? [Connect with us]\n\nRead more about what we are building in the **full article**.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/12/04/how-ai-robotics-quantum-are-reshaping-business-insights-from-the-tech-exploration-lab-industry-forum", "char_len": 2201, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::50", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 50, "text": "Interested in helping us scale to meet student demand? [Connect with us]\n\nRead more about what we are building in the **full article**.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/12/04/how-ai-robotics-quantum-are-reshaping-business-insights-from-the-tech-exploration-lab-industry-forum\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/industry-0-1024x768.jpg)At the December UW-Madison Technology & Innovation Leadership Forum, UW–Madison’s Tech Exploration Lab convened campus leaders and industry partners to explore the technologies shaping the future of business. The session featured a compelling presentation by faculty member and Wisconsin Institute for Discovery associate, Kevin Ponto, whose framing on Artificial Intelligence, Robotics, and Quantum Computing offered a strategic roadmap for leaders navigating rapid technological change.\n\n---\n\n## **The Three Technologies Every Leader Should Understand**\n\n### **1. AI — Deep Pattern Recognition at Unprecedented Scale**\n\nKevin explained how modern AI functions as a multi-layered pattern-recognition system capable of analyzing data in ways that were unimaginable only a few years ago. Its ability to automate complex tasks and surface hidden insights is reshaping product development, decision-making, and workforce design.\n\n### **2. Robotics — Accelerating Through AI Integration**\n\nAI is dramatically expanding what robotics can do. Kevin highlighted how the convergence of AI + robotics will transform operations, logistics, healthcare, manufacturing, and service industries over the coming decade.\n\n### **3. Quantum Computing — The Next Frontier**\n\nQuantum computing, though still in early development, will fundamentally change what is computationally possible. Kevin offered a rare, digestible explanation of how qubits work and why quantum systems will disrupt fields from cybersecurity to drug discovery.\n\n**The takeaway:**\nLeaders don’t need to be engineers — but they do need fluency in emerging tech to make sound strategic decisions.\n\n---\n\n## **Industry Breakouts: What Companies Are Thinking About Now**\n\nAfter Kevin’s talk, industry and campus leaders joined small-group discussions. Several themes stood out:\n\n### **Human–AI Collaboration Needs Clear Frameworks**", "char_len": 2278, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::51", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 51, "text": "need fluency in emerging tech to make sound strategic decisions.\n\n---\n\n## **Industry Breakouts: What Companies Are Thinking About Now**\n\nAfter Kevin’s talk, industry and campus leaders joined small-group discussions. Several themes stood out:\n\n### **Human–AI Collaboration Needs Clear Frameworks**\n\nPartners want practical guidance on when AI should act autonomously, when humans must intervene, and how to design workflows with trust and responsibility in mind.\n\n### **Scenario-Based, Experiential Learning Is Essential**\n\nBusiness leaders emphasized the need to train students in judgment, communication, and leadership within AI-enabled contexts — not just technical literacy.\n\n### **Interest in Applied Research & Analytics Support**\n\nParticipants explored opportunities for a student-led analytics or research support model that builds student skills while supporting campus units and industry partners.\n\n### **The Pace of Change Is Outrunning Static Curricula**\n\nParticipants agreed: flexible and iterative learning environments like the Tech Exploration Lab are increasingly critical.\n\n---\n\n## **Building a Testing Ground for Emerging Tech**\n\nKevin’s framing and the industry breakout insights point in the same direction:\nUW–Madison needs spaces where students, faculty, and industry can experiment, iterate, and de-risk emerging technologies.\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab is becoming exactly that — a campus crossroads where:\n\n* Students practice real-world innovation\n* Industry partners explore ideas safely\n* New models for leadership and collaboration emerge\n\nIf you’re interested in partnering, mentoring, or running an applied experiment with the Lab, we’d love to connect. Contact us to learn more.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/12/04/building-whats-next-highlights-from-the-tech-exploration-lab-student-demo-night\n\n#\n\n# **Student Innovation on Display: Highlights from the Tech Exploration Lab Demo Night**\n\nOn December 3, the Tech Exploration Lab hosted its Fall 2025 Student Demo Night at UW-Madison, bringing together student teams from Venture Build, Self-Directed Innovation, Industry Innovation, and Build Fest programs. The evening showcased creativity, technical talent, and the entrepreneurial spirit driving innovation across UW–Madison.", "char_len": 2283, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::52", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 52, "text": "hosted its Fall 2025 Student Demo Night at UW-Madison, bringing together student teams from Venture Build, Self-Directed Innovation, Industry Innovation, and Build Fest programs. The evening showcased creativity, technical talent, and the entrepreneurial spirit driving innovation across UW–Madison.\n\nIndustry partners, alumni, and campus collaborators joined the event to meet student teams, ask questions, and offer feedback. A special thank-you to our industry judges — Tejvir Mann, Tim Nott, Frank Hansen, and Michael Szewczyk — for lending their expertise and insight.\n\n---\n\n# **Venture Build Awards**\n\n**EverOS (Venture Build – 1st Place)**EverOS is a real-time AI orchestration platform for venue and security operators. It unifies video, audio, and sensor data to detect risks, reduce false alarms, and surface recommended actions instantly — improving situational awareness and public safety.\n\n---\n\n**SeaPay (Venture Build – 2nd Place)**SeaPay is a blockchain-enabled payment solution that helps hotels and alternative lodging providers accept cryptocurrency directly on their websites. It lowers fees, simplifies chargebacks, and expands payment options for global travelers.\n\n#\n\n---\n\n# **Self-Directed Innovation Awards**\n\n**First Place — PersonaXR**\nPersonaXR uses AI-powered virtual standardized patients in extended reality environments to help medical students practice clinical communication and decision-making.\n\n**Second Place — Bucky Match**\nBucky Match is an intelligent platform for validating major requirements and making navigation of a four-year degree program easy.\n\n---\n\n#\n\n## **The Energy in the Room**\n\nThroughout the evening, students demonstrated prototypes, shared research insights, and walked guests through their thought processes, challenges, and breakthroughs. Judges and attendees consistently remarked on the clarity, creativity, and ambition behind the work.\n\nDemo Night also highlighted the diversity of ideas students are exploring — spanning AI, robotics, digital health, XR, blockchain, sustainability, and campus-facing tools.\n\n---\n\n## **Congratulations to All Participating Teams**", "char_len": 2127, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::53", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 53, "text": "remarked on the clarity, creativity, and ambition behind the work.\n\nDemo Night also highlighted the diversity of ideas students are exploring — spanning AI, robotics, digital health, XR, blockchain, sustainability, and campus-facing tools.\n\n---\n\n## **Congratulations to All Participating Teams**\n\nYour curiosity, commitment, and courage to build are shaping the future of innovation at UW–Madison. We’re excited to support your continued exploration through the Lab’s Venture Discovery, Venture Build, Self-Directed Innovation, and industry challenge programs.\n\n---\n\n# **Looking Ahead**\n\nWith the rapid acceleration of AI and emerging technologies, spaces like the Tech Exploration Lab are becoming essential. Demo Night reflects the Lab’s mission perfectly:\nto give students a place to experiment, collaborate, and turn bold ideas into reality.\n\nWe look forward to seeing what this talent builds next.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/12/03/celebrating-an-incredible-venture-build-pitch-night\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/12/venture-build-1225-1024x768.jpeg)Our first Venture Build Pitch Night showcased 15 Wisconsin School of Business MBA-led teams presenting venture concepts developed in partnership with University of Wisconsin-Madison technical student teams in the Lab. Industry judges and ecosystem partners joined us for an evening of business insight for early-stage tech ideas.\n\n**Top 5 Things Our Judges Loved (and What They Want to See More Of)**\n\nAcross all 15 pitches, our judges consistently highlighted five elements that set strong founders apart:", "char_len": 1631, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::54", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 54, "text": "the Lab. Industry judges and ecosystem partners joined us for an evening of business insight for early-stage tech ideas.\n\n**Top 5 Things Our Judges Loved (and What They Want to See More Of)**\n\nAcross all 15 pitches, our judges consistently highlighted five elements that set strong founders apart:\n\n1. **Lead with a compelling, human problem**\n   Start with something relatable. Emotional connection and specificity help the audience care right away.\n2. **Keep the story visually simple**\n   Clear, uncluttered slides and quick demos went a long way. Photos, diagrams, and prototypes helped teams communicate their ideas effectively.\n3. **Show real customer validation**\n   The best pitches tied user insights directly into product decisions — and several teams demonstrated early traction or willingness-to-pay signals.\n4. **Define your wedge and go-to-market**Judges wanted to see where teams get early traction, how they differentiate, and the first paths to adoption.\n5. **Make the business case**Strong teams articulated value, scale, sustainability, and why someone would pay for the solution.\n\nThese insights will continue shaping how we coach student founders — and they reflect what truly resonated with our industry partners.\n\n**Congratulations to Our Winning Teams**\n\nThe judges had tough decisions, but three teams rose to the top with standout clarity, creativity, and potential:\n\n**Best Overall**\n\n**proTecht**\n An AI-powered compliance automation platform for federal cloud service providers reducing FedRAMP audit costs by up to 40% and accelerating security authorization. A polished concept with real market urgency.\n\n**Most Innovative Go-to-Market Approach**\n\n**EverOS**\n A real-time AI orchestration platform for venue operators and security teams. Their approach to pilots, including a UWPD “living lab,” showed a strong path to early traction.\n\n**Best Pitch**\n\n**ARHat+** A LiDAR/AR smartphone tool that identifies home safety risks and ADA compliance gaps in minutes, streamlining documentation and improving care coordination across health and housing systems.\n\n**Acknowledgments**", "char_len": 2105, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::55", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 55, "text": "UWPD “living lab,” showed a strong path to early traction.\n\n**Best Pitch**\n\n**ARHat+** A LiDAR/AR smartphone tool that identifies home safety risks and ADA compliance gaps in minutes, streamlining documentation and improving care coordination across health and housing systems.\n\n**Acknowledgments**\n\nWe were honored to kick off the evening with opening remarks from Shayna Hetzel (WEDC), who highlighted the importance of interdisciplinary teams and the state’s support for venture-scale innovation.\n\nA heartfelt thank-you to our judges for their thoughtful engagement and tough deliberations:\n\n* Garrett Lauderdale – Idea Fund of La Crosse\n* Brad Bodden – Wisconsin Investment Partners (WIP)\n* Mason Cook – MasterCraft Ventures\n\n**Looking Ahead**\n\nThis first Venture Build cohort set a new bar. We’re energized by their momentum, inspired by their creativity, and excited to continue building a program where technical founders gain the business insight, customer understanding, and early traction needed to launch what’s next.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/11/07/from-curiosity-to-startup-how-the-tech-exploration-lab-helped-a-student-tech-entrepreneur-turn-ideas-into-impact\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/11/Alka-Lakadia-Dermavision-600-x-600-300x300.png)When Alka Lakadia (’27) joined the UW Tech Exploration Lab in early 2025, she describes it as “a turning point” in her UW–Madison journey.\n\n“I was creating cool projects,” she said, “but the Lab taught me to think: *Is it going to matter? Is it creating a positive impact?*”\n\nThat mindset shift sparked DermaVision, her first AI-powered teledermatology venture aimed at making skin care more accessible. After success in the Lab’s Spring Showcase, Summer Venture Discovery Program, and national competitions, Alka returned this fall with a new direction — MadGlow, a social platform she calls “the Instagram of skin,” designed to help people track, share, and learn about their skin health through AI and community insights.\n\n“The Lab pushed me to connect my technical skills with real-world impact,” Alka said. “It gave me a place to experiment, get feedback, and actually build something meaningful.”", "char_len": 2228, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::56", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 56, "text": "of skin,” designed to help people track, share, and learn about their skin health through AI and community insights.\n\n“The Lab pushed me to connect my technical skills with real-world impact,” Alka said. “It gave me a place to experiment, get feedback, and actually build something meaningful.”\n\nAlka’s journey from idea to launch captures what the Tech Exploration Lab is all about — helping students explore emerging technologies, apply entrepreneurial thinking, and turn bold ideas into ventures with real-world impact.\n\nRead the full story on the UW–Madison Computer Sciences website:\n***Making connections: Alka Lakadia’s journey from international student to tech entrepreneur***\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/10/07/founder-stories-social-conversations-that-spark-whats-next\n\n**![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/networking.jpeg)Friday, October 10 • 5:30–7:00 PM**\n**Tech Exploration Lab, 1403 University Avenue**\n\nJoin us and Transcend UW for an intimate social following *Founder Stories: An Evening with Amazing Entrepreneurs.* Connect with campus leaders, alumni, and industry partners who are shaping the future of innovation at UW–Madison.\n\nFeatured guests include **Max Schauff**, Co-founder of *LineLeap* — UW alum, Transcend winner, and builder of a nightlife platform now serving 1.5M+ users nationwide — and **Mike Trigg**, Silicon Valley founder, executive, and investor who has scaled multiple startups to major exits and now coaches the next generation of entrepreneurs.\n\nLight refreshments provided. Attendance is limited.\n**Request an Invitation**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/09/17/build-nights-are-here-fridays-at-1403\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/IMG_1750-scaled.png)**Build Nights have wrapped up for the Spring Semester and will start again in Fall. Check the Lab’s discord for announcements and the Lab’s event calendar to RSVP.**\n\nTake part in the energy of our weekly series in collaboration with **Transcend UW** — **Build Nights at 1403!**", "char_len": 2109, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::57", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 57, "text": "Nights have wrapped up for the Spring Semester and will start again in Fall. Check the Lab’s discord for announcements and the Lab’s event calendar to RSVP.**\n\nTake part in the energy of our weekly series in collaboration with **Transcend UW** — **Build Nights at 1403!**\n\n**Every Friday | 6:00–10:00 PM**\n**1403 University Ave**Build Nights are your chance to create, connect, and have fun. Whether you’re working on a side project, growing a venture, or just exploring an idea, you’ll find space, support, and community here. We often have founder guest speakers who share their journey stories with time for conversation and questions.\n\nWhat to expect:\n\n* **Plenty of room to build** — bring your laptop and dive in.\n* **Snacks and board games** to keep the energy high.\n* **Peer mentors on site** — technical and venture mentors from the Tech Exploration Lab and Transcend — to help troubleshoot, iterate, or guide your ideas.\n* A welcoming community where curiosity, creativity, and collaboration come first.\n\nSo bring your friends, your imagination, and your projects-in-progress. Let’s make Friday nights the place where ideas turn into real innovations and companies.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/09/01/uw-tech-exploration-lab-featured-in-on-wisconsin-magazine-inventing-the-future\n\n# Mike Grall, CEO with Fulcrum Solutions watches a demo of a Quest headset with UW-Madison student Mason Baloun.\n\nWe’re thrilled to share that the **Wisconsin Foundation and Alumni Association’s On Wisconsin Magazine** has featured the UW Tech Exploration Lab in its article, *Inventing the Future*. The piece highlights the Lab’s role as a launchpad for students to explore emerging technologies, test new venture ideas, and connect with industry leaders and alumni mentors who bring real-world challenges into the classroom.\n\nOur work is powered by the guidance and expertise of incredible partners and alumni who give their time, insights, and problems to solve. They help UW–Madison students apply breakthrough technologies to real-world challenges and discover pathways to innovation.", "char_len": 2103, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::58", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 58, "text": "challenges into the classroom.\n\nOur work is powered by the guidance and expertise of incredible partners and alumni who give their time, insights, and problems to solve. They help UW–Madison students apply breakthrough technologies to real-world challenges and discover pathways to innovation.\n\nA special thank you to **Luke Anderson, Kurt Kober, and Michael Grall** who are featured in the article, as well as alumni leaders **Singari Seshadri, Christian Kaczmarczyk, Tim Bratland, Abram Becker, Kristin Storhoff, Timothy Davison, Tyler Waite, Daniel Borkhus, Jim Wuthrich, Jennifer Levenhagen, Brian Wiegand, and Kurt Malueg**—and so many others—for their leadership and mentorship.\n\nWe are also grateful for our **Executives-in-Residence and mentors** who made this summer a success: **Patrick Reetz, David Qu, Andrew S. Atwell, Mike Zhang, Matthew Kruepke, Kevin Ponto, Jirs Meuris, Heather Ferguson, Kendra Ramick, and Zekai Otles**.\n\nFinally, a thank you to our campus partners—the **Wisconsin School of Business, Discovery to Product, and the Wisconsin Institute for Discovery**—for sparking the momentum that drives this work.\n\nTogether, we’re shaping the next generation of innovators and entrepreneurs and strengthening the Wisconsin Idea through hands-on exploration, industry collaboration, and bold new ventures.\n\n📖 Read the full article here: *Inventing the Future* – On Wisconsin Magazine\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/08/26/ways-to-get-involved-fall-2025\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/20250709_120338-hackathon.jpg)The **UW Tech Exploration Lab** is where students from every discipline come to explore, build, and launch bold ideas. This fall, there are many ways to get involved depending on your interests and goals. And, yes, you can join more than one thing.\n\n---\n\n## Self-directed Innovation\n\nChoose your Adventure: Jump into hackathons, sandbox sessions, and themed explorations where you can test out new tools, pilot ideas, and learn by doing. You can just show up, bring your curiosity, and get hands-on experience. Or, propose your own idea or project to explore. **Spots are limited. Submit proposals by September 15.**\n\n---\n\n## Venture Build", "char_len": 2241, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::59", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 59, "text": "and themed explorations where you can test out new tools, pilot ideas, and learn by doing. You can just show up, bring your curiosity, and get hands-on experience. Or, propose your own idea or project to explore. **Spots are limited. Submit proposals by September 15.**\n\n---\n\n## Venture Build\n\nAlready have an idea, prototype, or MVP? **Venture Build** is a structured sprint (Sept 30 – Dec 3) where technical teams are paired with MBA students from the School of Business’ *New Product Development* course. Together, you’ll refine your value proposition, test with real users, and develop a go-to-market strategy.\n\n* Best for teams that want to move from **prototype to venture-ready concept**.\n\n**Apply by September 15 for Venture Build.**\n\n---\n\n## Innovation Fellow Program\n\nJoin the Lab’s competitive **Innovation Fellows cohort** and be part of our core student team driving innovation. Fellows work on Lab projects, industry collaborations, and venture experiments.\n\nTwo tracks are available:\n\n* **Volunteer Fellows** – flexible, exploratory, 1–7 hrs/week\n* **Industry Fellows (Paid)** – stipend-supported, 5–10 hrs/week tied to defined deliverables\n* Best for students seeking **broad exposure to innovation, cross-disciplinary teamwork, and industry mentorship**.\n\n**Apply by September 15 for the Innovation Fellow Program.**\n\n---\n\n## Douglas D. Bradley Digital Health Challenge\n\nIn Spring 2026, work with mentors and industry experts to explore how **emerging technologies and AI** can transform brain health, longevity, and aging. Teams tackle real-world use cases with high social impact and compete for **cash prizes**.\n\n* Open to students in **tech, business, health, design, and beyond**.\n\n**Register now for the Digital Health Challenge to be notified of pre-Challenge warm-events and other updates.**\n\n---\n\n## Weekly Sessions + Showcase\n\nAnyone can take part in **weekly Open Labs and sessions** featuring workshops, speakers, and team time.\n\nThe semester culminates in the **Fall Showcase & Demo Night on December 3**, an expo-style event for students, alumni, and industry partners.\n\n---\n\n## Who Can Get Involved\n\n* Open to **undergrads, grad students, and postdocs** from any major.\n* No prior experience required — just **curiosity, creativity, and commitment**.", "char_len": 2282, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::60", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 60, "text": "in the **Fall Showcase & Demo Night on December 3**, an expo-style event for students, alumni, and industry partners.\n\n---\n\n## Who Can Get Involved\n\n* Open to **undergrads, grad students, and postdocs** from any major.\n* No prior experience required — just **curiosity, creativity, and commitment**.\n\n**Questions?** Contact sandra.bradley@wisc.edu\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/08/25/congratulations-to-our-summer-innovation-venture-fellows\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/0819-1-scaled.jpg)\n\nThis summer, students at the **UW Tech Exploration Lab** rolled up their sleeves to explore emerging technologies, test early-stage startup ideas, and move forward internal Lab projects.\n\nTheir work spanned everything from AI prototypes to student experience innovations, including:\n\n* **AI Sports Agent** – Concepting an AI agent to connect sponsors with athletes.\n* **AI Research Assistant** – Building an AI model to streamline workflows and improve outcomes for researchers.\n* **Trusted to Lead AI Coach** – Exploring the feasibility of an “AI coach in your pocket” for students to engage with leadership principles and guidance.\n* **RFID Equipment Tracking** – Prototyping an innovation for novel use cases in equipment management.\n* **ChatBot for Entrepreneurs** – Automating support for entrepreneurs in challenging times.\n* **Polycast** – Advancing a solution to improve experiences for ESL learners.\n* **UW Match** – Supporting a student innovation to streamline course planning for UW students.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/0819-3.png)\n\nBeyond these projects, our Fellows also played a vital role in **exploring new ideas for the Lab, marketing, project management, industry engagement, events, hackathons, and Lab operations**—the behind-the-scenes work that makes new ventures possible.\n\nWe are incredibly proud of the **creativity, persistence, and entrepreneurial spirit** our Fellows brought to every challenge. Their contributions highlight the Lab’s role as a **launchpad for early-stage innovation and entrepreneurship—helping raw ideas take shape and move closer to venture readiness.**", "char_len": 2217, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::61", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 61, "text": "incredibly proud of the **creativity, persistence, and entrepreneurial spirit** our Fellows brought to every challenge. Their contributions highlight the Lab’s role as a **launchpad for early-stage innovation and entrepreneurship—helping raw ideas take shape and move closer to venture readiness.**\n\nStay tuned as we continue to expand opportunities for students to test bold ideas while engaging with alumni and industry partners to shape the **next generation of startups at UW–Madison.**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/08/21/ai-venture-discovery-program-a-summer-of-student-innovation\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/alka-vd.jpg) This summer, the UW Tech Exploration Lab piloted the **AI Venture Discovery Program**, designed to take promising student ideas from the spring semester and stress-test their potential for venture readiness. With dedicated mentors, Lab support, and our first-ever **Feedback Salon**, students had the opportunity to push their ideas further, gather real-world input, and experience the messy, exciting process of early-stage venture discovery.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/daniel-vd.jpg)\n\nWe are proud of the creativity and determination our students showed in presenting their progress. Among the standout projects:\n\n* **Dermavision** — AI-powered skin health analysis and personalized healthcare solutions.\n* **ARHAT+** — Market insights applied to UW–Madison research on AR-based accessibility assessments for aging at home.\n* **Ember AI** — Predictive models for early wildfire risk detection.\n* **InventoryAutomate** — AI and computer vision applied to smart retail inventory management.\n* **ARCA+** — Exploring pathways to translate UW–Madison AI + 3D research into real-world applications.\n* **Alzheimer’s Hub** – app for supporting patients and caregivers.\n* **PersonaFlow** – personal productivity AI tool.\n\n### What’s Next\n\nThe Venture Discovery summer program is just the beginning. As we expand this program, our goal is to help more early-stage ideas move into **venture-ready mode**—shaping the next generation of startups to emerge from UW–Madison.", "char_len": 2214, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::62", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 62, "text": "**PersonaFlow** – personal productivity AI tool.\n\n### What’s Next\n\nThe Venture Discovery summer program is just the beginning. As we expand this program, our goal is to help more early-stage ideas move into **venture-ready mode**—shaping the next generation of startups to emerge from UW–Madison.\n\nStay tuned as we continue to grow this work, and join us in celebrating the students, mentors, and partners who are making it possible.\n\n### Get Involved\n\nInterested in being part of this journey? Whether you’re a student ready to test an idea, an alum eager to give back, or a company looking to explore innovation challenges, the UW Tech Exploration Lab welcomes your involvement. Reach out to learn more about mentoring opportunities, sponsorships, or project collaborations.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/07/13/post-event-recap-ai-startup-mixer-and-hackathon-spark-real-time-innovation-at-uw-tech-exploration-lab\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/20250709_120338-hackathon-1024x576.jpg)\n\nNearly 50 students from across campus took part in Google’s AI Startup School followed by a 24-hour hackathon sponsored by the Lab.\n\n**Thank you to all who joined us on July 9th** for the AI Startup Mixer & Hackathon at the UW Tech Exploration Lab. It was a dynamic and electric evening where student passion met real-world insight, and where the energy of emerging innovation was on full display. These events were hosted as a capstone to **Google’s AI Startup School**, and they brought cutting-edge tools, education, and startup frameworks from Google to life.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/mixer-4-1024x576.jpg)\n\nStartup CEO, Kerra Guffey, hearing about student projects mid-hackathon.\n\nThis wasn’t your average hackathon. It was the culmination of a multi-week learning sprint, paired with mentor drop-ins, team coaching, and collaborative sessions—all designed to get students closer to what launching a real startup actually feels like. And true to the Lab’s mission, it fused **industry access, hands-on experimentation, and emerging tech exploration** to activate talent in ways the classroom can’t.", "char_len": 2214, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::63", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 63, "text": "team coaching, and collaborative sessions—all designed to get students closer to what launching a real startup actually feels like. And true to the Lab’s mission, it fused **industry access, hands-on experimentation, and emerging tech exploration** to activate talent in ways the classroom can’t.\n\nAnd set in the heart of the Hackathon schedule, our mixer wasn’t just about networking. **Industry leaders, alumni, and entrepreneurial professionals did more than drop by—they jumped in.** Throughout the event, guests circulated between student teams to hear early-stage pitches, offer valuable feedback, and share hard-won insights that helped shape ideas in real time. Projects ranged from API services, to browser extensions, to chatbots and agentic applications.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/hackathon-presos-1024x545.jpg)\n\nThe top five teams pitched to a campus and Google panel that provided feedback and ideas for next steps.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/mixer-3-1024x576.jpg)\n\nCybersecurity CEO and UW alum, Mike Grall, gives feedback on student ideas.\n\nThis kind of engagement is exactly what sets the Tech Exploration Lab apart. Our mission is to serve as a launchpad for innovation—connecting student talent, emerging technology, and real-world challenges through experimentation and exploration. And on July 9, that mission came to life. We were especially excited to see how many experienced programmers, whether they be master students or self-directed project veterans, showed up to learn about AI development for the first time. Armed with insights from Google’s best-in-class startup curriculum and support from visiting Google engineers, they tackled real-world problem spaces and developed promising early prototypes in just a matter of days.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/mixer-2-1024x576.jpg)\n\nMarketing expert and MBA candidate, Daniel Lockett, hears progress from student teams.\n\n**What made the evening special:**", "char_len": 2085, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::64", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 64, "text": "spaces and developed promising early prototypes in just a matter of days.\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/mixer-2-1024x576.jpg)\n\nMarketing expert and MBA candidate, Daniel Lockett, hears progress from student teams.\n\n**What made the evening special:**\n\n* Hands-on interaction with student teams building AI-powered startups in the Hackathon\n* Meaningful conversations that turned into coaching moments and creative breakthroughs\n* A shared sense of possibility at the intersection of entrepreneurship, AI, and impact\n\n**![Professionals Shawn Dennis and Fran Greenman hear practice pitches at the Mixer event.](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/07/mixer-1-1024x576.jpg)**\n\nStudents and industry leaders mingle during the mixer and pizza event.\n\n**To future participants,**we asked students what they would say to someone who would be curious about jumping into future events like this:\n\n* “Do it! Come up with a creative idea a few days in advance, plan a bit, and communicate well with your teammate throughout the whole time period.“\n* “Go for it! You might end up with a very cool project by the end, or at the very least you’ll probably learn a thing or two. Don’t be afraid to experiment and try new things!\n* “I’d say go for it—absolutely. It was an incredible experience where we not only got to build something meaningful but also learned a lot by collaborating under time pressure. You don’t need to be perfect or have everything figured out; just show up, stay curious, and keep building!”\n\n**To our alumni and industry guests: thank you** for showing up not just as spectators, but as collaborators. Your presence and participation made a lasting impression—and we’re just getting started.\n\nSee more student highlights from the hackathon and if you’re interested in engaging further—whether by proposing a project, mentoring a student team, or exploring ways to partner. **We’d love to hear from you.**Contact us at our industry page.\n\nThe buzz doesn’t stop here, we’re just getting started. More collaborations with Google are in motion, and the Lab will continue to serve as a launchpad where students, alumni, and partners come together to explore, experiment, and accelerate what’s next in AI.", "char_len": 2291, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::65", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 65, "text": "us at our industry page.\n\nThe buzz doesn’t stop here, we’re just getting started. More collaborations with Google are in motion, and the Lab will continue to serve as a launchpad where students, alumni, and partners come together to explore, experiment, and accelerate what’s next in AI.\n\n**Save the date**: **Join us August 18 for our end-of-summer networking** and see what’s launching next.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/06/29/jump-in-anytime-whats-happening-at-the-uw-tech-exploration-lab-this-summer-fall\n\n## **Summer & Fall 2025**\n\nThe **UW Tech Exploration Lab** is a **safe, flexible space** where **multidisciplinary students** can experiment with **emerging technologies — especially applied AI —** and bold **entrepreneurial ideas**, while connecting directly with **alumni and industry partners** who help turn sparks into real-world impact.\n\nStudents here don’t just learn — they test, build, and collaborate across disciplines, shaping what’s next for AI and other frontier tech, right in the heart of campus.\n\n**Most of our events are open to everyone across campus — students, researchers, alumni, and industry partners alike.**\n\nSee **what’s bubbling in the Lab this summer** — and get ready for even more this fall.\n\n---\n\n### **Weekly Open Labs**\n\n**Every Thursday, 3:30–5:30 PM | 1403 University Ave**\nDrop in to see what student teams are building, pitch your own idea, or chat with others experimenting with new tech. No sign-up needed — just bring your curiosity and join the conversation.\n\n---\n\n### **AI Startup Hackathon & Pop-Up Sprint**\n\n**July 9–10, 2025 | 1403 University Ave**\n\n* **AI Startup Hackathon:** Dive into a 24-hour AI build sprint starting on July 9 at 11:00. Food, fun, industry mentors, and drawings for prizes! Register here\n* **AI Startup Mixer:** July 9, 5:00–7:00 PM — mingle with students, early founders, alumni, and industry. See prototypes in progress. Mixer RSVP\n* **Google and Campus Feedback Session (Invite Only):** July 10, 9:00–10:30 AM — select teams present to Google and campus reps for live insights.\n\n---\n\n### **Executives & VCs in Residence Office Hours (virtual)**\n\nMeet virtually 1:1 with industry leaders through our **Executives & VCs in Residence** program:", "char_len": 2246, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::66", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 66, "text": "and Campus Feedback Session (Invite Only):** July 10, 9:00–10:30 AM — select teams present to Google and campus reps for live insights.\n\n---\n\n### **Executives & VCs in Residence Office Hours (virtual)**\n\nMeet virtually 1:1 with industry leaders through our **Executives & VCs in Residence** program:\n\n**Pat Reetz**\nMeet Pat Reetz, innovation advisor and former CTO, for practical guidance on building, scaling, and funding new ventures. LinkedIn\n\n**Singari Seshadri**\nConnect with Singari Seshadri, a seasoned corporate innovator and startup founder, to talk applied AI, emerging tech, and corporate partnerships. LinkedIn\n\n**Christian Kaczmarczyk**\nSit down with Christian Kaczmarczyk, early-stage investor and deep-tech entrepreneur, for honest advice on turning frontier ideas into investable companies. LinkedIn\n\nRead more about these alums with deep industry experience. More dates added throughout the summer — stay tuned! See Executives & VCs in Residence and subscribe to the Lab’s calendar to take part.\n\n---\n\n**Workshop (virtual)****Is This a Thing? Turning Ideas Into Clear Next Steps**\n**July 14, 2025 | 4:00 CT | Virtual**\nNYU advisor and entrepreneur Dana Mauriello will guide you through her 5-step method to test early ideas, stress-test assumptions, and decide what’s worth building (or scrapping) before you waste time. Hands-on, practical, and easy to apply. RSVP for this free event.\n\n---\n\n### **Venture Discovery Salon + Networking****August 18, 2025 | 1403 University Ave | During ForwardFest**\n\n* **Salon (Invite Only):** A deeper dive for select founders, alumni, and partners.\n* **Networking Reception:** 3:30–5:30 PM — connect with alumni, industry, and campus collaborators as part of ForwardFest. RSVP for this event\n\n---\n\n**Lab Fall Kickoff****September 10, 2025 | 5:30 PM | Deluca Forum, Discovery Building**\nFor students: Meet the Lab team, learn about fall projects and opportunities, and sign up to get involved. Info & RSVP\n\n---\n\n**Campus-Wide Startup Ecosystem Kickoff****September 12, 2025 | Campus-Wide | Details Coming Soon**\nFor students: We’re joining forces with student orgs, campus partners, and the Madison startup community to spotlight every opportunity for student founders, builders, and early-stage teams to plug in and launch.\n\n---", "char_len": 2281, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::67", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 67, "text": "Ecosystem Kickoff****September 12, 2025 | Campus-Wide | Details Coming Soon**\nFor students: We’re joining forces with student orgs, campus partners, and the Madison startup community to spotlight every opportunity for student founders, builders, and early-stage teams to plug in and launch.\n\n---\n\n### **Student Orgs & Co-Innovation Lab Pop-Ups**\n\nThis fall, look for pop-ups, sprints, and hands-on experiments with **student orgs like WAISI, dotData, and WE. We also are working with partners and other forward-thinking companies to run Co-labs and sprints**. We’re creating a **flexible, safe space** for students from across campus to test new tools, share ideas, and tackle real-world challenges — all in collaboration with alumni and industry mentors. **Details dropping soon — bring your ideas and let’s solve big problems together! Contact us with questions.**\n\n---\n\n**Join Us**Most events are **open to students, researchers, alumni, and industry friends** — so jump in, bring your ideas, and see what’s possible. Subscribe to our email list or contact us with questions.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2025/06/26/2990\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/06/h4-1024x383.jpg)\nReady to turn your ideas into working AI agents? The UW Tech Exploration Lab is excited to invite you to our AI Startup School Hackathon – whether you’re an AI veteran or completely new to the space, this event is designed for you.\n\n**Two Ways to Participate:**\n\n🚀**24 Hour Hackathon (July 9-10)**\nBuild something amazing with your team using cutting-edge tools like Vertex AI, Gemini models, and the Agent Development Kit. Present to Google and compete for great prizes!\n\n⚡ **Pop-Up AI Sprint (July 9 afternoon only)**\nPerfect for beginners! A hands-on workshop where you’ll explore AI possibilities – no coding required, just bring your curiosity and creativity.\n\n**What’s Waiting for You:**\n\n* Free food throughout the event\n* Networking mixer with Google reps, industry professionals and alumni\n* Hands-on experience with industry-leading tools\n* Connection with fellow builders and innovators\n\nWhether you’re looking to push the boundaries of what’s possible with AI or just want to understand what all the buzz is about, we’ve got a spot for you.", "char_len": 2290, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::68", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 68, "text": "reps, industry professionals and alumni\n* Hands-on experience with industry-leading tools\n* Connection with fellow builders and innovators\n\nWhether you’re looking to push the boundaries of what’s possible with AI or just want to understand what all the buzz is about, we’ve got a spot for you.\n\n**REGISTER HERE!**\n\n**When:** July 9th (11 AM CDT) – July 10th (11 AM CDT)\n**Where:**1403 University Ave, Madison, WI\n\nQuestions? **Email us**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/?post_type=post\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab is hiring for 2026–27. We’re expanding our student team to work on applied AI and emerging technology — real projects, real industry partners, real outcomes. These positions are for the …\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab is heading into summer with momentum — and we’re kicking things off with an open, informal gathering at the Lab. Come meet the community, grab some pizza, and hear what’s …\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab will be in San Francisco on June 25, bringing a select group of Founder Lab teams to engage with the broader Bay Area innovation ecosystem. Following a focused feedback session …\n\nThinking about raising money but not sure if you should? Or how ready you really are? Join us for a candid, student-focused networking session where you can: Get real feedback on your idea or startup …\n\nAs part of the Tech Exploration Lab’s Venture Pathway, Founder Lab brings together teams that are moving beyond exploration and into shaping real-world innovation and venture opportunities. On April 23 at 3:30 PM, Founder Lab …\n\nCelebrating Innovation and Venture Momentum Last week’s Tech Exploration Lab Demo Night brought together a mix of students, industry partners, alumni, and the broader innovation community for an evening of showcasing applied innovation. Student teams …\n\nSee a map for the April 10 Demo Night Health, Wellness & Human Performance NeuroTrackMobile-based system designed to monitor subtle changes in neurological function for individuals with Multiple Sclerosis, using daily tests and passive data …", "char_len": 2057, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::69", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 69, "text": "of showcasing applied innovation. Student teams …\n\nSee a map for the April 10 Demo Night Health, Wellness & Human Performance NeuroTrackMobile-based system designed to monitor subtle changes in neurological function for individuals with Multiple Sclerosis, using daily tests and passive data …\n\nJoin us for the Digital Health Challenge Finalist Presentations, where student teams from across UW–Madison will share their work exploring innovation in brain health and healthcare. These teams have been developing and testing ideas at …\n\nThis past weekend, Xorbix Technologies partnered with the Lab to run a hackathon, where student teams tackled a real-world AI and data challenge. In just a few hours, students generated a wide range of creative …\n\nThe Four Weeks to Demo Sprint from the UW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab helps students move from early ideas to a clear, demo-ready concept. The sprint is open to all Tech Exploration Lab students working on …\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/04/07/digital-health-challenge-finalists-student-teams-present-whats-next-in-health-innovation\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/08/digital-health-header-300x200.png)Join us for the Digital Health Challenge Finalist Presentations, where student teams from across UW–Madison will share their work exploring innovation in brain health and healthcare.\n\nThese teams have been developing and testing ideas at the intersection of AI, emerging technologies, and real-world health challenges and this is a chance to hear directly from them as they present their insights, approaches, and next steps. **Read more about the Challenge**and **see submissions**.\n\n**Finalist Presentations\nFriday, April 10**\nhttps://luma.com/dwu4ntf9\n\nAn industry judging panel will evaluate finalist teams and award prizes at this event. The Lab’s Demo Night with a broader set of student innovators follows at 5:30: https://luma.com/bik11b3b\n\nThis is a unique opportunity to see early-stage ideas, engage with student teams, and get a look at what’s emerging in digital health.\n\nAll are welcome to attend.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/07/build-an-idea-test-it-demo-it-in-four-weeks", "char_len": 2231, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::70", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 70, "text": "5:30: https://luma.com/bik11b3b\n\nThis is a unique opportunity to see early-stage ideas, engage with student teams, and get a look at what’s emerging in digital health.\n\nAll are welcome to attend.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/07/build-an-idea-test-it-demo-it-in-four-weeks\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/ad1dc454-d758-474c-98d9-dc6ab2f26021-200x300.png)The Four Weeks to Demo Sprint from the UW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab helps students move from early ideas to a clear, demo-ready concept.\n\nThe sprint is open to all Tech Exploration Lab students working on projects—including Digital Health, Self-Directed Innovation, Venture Discovery, and Founder Lab. It is also open to any UW–Madison students independently exploring an idea.\n\nParticipants can join any part of the sprint, or take part in the full four-week sequence.\n\nThe goal is simple: move from idea → concept → demo.\n\n# What You’ll Work On\n\nOver the course of the sprint, students will:\n\n* Define and sharpen a problem and use case\n* Test key assumptions\n* Build or refine a lightweight concept\n* Prepare a 2–3 minute demo\n\nThe sprint culminates in **Demo Night on April 10**, where teams can share what they built, what they learned, and what might be worth pursuing next.\n\n# Sprint Schedule\n\n### Week 1 — Define Your Use Case (*Workshop completed)*\n\nStudents worked on clarifying the person → task → problem behind their ideas and began drafting an experiment plan.\n\n### Week 2 — Explore & Validate (*Independent work week)*\n\nStudents spend this week finishing experiment plans and exploring their idea through:\n\n* Early research and testing\n* Validating assumptions\n* Prototyping or sketching concepts\n* Identifying what their demo might show\n\nDrop in on Open Labs M and W 3:00-6:00 with questions or to bounce ideas with Lab staff.\n\n### Week 3 — Build, Test & Troubleshoot (**Friday, March 20 | 4:30–6:00 PM)**\n\nThis session focuses on **moving ideas forward and working through challenges.**\n\nStudents will share what they’ve been exploring, troubleshoot technical or product questions, and receive **structured peer feedback** while refining their demo concept.\n\n**Register for Build, Test & Troubleshoot**\n\n---", "char_len": 2253, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::71", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 71, "text": "session focuses on **moving ideas forward and working through challenges.**\n\nStudents will share what they’ve been exploring, troubleshoot technical or product questions, and receive **structured peer feedback** while refining their demo concept.\n\n**Register for Build, Test & Troubleshoot**\n\n---\n\n### Week 4 — Package & Present Your Idea (**Friday, March 27 | 4:30–6:00 PM)**\n\nThe final session focuses on turning your concept into a clear and compelling demo.\n\nStudents will practice short 2–3 minute presentations, refine how they communicate their idea, and receive feedback on how to make their demo clear and engaging before Demo Night.\n\n**Register for Package & Present Your Idea**\n\n# Demo Night — April 10\n\nStudents participating in the sprint can optionally present their work at **Demo Night**, an exploration showcase focused on learning and experimentation. Instead of polished startup pitches, teams share:\n\n* What they explored\n* What they built\n* What they learned\n\nCash prizes will be awarded for most innovative and most impactful ideas in select focus areas.\n\n# Who Should Participate\n\nThis sprint is ideal for:\n\n* Tech Exploration Lab students currently working on projects\n* Students developing early venture ideas\n* Builders experimenting with AI or emerging technologies\n* Anyone who wants to test an idea and create a demo\n\nYou can **join a single session or participate in the full sprint.**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/04/from-factory-data-to-ai-a-hands-on-workshop-hackathon-with-xorbix\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/1-791x1024.png)Real innovation doesn’t start with theory. It starts with real problems.\n\nOn **March 14**, the **UW Tech Exploration Lab** is partnering with **Xorbix Technologies** to host a hands-on workshop and hackathon exploring how manufacturing data can be transformed into analytics and AI-driven insights.\n\nStudents will work directly with engineers from Xorbix to learn how production data flows through modern data platforms like **Databricks**, and how those pipelines ultimately power dashboards, analytics, and machine learning systems.", "char_len": 2168, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::72", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 72, "text": "data can be transformed into analytics and AI-driven insights.\n\nStudents will work directly with engineers from Xorbix to learn how production data flows through modern data platforms like **Databricks**, and how those pipelines ultimately power dashboards, analytics, and machine learning systems.\n\nThe day begins with a **practical, applied workshop** covering how operational data is ingested, modeled, and turned into meaningful metrics. In the afternoon, participants will move into a **guided hackathon**, where teams will explore how analytics and AI could support real operational decisions in a manufacturing-style scenario.\n\nStudents might explore questions like:\n\n* What patterns in factory data signal equipment downtime?\n* How can analytics help identify quality issues earlier?\n* What kinds of dashboards help operators make better decisions?\n* Could an AI assistant help monitor production systems?\n\nTeams will present their ideas at the end of the event, with **cash prizes awarded for the top pitches**.\n\nThis event is designed to be **small, interactive, and hands-on**, giving students the opportunity to collaborate with peers across disciplines and get exposure to how modern companies actually work with data and AI.\n\nStudents from **engineering, computer science, data science, analytics, and business** are all encouraged to participate.\n\nFood and drinks will be provided, and teams will work directly with practitioners throughout the day.\n\n**Interested in joining?**\n\nRegister here:\nhttps://luma.com/eyo1apvf\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/03/fourth-wednesday-march\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/fourth-wednesday-g-300x200.png)We’re excited to invite you to a Fourth Wednesday gathering at the UW Tech Exploration Lab — a monthly opportunity for students, alumni, founders, and professionals to come together, share ideas, and strengthen Madison’s innovation community.\n\nWe warmly welcome the professional community and anyone curious about innovation, entrepreneurship, or emerging tech to join us. This event is free — **just RSVP** so we know how much pizza to order.\n\nCome for the story, stay for the connections, and help us shape this new monthly tradition.", "char_len": 2262, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::73", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 73, "text": "warmly welcome the professional community and anyone curious about innovation, entrepreneurship, or emerging tech to join us. This event is free — **just RSVP** so we know how much pizza to order.\n\nCome for the story, stay for the connections, and help us shape this new monthly tradition.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/03/02/4-weeks-to-demo-join-the-sprint\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/week-1-1024x683.png)Have an idea you’ve been circling but haven’t fully framed?\n\nCurious about an emerging technology but unsure how to define a strong use case?\n\nWe’re launching a focused **4-week sprint to Demo Night (April 10)** designed to help you move from exploration to a clear, compelling concept — and we’re kicking it off this Friday.\n\n## Week 1: Defining the Problem\n\n**Friday, March 6 | 4:30–6:00 PM**\n\nThis first session will help you clarify the foundation of your idea. We’ll workshop practical frameworks to define:\n\n* The problem you’re solving\n* Who it affects\n* Why it matters\n* What your use case will be for the next four weeks\n\nYou’ll leave with a clearer direction and a concrete starting point.\n\n**RSVP here**\n\n## Who Should Attend?\n\nThis sprint is open to:\n\n* Digital Health Challenge participants\n* Self-Directed Innovation students\n* Venture Discovery teams\n* Founder Lab students\n* Anyone working independently on an idea\n\nNo polished pitch required. Just bring what you’re thinking about.\n\n## What the 4-Week Sprint Looks Like\n\nEach week builds toward Demo Night:\n\n* **Week 1:** Define your use case\n* **Week 2:** Explore & validate\n* **Week 3:** Develop a concept or lightweight prototype\n* **Week 4:** Refine your story and prepare for Demo Night\n\n## Demo Night — April 10\n\nDemo Night is an exploration showcase and a celebration of student innovation.\n\nYou’ll:\n\n* Share what you built\n* Receive feedback from industry and campus leaders\n* Compete for cash prizes in select tracks\n\nAwards will recognize the most innovative and impactful ideas. **More info on Demo Night**.\n\nWhether you’re aiming for a prize, feedback, or momentum, this sprint is designed to help you get ready.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/industry-challenges-and-hackathons", "char_len": 2252, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::74", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 74, "text": "in select tracks\n\nAwards will recognize the most innovative and impactful ideas. **More info on Demo Night**.\n\nWhether you’re aiming for a prize, feedback, or momentum, this sprint is designed to help you get ready.\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/industry-challenges-and-hackathons\n\n## **From Real-World Challenges to Innovation and Ventures**\n\nThe Tech Exploration Lab partners with industry to translate real-world challenges into hands-on experimentation, deployable innovation, and new venture opportunities.\n\nThrough challenges, hackathons, and focused sprints, we create structured environments where student teams work on meaningful problems using applied AI and emerging technologies—generating fresh ideas, testing solutions, and building momentum.\n\nFor industry partners, this is a low-risk way to explore what’s possible—while building a pipeline of talent and ideas.\n\n## **How It Works**\n\n* **Start with a real challenge**\n  Partners bring forward a problem, opportunity space, or area of interest\n* **Activate student teams**\n  Cross-disciplinary teams explore, build, and prototype solutions\n* **Test ideas quickly**\n  Through short, focused engagements designed for speed and creativity\n* **Surface outcomes**\n  Including early-stage solutions, new use cases, and venture opportunities\n\n## **Why It Matters**\n\n* Explore new ideas without committing significant internal resources\n* Gain fresh perspectives from emerging talent\n* Identify high-potential opportunities early\n* Build relationships with students who are actively shaping what’s next\n\n> **This is not theoretical work—teams are building, testing, and advancing ideas in real time.**\n\n# **Examples from the Lab**\n\n## **Digital Health Challenge (Spring 2026)**\n\n![NeuroTrack, a novel solution for MS patients, presents at the Lab's Digital Health Challenge in Spring 2026](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/04/neurotrack-3-300x179.jpg)\n\nNeuroTrack, a novel solution for MS patients, presents at the Lab’s Digital Health Challenge in Spring 2026\n\nFocused on brain health, this challenge brought together students to explore how AI and digital technologies can improve quality of life for patients and caregivers.", "char_len": 2239, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::75", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 75, "text": "a novel solution for MS patients, presents at the Lab’s Digital Health Challenge in Spring 2026\n\nFocused on brain health, this challenge brought together students to explore how AI and digital technologies can improve quality of life for patients and caregivers.\n\nTeams developed solutions ranging from neurological monitoring tools to emotionally intelligent AI companions, with top teams advancing toward continued development and real-world application.\n\n---\n\n![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2016/08/amfam-300x200.jpg)\n\nTeams working in a 24-hour hackathon format to build out novel solutions.\n\n## **BuildFest (Fall 2025)**\n\nSponsored by Cursor, a Lab-led build sprint designed to move students from early ideas into tangible prototypes.\n\nTeams worked across a range of sectors to build out AI and blockchain solutions, exploring new concepts and shaping venture opportunities in a fast-paced, collaborative environment.\n\n---\n\n![Tyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/03/IMG_0662-300x225.jpg)\n\nTyler Faulkner with Xorbix coaches students during a day-long hackathon.\n\n## **Xorbix Hackathon (Spring 2026)**\n\nIn partnership with Xorbix, this hands-on hackathon gave students access to real-world data and industry context, challenging them to develop practical solutions using modern tools and platforms.\n\nThe result: high-quality prototypes, new use cases, and direct exposure for students to real industry problems and expectations.\n\n---\n\n# **Engage with the Lab**\n\nWhether through a focused challenge, hackathon, or ongoing collaboration, the Tech Exploration Lab provides a way to:\n\n* Test ideas quickly\n* Explore emerging technologies in context\n* Build a pipeline of talent and innovation\n\n## **Let’s Build What’s Next**\n\nIf you’re interested in bringing a challenge to the Lab or exploring ways to engage, we’d love to connect.\n\n**[Contact Us]**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/open-student-assistant-positions-uw-tech-exploration-lab-2026-27", "char_len": 2109, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::76", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 76, "text": "of talent and innovation\n\n## **Let’s Build What’s Next**\n\nIf you’re interested in bringing a challenge to the Lab or exploring ways to engage, we’d love to connect.\n\n**[Contact Us]**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/open-student-assistant-positions-uw-tech-exploration-lab-2026-27\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab moves applied AI and emerging technology ideas from campus exploration into real-world validation. We are expanding our team of Fellows, student builders and associates, and staff for the 2026–27 academic year.\n\n**Application deadline: August 14, 2026.**\n\nTo apply, **complete this form**.\n\n* **Graduate student positions** — Leadership Fellows (open to graduate students, MBAs, and post-doctoral researchers)\n* **Undergraduate positions** — AI/Technical Builders and Associates (open to currently enrolled UW undergraduates only)\n\n### Graduate Student Positions\n\n*These positions are open to currently enrolled graduate students, MBAs, and post-doctoral researchers.*\n\n**Compensation:** $25/hour  |  **Hours:** Up to 20 hrs/week  |  **Reports to:** Associate Director (except Industry & Alumni Engagement Fellow, who reports to Executive Director)\n\n#### Industry Projects Fellow\n\nThe Industry Projects Fellow owns execution of the Lab’s industry Co-Lab partnerships and sponsored project engagements. The Fellow runs the industry project track end-to-end, managing partner relationships, scoping problems, coordinating student teams, and ensuring deliverables are met.\n\n**What You’ll Own**\n\n* Industry Co-Lab partnerships and sponsored industry projects from problem scoping through final deliverable\n* Primary day-to-day contact for industry partners, managing timelines, communications, and expectations\n* Execution of the Digital Health Challenge and other industry-sponsored engagements\n* Management of internal, process related projects for the Lab as required\n* Project documentation, partner-facing materials, and progress reporting\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**", "char_len": 1991, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::77", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 77, "text": "communications, and expectations\n* Execution of the Digital Health Challenge and other industry-sponsored engagements\n* Management of internal, process related projects for the Lab as required\n* Project documentation, partner-facing materials, and progress reporting\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* MBA student or graduate student with strong project management discipline and professional communication skills\n* Professionally credible in industry settings — comfortable representing the Lab with corporate partners\n* Organized and systematic with strong follow-through\n* Interest in corporate innovation, technology partnerships, or entrepreneurship\n\n#### Research Translation Fellow\n\nThe Research Translation Fellow owns the Lab’s research-to-market pipeline — engaging with UW faculty and researchers, identifying commercial and applied potential in their work, and moving promising opportunities into student-executable projects or venture pathways.\n\n**What You’ll Own**\n\n* The Lab’s pipeline of research translation opportunities, from initial faculty conversations through student team engagement\n* Commercialization briefs, market framing documents, and project summaries that make research outputs accessible to students and industry partners\n* Relationships across UW research centers, labs, and academic units\n* Prioritization of which opportunities enter the active project pipeline\n* Management of internal, process related projects for the Lab as required\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* Post-doctoral researcher or graduate student with genuine interest in technology commercialization or tech transfer\n* Comfortable engaging with faculty on their terms and translating that work for a business or investor audience\n* Technically literate across domains — broad curiosity and range over deep specialization in one area\n* Strong project manager with consistent availability for sustained relationship-building\n\n#### Student Venture Pathway Fellow", "char_len": 1956, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::78", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 78, "text": "terms and translating that work for a business or investor audience\n* Technically literate across domains — broad curiosity and range over deep specialization in one area\n* Strong project manager with consistent availability for sustained relationship-building\n\n#### Student Venture Pathway Fellow\n\nThe Student Venture Pathway Fellow owns the operational rhythm of the Lab’s student innovation and venture pathway, the structured progression from Self-Directed Innovation through Discovery, Build, and Founder Lab. The Fellow owns the systems and logistics that keep the pathway running: milestone tracking, team check-ins, BuildFest coordination, and making sure students know where they are and what comes next.\n\n**What You’ll Own**\n\n* Operational rhythm of the student venture pathway — milestone checkpoints, team progression tracking, and pathway documentation\n* Logistics for Build Nights, BuildFest, Founder Lab sessions, and other student-facing programming\n* Team check-ins and flagging teams that need additional coaching or support\n* Student onboarding into the pathway and internal communications\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* MBA student or graduate student with genuine interest in entrepreneurship or innovation programming\n* Strong project manager — you build systems, track milestones, and don’t let things slip\n* Comfortable working with peers in a coaching-adjacent capacity\n* Entrepreneurial instincts are a plus\n\n#### Industry & Alumni Engagement Fellow\n\n**Reports to:** Executive Director\n\nThe Industry & Alumni Engagement Fellow owns the Lab’s partner outreach, alumni relationship management, and external engagement pipeline — working directly with the Executive Director to grow and maintain the network that sustains the Lab’s industry and community connections.\n\n**What You’ll Own**\n\n* The Lab’s CRM and partner/alumni contact database\n* Outreach to prospective industry partners and alumni — drafting communications, scheduling meetings, and tracking follow-up\n* Briefing materials and talking points for Executive Director meetings with external stakeholders\n* Coordination of partner and alumni engagement events and stewardship touchpoints\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**", "char_len": 2198, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::79", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 79, "text": "partners and alumni — drafting communications, scheduling meetings, and tracking follow-up\n* Briefing materials and talking points for Executive Director meetings with external stakeholders\n* Coordination of partner and alumni engagement events and stewardship touchpoints\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* MBA student or graduate student with strong professional presence and genuine interest in partnerships or alumni relations\n* Excellent written communicator — comfortable drafting outreach and professional correspondence\n* Detail-oriented relationship manager who doesn’t let things fall through the cracks\n* Organized and consistent — relationship pipelines require steady follow-through\n\n---\n\n### Undergraduate Positions\n\n*These positions are open to currently enrolled UW undergraduates only.*\n\n**Compensation:** $15/hour  |  **Hours:** 10–15 hrs/week\n\n#### AI/Technical Builder\n\n**Reports to:** Associate Director\n\nTechnical Builders are the hands-on core of the Lab’s project and experimentation work. Each Builder is embedded in one or more active projects — building prototypes, running experiments with frontier technologies, and contributing to campus and industry-driven challenges. This is not a passive learning role. Builders are expected to ship, test, and iterate. The Lab works across AI, blockchain, extended reality, and emerging platforms.\n\n**What You’ll Do**\n\n* Work on active Lab projects — building, prototyping, and experimenting with frontier technologies\n* Contribute to campus-driven and industry-sponsored technical challenges\n* Participate in Build Nights and collaborative work sessions\n* Document your work and share findings with the broader Lab community\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* Undergraduate in CS, data science, engineering, information science, or a related field — or demonstrated technical ability from a non-traditional background\n* Experience with at least one programming language or technical platform; genuine interest in AI, blockchain, XR, or adjacent areas\n* Builder’s mindset: you finish things, you learn from what breaks, and you want to make something real\n* Sophomore standing or above preferred; exceptional first-years considered\n\n#### Events & Operations Associate\n\n**Reports to:** Associate Director", "char_len": 2261, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::80", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 80, "text": "in AI, blockchain, XR, or adjacent areas\n* Builder’s mindset: you finish things, you learn from what breaks, and you want to make something real\n* Sophomore standing or above preferred; exceptional first-years considered\n\n#### Events & Operations Associate\n\n**Reports to:** Associate Director\n\nThe Events & Operations Associate owns the logistics behind every Lab event — from weekly Build Nights to BuildFest and partner showcases. This person makes sure spaces are booked, equipment is ready, catering is ordered, and the run-of-show is tight.\n\n**What You’ll Do**\n\n* Book and manage space reservations for all Lab events across the semester\n* Coordinate event logistics: catering, AV setup, materials, signage, and room configuration\n* Build and maintain run-of-show documents for all events\n* Serve as the on-site point person during events — setup, execution, and breakdown\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* Highly organized and detail-oriented — logistics failures bother you personally\n* Proactive communicator who confirms details in advance and follows up without being asked\n* Prior experience with event planning, student org leadership, or venue coordination a plus\n* Able to be physically present for events including some evenings\n\n#### Student Engagement Associate\n\n**Reports to:** Associate Director\n\nThe Student Engagement Associate is the Lab’s community builder — the person who makes sure students feel connected, recognized, and plugged in. This role owns the internal student experience: onboarding new members, organizing community events, running recognition moments, and making sure students feel like they belong to something worth showing up for.\n\n**What You’ll Do**\n\n* Own student onboarding — welcoming new members and connecting them to the right people and projects\n* Organize internal community events: socials, celebrations, and informal gatherings\n* Run recognition programs that highlight student work and contributions\n* Track engagement and flag to the Associate Director when participation is slipping\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**", "char_len": 2061, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::81", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 81, "text": "the right people and projects\n* Organize internal community events: socials, celebrations, and informal gatherings\n* Run recognition programs that highlight student work and contributions\n* Track engagement and flag to the Associate Director when participation is slipping\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* Genuinely people-oriented — you notice when someone is disengaged and you do something about it\n* Strong communicator with a warm, inclusive presence\n* Experience with student organizations, community building, or peer leadership\n* Genuinely excited about technology and innovation\n\n#### Communications Associate\n\n**Reports to:** Executive Director, with day-to-day direction from outside marketing consultant\n\nThe Communications Associate manages the Lab’s day-to-day content and social media presence — keeping the Lab visible, consistent, and compelling across channels. This person works within a communications strategy set by an outside marketing consultant and executes with creativity and reliability.\n\n**What You’ll Do**\n\n* Create and publish content across the Lab’s social media channels (LinkedIn, Instagram, and others)\n* Write and distribute internal communications including newsletters and program announcements\n* Produce promotional content for Lab events — Build Nights, BuildFest, Co-Labs, and partner showcases\n* Capture and document student project stories, spotlights, and Lab milestones\n\n**Who We’re Looking For**\n\n* Strong writer with an instinct for clear, engaging communication\n* Comfortable managing social media platforms professionally\n* Interested in technology, innovation, and entrepreneurship as subject matter\n* Some experience with graphic design tools (Canva, Adobe, Figma) a plus\n\n---\n\n**Apply here.** **Deadline: August 14, 2026.**\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2025/11/PRESS-RELEASE-Build-Fest-Nov.-2025-final.pdf\n\nPRESS RELEASE\nFOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE\nUW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab Hosts First-Ever Badger Build Fest,\nShowcasing Student Innovation in AI, Blockchain, and Venture Building\nMADISON, Wis.", "char_len": 2092, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::82", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 82, "text": "RELEASE\nFOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE\nUW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab Hosts First-Ever Badger Build Fest,\nShowcasing Student Innovation in AI, Blockchain, and Venture Building\nMADISON, Wis.\n\n— November 18, 2025 — The UW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab and Badger\nBlockchain hosted the inaugural Badger Build Fest on November 15–16, bringing together more\nthan 140 students from across campus for a high-energy, 24-hour build sprint focused on AI,\nblockchain, and emerging technologies.\n\nOver the course of the weekend, students collaborated on rapid prototypes, validated real-world\nproblems, and pitched concepts with credible venture pathways.\n\nIn total, $6,500 in prizes were\nawarded across 16 winning teams spanning both the Cursor Venture Track and the Blockchain\nTrack.\n\n“Badger Build Fest brought out the best of what UW students do when they have space and\nsupport to build quickly and think boldly,” said Sandra Bradley, Executive Director of the Tech\nExploration Lab.\n\n“This event blended hands-on creation with rapid venture-building — and the\nmomentum we saw this weekend is only the beginning.”\nVenture Track Winners (Powered by Cursor)\nStudents competing in the Cursor Venture Track were evaluated not just on what they built, but\non the strength of their problem definition, market insight, and venture readiness.\n\nFirst Place — StyleSwap\nAddresses limited and wasteful wardrobe options by enabling digital closet-sharing and\nborrowing among friends.\n\nSecond Place — UniBud\nSupports overwhelmed undergraduates with an AI-powered guide that personalizes milestones\nand provides advisors real-time insight.\n\nThird Place — ClearMove\nProtects renters’ rights by turning leases, checklists, and photos into organized, shareable\nevidence.\n\nAdditional award recipients included:\n● TimeMyGate — Best New Market Creation: Smart, real-time guidance on when to\nleave for the airport.\n\n● BluWorld — Most Unexpected Project: Social and blockchain incentives to spark\nreal-world adventure.\n\n● Fairlytics — Most Ready to Go to Market: Real-time bias monitoring for AI predictions.\n\n● Ares — Best Insight to Interface: Predictive AI awareness for air traffic controllers to\nprevent incidents.", "char_len": 2180, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::83", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 83, "text": "— Most Unexpected Project: Social and blockchain incentives to spark\nreal-world adventure.\n\n● Fairlytics — Most Ready to Go to Market: Real-time bias monitoring for AI predictions.\n\n● Ares — Best Insight to Interface: Predictive AI awareness for air traffic controllers to\nprevent incidents.\n\n● BadgerFlix — Most Balanced Project: Transforming long lectures into short, bingeable\nlearning experiences.\n\nA full list of submissions is available at: https://badger-build-fest.devpost.com/submissions\nA Campuswide Effort Backed by Industry Partners\nBadger Build Fest was made possible through the generous support of campus partners and\nindustry sponsors who contributed funding, facilitated workshops and salons, offered office\nhours, served as judges, and mentored student teams throughout the weekend.\n\nSponsors\nincluded: Cursor, Kinetic Solutions, Strato VC, Cloud Native Madison, Gemini, Turtle.xyz with\nSolana, UW-Madison CDIS, Wisconsin Institute for Discovery and the Wisconsin School of\nBusiness.\n\nA Milestone for UW’s Emerging Tech and Venture Ecosystem\nBadger Build Fest reflects the Tech Exploration Lab’s growing role as a hub for applied\ninnovation, venture discovery, and interdisciplinary collaboration across UW–Madison.\n\n“Students didn’t just build — they framed real problems, tested assumptions, and pitched ideas\nwith a clear path to adoption,” Bradley said.\n\n“That combination of speed and purpose is exactly\nwhat today’s innovation landscape requires.”\nGiven the strong turnout and overwhelmingly positive feedback, the Tech Exploration Lab plans\nto make Badger Build Fest an annual signature event.\n\nHigh-resolution photos from the weekend can be requested from sandra.bradley@wisc.edu.\n\nWhat’s Next\nThe momentum continues with several upcoming programs:\n● December 3 Student Demo Night — A concourse-style showcase of student projects\nfrom across the Tech Exploration Lab.\n\n● Digital Health Challenge (Spring 2026) — A semester-long initiative focused on brain\nhealth and digital innovation.\n\nOrganizations interested in sponsoring, mentoring, or partnering on future events are\nencouraged to contact the Tech Exploration Lab.\n\nMedia Contact:\nUW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab\nsandra.bradley@wisc.edu - techexplorationlab.wisc.edu", "char_len": 2249, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::84", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 84, "text": "initiative focused on brain\nhealth and digital innovation.\n\nOrganizations interested in sponsoring, mentoring, or partnering on future events are\nencouraged to contact the Tech Exploration Lab.\n\nMedia Contact:\nUW–Madison Tech Exploration Lab\nsandra.bradley@wisc.edu - techexplorationlab.wisc.edu\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/02/18/were-hiring-student-assistant-outreach-events\n\n*(Community Engagement | Campaigns | Event Experience)*\n\nDo you enjoy connecting people, promoting meaningful work, and creating welcoming, high-impact events?\n\nAre you energized by the intersection of innovation, students, and industry?\n\nThe UW Tech Exploration Lab is seeking a Student Assistant to support outreach, communications, and event experiences that bring our community together. This role is ideal for someone who is organized, proactive, and excited to help grow the Lab’s network and visibility.\n\n## **What You’ll Do**\n\nYou will work with the Leadership Fellow for Brand & Marketing to:\n\n* Promote Lab programs and events to students, alumni, and industry audiences\n* Draft and schedule outreach messages across email, social, and Discord\n* Support marketing campaigns and partner communications\n* Assist with event planning, logistics, and on-site experience\n* Help create and distribute marketing materials and signage\n* Track engagement metrics and summarize outreach impact\n* Identify opportunities to expand the Lab’s reach across campus and beyond\n\n## **What We’re Looking For**\n\n* Strong written communication and organizational skills\n* Comfort engaging with diverse audiences (students, faculty, partners)\n* Interest in marketing, community building, or event management\n* Ability to manage multiple tasks and meet deadlines\n* Curiosity about innovation ecosystems and emerging technology\n\n## **What You’ll Gain**\n\n* Hands-on experience in outreach and community engagement\n* Exposure to industry partners and alumni networks\n* Event planning and campaign execution experience\n* Insight into how innovation programs build momentum and participation\n\n**Time Commitment:** 10–12 hours/week (flexible)\n**Compensation:** $15/hour\n\n[**Apply here**]\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/01/09/open-house-at-1403-at-the-intersection-of-innovation-entrepreneurship", "char_len": 2296, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "tech-exploration-lab::85", "doc_slug": "tech-exploration-lab", "chunk_index": 85, "text": "Insight into how innovation programs build momentum and participation\n\n**Time Commitment:** 10–12 hours/week (flexible)\n**Compensation:** $15/hour\n\n[**Apply here**]\n\n## [page] https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/2026/01/09/open-house-at-1403-at-the-intersection-of-innovation-entrepreneurship\n\n**![](https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/2307/2026/01/open-house-200x300.png)**UW Tech Exploration Lab Open House**** **January 30 | 4:30–6:30 PM | 1403 University Ave**\n\nRESCHEDULED FROM JANUARY 23 DUE TO WEATHER\n\nCurious about how emerging technology, entrepreneurship, and real-world problem-solving come together at UW–Madison?\n\nJoin us at **1403 University Ave**, the home of the UW Tech Exploration Lab — a space designed for students, campus innovators, alumni, and industry partners who want to explore what’s possible at the intersection of innovation and impact.\n\nNo formal presentations. It’s an open environment to wander, ask questions, meet people, and discover where you might plug in this spring.\n\n**Explore the space**\nWalk through 1403 and see how it’s being activated as a hub for experimentation, venture discovery, and industry collaboration.\n\n**Mini Innovation Fair**\nBrowse tables highlighting everything happening in the Lab this semester, including:\n\n* **Events & Open Labs** – Build Nights, Open Labs, Demo Night\n* **Digital Health Challenge** – industry-defined problems in healthcare innovation\n* **Self-Directed Innovation** – explore emerging tech without needing a startup idea\n* **Venture Pathway** – Discovery, Build, and Founder Lab for student founders\n\n**Campus & Student Orgs**\nConnect with groups and resources that help turn ideas into action.\n\nWhether you already have a startup idea or you’re simply curious about emerging technology, this is the perfect way to see what’s available — and where you belong.\n\n**Stop in anytime between 4:30 and 6:30 PM.**\nLight refreshments will be available.\n\n**< RSVP >**", "char_len": 1966, "id": 9, "source": "Tech Exploration Lab", "type": "static_html", "category": "makerspace", "url": "https://techexplorationlab.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::0", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com\n\nClick here to access the Transcend UW Pitch Competition Brochure.\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# TRANSCEND UW\n\n![b78909ea-78e0-49d8-b892-c1845c92e85e.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_849000dba1d6446e8e456b5c8818bed3~mv2.png/v1/crop/x_0,y_0,w_1024,h_829/fill/w_432,h_350,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/b78909ea-78e0-49d8-b892-c1845c92e85e.png)\n\nUniversity of Wisconsin's premier student-led entrepreneurship & startup organization.​​\n\n​\n\n​\n\n​​​​​​\n\nLearn More\n\n## $500K\n\n## Given out as Prize Money\n\n## 10 years\n\n## Hosting pitch competition\n\n## 20+ Sponsors\n\n## Supporting our events\n\n![Screenshot 2025-12-03 014532.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_4629274edc5d4f1ca1d9e158bbab6536~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_643,h_639,al_c,q_90,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/Screenshot%202025-12-03%20014532.png)\n\n## How To Get Involved\n\nWe are looking for people who are passionate about entrepreneurship and innovation. Everyone from any major, degree level, or occupation are encouraged to join us at Transcend UW. You'll be:\n\n​\n\n* Assisting with the planning and execution of events and workshops.\n* Conducting market research to identify new opportunities for student entrepreneurs.\n* Developing and maintaining relationships with key stakeholders on campus and in the community.\n\nJoin the Mission\n\n## Students of all majors are welcome.\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## Transcend UW History\n\n## 2013\n\n1ST ANNUAL STARTUP CHALLENGE", "char_len": 1917, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::1", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## Transcend UW History\n\n## 2013\n\n1ST ANNUAL STARTUP CHALLENGE\n\nIn 2013, Transcend UW hosted its first annual startup challenge, which brought together students from a variety of disciplines to pitch their ideas and compete for funding. The event was a huge success and has since become an annual tradition.\n\n## 2010\n\nTRANSCEND UW IS FOUNDED\n\nTranscend UW was founded in 2010 with the goal of fostering a culture of innovation and entrepreneurship on campus. Our first event was a small workshop on idea generation, and since then we have grown to become one of the largest and most active student organizations on campus.\n\n## 2025\n\n10TH ANNUAL STARTUP COMPETITION\n\nThe 10th Transcend UW Competition will be held in 2025 where winners will divide up a record amount of prize money. Ready to Launch Your Idea?\n\nSee our Winners\n\nInnovative Hub\n\nTranscend UW is an innovative hub designed to provide students with a platform for personal development and growth. Our organization is committed to challenging the status quo and fostering a community of innovators. We offer a wide range of opportunities for members to explore new ideas, develop their skills and build meaningful connections. Our goal is to inspire and encourage individuals to transcend their limits by pushing beyond their comfort zones. Join us today and be a part of a dynamic community of individuals dedicated to making a positive impact on the world.\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_011572ff0ee748c494ef0791383cfb18~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_357,h_345,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_011572ff0ee748c494ef0791383cfb18~mv2.jpg)\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_8728618de10b4ff986eac0bcdab581f8~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_357,h_345,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_8728618de10b4ff986eac0bcdab581f8~mv2.jpg)\n\nIncredible Support", "char_len": 2082, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::2", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "Support\n\nAt Transcend UW, we believe that the entrepreneurial spirit is essential for a thriving economy and society. Our mission is to support and empower innovative students on the UW-Madison campus. Through our programs and resources, we aim to provide students with the skills and experience necessary to start their own businesses and make a positive impact in the world. If you want to learn more about what we do, feel free to explore our website or come visit us on campus.\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/about\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# ABOUT TRANSCEND UW\n\nTranscend UW is a student organization focused on providing invaluable resources and opportunities to students on campus who are interested in creating their own ventures. We do not limit our member’s ideas to tech, mobile applications or purely entrepreneurial ventures; instead we encourage collaboration between majors and focuses which we hope inspires start-up ideas that can change the world.\n\nTRANSCEND\n\nUniversity of Wisconsin\n\n### Instagram Feed\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## Transcend UW Gallery\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_9276a00094f647019f425a6afac76ac1~mv2.jpg/v1/fit/w_1440,h_961,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_9276a00094f647019f425a6afac76ac1~mv2.jpg)\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_011572ff0ee748c494ef0791383cfb18~mv2.jpg/v1/fit/w_480,h_360,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_011572ff0ee748c494ef0791383cfb18~mv2.jpg)", "char_len": 1862, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::3", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 3, "text": "25a6afac76ac1~mv2.jpg/v1/fit/w_1440,h_961,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_9276a00094f647019f425a6afac76ac1~mv2.jpg)\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_011572ff0ee748c494ef0791383cfb18~mv2.jpg/v1/fit/w_480,h_360,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_011572ff0ee748c494ef0791383cfb18~mv2.jpg)\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_60776f2d1956484c80bdfa8aac3b934d~mv2.jpg/v1/fit/w_960,h_640,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_60776f2d1956484c80bdfa8aac3b934d~mv2.jpg)\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_c0e48accb53f4d0680ed0db2f1f7de5b~mv2.png/v1/fit/w_480,h_642,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_c0e48accb53f4d0680ed0db2f1f7de5b~mv2.png)\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_04ea117745e84c84a1bf4fca2308e82c~mv2.png/v1/fit/w_480,h_483,q_90,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_04ea117745e84c84a1bf4fca2308e82c~mv2.png)\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/mission-statement\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# MISSION STATEMENT\n\n##### Transcend UW is a student organization focused on providing invaluable resources and opportunities to students on campus who are interested in creating their own ventures. We do not limit our member’s ideas to tech, mobile applications or purely entrepreneurial ventures; instead we encourage collaboration between majors and focuses which we hope inspires start-up ideas that can change the world.\n\n##### ​\n\n##### Our utility comes from the vast network of alumni and professionals from the Madison area and beyond which we tap regularly for inspiring talks and informative workshops that our members can utilize to expand their knowledge beyond their curriculum and hopefully apply it towards innovation. Our impact goes beyond the resources we provide and the knowledge we impart to our members.\n\n##### Our core concept is to inspire the Madison student community to create businesses and innovative ideas that will change the world.\n\nTRANSCEND\n\nUniversity of Wisconsin\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/meet-the-team-1\n\n# Meet The Team", "char_len": 2212, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::4", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 4, "text": "provide and the knowledge we impart to our members.\n\n##### Our core concept is to inspire the Madison student community to create businesses and innovative ideas that will change the world.\n\nTRANSCEND\n\nUniversity of Wisconsin\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/meet-the-team-1\n\n# Meet The Team\n\n![_SJJ9313-Edit-2_edited.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_5b079be133cc4136a321ee9fe7e7a005~mv2.png/v1/crop/x_0,y_536,w_1385,h_1021/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/_SJJ9313-Edit-2_edited.png)\n\nPresident\n\nName: Siddharth (Sid) Singh\nYear: Junior\nMajor: CS & Certificate in Entrepreneurship\n\n​Entrepreneurship excites me because it allows me to create solutions that make a real-world impact. Transcend UW provides the perfect environment to collaborate with innovative students and turn ideas into action, helping grow the entrepreneurial spirit on campus.\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![IMG_0167.PNG](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_7897e4f355a642b4a1a34b2f6c19f1ef~mv2.png/v1/crop/x_0,y_714,w_1170,h_862/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/IMG_0167_PNG.png)\n\nVice-President\n\nName: Suha Afzar\nYear: Junior\nMajor: CS, DS, & Certificate in Entrepreneurship\n\nBeing part of Transcend helps me meet and support innovators and problem solvers at UW-Madison. I am passionate about using entrepreneurship to solve real world problems creatively!\n\n​\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![IMG_4845 2.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_3581d5d212514d12970caed3ece78f09~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_902,w_3024,h_2228/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/IMG_4845%202.jpg)\n\nEvents Lead\n\nName: Masha Mochalnikova\nYear: Senior\nMajor: Chemical Engineering", "char_len": 2090, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::5", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 5, "text": "2.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_3581d5d212514d12970caed3ece78f09~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_902,w_3024,h_2228/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/IMG_4845%202.jpg)\n\nEvents Lead\n\nName: Masha Mochalnikova\nYear: Senior\nMajor: Chemical Engineering\n\n​I have joined Transcend my freshman year because I liked the intersection between engineering and business. I did events for the last 2.5 years, and I loved seeing all the amazing pitches at the competitions.\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![large_edited.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_48a0cc0b6392473d9c56e1ef4ddafa45~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_283,w_1200,h_884/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/large_edited.jpg)\n\nEvents Lead\n\nName: Andy Zhu\nYear: Freshman\nMajor: Mechanical Engineering & Certificate in Manufacturing Engineering & Six Sigma​​\n\n​\n\nI joined Transcend to foster a space for entrepreneurship and to expand opportunities for innovation both on and off campus.\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![image003.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_f74f2ba5b2eb4ce48ca74a6e0f5fafb6~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_27,w_4032,h_2971/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/image003.jpg)\n\nTreasurer\n\nName: Shradha Godishala\nYear: Junior\nMajor: Data Science and Economics\n\nI have been a part of Transcend for 2 years and I am involved with VC work, so I enjoy being around entrepreneurship\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![IMG_2926_edited.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_9a08e94992e9487eb683cfbbc4f5376f~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_88,w_1170,h_862/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/IMG_2926_edited.jpg)\n\nOutreach\n\nName:  Krithi Gopinath\n\nYear: Junior\nMajor: Neurobiology", "char_len": 2269, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::6", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 6, "text": "Krithi Gopinath\n\nYear: Junior\nMajor: Neurobiology\n\n​I’ve always been drawn to the energy of ideas in motion — watching startup pitches and seeing how people bring something from thought to reality is endlessly cool to me. Transcend has been a space where I get to be around that kind of momentum and creativity, and it’s made me more excited to explore my own interests without overthinking or second-guessing.\n\n​\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![pancras2 (2).jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_2862e1a70a2541e4aac2d642dcafa721~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_646,w_1242,h_915/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/pancras2%20(2).jpg)\n\nSecretary\n\nName: Michael Pancras\nYear: Sophomore\nMajor: CS & DS​​\n\n​\n\nI joined Transcend UW because I aspire to launch my own startup one day. This club gives me the opportunity to learn the inner workings of successful ventures while gaining hands-on experience in turning ideas into reality.\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![image (27)_edited.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_8e2b0893841a4c56a701c64d4674e121~mv2.png/v1/crop/x_0,y_317,w_952,h_701/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/image%20(27)_edited.png)\n\nWeb Lead\n\nName: Anish Srinivasan\nYear: Freshman\nMajor: Computer Science​​\n\n​\n\nI love all things entrepreneurship, from tech startups to online businesses. I want to help others bring their own ideas to life while learning new things along the way myself!\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)", "char_len": 2001, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::7", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 7, "text": "I want to help others bring their own ideas to life while learning new things along the way myself!\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![original.jpeg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_59176e92fcbc41088b88c7973274d40d~mv2.jpeg/v1/crop/x_0,y_485,w_2006,h_1478/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/original.jpeg)\n\nExecutive Team Member\n\nName: Cullan Wickramasuriya\nYear: Freshman\nMajor: Computer Engineering​​\n\n​\n\nI joined Transcend because I am passionate about startups and entrepreneurship opportunities in engineering.\n\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/aa0402eb9ba2430d9d0620b59556efca.png)\n\n![original (1).jpeg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_8675ad20161540d5b38f982928fb651e~mv2.jpeg/v1/crop/x_0,y_81,w_1154,h_850/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/original%20(1).jpeg)\n\nExecutive Team Member\n\nName: Priyanshu Ghosh\n\nYear: Freshman\nMajor: CS & Statistics​​\n\n​\n\nAs a two-time founder, I joined Transcend to mentor aspiring entrepreneurs and collaborate with UW administration to expand entrepreneurship on campus.\n\n![PIC.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_1d3457507d4045bf9bc6b9a5d85d1b76~mv2.png/v1/crop/x_0,y_190,w_800,h_589/fill/w_456,h_336,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/PIC.png)\n\nExecutive Team Member\n\nName: Dhriti Nekkalapudi\n\nYear: Freshman\nMajor: Biomedical Engineering​​\n\n​\n\nI joined transcend for exposure to entrepreneurship and the startup environment.\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/competitions\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_122,h_69,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## INCUBATE YOUR STARTUP WITH TRANSCEND", "char_len": 2093, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::8", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 8, "text": "Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_122,h_69,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## INCUBATE YOUR STARTUP WITH TRANSCEND\n\nTranscend UW helps you develop your startup idea by providing mentorship, funding opportunities, and access to a community of like-minded individuals. We encourage cross-disciplinary collaboration, so you can find the perfect team to bring your idea to life.\n\n![transcend-6.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_8728618de10b4ff986eac0bcdab581f8~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_123,h_92,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_8728618de10b4ff986eac0bcdab581f8~mv2.jpg)\n\n### FUEL YOUR CREATIVITY\n\nAt Transcend UW, we believe that creativity is key to success. That's why we offer workshops, events, and networking opportunities to help you generate new ideas and stay inspired. Join our community and let your imagination run wild!\n\n### MAKE A POSITIVE IMPACT\n\nTranscend UW is committed to making a difference in our world. We support startups that have a social or environmental mission, and we encourage all our members to think about the impact their ventures can have. Join us and be part of the change you want to see!\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_79,h_45,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## CONNECT WITH THE TRANSCEND UW COMMUNITY\n\nOur entrepreneurship community allows you to connect with other members of the Transcend UW community, share your ideas, and get feedback. You can also access exclusive resources, such as business templates and legal advice, to help you navigate the startup world.\n\n![transcend-4.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_61802b62c13b4154b601d9fd19c8aba8~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_123,h_92,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_61802b62c13b4154b601d9fd19c8aba8~mv2.jpg)\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/upcoming", "char_len": 2130, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::9", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 9, "text": "the startup world.\n\n![transcend-4.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_61802b62c13b4154b601d9fd19c8aba8~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_123,h_92,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_61802b62c13b4154b601d9fd19c8aba8~mv2.jpg)\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/upcoming\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# 2026 Competition Applications are closed.\n\nTranscend UW is the perfect place to grow your skills and work on exciting projects that can make a real difference. We are looking for talented individuals who are passionate about innovation and entrepreneurship.\n\n## Explore our 2025 Competition\n\n2025 Winners\n\nTeams & Judges\n\n## Competition Structure\n\n### Location (Both Days): Discovery Building 330 N Orchard Street, Madison, WI 53715\n\n### ​\n\n#### Day 1 – April 16\n\n* Pitches run from 9:00 AM – 5:30 PM\n* You will receive a SignupGenius to select your pitch slot\n\nPitch Format:\n\n* Total time: 10 minutes (hard stop)\n* Recommended: 7 min pitch + 3 min Q&A\n* No live demos allowed\n\n+ You may include images or pre-recorded videos in your presentation\n\nPoster Session (12:00 – 1:00 PM):\n\n* Open to the public\n* Think of this as a chance to showcase your product more interactively\n* Teams who opt in via the deliverables form will be assigned a table\n* Live demos ARE allowed here\n* Judges will walk around during this time\n\nResults:\n\n* Finalist decisions will be sent by 10:00 PM\n* Selected teams will receive a follow-up + SignupGenius for Day 2 slots\n\n#### Day 2 – April 17\n\n* Top 16 teams from Day 1 will advance\n\nFormat Changes (Important):\n\n* Pitches start at 8:20 AM\n* Pitch: 10 minutes (hard stop)\n* Followed by: 10 minutes of Q&A\n* Live demos ARE allowed as part of your pitch\n* All final pitches will be open to the public and take place on the main stage (anyone can be in the audience)\n* Pitches conclude at 4:00 PM sharp\n* Followed by:\n\n+ Networking + Awards Ceremony (4:00 – 6:00 PM)\n\n​\n\nWe would highly recommend at least one person from your team\n\nbeing present for the networking and awards. Failure to have a team member", "char_len": 2265, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::10", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 10, "text": "place on the main stage (anyone can be in the audience)\n* Pitches conclude at 4:00 PM sharp\n* Followed by:\n\n+ Networking + Awards Ceremony (4:00 – 6:00 PM)\n\n​\n\nWe would highly recommend at least one person from your team\n\nbeing present for the networking and awards. Failure to have a team member\n\npresent will result in forfeiting your award (i.e., if your team wins but no one is there, the award will not be given).\n\n## Prizes\n\n### ​All teams from Day 1 are eligible for a $2,500 prize\n\n​​\n\n* Additional prizes will be distributed among finalists\n* Full breakdown will be made public one week before the competition\n\n​\n\n## What Judges Are Looking For\n\nHere are some of the key things judges will be looking for:\n\n​\n\n* Team – Why you? What gives you an edge to build this?\n* Market – Real problem, real demand, meaningful size\n* Traction as a business – Users, revenue, pilots, validation\n* Overall growth potential – Can this actually scale into something big?\n\n​\n\nNote: This is a pitch competition, but pitching well alone won’t carry you. Judges care about whether you’re building something real.\n\n![New Project (13)_edited.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_9feb8a38f0f14f8aa62f99b6e6b49dfc~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_117,h_75,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_9feb8a38f0f14f8aa62f99b6e6b49dfc~mv2.jpg)\n\n### Optional (Highly Recommended) Session\n\n### ​\n\nWe’re hosting a Business 101 session with Michael Best:\n\n​\n\n* Date: March 26\n* Time: 6:00 – 8:00 PM\n* Location: 1403 University Ave\n\n​\n\nThis will cover incorporation, legal structures, and different pathways for building your startup. Strongly recommend attending.\n\n​\n\nRSVP here: https://luma.com/v9zt4u7f\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/previous\n\n## Transcend UW 2025\n\n![Alira - 1st Place](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_7926f6fc673848b7a74c2c93e8a68e8a~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_46,h_31,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_7926f6fc673848b7a74c2c93e8a68e8a~mv2.png)\n\nAlira - 1st Place\n\n![RedElevenLabs - 2nd Place](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_86fb3c21ec7f45edbf069712bdc57ad2~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_46,h_30,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_86fb3c21ec7f45edbf069712bdc57ad2~mv2.png)\n\nRedElevenLabs - 2nd Place", "char_len": 2283, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::11", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 11, "text": "- 1st Place\n\n![RedElevenLabs - 2nd Place](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_86fb3c21ec7f45edbf069712bdc57ad2~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_46,h_30,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_86fb3c21ec7f45edbf069712bdc57ad2~mv2.png)\n\nRedElevenLabs - 2nd Place\n\n![FrameChat - General Track: Alumni Award](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_2cfd8a9ea79a4435b6725e0996efd45b~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_102,h_154,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_2cfd8a9ea79a4435b6725e0996efd45b~mv2.png)\n\nFrameChat - General Track: Alumni Award\n\n![Alira - 1st Place](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_7926f6fc673848b7a74c2c93e8a68e8a~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_46,h_31,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/ad5310_7926f6fc673848b7a74c2c93e8a68e8a~mv2.png)\n\nAlira - 1st Place\n\n1/13\n\nPhoto Credits: Muiz Aminu\n\nSee All 2025 Teams & Judges\n\n## Transcend UW 2024\n\n![Sprout-1st](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_4e3d5faf759e4ca5906b3b85326bcba3~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_4e3d5faf759e4ca5906b3b85326bcba3~mv2.jpg)\n\nSprout-1st\n\n![MarketMate - 2nd Palce](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_1107e31f8ce54aff8680413e35368824~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_1107e31f8ce54aff8680413e35368824~mv2.jpg)\n\nMarketMate - 2nd Palce\n\n![Best Pitch General - My Wedding Hub](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_8291c270aa8541ddad9a7e83ed85f3c2~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_8291c270aa8541ddad9a7e83ed85f3c2~mv2.jpg)\n\nBest Pitch General - My Wedding Hub\n\n![Sprout-1st](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_4e3d5faf759e4ca5906b3b85326bcba3~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_4e3d5faf759e4ca5906b3b85326bcba3~mv2.jpg)\n\nSprout-1st\n\n1/13\n\n## Transcend UW 2023\n\n![First Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_cbf954820c7b479b9bea814b78aba3b3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_111,h_108,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_cbf954820c7b479b9bea814b78aba3b3~mv2.png)\n\nFirst Place - $10000", "char_len": 2207, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::12", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 12, "text": "Transcend UW 2023\n\n![First Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_cbf954820c7b479b9bea814b78aba3b3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_111,h_108,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_cbf954820c7b479b9bea814b78aba3b3~mv2.png)\n\nFirst Place - $10000\n\nHuan Yoei Lee\nVinesh Janarthanan\nCrib is a marketplace that makes subleasing easier than ever. Users can find personalized subleases in 3 clicks and sublease their apartment in under 30 seconds. Our goal is to become a one-stop shop for subleasing.\n\n![Second Place - $7000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_f76e042b4a54441380385005ad288f02~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_110,h_106,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_f76e042b4a54441380385005ad288f02~mv2.png)\n\nSecond Place - $7000\n\nCameron Roth,\nMatthew Samuels\nTixplorer is the first ever price comparison website for ticket merchants in the US and Canada. Currently on this platform you can search any sporting event and find the cheapest tickets including all hidden fees in a matter of seconds.\n\n![Fifth Place - Jaiye](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_8504c6154e5c44f39968dc90fc87c8be~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_109,h_108,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_8504c6154e5c44f39968dc90fc87c8be~mv2.png)\n\nFifth Place - Jaiye\n\nDamola Owolabi\nThe goal is to design a mobile app that provides a platform for diasporans of African descent to connect, build relationships, and establish a sense of community. The app aims to provide a unique and engaging user experience by incorporating interactive features beyond the traditional swiping function to increase user engagement and connection.\n\n![First Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_cbf954820c7b479b9bea814b78aba3b3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_111,h_108,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_cbf954820c7b479b9bea814b78aba3b3~mv2.png)\n\nFirst Place - $10000\n\nHuan Yoei Lee\nVinesh Janarthanan\nCrib is a marketplace that makes subleasing easier than ever. Users can find personalized subleases in 3 clicks and sublease their apartment in under 30 seconds. Our goal is to become a one-stop shop for subleasing.\n\n1/5\n\n## Transcend UW 2022", "char_len": 2201, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::13", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 13, "text": "Place - $10000\n\nHuan Yoei Lee\nVinesh Janarthanan\nCrib is a marketplace that makes subleasing easier than ever. Users can find personalized subleases in 3 clicks and sublease their apartment in under 30 seconds. Our goal is to become a one-stop shop for subleasing.\n\n1/5\n\n## Transcend UW 2022\n\n![First Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_1dbbfbb1f5fb400c9bb0ea9eb20abea1~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_57,h_69,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_1dbbfbb1f5fb400c9bb0ea9eb20abea1~mv2.png)\n\nFirst Place - $10000\n\nNudge by Longevity\n\n![Second Place - $7000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7b168ab75e1448da9a873e153d747f0c~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_46,h_35,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7b168ab75e1448da9a873e153d747f0c~mv2.png)\n\nSecond Place - $7000\n\nMy Home Stars\n\n![Third Place - $5000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_f14aebffe9604ca2b84e45cc428c8658~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_76,h_70,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_f14aebffe9604ca2b84e45cc428c8658~mv2.png)\n\nThird Place - $5000\n\nSolis\n\n![First Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_1dbbfbb1f5fb400c9bb0ea9eb20abea1~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_57,h_69,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_1dbbfbb1f5fb400c9bb0ea9eb20abea1~mv2.png)\n\nFirst Place - $10000\n\nNudge by Longevity\n\n1/3\n\n## Transcend UW 2021\n\n![Alumni Award](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7cdf976320a1460bb1be6530ac594daa~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7cdf976320a1460bb1be6530ac594daa~mv2.png)\n\nAlumni Award\n\n![Main Stage Best Prototype](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_cd0041c423b844c49299f9ac94dbcf71~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_cd0041c423b844c49299f9ac94dbcf71~mv2.png)\n\nMain Stage Best Prototype\n\n![2nd Place](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_20a4420745394703b72fba26cf9b58e8~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_20a4420745394703b72fba26cf9b58e8~mv2.png)\n\n2nd Place", "char_len": 2135, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::14", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 14, "text": "Stage Best Prototype\n\n![2nd Place](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_20a4420745394703b72fba26cf9b58e8~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_20a4420745394703b72fba26cf9b58e8~mv2.png)\n\n2nd Place\n\n![Alumni Award](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7cdf976320a1460bb1be6530ac594daa~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7cdf976320a1460bb1be6530ac594daa~mv2.png)\n\nAlumni Award\n\n1/17\n\n## Transcend UW 2019\n\n![Grand Prize - $15000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_f38affd2702e4f6496cc74ae4594a641~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_60,h_60,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_f38affd2702e4f6496cc74ae4594a641~mv2.png)\n\nGrand Prize - $15000\n\nDrip is a mobile ordering & rewards platform built for local coffee shops to offer their customers the same conveniences as bigger chains such as Starbucks.\n\n![Second Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_3f435e9a7ac1481fbeb92245be419937~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_60,h_60,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_3f435e9a7ac1481fbeb92245be419937~mv2.png)\n\nSecond Place - $10000\n\nAll Brick Medical is a medical device company. Our flagship product, The ErgoSyringe adaptor, provides an ergonomic solution for performing syringe procedures in the healthcare industry\n\n![Early Stage Best Posterpng](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_cedba067715a4f5ebbc3b1a096515745~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_75,h_60,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_cedba067715a4f5ebbc3b1a096515745~mv2.png)\n\nEarly Stage Best Posterpng\n\nAn AI-powered Adjustable Visual Search Engine for online apparel retailers that improves user experience and search relevancy with label-enhanced image query.\n\n![Grand Prize - $15000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_f38affd2702e4f6496cc74ae4594a641~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_60,h_60,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_f38affd2702e4f6496cc74ae4594a641~mv2.png)\n\nGrand Prize - $15000\n\nDrip is a mobile ordering & rewards platform built for local coffee shops to offer their customers the same conveniences as bigger chains such as Starbucks.\n\n1/13\n\n## Transcend UW 2018", "char_len": 2245, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::15", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 15, "text": "Prize - $15000\n\nDrip is a mobile ordering & rewards platform built for local coffee shops to offer their customers the same conveniences as bigger chains such as Starbucks.\n\n1/13\n\n## Transcend UW 2018\n\n![First Place - $15000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7322723388bf4e4697667803195e6d48~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7322723388bf4e4697667803195e6d48~mv2.jpg)\n\nFirst Place - $15000\n\nLineLeap, a fast-pass for nightclubs that allows users to bypass big crowds, now available in 11 cities.\nPictured: Max Schauff\n\n![2nd Place - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7c0a0e2304c3446aa3e0af8675ee14f6~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7c0a0e2304c3446aa3e0af8675ee14f6~mv2.jpg)\n\n2nd Place - $10000\n\nSafeRotation, a device for diabetics to minimize bruising complications while self-administering insulin injections.\nPictured: Shawn Michels\n\n![Early Stage Social Entrepreneurship](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_d5320fb7a0024a9fa8132282bcffaf30~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_d5320fb7a0024a9fa8132282bcffaf30~mv2.jpg)\n\nEarly Stage Social Entrepreneurship\n\nTurnIt, an automatic page turning device for helping people with disabilities read books.\nPictured: Seth Eiseman, Kevin Kirk, Ben Gabbard, Matt Czerwinski\n\n![First Place - $15000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7322723388bf4e4697667803195e6d48~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7322723388bf4e4697667803195e6d48~mv2.jpg)\n\nFirst Place - $15000\n\nLineLeap, a fast-pass for nightclubs that allows users to bypass big crowds, now available in 11 cities.\nPictured: Max Schauff\n\n1/11\n\n## Transcend UW 2017\n\n![Grand Prize Winner - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_6f07c3b726c44b748322ef7241f67509~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_6f07c3b726c44b748322ef7241f67509~mv2.jpg)\n\nGrand Prize Winner - $10000", "char_len": 2102, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::16", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 16, "text": "Transcend UW 2017\n\n![Grand Prize Winner - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_6f07c3b726c44b748322ef7241f67509~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_6f07c3b726c44b748322ef7241f67509~mv2.jpg)\n\nGrand Prize Winner - $10000\n\nLinectra, technology patent pending, has designed an advanced 3D printer to print high-quality, high-quantity metal parts to be used in manufacturing.\n\n![2nd Place - $8000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_1ee33f01b704403f9cec7a1c153312e4~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_1ee33f01b704403f9cec7a1c153312e4~mv2.jpg)\n\n2nd Place - $8000\n\nCairo Beverage’s first beverage line, inspired by Middle-Eastern/Mediterranean tea-based drinks, will is flavorful and refreshing with none of the sugar of traditional soft drinks.\n\n![Best Poster Session - $2000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_611c8a71145d4cd1b08a489aa5824553~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_611c8a71145d4cd1b08a489aa5824553~mv2.jpg)\n\nBest Poster Session - $2000\n\nAtrility Medical has developed a compact device to improve healthcare provers’ ability to diagnose and treat post-operative arrhythmias in patients following cardiac surgery.\n\n![Grand Prize Winner - $10000](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_6f07c3b726c44b748322ef7241f67509~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_98,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_6f07c3b726c44b748322ef7241f67509~mv2.jpg)\n\nGrand Prize Winner - $10000\n\nLinectra, technology patent pending, has designed an advanced 3D printer to print high-quality, high-quantity metal parts to be used in manufacturing.\n\n1/9\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/success-stories\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_22,h_12,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# Success Stories\n\nYour Journey doesn't have to end at Transcend", "char_len": 2098, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::17", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 17, "text": "Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_22,h_12,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# Success Stories\n\nYour Journey doesn't have to end at Transcend\n\n![Future Prospect - SideShift.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_afa74179664d45d9a69fec32a4fb32d4~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_405,h_271,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/Future%20Prospect%20-%20SideShift.jpg)\n\n## Side Shift\n\nRevolutionizing the process of hiring Gen Z, Side Shift allows students to apply for campus jobs with just one click. The app has more than a 1000 users​​​ and serves businesses and users in UW-Madison and other Big Ten Universities.\n\n​\n\nCompeted: 2024, Won \"Best Future Prospect\"\n\n​\n\nLearn More\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_7322723388bf4e4697667803195e6d48~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_405,h_271,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_7322723388bf4e4697667803195e6d48~mv2.jpg)\n\n## Line Leap\n\nAllowing users to skip the line and reserve spots at their favorite venue, the Line Leap app boasting an impressive 900,000 downloads. The startup serves users and 400+ venues across 80 cities nationwide. Line Leap was also part of Y Combinator's S19 batch, a highly competitive accelerator program known for nurturing top startups like Airbnb, Stripe, and Dropbox.\n\n​\n\nCompeted: 2018, Won 1st Place\n\nLearn More\n\n![](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_4e3d5faf759e4ca5906b3b85326bcba3~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_405,h_271,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_4e3d5faf759e4ca5906b3b85326bcba3~mv2.jpg)\n\n## Sprout\n\nTranscend's most recent first place winner, Sprout offers a way for users to easily build wealth by investing their spare change right from their phone. Currently, Sprout is inviting users to join its beta program.\n\n​\n\nCompeted: 2024, Won 1st Place\n\nLearn More\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_20,h_11,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\nReady to Compete?\n\nGet More Info\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/events", "char_len": 2261, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::18", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 18, "text": "(13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_20,h_11,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\nReady to Compete?\n\nGet More Info\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/events\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## Spring 2026\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/about-9\n\n![New Project (13)_edited.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_37e70a3c00724b139c0ed64730046581~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_147,h_95,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_37e70a3c00724b139c0ed64730046581~mv2.jpg)\n\n## The Transcend Podcast\n\nEvery episode, we sit down with student founders, alumni entrepreneurs, and community leaders to hear the real stories behind starting something new - the highs, the lows, and the lessons learned along the way.\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/how-can-you-help\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## HOW CAN YOU HELP?\n\n### Students\n\nJoin Transcend and be a part of something great!\n\nJoin Us\n\n### Mentors\n\nIf you want to be a mentor for any of events, visit the mentors section!\n\nMentor\n\n### Sponsors\n\nSponsor Transcend Competition and advertise your business!\n\nSponsor\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/startup-opportunities\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## Job Listings\n\nSee Open Roles\n\n### Linkyr\n\n​​Social apps isolated us into solo swiping and endless scrolling, Lynkr is on a mission to bring people together in real life. We make it easy for you to host events and find communities to broaden and deepen your network—whether that’s on a college campus, a run club, or any group that wants to get together.", "char_len": 2286, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::19", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 19, "text": "isolated us into solo swiping and endless scrolling, Lynkr is on a mission to bring people together in real life. We make it easy for you to host events and find communities to broaden and deepen your network—whether that’s on a college campus, a run club, or any group that wants to get together.\n\nLynkr helps you discover and create unforgettable experiences within your curated community. Guests can connect over shared photo albums, chat, and can collaborate on event playlists. And for hosts, we make the event planning process easy and engaging: Invite entire groups with a single click, utilize features that drive engagement and dramatically boost revenue, get free merch, and more. Whether it’s a weekly run club, a housewarming party, or a professional networking event, Lynkr gives you the tools to bring people together for meaningful, real connections.\n\n​\n\nBuilt by community builders and college dropouts, Lynkr is growing exponentially. We first launched at UChicago last year, and soon after spread to over 20% of the total undergraduate population. Within a few months of this school year, we’ve tripled: students have hosted hundreds of events and have sent out over 7k invites. We have raised almost half a million dollars from seed investors in Facebook, Instagram, Snapchat, Twitter, LinkedIn, Uber, & more.\n\n​\n\n​\n\nEmilyWheeler@LinkrMe.Net                                    9175651343\n\n* ![Instagram](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/8d6893330740455c96d218258a458aa4.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/8d6893330740455c96d218258a458aa4.png)\n* ![LinkedIn](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/48a2a42b19814efaa824450f23e8a253.png/v1/fill/w_39,h_39,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/48a2a42b19814efaa824450f23e8a253.png)\n\nSee Open Roles\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/students\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_41,h_23,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# STUDENTS\n\nTranscend UW is open to all students who want to bring new ideas, energy, and value to the entrepreneurial community.\n\nTo apply for the Executive Member position, please apply here.", "char_len": 2286, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::20", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 20, "text": "STUDENTS\n\nTranscend UW is open to all students who want to bring new ideas, energy, and value to the entrepreneurial community.\n\nTo apply for the Executive Member position, please apply here.\n\nYou’re always welcome to drop by our Executive Team Meetings, at 1403 University Ave to see what we’re about.\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/mentors\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_27,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# MENTORS\n\nTranscend UW is a student organization that aims to provide invaluable resources and opportunities to students on campus who are interested in creating their own ventures. If you have an idea that you want to partner on and help us reach our goal, fill out the mentor form below:\n\nMentor Form\n\nDan O.\n\nDan Olszewski, UW Professor\n\n“The Transcend competition is a great compliment to the entrepreneurial lessons students are learning in the classroom.  It allows students to put the concepts to use immediately and create an innovative product.  The experience results in the student teams dramatically expanding their entrepreneurial mindset which will only benefit them in their future careers.”\n\n![Transcend Mentor](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_d2cd689c0a214affa9714fd609840664~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_238,h_337,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/image.png)\n\nJohn S.\n\nThe Transcend Competition is a fantastic opportunity for UW-Madison students! They can develop diverse ideas, work on them with guidance and support during the year, and compete for generous prizes. They also improve their skills, gain confidence, and connect with mentors and judges from industry. It’s well run and well worth doing for students at any stage of their entrepreneurial journey!\n\nMy very best wishes,\n\nJohn", "char_len": 2142, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::21", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 21, "text": "with guidance and support during the year, and compete for generous prizes. They also improve their skills, gain confidence, and connect with mentors and judges from industry. It’s well run and well worth doing for students at any stage of their entrepreneurial journey!\n\nMy very best wishes,\n\nJohn\n\n![Transcend Mentor](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_8bfe2d63e6614f29ad6ef94c11e4e8e5~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_240,h_359,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_8bfe2d63e6614f29ad6ef94c11e4e8e5~mv2.png)\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/donate\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_43,h_24,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# Sponsor\n\nLooking forward to sponsoring a Transcend UW event? Use the link below!\n\nSponsor\n\n### Fund Name for Transcend UW: Innovation Days Fund - 112340033\n\n## HOW SPONSORSHIPS HAVE HELPED US..\n\n2010\n\nTRANSCEND UW IS FOUNDED\n\nTranscend UW was founded in 2010 with the goal of fostering a culture of innovation and entrepreneurship on campus. Our first event was a small workshop on idea generation, and since then we have grown to become one of the largest and most active student organizations on campus.\n\n2013\n\nFIRST ANNUAL STARTUP CHALLENGE\n\nIn 2013, Transcend UW hosted its first annual startup challenge, which brought together students from a variety of disciplines to pitch their ideas and compete for funding. The event was a huge success and has since become an annual tradition.\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/sponsors\n\n![New Project (13).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_49,h_28,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,blur_2,enc_avif,quality_auto/3c7a80_52892290ec1d42b7ad133b358323e1a3~mv2.png)\n\n# SPONSORS\n\nWant to sponsor our competition and advertise your organization? Click the link below!\n\nSponsor\n\n### Fund Name for Transcend UW: Innovation Days Fund - 112340033\n\n### If you need to contact us regarding sponsorship with Transcend, please contact transcenduw@gmail.com", "char_len": 2155, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::22", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 22, "text": "SPONSORS\n\nWant to sponsor our competition and advertise your organization? Click the link below!\n\nSponsor\n\n### Fund Name for Transcend UW: Innovation Days Fund - 112340033\n\n### If you need to contact us regarding sponsorship with Transcend, please contact transcenduw@gmail.com\n\n![Aifa Color.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_300e92729f014709b215cca84256e90c~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_273,h_92,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/Aifa%20Color.png)\n\n![WARF_100_primary_color.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_ab8cac82c6504952bad53c0beb24be85~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_273,h_272,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/WARF_100_primary_color.png)\n\n![amfam rgb (1).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_7235bab9270e45e5b7d4a90b28d8ca70~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_373,h_198,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/amfam%20rgb%20(1).png)\n\n![lineleap-horizontal black (1).png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_39322fcae1fa4c858beebf6aa487a1e9~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_282,h_66,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/lineleap-horizontal%20black%20(1).png)\n\n![qualcomm logo rgb blue.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_c697c9cce5114ba99d1e4e8b9c0fa964~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_564,h_176,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/qualcomm%20logo%20rgb%20blue.png)\n\n![D2P Vertical large JPG.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_114a1cbdfe924634b3648d0aafa9f9fe~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_261,h_187,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/D2P%20Vertical%20large%20JPG.jpg)\n\n![MGE alone 342 (1)_edited.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_da9fb8a4d9854ff99be65bb2cae28e43~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_341,h_124,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/MGE%20alone%20342%20(1)_edited.png)\n\n![images.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_edce62b4ae934d15870e0a79f25dca7b~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_378,h_103,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/images.png)\n\n![Weinart.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_b0ff6cf5874640d691397b5667de7b75~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_13,w_200,h_176/fill/w_164,h_144,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/Weinart.jpg)", "char_len": 2160, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::23", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 23, "text": "~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_378,h_103,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/images.png)\n\n![Weinart.jpg](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_b0ff6cf5874640d691397b5667de7b75~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_0,y_13,w_200,h_176/fill/w_164,h_144,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/Weinart.jpg)\n\n![Screenshot 2025-02-24 at 1.48.29 PM.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ad5310_baab41f78ef647c7ba77d9814d6c36ef~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_271,h_124,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/Screenshot%202025-02-24%20at%201_48_29%20PM.png)\n\n![IMG_0280.png](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_fc469fc5bcbf4026b5c47e61c1f333aa~mv2.png/v1/crop/x_0,y_3,w_300,h_162/fill/w_229,h_124,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/IMG_0280.png)\n\n![Fetch Logo](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_6bcea13b4d434654bca1035417bcfbe8~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_200,h_156,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_6bcea13b4d434654bca1035417bcfbe8~mv2.jpg)\n\n![Badger Consulting Logo](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_456a7c2dab794bf6867d8e4365cd69cd~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_378,h_127,al_c,q_85,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_456a7c2dab794bf6867d8e4365cd69cd~mv2.png)\n\n![Makerspace UW-Madison Logo](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_f41befbc87a8449eb94391e3778110f3~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_169,h_169,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_f41befbc87a8449eb94391e3778110f3~mv2.png)\n\n![StartingBlocks Madison Logo](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_f6bedc147f1948808ef1f2a586d818c5~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_353,h_143,al_c,q_85,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_f6bedc147f1948808ef1f2a586d818c5~mv2.png)\n\n![Contrary Logo](https://static.wixstatic.com/media/908254_4817dbb0fcd949f79393f92c5e73080f~mv2.png/v1/fill/w_307,h_51,al_c,q_85,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/908254_4817dbb0fcd949f79393f92c5e73080f~mv2.png)\n\n## [page] https://www.transcenduw.com/_files/ugd/ad5310_61ab87a269364c58b0713ac20f781a97.pdf\n\nth\n10 Anniversary\nSUMMER BLUES\n2 0 2 5\nTranscend UW Competition Program", "char_len": 2023, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::24", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 24, "text": "[page] https://www.transcenduw.com/_files/ugd/ad5310_61ab87a269364c58b0713ac20f781a97.pdf\n\nth\n10 Anniversary\nSUMMER BLUES\n2 0 2 5\nTranscend UW Competition Program\n\nWELCOME\nWelcome to the 10th annual Transcend Madison Innovation\nCompetition! The entire team at Transcend UW is pleased to\nbring you a showcase of the University of Wisconsin-\nMadisonʼs finest student talent in entrepreneurship and\ninnovation. Our mission is to support student ideas- no matter\nthe industry. From healthcare to education to innovative\nsnacks and beyond, our students are putting their ideas into\naction across the board and contributing to the world of\ntomorrow.\nThrough the competition, we hope to give students a head-\nstart on turning their ideas into concrete plans. This year, we\nare proud to give away over $40,000 in equity-free prizes.\nThis would not be possible without the generous contributions\nof our sponsors and local supporters.\nOn behalf of Transcend UW, thank you for coming, and enjoy\nthe 2025 Transcend Madison Innovation Competition. We\nhope to see you next year for the 10th Annual Competition!\n2\n\nSPONSORS\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nTranscend Alumni\n3\n\nCONTENTS\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nSponsors 3\nAgenda 5\nMap 6\nAwards 7\nCompetitors 9\nJudges 26\nTranscend 37\n4\n\nAGENDA\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nThursday April 10th\nPlacement Round Pitches - Morning 9:00 AM\nPoster & Prototype Session 12:00 PM\nPlacement Round Pitches - Afternoon 1:00 PM\nPlacement Round Judges Deliberation 4:20 PM\nFriday April 11th\nGeneral Track Group Pitches 8:20 AM\nAdvanced Track Group Pitches 8:20 AM\nJudges Deliberation - All Tracks 4:00 PM\nNetworking Session 4:30 PM\nAwards Ceremony Begins 5:00 PM\n5\n\nEVENT MAP\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nDay 1:\nPoster/\nPrototype\nDay 1:\nSession\nRoom 1\nDay 2:\nAdvanced Track\nNetworking &\nAwards\nCeremony\nDay 1:\nRoom 2\nCheck -in\nDay 2:\nGeneral Track\nRestrooms\n6", "char_len": 1947, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::25", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 25, "text": "- All Tracks 4:00 PM\nNetworking Session 4:30 PM\nAwards Ceremony Begins 5:00 PM\n5\n\nEVENT MAP\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nDay 1:\nPoster/\nPrototype\nDay 1:\nSession\nRoom 1\nDay 2:\nAdvanced Track\nNetworking &\nAwards\nCeremony\nDay 1:\nRoom 2\nCheck -in\nDay 2:\nGeneral Track\nRestrooms\n6\n\nAWARDS\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nAdvanced Track\nTop 5 Placement\n1st Place $10,000\n2nd Place $7,000\n3rd Place\n$5,000\n4th Place\n$2,500\n5th Place\n$2,500\nAdvanced Track Placement\n$2,500\nFuture Prospect Award\n$1,000\nBest Pitch\n$1,000\nBest Prototype/Demo\nAlumni Award $1,000\nGeneral Track\nOn the Horizon Award $1,500\nBest Pitch $750\nBest Visual $750\nAlumni Award $750\n7\n\nCOMPETITORS\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition 2025\nAlira\nAlira is a mobile and web-based platform that\npersonalizes the college dining experience. Students\nsimply select their favorite meals and dietary\npreferences, and Alira takes care of the rest. They\nreceive personalized menus and notifications showing\nwhere and when their preferred meals are being\nserved. The app also includes simple one-tap nutrition\ntracking. On the university side, Alira collects real-\ntime data on student preferences and dietary trends,\nhelping dining services optimize menus, reduce food\nwaste, and better serve their student populations.\nBeach Ease\nBeachEase is an innovative vending machine solution\nwith first-mover advantage and unique features,\nfilling a crucial gap in automated beach retail by\nbringing a proven model from airports to the\nuntapped beach sector. It provides hygienic and 24/7\ninstant access to beach gear like sandals, hats and\nsunglasses, SPF sunscreens and lip balms, toys, and\nmini first aid kits - all priced under $10 (prices scaled\nfor better quality), and available at beach entrances.\nIt ensures fast, affordable, on-demand access,\ncatering to both, those in need of essentials as well\nas impulse buyers. BeachEase is solar-powered,\nallowing deployment where electricity is limited.", "char_len": 1981, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::26", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 26, "text": "aid kits - all priced under $10 (prices scaled\nfor better quality), and available at beach entrances.\nIt ensures fast, affordable, on-demand access,\ncatering to both, those in need of essentials as well\nas impulse buyers. BeachEase is solar-powered,\nallowing deployment where electricity is limited.\n\nBlitzPrompts\nBlitzPrompts works directly with small businesses to\ndevelop personalized AI prompt libraries tailored to\ntheir operational needs. BlitzPrompts also features a\nweb extension that works directly within AI tools like\nChatGPT and Claude, allowing users to create,\nmanage, and access their custom prompts. By\neliminating repetitive prompt writing and streamlining\nAI interactions, BlitzPrompts helps small businesses\nsave valuable time, enabling them to focus more\neffectively on their core business activities.\nBoxMate\nBoxMate functions similarly to Airbnb, but for storage.\nThe platform connects student renters with extra\n.\napartment space over the summer to those looking for\nconvenient storage options. Users visit the BoxMate\nwebsite, click \"get started,\" select their preferred\nstorage location (including specific apartments or\nnearby options), choose flexible move-in and move-\nout dates, and select the items they wish to store.\nUnlike traditional services requiring full-summer\npayments, BoxMate allows students to pay monthly,\nstarting with just the first month's payment upon\nbooking.\n10", "char_len": 1410, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::27", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 27, "text": "(including specific apartments or\nnearby options), choose flexible move-in and move-\nout dates, and select the items they wish to store.\nUnlike traditional services requiring full-summer\npayments, BoxMate allows students to pay monthly,\nstarting with just the first month's payment upon\nbooking.\n10\n\nEmpOUR\nEmpOUR is a digital-first mentorship and career\ndevelopment platform helping students and early-\ncareer professionals rise, lead, and succeed. Through\ncurated resources, mentorship, and real-time\nopportunities, we’re closing the gap between\npotential and access—without the barriers of paywalls\nor privilege. Our web-based platform provides\ntailored career guides, resume and interview prep\ntools, identity-conscious support, and access to\nmentors and industry professionals across disciplines.\nMembers can attend expert-led webinars, explore\ncareer paths through community-driven insight, and\nsubscribe to a biweekly newsletter offering actionable\nadvice and real-time opportunities.\nENDLESS\nENDLESS is a narrative-driven digital publication and\ncreative platform that profiles artists while\ntransparently exploring the intersection of AI and\nvisual art. Through a vertical Instagram feed and\n.\ncompanion website, we publish ethically adapted\nartwork and artist features, complete with side-by-\nside comparisons, contextual writing, and proper\ncitation. Future phases include a curated\nmarketplace, artist submission portal, auction\nfeatures, and a physical gallery-studio space in NYC.\nENDLESS challenges unethical AI use, uplifts artists,\nand builds trust through intentional curation and\ncommunity.\n11", "char_len": 1612, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::28", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 28, "text": "contextual writing, and proper\ncitation. Future phases include a curated\nmarketplace, artist submission portal, auction\nfeatures, and a physical gallery-studio space in NYC.\nENDLESS challenges unethical AI use, uplifts artists,\nand builds trust through intentional curation and\ncommunity.\n11\n\nFillUp\nBut what if you never had to wait in line for a drink\nagain? FillUp is the first and only AI-powered point-\nof-sale platform that uses machine learning to\noptimize ordering, improve customer experience, and\nincrease sales and 9ps. Designed for all high-volume\nvenues, FillUp seamlessly integrates with existing\npoint-of-sale systems to streamline service and\nmaximize revenue. With AI-driven drink\nrecommendations, bulk credit discounts, and one-\ntouch ordering, FillUp isn’t just another point-of-sale\nplatform—it’s the future of high-volume ordering.\nFlux\nFlux is a hybrid of professional-scale social\nnetworking and swipe-based, high-speed interaction\nof Tinder. Users can create rich, intention-driven\nprofiles, swipe to match with peers, mentors, or\ncolleagues, and filter matches by industry, interests,\nor academic studies. For example, I am a business\nstudent with an innovative technology idea, but lack\nthose technical skills. I can just find someone with\nthose skills on flux. Flux makes it intuitive, fast, and\nenjoyable to make meaningful connections in\nnetworking for the new age.\n12", "char_len": 1397, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::29", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 29, "text": "interests,\nor academic studies. For example, I am a business\nstudent with an innovative technology idea, but lack\nthose technical skills. I can just find someone with\nthose skills on flux. Flux makes it intuitive, fast, and\nenjoyable to make meaningful connections in\nnetworking for the new age.\n12\n\nFrameChat\nFrameChat is a mobile WebAR application that allows\nmuseum visitors to view and share real-time comments\non artworks through augmented reality. When a visitor\npoints their phone camera at a supported piece, the\napp uses an image recognition model to identify it\nand overlay live “comment bubbles” — short, floating\nmessages left by others. Visitors can also submit their\nown reactions, creating a dynamic, community-driven\ninterpretation anchored to each artwork.\nGrocery Guide\nGrocery Guide will feature a top view map of the\nstore, labeling sections and specific products on your\ngrocery list. Based on their grocery list, the app will\ngive an optimal route through the store. Customers\nwill also be able to see their current location within\nthe store. Additional features will include providing\ndetails about which stores have products needed and\nwhich are cheapest. There will also be a call-a-worker\nfunction for when the map is insufficient. Ads may be\ndisplayed based on where the user is in the store.\n13", "char_len": 1322, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::30", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 30, "text": "their current location within\nthe store. Additional features will include providing\ndetails about which stores have products needed and\nwhich are cheapest. There will also be a call-a-worker\nfunction for when the map is insufficient. Ads may be\ndisplayed based on where the user is in the store.\n13\n\nHopTimized\nOur service will allow users to input a desired date\nrange and destinations of interest. HopTimized will\nthen scrape flight data between the various\ndestinations in order to find the cheapest route across\nmultiple destinations. If one wanted to travel to\nSeattle, Chicago, and New York but the destination\norder was not important to the user, HopTimized would\noptimize the cheapest route for your vacation while\nalso abiding by any input parameters.\nImpactChain\nImpactChain is a social giving platform for charities to\ntell their stories through short videos and donors\ncontribute through financial donations or social media\npromotion. Charities can create project milestones\nwith donation goals to be displayed in their short\nvideos, showing donors the tangible outcomes of their\ncontributions. Donors can view real-time transparency\nmetrics displayed directly on a charity’s page, showing\nexactly how funds are allocated. Both donors and\ncharities can film, edit, and publish videos using\nImpactChain on a smartphone or computer.\n14\n\nIn-dome\n. In-Dome is an intuitive digital platform (initially\nwebsite-based, evolving into a mobile app) that offers\non-demand home services:Cleaning Services: Routine,\ndeep, move-out, and post-event cleaning.Furniture\nAssembly/Moving: Assistance with furniture assembly,\nrelocations, and small moves. Personal Grooming:\nConvenient, in-home haircuts and basic grooming\nservices.Future expansions include integrating\nhealthcare services (e.g., vaccinations, diagnostic\ntesting) directly into customers’ homes, positioning In-\nDome as a comprehensive home-services\necosystem\nInsta-Desk\nThe Insta-Desk is a mobile work surface that goes\nwherever you go. It is rigid for writing and support on\none side, and can be rolled up to fit into the water\nbottle pocket of your backpack when flipped to the\nother side. From small lecture hall desks to taking\nnotes in bed, the Insta-Desk can create a better\nworkspace in any environment.\n15", "char_len": 2274, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::31", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 31, "text": "goes\nwherever you go. It is rigid for writing and support on\none side, and can be rolled up to fit into the water\nbottle pocket of your backpack when flipped to the\nother side. From small lecture hall desks to taking\nnotes in bed, the Insta-Desk can create a better\nworkspace in any environment.\n15\n\nJolly\nJolly is an all-in-one social and entertainment app\ndesigned for seniors, offering a seamless way to stay\nconnected, informed, and engaged. With voice control\nand text-to-speech, users can easily navigate the\napp, listen to daily news highlights, enjoy a \"Movie of\nthe Day\" with audio descriptions, and create\npersonalized music playlists. Fun memory games,\npodcasts, and a contact feature allow seniors to stay\nmentally sharp and socially active.\nLearnripl, Inc.\nLearnripl is an AI-powered tool that helps teachers\nmake learning more engaging and applicable.\nTeachers create a classroom, while students set up\naccounts that store their interests—like basketball or\nskiing. Then, our multi-agent model consists of three\nspecialized agents working together to personalize\nassignments for each student based on previous\nexamples. The result? Students receive assignments\nthey actually enjoy, while teachers maintain full\ncontrol over their course framework and objectives.\n16\n\nLigi\nLigi is a workout tracking app which combines a sleek\nand simple interface with social platform that allows\nusers to easily track, share, and find new workouts\nwith others. Users looking for a new workout or new\ngym-goers looking for guidance can quickly find\nsuggested workouts created by trainers or influencers,\nas well as search for plans created by friends or\nfamily. Our proprietary algorithm automatically caters\nevery workout plan to the individual by adjusting the\nplan’s suggested weights. We aim to remove the\nguesswork and make progress feel accessible,\npersonalized, and motivating for everyone.\nLogger\nLogger is a mobile app that tailors optimal workout\nroutines to users’ specific needs and goals. It tracks\nboth lifting and cardiovascular activities while\nproviding real-time, personalized progression targets.\nBy leveraging a machine learning-powered language\nmodel, Logger continuously refines recommendations\nbased on accumulated user data, ensuring optimal\nand scientifi\n17", "char_len": 2279, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::32", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 32, "text": "needs and goals. It tracks\nboth lifting and cardiovascular activities while\nproviding real-time, personalized progression targets.\nBy leveraging a machine learning-powered language\nmodel, Logger continuously refines recommendations\nbased on accumulated user data, ensuring optimal\nand scientifi\n17\n\nMotionPlay\nMotionPlay is an AI-powered tennis coaching app that\ncombines human pose estimation, 3D motion capture\nand large language models (LLMs) to deliver instant,\npersonalized feedback using just a smartphone. The\nplatform also builds a peer-based (C-to-C) tennis\ncommunity where players can share swings, compete\nin virtual challenges, and grow together. It’s like\nhaving a coach and a training partner—anytime,\nanywhere.\nNomad\nNomad simplifies the process of planning travel\nexcursions. Nomad is an application that allows users\nto choose travel activities based on recommendations\nand tips from people in their direct network. By\nallowing travelers to follow their friends and see their\nrecommendations, Nomad can create personalized\nrecommendations and trusted, summarized ratings on\naccommodations, dining, and attractions, making\ntravel planning effortless, better tailored, and more\nenjoyable. Travelers can also connect with others in\ntheir abroad programs and seamlessly coordinate\ntravel with their companions. Users post ratings to\ntheir networks, and other Nomads can save and\ninteract with other posts on their feed.\n18", "char_len": 1435, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::33", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 33, "text": "planning effortless, better tailored, and more\nenjoyable. Travelers can also connect with others in\ntheir abroad programs and seamlessly coordinate\ntravel with their companions. Users post ratings to\ntheir networks, and other Nomads can save and\ninteract with other posts on their feed.\n18\n\nOlanah\nOlanah is software that makes therapy homework easy\nand engaging. Therapists send pre-built or customized\nactivities, based on research, to clients’ devices.\nClients get motivating notifications and an app\nexperience to boost completion, while therapists track\nprogress easily. HIPAA-compliant & secure, Olanah\nsaves time, enhances care, and strengthens client-\ntherapist relationships in a growing digital mental\nhealth space.\nPatch\nPatch is a local farm marketplace app available for\niOS and Android. Right from the home screen, users\njump into a live feed of nearby listings and in one\nswipe can open the listings map to see what’s close\nby. They can message the seller to ask a question, and\neither pay through the app or arrange a pickup\ndirectly. After a purchase, buyers can leave a written\nreview on the seller’s profile. For sellers who want to\ngain traction, Patch Plus is a monthly subscription that\nunlocks verified badges and boosts their listings on\nthe map and feed.\n19", "char_len": 1282, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::34", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 34, "text": "and\neither pay through the app or arrange a pickup\ndirectly. After a purchase, buyers can leave a written\nreview on the seller’s profile. For sellers who want to\ngain traction, Patch Plus is a monthly subscription that\nunlocks verified badges and boosts their listings on\nthe map and feed.\n19\n\nPEAR\nPEAR is an AI-powered learning platform that uses AR\nheadsets to project digital music notes above a real\npiano keyboard. Users receive instant voice feedback\non timing, accuracy, and technique while practicing.\nThe system adapts to each learner by analyzing\nperformance and highlighting areas for improvement.\nPEAR turns music practice into an immersive, game-\nlike experience that’s intuitive and fun. PEAR can also\nbe integrated into classrooms, offering schools a\ncost-effective and scalable alternative to traditional\nprivate instruction. Future updates will support other\ninstruments and multiplayer jam sessions.\nSprout\nPopilly\nPopilly is a light, crispy snack made from lotus seeds, a\nsuperfood that has been enjoyed in India for centuries.\nWith bold flavors like Peri-Peri, Salt & Pepper, Chaat\nMasala and Barbecue, Popilly delivers a crunchy, plant-\nbased snack that is gluten-free, rich in antioxidants, high\nin fiber and protein, and low in calories. It’s the perfect\nsnack for those seeking a satisfying, on-the-go treat\nwithout compromising on health. The product will be\nprocessed and packaged in India, then imported to the\nU.S. to meet the growing demand for clean, functional,\nand flavorful snacks.\n20", "char_len": 1518, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::35", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 35, "text": "fiber and protein, and low in calories. It’s the perfect\nsnack for those seeking a satisfying, on-the-go treat\nwithout compromising on health. The product will be\nprocessed and packaged in India, then imported to the\nU.S. to meet the growing demand for clean, functional,\nand flavorful snacks.\n20\n\nQuicko\nQuicko is a Q-Commerce grocery delivery platform\nusing a micro-fulfillment model. Each fulfillment hub\nwill stock 3,000 popular SKUs and cover a 3-3.5 km\nradius for ultra-fast deliveries. Customers can order\nvia our web-app and receive groceries in under 15\nminutes.\nRedelevenlabs\nRedelevenlabs has created an AI tool to assist the\nAdult content industry in stoping the illegal spread of\nminors in adult videos. We use Visual and Audio to get\nan 80%+ accuracy on the age of every person visible\nin the videos. This will be used as an initial scanner,\nblocking obvious illegal uses and sending questionable\n/ indecisive videos to a secondary stage. The current\nmethod has a person scan about 500 - 800 videos a\nday, while our technology can scan about 720,000\nvideos a day. This product is the first in many uses of\nvoice and video to crack down on illegal uses of SaaS\nproducts.\n21", "char_len": 1186, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::36", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 36, "text": "sending questionable\n/ indecisive videos to a secondary stage. The current\nmethod has a person scan about 500 - 800 videos a\nday, while our technology can scan about 720,000\nvideos a day. This product is the first in many uses of\nvoice and video to crack down on illegal uses of SaaS\nproducts.\n21\n\nRELA\n. RELA is a lightweight Bluetooth sensor that pairs with a\nmobile app to track real-time workout movement. The\napp transforms this data into a game, making users feel\nlike they’re inside an interactive video game while they\ntrain. Built completely in-house, the device works across\nexercises, specializing in strength-based workouts. New\ngym-goers can find working out motivating and less\nintimidating. Experienced lifters can use RELA to get\ndeeper insights into their form, consistency, and effort.\nIt’s a personal trainer, gaming console, and performance\ndashboard—all in one.\nSkylark Energy\nSolutions\nOur software-based product helps electric utilities\ndetect and mitigate wildfire risk. Based on industry\nstandards that describe the thermal behavior of\ntransmission lines, we first calculate the temperature\nand sagging (i.e., distance to vegetation) of their\nlines in real time using forecastable ambient weather\nparameters (e.g., air temperature, wind) and the\nutility’s operational data (e.g., voltage and current\nlevel). By combining this information with the US\nGeological Survey’s publicly available Wildland Fire\nPotential Index (WFPI), we can quantify wildfire risk\nusing our proprietary algorithm.\n22", "char_len": 1517, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::37", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 37, "text": "(e.g., air temperature, wind) and the\nutility’s operational data (e.g., voltage and current\nlevel). By combining this information with the US\nGeological Survey’s publicly available Wildland Fire\nPotential Index (WFPI), we can quantify wildfire risk\nusing our proprietary algorithm.\n22\n\nSmartMigrate\nSmartMigrate is an application that guides users\nthrough the I-589 asylum form one question at a time,\n..using clear explanations, AI support, and real-time\nlanguage translation. The app generates a completed\nUSCIS PDF based on user inputs without storing any\npersonal data, ensuring privacy. SmartMigrate\nincludes helpful visuals, such as maps for country of\norigin, icons for marital status, and definitions for\nlegal terms. It is built specifically for legal service\nproviders to streamline client intake and multiply their\ncaseload capacity.\nTecaran\nTecaran is a startup creating innovative products with\ncustomer safety as the top priority. Our first product\nis smart headphones integrated with built-in cameras\nand a connected mobile app, enabling hands-free\nvideo recording and real-time safety monitoring. With\nTecaran, travelers and solo commuters can record\ntheir surroundings and activate the Watch Over\nfeature in unsafe situations, allowing trusted friends\nto monitor their journey.\n23", "char_len": 1297, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::38", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 38, "text": "built-in cameras\nand a connected mobile app, enabling hands-free\nvideo recording and real-time safety monitoring. With\nTecaran, travelers and solo commuters can record\ntheir surroundings and activate the Watch Over\nfeature in unsafe situations, allowing trusted friends\nto monitor their journey.\n23\n\nTwyne\nTwyne targets socially active young adults and\nprofessionals in Chicago, typically ages 22 to 35,\nwho frequently make plans with friends. This includes\n.\nboth locals looking for new experiences and travelers\nexploring the city together. These users often face\nplanning friction like conflicting preferences, limited\navailability, and the challenge of finding something\neveryone is excited about. This group values quick,\nlow-effort ways to discover and align on plans,\nmaking them a strong fit for Twyne’s streamlined,\nsocial approach to activity planning.\nVelos\nVelos is a forecasting app that provides actionable\nsuggestions for restaurants on menu demand, labor\n.\nneeds, and inventory usage. Instead of replacing\ncurrent hardware, Velos scrapes reports from\nplatforms like Square and Toast, processes the data\nusing our innovative algorithm, and delivers clear,\nactionable suggestions. suggestions. This approach\nallows restaurants to leverage sophisticated analytics\nto optimize their operations without the cost or\ncomplexity of switching POS providers.\n24", "char_len": 1367, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::39", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 39, "text": "like Square and Toast, processes the data\nusing our innovative algorithm, and delivers clear,\nactionable suggestions. suggestions. This approach\nallows restaurants to leverage sophisticated analytics\nto optimize their operations without the cost or\ncomplexity of switching POS providers.\n24\n\nViralist\nVirialist is a B2B platform that connects small businesses\nwith nearby users, who - in exchange for free products\nfrom the business - perform product promotion on their\npersonal social media for the business. It starts with both\nthe business and user creating their own accounts and the\nbusiness inputting its marketing goals and what it expects\nfrom its influencers. The user self inputs his niche and what\nkind of business he/she believes represents his/her\npersonal brand. A pairing algorithm will match the business\nand influencer together based on the best predictive fit,\nand the user then will create content based on what the\nbusiness has inputted for their content expectations.\nWhat’s the move?\nWhat’s the Move? is a social networking and mapping\napplication designed to connect users with small\nbusinesses, unique restaurants, and hidden gems in their\narea. While traditional online mapping services prioritize\nmajor chains, this application instead emphasizes local\nbusiness and niche activities providing users with great\nexperiences and economic support for local businesses.\nWith artificial intelligence-driven recommendations,\nexciting challenges, and seamless ad integration, What’s\nthe Move? engages users on a platform to promote\ndiscovery, new adventures, and interaction with friends\nand family.\n25", "char_len": 1620, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::40", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 40, "text": "with great\nexperiences and economic support for local businesses.\nWith artificial intelligence-driven recommendations,\nexciting challenges, and seamless ad integration, What’s\nthe Move? engages users on a platform to promote\ndiscovery, new adventures, and interaction with friends\nand family.\n25\n\nPLACEMENT ROUND JUDGES\nMichele Boal\nM.ichele Boal was the co-founder of Quotient\nTechnology Inc. (formerly Coupons.com), where she\nserved as Chief Philanthropy Officer and\nspearheaded initiatives like Coupons for Change to\nsupport non-profit organizations. Currently, she is\nthe Founder and CEO of Kadima. Michele's\ncommitment to social impact is further\ndemonstrated by her role as a Strategic Advisor for\nChange, a platform leading the next generation of\ngiving, activism and social impact in. As a UW-\nMadison alumna, she has been recognized for her\nentrepreneurial achievements, including induction\ninto the Weinert Center Hall of Fame.\nMike Fix\nMike Fix is a frontend engineer, currently working\nfor Frontier at Stripe and also leads the Open\nSource team. In a former life, Mike attended UW\nMadison, completing a Bachelors Degree in\nComputer Engineering and Computer Sciences.\nAlong with friends, Mike co-founded the\nTranscend Madison Innovation Competition.\n26\n\nSamir Gupta\nSamir Gupta serves as a VP of Engineering leading\nQualcomm's Multimedia Solutions department. In\nhis 30 years at Qualcomm, he has developed\nQualcomm's foundational DSP platforms, founded\nthe Audio Technologies team delivering IP to\nmobile, wireless headsets, automotive, wearables,\nand connected devices , and created new product\ntechnologies in sensors and biometrics. He is\ncurrently involved in spearheading Qualcomm's\ngrowth in Internet of Things Solutions including\nEdge AI, multimedia and microservices.\nDervis Gursoy\nUW Engineering alumni who followed his early\nchildhood passion for ag-tech and founded\nSpraycision. Spraycision is an agricultural\nautomation product used in spray applications of\nspecialty crops such as fruits, citrus and tree\nnuts. It retrofits to conventional orchard sprayers\nand automatically actuates nozzles on/off as\nwell as adjusting the flow-rate by detecting crop\narchitecture via LiDAR technology.\n27", "char_len": 2213, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::41", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 41, "text": "an agricultural\nautomation product used in spray applications of\nspecialty crops such as fruits, citrus and tree\nnuts. It retrofits to conventional orchard sprayers\nand automatically actuates nozzles on/off as\nwell as adjusting the flow-rate by detecting crop\narchitecture via LiDAR technology.\n27\n\nEd Javier\nEd is a seasoned executive with over 15 years of\nexperience in the startup ecosystem, specializing in\nbuilding, scaling, and transforming high-growth\ncompanies. He played a key role in the success of\nCars.com and HomeFinder.com, driving growth and\ninnovation. In 2015, as General Manager, he led the\nsuccessful pivot and sale of a leading real estate\nplatform.\nChris Meyer\nChris graduated from UW with a BS'08/MS'10 in\nMechanical Engineering working on diesel\nemissions at the Engine Research Center. He\ncompeted in business, environment, and invention\ncompetitions from 2005-2010 winning over $40k\nin prizes from a variety of ideas and founded\nSector67 when he graduated. Sector67 is a\nhackerspace that provides community access to\ntools, equipment, technology, and workspace for\nindividuals and businesses.\n28\n\nTad Milbourn\nTad Milbourn is currently the solo founder of\nRankedVote — the best way to run ranked choice\nvoting contests online. Previously, he was Co-\nfounder and CEO of Payable (acquired by Stripe)\nwhere he raised $2.9M in VC funding from Y-\nCombinator, Redpoint Ventures, Freestyle Capital,\nGeneral Catalyst and more. Tad also held business\nand innovation leadership roles at Intuit focusing on\nsmall businesses, entrepreneurship, and tax.\nNick Myers\nNick Myers is the Co-Founder of RedFox AI, a\nMadison-based AI and digital healthcare startup\nfocused on transforming medical device and\nspecialty nurse program training, support, and\ncontinuing education. Nick is also the President\nof RedFox Consulting Group focused on helping\nenterprise businesses adopt and implement AI\ntools, and is a global speaker on AI, the future of\nwork, and data privacy. He has been featured in\npublications like the Wisconsin State Journal and\nthe Property Guru Property Report and is the\nrecipient of several local awards including the\nMadison Magazine Brian Howell Excellence in\nInnovation Award and InBusiness 40 Under 40.\n29", "char_len": 2234, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::42", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 42, "text": "the future of\nwork, and data privacy. He has been featured in\npublications like the Wisconsin State Journal and\nthe Property Guru Property Report and is the\nrecipient of several local awards including the\nMadison Magazine Brian Howell Excellence in\nInnovation Award and InBusiness 40 Under 40.\n29\n\nSara Poticha\nSara has 30+ years of experience leading startups and\nestablished organizations, building the structures and\ntools needed to drive business growth. She’s\nresponsible for the day-to-day management and\nbusiness operations of Global Repair Group (GRG), a\nnational company focusing on repairing and replacing\nassistive devices for airline customers worldwide.\nBefore her current position, Sara raised VC funding and\nlaunched a disability staffing firm headquartered in\nDenver, CO. Sara is currently the Vice Chair of Reading\nPower, a two-time mentor for College Bound\nOpportunities, an active Trustee on the Jewish Women’s\nFoundation.\nBrian Schneirow\nBrian Schneirow has worked for over 20 years in\nSilicon Valley in nearly every aspect of product\nand software development. He has extensive\nexperience in large scale systems design and\noperation. His experience encompasses 15 years\nat Google plus 4 other startups, 3 of which\nsuccessfully IPO'd or were acquired.\n30\n\nGENERAL TRACK JUDGES\nJoel Baraka\nJ.oel Baraka serves as a Project Engineer at CG\nSchmidt, Inc. and is the Co-founder of My Home\nStars. He earned a B.S. in Civil Engineering from\nUW-Madison and previously competed in\nTranscend, securing 2nd place. Has been\nrecognized by the In Business Magazine as a 40\nunder 40 recipient. He has also given a TED Talk,\nsharing his personal journey of education while\ngrowing up in the Kyangwali Refugee Camp and\nhighlighting the initiatives of My Home Stars\naimed at improving access to quality education\nfor refugee children.\nLou Elson\nI've called the Madison area home for over 17\nyears and became a licensed Realtor in 2018 to\nfollow my passion for real estate. Today, I work\nwith buyers and sellers across Southern\nWisconsin, helping them navigate the process\nwith confidence. At Lou Elson Real Estate, I lead\na team of licensed Realtors dedicated to making\nhome buying and selling as simple and exciting as\npossible.\n31", "char_len": 2233, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::43", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 43, "text": "to\nfollow my passion for real estate. Today, I work\nwith buyers and sellers across Southern\nWisconsin, helping them navigate the process\nwith confidence. At Lou Elson Real Estate, I lead\na team of licensed Realtors dedicated to making\nhome buying and selling as simple and exciting as\npossible.\n31\n\nJames Kardatzke\nJames Kardatzke is the CEO of Quiver\nQuantitative, an investment research platform\nbuilt for retail investors. Quiver has over 500,000\nregistered users, and has been featured in\nplatforms such as the Financial Times, the\nWashington Post, and Bloomberg. James founded\nthe company with his twin brother, while he was a\nstudent at UW-Madison.\nChris Meyer\nChris graduated from UW with a BS'08/MS'10 in\nMechanical Engineering working on diesel\nemissions at the Engine Research Center. He\ncompeted in business, environment, and\ninvention competitions from 2005-2010 winning\nover $40k in prizes from a variety of ideas and\nfounded Sector67 when he graduated. Sector67\nis a hackerspace that provides community\naccess to tools, equipment, technology, and\nworkspace for individuals and businesses.\n32\n\nYu-Lin Yang\nYu-Lin is a Product Manager at Microsoft, where\nhe spends his days building Azure — one of the\nworld's largest cloud platforms. A proud UW–\nMadison alum and former Transcend UW President\nand competitor, Yu-Lin is passionate about\nmarketplace startups and enjoys diving deep into\nAI topics such as agents and AI infrastructure.\n.\n33", "char_len": 1450, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::44", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 44, "text": "where\nhe spends his days building Azure — one of the\nworld's largest cloud platforms. A proud UW–\nMadison alum and former Transcend UW President\nand competitor, Yu-Lin is passionate about\nmarketplace startups and enjoys diving deep into\nAI topics such as agents and AI infrastructure.\n.\n33\n\nADVANCED TRACK JUDGES\nJordan Black\nJordan Black served as the president of Transcend\nfor the 2018 competition. After earning a B.S. in\nMechanical Engineering, he launched his career as\na Manufacturing Development Engineer at\nSpaceX, later becoming Manager of Avionics\nResearch and Development. Today, he is the CEO\nand co-founder of Senra Systems, a fast-growing\nhardtech company with a team of 75+ providing\ncritical electrical wiring solutions to aerospace\nand defense companies. Backed by top-tier\ninvestors—including Sequoia, Founders Fund, a16z,\nand General Catalyst—Senra Systems is shaping\nthe future of American manufacturing technology.\nSamir Gupta\nSamir Gupta serves as a VP of Engineering\nleading Qualcomm's Multimedia Solutions\ndepartment. In his 30 years at Qualcomm, he\nhas developed Qualcomm's foundational DSP\nplatforms, founded the Audio Technologies team\ndelivering IP to mobile, wireless headsets,\nautomotive, wearables, and connected devices ,\nand created new product technologies in sensors\nand biometrics. He is currently involved in\nspearheading Qualcomm's growth in Internet of\nThings Solutions including Edge AI, multimedia\nand microservices.\n34", "char_len": 1461, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "transcend-uw::45", "doc_slug": "transcend-uw", "chunk_index": 45, "text": "IP to mobile, wireless headsets,\nautomotive, wearables, and connected devices ,\nand created new product technologies in sensors\nand biometrics. He is currently involved in\nspearheading Qualcomm's growth in Internet of\nThings Solutions including Edge AI, multimedia\nand microservices.\n34\n\nXiao He\nXiao He, once a competitor and organizer at\nTranscend Madison, now comes full circle as a\njudge, mentoring the next generation of\nentrepreneurs. After launching his own startup,\nKilter, he played a key role in securing cloud\ninfrastructure at Twilio, a fast-growing startup that\nbecame a major player in communications. Now at\nCredit Karma, he continues to focus on building\nsecurity at scale. With experience spanning student\nstartups to high-growth companies, Xiao is\npassionate about helping founders refine their ideas\ninto scalable businesses.\nEd Javier\nEd is a seasoned executive with over 15 years of\nexperience in the startup ecosystem, specializing\nin building, scaling, and transforming high-\ngrowth companies. He played a key role in the\nsuccess of Cars.com and HomeFinder.com,\ndriving growth and innovation. In 2015, as\nGeneral Manager, he led the successful pivot\nand sale of a leading real estate platform.\n35\n\nTad Milbourn\nTad Milbourn is currently the solo founder of\nRankedVote — the best way to run ranked choice\nvoting contests online. Previously, he was Co-\nfounder and CEO of Payable (acquired by Stripe)\nwhere he raised $2.9M in VC funding from Y-\nCombinator, Redpoint Ventures, Freestyle Capital,\nGeneral Catalyst and more. Tad also held business\nand innovation leadership roles at Intuit focusing\non small businesses, entrepreneurship, and tax.\n36\n\nMEET OUR TEAM\nVIKRANTH MANDADI ANAJANCY PONCE\nPresident Vice-President\nSHRADHA GODISHALA ANNA CHEN MASHA MOCHALNIKOVA\nMarketing Lead Treasurer Events Lead\nSIDDHARTH SINGH SUHA AFZAR JOSHUA ZHANG\nOutreach Lead Web Lead Secretary\n37\n\nMEET OUR TEAM\nASHWATH KALLAM SABRINA SHI\nCoordinator Coordinator\nALINA ZHANG JIAYI CHEN\nCoordinator Coordinator\nNOT PICTURED\nMICHAEL PANCRAS\nCoordinator\n38\n\nTHANK YOU\nTO OUR SPONSORS,\nTO OUR MENTORS,\nTO OUR JUDGES,\nTO OUR ALUMNI,\nand TO OUR COMPETITORS,\nFOR AN AMAZING\n10 YEARS!\n2 0 2 5", "char_len": 2187, "id": 12, "source": "TranscendUW", "type": "static_html", "category": "student-org", "url": "https://www.transcenduw.com/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::0", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company\n\n## LAUNCH YOUR **STARTUP NOW**\n\nYou’ve solidified your idea, done your due diligence and drafted your business plan. It’s time to take the next step.\n\nWhen you work with WARF, we share your goal: to advance UW-Madison technologies from lab to market to benefit the world. Because your long-term success means furthering this mission, we’re here for you long after the license agreement is signed to educate, accelerate and provide support.\n\n### Let’s get to work.\n\nHere’s a walkthrough of the process:\n\n1. On your own or with a WARF licensing manager’s  help, **determine the feasibility** of your startup. Carefully consider the market for your innovative solution and its accessibility to a startup, as well as any additional development and/or rights your technology would need before it’s ready for market.\n2. Decide **which founders will actively participate** in your company and their roles.\n3. **Develop your business plan**. Your plan explains the strategy behind your new company and WARF will use this document to help you determine the viability of your plans.\n4. If you need additional time to evaluate the commercial potential of your technology or develop your full business plan, you can **request a six-month standstill period** from WARF. During this time, WARF will keep the technology available for potential licensing to your new company.\n5. Submit your business plan to **your licensing manger**. (See our Contact Us page to search for WARF team members.)\n6. Refine your business plan through **conversations with WARF**.\n7. Establish your startup as a **legal entity** so you can enter into license and equity agreements with WARF.\n8. Negotiate and execute **licensing agreements with WARF**.", "char_len": 1780, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::1", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "(See our Contact Us page to search for WARF team members.)\n6. Refine your business plan through **conversations with WARF**.\n7. Establish your startup as a **legal entity** so you can enter into license and equity agreements with WARF.\n8. Negotiate and execute **licensing agreements with WARF**.\n\nAfter your agreements are set, WARF will be available to your startup on an ongoing basis to provide support. There are milestones and obligations that will be outlined in your agreement that you’ll meet and there are commitments that we’ll fulfill as well.\n\n![Man and women smiling in a medical room](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/smallerRectangleInteriorStartingCompany.jpg)\n\n## WHAT WARF BRINGS TO THE TABLE **TO MAKE YOU SUCCESSFUL**\n\nWARF views our commitment to startups as a partnership. Far beyond a technology licensing agreement, we’re focused on your success.\n\nWe are part of UW-Madison Innovate Network, UW-Madison’s front door for resources that support campus and entrepreneurs.\n\nWe have access to market reports. Reach out to your licensing manager to request market information.\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/about-warf/careers\n\n## GUIDING WORLD-CHANGING TECHNOLOGIES TO MARKET\n\nWARF is one of the first and most successful tech transfer offices in the world. The core of what we do is advancing UW-Madison and Morgridge Institute for Research discoveries to benefit people across Wisconsin and around the globe.\n\nWe are stewards, collaborators and innovators. From intellectual property, commercialization, investment, engagement and more, each member of our staff is committed to our mission of supporting scientific research and innovation at the university.\n\nWARF is an Equal Opportunity Employer and is committed to fostering and supporting an inclusive workplace. We are committed to working with and providing reasonable accommodations to individuals with disabilities throughout the employment process. If you need to request accommodations, please send an email to [email protected] or call Human Resources at 608-960-9850.\n\nWARF participates in E-Verify.\n\nIMPORTANT: Health Coverage Tax Documents Available", "char_len": 2150, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::2", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "reasonable accommodations to individuals with disabilities throughout the employment process. If you need to request accommodations, please send an email to [email protected] or call Human Resources at 608-960-9850.\n\nWARF participates in E-Verify.\n\nIMPORTANT: Health Coverage Tax Documents Available\n\nIn compliance with the Affordable Care Act (ACA), WARF will provide Form 1095-C to all eligible employees and covered individuals upon request. This form includes information about the health insurance coverage we offered employees during the 2025 tax year.\n\nTo request a copy of your Form 1095-C or for further information, contact:\nMaureen Miner, Director of Human Resources\n614 Walnut Street, 13th floor\nMadison, WI 53726\n[email protected]\n608-960-9850\n\n---\n\n### Open Positions\n\nThere are no open positions at this time.\n\n---\n\n### Joining A Leader in Tech Transfer\n\nWARF designed our employee benefits program to really take care of our employees and their families. We know that addressing health and wellness, professional development and work-life balance as an employer has helped us maintain the highest caliber employees.\n\nYour benefits could include:\n\n* Comprehensive medical and dental health benefits\n* Domestic partner coverage\n* Life insurance policy\n* Short-term and long-term disability coverage\n* Generous paid time off policy, including time off to volunteer\n* Employer-funded defined benefit plan\n* Voluntary employee-funded defined contribution plan\n* Tuition assistance program\n* Relocation assistance\n* Employee assistance and wellness programs\n* Use of university facilities\n* Zipcar and B-cycle memberships and bus pass\n* Convenient employer-paid parking\n\n---\n\n### Internships at WARF\n\nSuccessful WARF interns use their time in our offices gaining hands on experience and using it as a steppingstone to their future endeavors. Our past interns have gone on to serve in fields like licensing, marketing and event management. Our internship program includes:\n\n* Flexible work hours\n* Competitive pay\n* Professional skill development\n* Networking opportunities with WARF and its partners\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/contact-us\n\n## Connect with **WARF Employees**\n\nFilter By:\n\nBeth (Werner) Fischer\n\n### Beth (Werner) Fischer\n\nDirector of IP, Life Sciences", "char_len": 2281, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
