onic vision aid for profoundly blind individuals\n\n![WiscMed home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_WiscMed.png)\n\n### Wisc Med LLC\n\nWispr Digital Otoscope reliably provides a clear view of the eardrum\n\n![XCell Science home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_XCell.png)\n\n### XCell Science Inc.\n\nGeneration of high quality and quantity of neural cells from human stem cells", "char_len": 2248, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::82", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 82, "text": "Wisc Med LLC\n\nWispr Digital Otoscope reliably provides a clear view of the eardrum\n\n![XCell Science home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_XCell.png)\n\n### XCell Science Inc.\n\nGeneration of high quality and quantity of neural cells from human stem cells\n\n![Xylome home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_Xylome.jpg)\n\n### Xylome Corporation\n\nUnconventional yeasts for production of second generation biofuel precursors from existing feedstocks\n\n---\n\n## SUCCESSFUL EXITS\n\n![Alfa Light home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_AlfaLight.jpg)\n\n### AlfaLight\n\nReliable, rugged and efficient laser and electro-optical systems for defense and security applications\n\n![CDI home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_CDI.jpg)\n\n### Cellular Dynamics International\n\nFully functioning human cells in industrial quantities\n*IPO preceded acquisition*\n*Acquired by Fujifilm in 2015*\n\n![DateChat home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_DataChat.png)\n\n### DataChat Inc.\n\nConversational intelligence platform\n*Acquired by Mews in 2025*\n\n![Imago home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_imago.jpg)\n\n### Imago\n\nLEAP™ microscope for 3-D structure and composition analysis at the nanoscale\nAcquired by Ametek in 2010\n\n![Lactic Solutions home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_Lactic-Solutions.jpg)\n\n### Lactic Solutions LLC\n\nDeveloping genetically modified lactic acid bacteria products specifically for the biofuels industry.\nAcquired by Lallemand in 2017\n\n![LifeGen Technologies home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_lifegen.jpg)\n\n### LifeGen Technologies LLC\n\nGene expression profiling as it relates to the aging process\nAcquired by Nu Skin Enterprises Inc. in 2011\n\n![Mirus home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_Mirus.jpg)\n\n### Mirus Bio\n\nInnovative nucleic acid research reagents\nAcquired by Roche in 2008\n\n![NeuWave Medical home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_neuwave.jpg)\n\n### NeuWave Medical\n\nFast, minimally invasive and highly effective soft tissue ablation system\n*Acquired by Ethicon in 2016*", "char_len": 2216, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::83", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 83, "text": "Mirus Bio\n\nInnovative nucleic acid research reagents\nAcquired by Roche in 2008\n\n![NeuWave Medical home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_neuwave.jpg)\n\n### NeuWave Medical\n\nFast, minimally invasive and highly effective soft tissue ablation system\n*Acquired by Ethicon in 2016*\n\n![NimbleGen home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_NimbleGenInc.jpg)\n\n### NimbleGen Inc.\n\nDNA microarrays, consumables and instruments\nAcquired by Roche in 2007\n\n![Silatronix home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_Silatronix.jpg)\n\n### Silatronix Inc.\n\nOrganosilicon compounds for energy storage devices, especially electrolytes for lithium-ion batteries\n\n![SoftSwitching home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_SoftSwitching.jpg)\n\n### Soft Switching Technologies\n\nProtection against voltage sags and momentary outages\nAcquired by Rockwell Automation in 2012\n\n![Stratatech home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Startups_Stratatech.jpg)\n\n### Stratatech Corporation\n\nSkin regeneration and repair products for therapeutic use\nAcquired by Mallinckrodt Pharmaceuticals in 2016\n\n![Third Wave Technologies home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_thirdwave.jpg)\n\n### Third Wave Technologies\n\nMolecular diagnostics for DNA and RNA analysis applications\nAcquired by Hologic in 2008\n\n![Tissue Regeneration Systems home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_TissueRegenerationSystems.png)\n\n### Tissue Regeneration Systems\n\nSkeletal reconstruction and bone regeneration technology\n\n![TomoTherapy home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_TomoTherapy.jpg)\n\n### TomoTherapy\n\nPrecise cancer treatment system\n*IPO preceded acquisition*\n*Acquired by Accuray in 2011*\n\n![Virent home](https://www.warf.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/Startups_Virent.jpeg)\n\n### Virent Inc.\n\nPlatform that converts soluble biomass-derived sugars into gasoline, diesel and more\nAcquired by TESORO in 2016\n\n---\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/tang\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Weiping Tang**  Professor of Pharmacy  School of Pharmacy |  |", "char_len": 2234, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::84", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 84, "text": "biomass-derived sugars into gasoline, diesel and more\nAcquired by TESORO in 2016\n\n---\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/tang\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Weiping Tang**  Professor of Pharmacy  School of Pharmacy |  |\n\n**Research area**Drug discovery—developing new therapeutics for the treatment of human illnesses such as cancer, infectious diseases and neurodegenerative diseases.\n\n* Lab page\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“I am always excited to see how molecules designed by us modulate the function of proteins and other macromolecules in cells, especially those with potential applications for the development of therapeutics to treat human diseases.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“Some of our work will lead to new tools for other researchers to use, and some of our work may eventually lead to new therapeutics. As a researcher and innovator, I hope to contribute to the development of new drug discovery methods that can accelerate the drug development process and make it more efficient. This could include the development of new strategies, platforms and modalities.”\n\n> *Weiping has a great deal of expertise in protein-targeted degraders as well as lysosomal-targeted degraders. We expect these two modalities will be the future of new therapeutics to treat currently untreatable diseases.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/blackwell\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Helen Blackwell**  Professor of Chemistry  College of Letters & Science |  |\n\n**Research area**Devising novel chemical tools to decode and interfere with bacterial communication pathways.\n\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“The unknown! I became a professor to ask my own specific research questions and mentor students full-time–I love the unexpected result that takes us in new directions, and simply learning new things about our world.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**", "char_len": 2235, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::85", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 85, "text": "more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“The unknown! I became a professor to ask my own specific research questions and mentor students full-time–I love the unexpected result that takes us in new directions, and simply learning new things about our world.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“I would love our findings to contribute to the understanding of how bacteria interact in their myriad natural environments and how we can harness these interactions to treat infectious disease. I hope to continue to work with students here at UW to discover chemical approaches to decipher these bacterial interactions.”\n\n> *Helen has developed exciting technologies in the areas of biofilms and quorum sensing that could be transformative to control infection-causing agents in the near future.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/gong\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Shaoqin “Sarah” Gong**  Professor of Ophthalmology & Visual Sciences  School of Medicine & Public Health |  |\n\n**Research area**Design, synthesis/fabrication and characterization of novel biomaterials and nanomaterials. Ongoing multidisciplinary projects that bridge engineering with materials science, chemistry and the life sciences.\n\n* Lab Page\n* Patents, publications, and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“One aspect that I find particularly exciting is the development of novel biomaterials for targeted drug and gene therapy, immunotherapy and cell therapy. By designing and synthesizing innovative drug/gene delivery systems and tissue engineering scaffolds, our research has the potential to create new gene/genome editing therapies that can cure the root causes of genetic diseases or new cell therapies that can fight against blindness.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**", "char_len": 1957, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::86", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 86, "text": "innovative drug/gene delivery systems and tissue engineering scaffolds, our research has the potential to create new gene/genome editing therapies that can cure the root causes of genetic diseases or new cell therapies that can fight against blindness.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“As a researcher and innovator, I hope to continue making significant contributions in areas such as drug delivery systems, genome editing, cancer immunotherapy, cell therapy and antimicrobial materials. My goal is to advance our scientific understanding of these subjects and develop novel therapies that can revolutionize patient care and improve overall health outcomes.”\n\n> *Sarah has developed exciting delivery technologies for biologics, and we expect them to be transformative for the field.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/pijkeren\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Jan-Peter (JP) van Pijkeren**  Associate Professor of Food Science |  |\n\n**Research area**Working at the interface of industry and medicine, focusing on the gut symbiont species Limosilactobacillus reuteri, for which select strains have demonstrated health-promoting, i.e., probiotic, properties. The ultimate goal of our research program is to leverage knowledge on probiotic mechanisms toward the development of next-generation probiotics, i.e., microbial therapeutics.\n\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“What excites me is the melding of basic and translational sciences. I really love basic science–thinking about mechanisms that relate to probiosis and microbial ecology, while, at the same time, thinking of approaches to apply such mechanisms toward a next-gen therapeutic or probiotic. To test the next-gen probiotics, we are working with different partners in academia and industry to further enhance strain development.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**", "char_len": 2079, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::87", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 87, "text": "ecology, while, at the same time, thinking of approaches to apply such mechanisms toward a next-gen therapeutic or probiotic. To test the next-gen probiotics, we are working with different partners in academia and industry to further enhance strain development.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“Ultimately, I hope we will develop a probiotic strain that will be used in the clinic. Currently, we are optimizing recombinant protein production, stability and delivery using bioreactors, and assessing therapeutic efficacy in preclinical models. The idea that our efforts may lead to a therapeutic solution is equally motivational as exciting!”\n\n> *We are very excited about the potential applications of the technologies developed by JP. We believe that this platform can make a difference in several industries.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/dey\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Mahua Dey**  Associate Professor (Tenure) of Neurological Surgery |  |\n\n**Research area**Dey’s translational research laboratory studies the immune response to malignant brain cancers (both primary and metastatic). The lab’s mission is to develop successful immunotherapies for these devastating illnesses, while training the next generations of neurosurgeons, scientists and medical students.\n\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n* WARF Innovation Award Nomination\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“My lab is primarily focused on developing new immunotherapies for brain cancer, where we leverage a patient’s own immune system and use our genomic understanding of a specific patient’s cancer to develop a personalized therapeutic cancer vaccine. What’s currently most exciting is a personalized, gene-modified tumor vaccine we developed from patient tumor cells that can super charge an aging immune system to better attack cancer cells. It has shown great efficacy in multiple types of mouse brain tumor models, and we’re really excited about moving it into the clinical realm in an early phase clinical trial to offer hope to brain cancer patients.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**", "char_len": 2286, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::88", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 88, "text": "aging immune system to better attack cancer cells. It has shown great efficacy in multiple types of mouse brain tumor models, and we’re really excited about moving it into the clinical realm in an early phase clinical trial to offer hope to brain cancer patients.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“If I look at the really big picture, I will consider our mission successful if we can find an effective treatment for malignant brain cancer. That’s our overall goal. To get there, I think the smaller goals are to, on the one hand, develop these personalized vaccines as therapeutic modalities, and in parallel, to develop biomarkers and ways to track brain cancer that will tell us if our vaccines are working or not, in real time. It’s kind of a triple-pronged approach of attacking this disease by developing: effective therapeutics, better multi-modal monitoring and a biomarker-driven treatment strategy.”\n\n> *We are excited about the work Mahua’s lab is performing. I think everybody understands the importance to treat, and hopefully cure, cancer, particularly debilitating diseases such as malignant brain tumors.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/hernandez\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Reinier Hernandez**  Assistant Professor of Medical Physics |  |\n\n**Research area**The Advanced Radiotheranostics Laboratory aims to harness the power of radionuclides to tackle problems in diverse areas of biomedical research. The lab focuses on developing radiopharmaceutical (theranostics) agents for molecular imaging and radiotherapy of advanced cancers. The research group is also interested in understanding the radiobiology of radionuclides to design more effective theranostic agents and explore synergistic combinations with other systemic therapies, such as DNA repair inhibition and immunotherapy.\n\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**", "char_len": 2092, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::89", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 89, "text": "in understanding the radiobiology of radionuclides to design more effective theranostic agents and explore synergistic combinations with other systemic therapies, such as DNA repair inhibition and immunotherapy.\n\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“Over the last decade, radiopharmaceuticals have experienced a renaissance, with the FDA approval of two agents for treating advanced metastatic neuroendocrine and prostate cancer. This renewed interest has catalyzed innovations in isotope production, imaging technologies and drug development. We are proud to be at the forefront of radiopharmaceutical (theranostics) development in the U.S. and worldwide. Our lab has developed several novel radiopharmaceutical agents targeting PSMA, CAIX and cancer lipid metabolism. We are currently spearheading the clinical translational effort toward the first-in-human testing in patients with advanced prostate cancer, renal cell carcinomas or melanomas. Witnessing the progression of these agents from idea inception to first-in-human studies has been incredibly exciting and rewarding.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“Our primary goal is to reduce mortality and improve the quality of life in patients with advanced cancer. First, we hope our agents will make a meaningful difference in the lives of patients by either curing them of the disease or enhancing their quality of life. In addition, our vision is to expand the use of these potentially life-saving technologies by generating other agents targeting high unmet clinical needs, like lung, pancreatic or brain cancer. We firmly believe that radiopharmaceuticals will solidify as one of the main pillars of cancer treatment. Finally, because of their unique theranostic capacity, many of our agents will have diagnostic applications, helping physicians identify, assess and treat disease more effectively. In fact, theranostics is at the center of personalized medicine.”\n\n> *Reinier is at the forefront of the development of radiotherapeutics working in his lab and together with WARF Therapeutics.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847", "char_len": 2223, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::90", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 90, "text": "is at the center of personalized medicine.”\n\n> *Reinier is at the forefront of the development of radiotherapeutics working in his lab and together with WARF Therapeutics.*\n>\n> *– Rafael Diaz, WARF, Licensing Manager*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nRafael Diaz, [email protected], 608.960.9847\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/forest\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Cary Forest**  Professor of Physics and Director of the Plasma Physics Laboratory |  |\n\n**Research area** The Wisconsin Plasma Physics Laboratory (WiPPL) operates several multi-investigator, intermediate-scale plasma physics devices, and represents the plasma physics efforts within the physics department. WiPPL serves both UW and external users and supports the core of a broad research program to understand the flow of energy between fields and particles in plasmas.\n\n* Faculty page\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“I work at the boundary between plasma physics and nuclear fusion. As the director of the Plasma Physics Lab, I study astrophysical questions in lab and am involved in the WHAM experiment, which is a prototype for next-generation fusion power plants. I’m proud of being an experimental plasma physics researcher, and I can go in many directions in the field. The science is what drives me—I’m very loyal to my field.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“I of course would love to provide mankind with a limitless clean source of energy that movies humans forward, and I started working in the field because fusion was an interesting, challenging problem, and I hoped to have an impact. One way to have an impact is to train really good students, and I’m very proud of my students’ achievements.”", "char_len": 1811, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::91", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 91, "text": "with a limitless clean source of energy that movies humans forward, and I started working in the field because fusion was an interesting, challenging problem, and I hoped to have an impact. One way to have an impact is to train really good students, and I’m very proud of my students’ achievements.”\n\n> *Professor Cary Forest is exploring some of the most exciting frontiers in physics—where the science of stars meets the future of energy. His work connects two powerful ideas: how the sun creates energy (fusion) and how magnetic fields shape the universe (plasma astrophysics). By building and testing new kinds of fusion systems, he’s helping pave the way toward energy sources that could one day power our world.*\n>\n> *– Jeanine Burmania, WARF, Senior Director, IP and Licensing*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nJeanine Burmania, [email protected], 608.960.9846\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/raval\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Amish Raval**  Professor of Medicine |  |\n\n**Research area**Evaluating novel cardiovascular regenerative medicine therapies. The research group uses stem cells, gene transfer agents and extracellular matrices to develop improved biologic delivery methods and durable treatments for patients with advanced heart disease. The team is currently developing innovative treatments that utilize stem cells and unique biomaterials that can be delivered minimally invasively using catheters to patients with advanced ischemic and structural heart disease. The laboratory has expertise in therapeutic cell characterization, transcatheter delivery and interventional imaging, cardiac biomaterials, small/large animal cardiovascular disease models, federal regulatory requirements for biologics therapies and the design and execution of Phase I, II and III clinical trials.\n\n* Faculty page\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**", "char_len": 1976, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::92", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 92, "text": "cardiac biomaterials, small/large animal cardiovascular disease models, federal regulatory requirements for biologics therapies and the design and execution of Phase I, II and III clinical trials.\n\n* Faculty page\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“I’ve been a cardiologist for 24 years and done clinical trials and research for over 20 years. In that time, areas of technology have emerged—medication, pharmaceuticals, biologics, devices and novel therapies, but nothing has yet been invented, created or approved to repair the failing heart. My real interest is finding therapies that will fundamentally alter injury in a favorable way at the tissue level and restore lost heart function, to reverse or prevent damage to the heart. What excites me is being able to interact with interesting people, innovate and speak to others, while I work on projects that are directed toward rescuing and remuscularizing and revascularizing the heart, without having to do a full-blown heart transplant.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“I hope to further the field of cardiovascular regenerative medicine, using my expertise to deliver cells, in a seamless way that patients can tolerate, is cost effective and is easy to perform, to improve outcomes for heart patients. Even if it doesn’t happen in my lifetime, I want to contribute to the field and move the needle forward. It’s like a big puzzle, and everyone has their areas of expertise. Mine is, we have the cells, now how do we integrate them into the heart minimally or non-invasively, without interrupting a patient’s life too much?”\n\n> *Dr. Raval is an innovative and important researcher in his field. His contributions have already advanced the state of cardiovascular repair and treatment and his inventions are nearing first-in-human clinical trials.*\n>\n> *– Andy DeTienne, WARF, Director of Licensing*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nAndy DeTienne, [email protected], 608.960.9857\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/capitini\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Christian Capitini**  Professor and Chief of Pediatric Hematology, Oncology, Transplant and Cellular Therapy |  |", "char_len": 2253, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::93", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 93, "text": "608.960.9857\n\n## [page] https://www.warf.org/commercialize/uw-madison-inventor-profiles/capitini\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| Meet the University of Wisconsin-Madison’s  **Christian Capitini**  Professor and Chief of Pediatric Hematology, Oncology, Transplant and Cellular Therapy |  |\n\n**Research area**Development of cell-based immunotherapies, including natural killer (NK) cells and CAR T cells, for the treatment of pediatric solid tumors like neuroblastoma, osteosarcoma and rhabdomyosarcoma. The lab also develops alternatively activated macrophages for complications of bone marrow transplant, including graft-versus-host-disease (GVHD) and acute radiation syndrome.\n\n* Faculty page\n* Lab website\n* Patents, publications and more\n\n**What excites you about your work?**\n\n“One of our areas of focus for IP has been in cell and gene therapy related to CAR T cells, and we’re in the process now of translating one of these assets for a first-in-human clinical trial. The School of Medicine and Public Health just announced a strategic collaboration with Cellares, a research contract and development manufacturing organization (CDMO), to automate the manufacturing of a CRISPR-edited GD2 CAR-T investigational therapy, using a device that can make these cells in multiplex fashion for the first time. I’m really excited about it. Now, we control the drug development process from beginning to end.”\n\n**What do you hope to achieve?**\n\n“The excitement of this kind of technology—for the first time, a university can be in the drug making business—is the fact that cells from our body are being synthetically engineered and designated as drugs by the FDA, and now, it’s not about pills or infusions; it’s about personalized medicine—weaponizing a patient’s immune system against cancer or other diseases. There’s an opportunity for commercialization, innovation and to offer unique therapies that make us a destination medical center. You only can get it here. When CAR T first came out, it came out of universities and got licensed by companies, and we got exposed to it through multicenter studies, but it will be transformative if something gets made here.”", "char_len": 2157, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "warf-starting-a-company::94", "doc_slug": "warf-starting-a-company", "chunk_index": 94, "text": "and to offer unique therapies that make us a destination medical center. You only can get it here. When CAR T first came out, it came out of universities and got licensed by companies, and we got exposed to it through multicenter studies, but it will be transformative if something gets made here.”\n\n> *WARF is tremendously excited for the progress Dr. Capitini and his collaborators have made. In the very near future we should see his work in the clinic, treating patients in a first-in-human trial.*\n>\n> *– Andy DeTienne, WARF, Director of Licensing*\n\n**Want to learn more?**\n\nAndy DeTienne, [email protected], 608.960.9857", "char_len": 626, "id": 5, "source": "WARF - Starting a Company", "type": "static_html", "category": "legal", "url": "https://www.warf.org/commercialize/starting-a-company/"}
{"chunk_id": "weinert-center::0", "doc_slug": "weinert-center", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://business.wisc.edu/centers/weinert/\n\n![Students working on a group building project.](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Weinert_MEB2018-_PlanningToPivot_Olszewski_0618_PN23437-1.avif)\n\n# Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship\n\n---\n\n## The Entrepreneurial Mindset: Imagine, Create, and Lead\n\nThe Weinert Center fosters entrepreneurial thinking for students at all levels across campus, whether undergraduate or graduate, business majors, or students in a nonbusiness program.\n\nCutting-edge technologies, innovative business models, and ever-changing market landscapes determine which firms thrive and which do not. The Weinert Center equips you with entrepreneurial skills to thrive in any business environment.\n\nWe support teaching, research, and service to bring entrepreneurial thinking to startups and established organizations. Individuals bring a unique outlook and fresh problem-solving perspectives to the marketplace and help make companies agile.\n\nNamed a top entrepreneurship program by the Princeton Review, Financial Times, and the United States Association for Small Business and Entrepreneurship (USASBE).\n\n6\n\nundergraduate alumni startup founders among public U.S. schools\n\n—Pitchbook, 2025\n\n8\n\ngraduate alumni startup founders among public U.S. schools\n\n—Pitchbook, 2025\n\n## Learning In and Out of the Classroom\n\nClasses give you lifelong success skills. We have provided nearly 1,000 hands-on student projects outside the classroom with local firms. Prepare for roles such as business founder, product manager, engineer/scientist, new product designer, marketing or finance professional, nonprofit administrator, or consultant.\n\n![Four men sitting around a table with the man on the left talking and making gestures with his hands](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BE_Clinic_Photo_2400x1600v2-1024x683.jpg)\n\n### Business and Entrepreneurship Clinic", "char_len": 1918, "id": 6, "source": "Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://business.wisc.edu/centers/weinert/"}
{"chunk_id": "weinert-center::1", "doc_slug": "weinert-center", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "professional, nonprofit administrator, or consultant.\n\n![Four men sitting around a table with the man on the left talking and making gestures with his hands](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/BE_Clinic_Photo_2400x1600v2-1024x683.jpg)\n\n### Business and Entrepreneurship Clinic\n\nIn collaboration with the Law and Entrepreneurship Clinic, the Wisconsin Institute of Discovery, and the Wisconsin Alumni Research Foundation (WARF), the Business and Entrepreneurship Clinic provides free business advice and services for Wisconsin-based entrepreneurs.\n\nLearn more about the clinic\n\n![A man giving a speech at Morgridge Entrepreneurial Bootcamp dinner](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Weinert_MEB_Dinner_0619_PN22707-1-1024x719.jpg)\n\n### Discovery to Product\n\nDiscovery to Product (D2P) provides resources that can help transform innovations originating at UW–Madison into products and services that change the world.\n\nLearn more about D2P\n\n![Students looking at objects at the 100 Hour Challenge](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/11_14_13-100-Hour-Challenge-023-2400x1600-1-1024x683.jpg)\n\n### Initiative for Studies in Transformational Entrepreneurship (INSITE)\n\nINSITE supports and fosters entrepreneurial research, curriculum development, and programming. As a primary resource for entrepreneurs, INSITE maintains a comprehensive directory of resources on campus and in the community.\n\nExplore resources and opportunities\n\n## Events\n\n![Two women giving a presentation](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/Weinert_WisconsinEntrepreneurshipShowcase_1018_PLN0025-1-1024x750.jpg)\n\n### Entrepreneurship workshops\n\nA wide range of workshops is held on the UW–Madison campus for anyone interested in entrepreneurial topics.\n\nExplore workshop offerings\n\n![Amy Jo Pedone holding cupcakes](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/weinert-dist-entrep-lunch-amy-jo-pedone-2400x1600-1-1024x683.jpg)\n\n### Distinguished Entrepreneurs Lunch\n\nLearn about the experiences of entrepreneurs from a broad range of endeavors.\n\nView upcoming lunches\n\nView our photo gallery\n\n## Programs We Support\n\n### Undergraduate\n\n#### Major in entrepreneurship", "char_len": 2211, "id": 6, "source": "Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://business.wisc.edu/centers/weinert/"}
{"chunk_id": "weinert-center::2", "doc_slug": "weinert-center", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "Distinguished Entrepreneurs Lunch\n\nLearn about the experiences of entrepreneurs from a broad range of endeavors.\n\nView upcoming lunches\n\nView our photo gallery\n\n## Programs We Support\n\n### Undergraduate\n\n#### Major in entrepreneurship\n\nEarn a Bachelor of Business Administration degree with a major in entrepreneurship through the Department of Management and Human Resources.\n\nLearn about the major\n\n#### Courses for UW–Madison undergraduates\n\nBusiness and nonbusiness majors can explore entrepreneurship to complement their field of study.\n\nRead about course offerings\n\n#### Certificate in Entrepreneurship for Nonbusiness Majors\n\nThe Certificate in Entrepreneurship is open to undergraduate students earning any nonbusiness degree at UW–Madison.\n\nLearn more about the certificate\n\n#### New Venture Creation Badge\n\nThe New Venture Creation Badge is open to undergraduate students earning any degree at UW–Madison.\n\nLearn more about the badge\n\n### Graduate\n\n#### Certificates for MBA and other graduate students\n\nEarn a certificate in entrepreneurship or strategic innovation while enrolled in any degree-granting graduate program at UW–Madison.\n\nEntrepreneurship\nStrategic Innovation\n\n#### MBA Fellowship in Enterprise Development\n\nWisconsin Full-time MBA students interested in starting a new business or taking an existing business to a new level can apply for this focused one-year program.\n\nLearn about the fellowship\n\n#### Wisconsin Applied Ventures in Entrepreneurship (WAVE)\n\nUW–Madison graduate students from any discipline may apply for this applied practicum in starting and growing entrepreneurial businesses.\n\nLearn about WAVE\n\n#### Morgridge Entrepreneurial Bootcamp (MEB)\n\nThis one-week intensive training is open to graduate students in the sciences, engineering, and math.\n\nLearn about MEB\n\n### Doctoral Programs\n\n#### PhD\n\nEarn a doctorate in management and human resources with a focus on entrepreneurship.\n\nLearn more about a Wisconsin PhD\n\n#### Doctoral minor\n\nNonbusiness doctoral students can earn a minor in entrepreneurship.\n\nLearn more about PhD Minor\n\n## Weinert Center News\n\nRead the latest updates, alumni news, and more.\n\n### EntrepreNews Spring 2026\n\nJune 2, 2026", "char_len": 2195, "id": 6, "source": "Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://business.wisc.edu/centers/weinert/"}
{"chunk_id": "weinert-center::3", "doc_slug": "weinert-center", "chunk_index": 3, "text": "a focus on entrepreneurship.\n\nLearn more about a Wisconsin PhD\n\n#### Doctoral minor\n\nNonbusiness doctoral students can earn a minor in entrepreneurship.\n\nLearn more about PhD Minor\n\n## Weinert Center News\n\nRead the latest updates, alumni news, and more.\n\n### EntrepreNews Spring 2026\n\nJune 2, 2026\n\n![John Surdyk](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Surdyk-John-368x512.jpg)\n\n### A Fond Farewell to a Colleague: John Surdyk\n\nMay 29, 2026\n\n### The Launchpad Moment: From Classroom to What’s Next\n\nMay 22, 2026\n\n## Explore the Weinert Center\n\n![Grainger Hall icon.](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/grainger.avif)\n\n### History and mission\n\nThe Weinert Center has been a leader in entrepreneurship education, outreach, and research since 1986.\n\n![People speaking icon.](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/tutoring.avif)\n\n### Advisory boards\n\nThe Weinert and WAVE board members provide guidance, advice, and support for our programs.\n\n![lightbulb icon.](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/entrepreneurship.png)\n\n### Hall of Fame\n\nGet inspired by our entrepreneurial leaders.\n\n![handshake with dollar sign icon.](https://business.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/finance-invest-bank.png)\n\n### Invest\n\nGifts to the Weinert Center are welcome year-round and make a lasting impact on the opportunities and resources we provide.\n\n## Connect With Us\n\n### Contact us\n\nContact us to learn more about the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship.\n\nContact us\n\n### Find us!\n\nFacebook\n\nInstagram\n\nLinkedIn\n\n### Join our mailing list\n\nReceive highlights in our quarterly newsletter and receive information on special events and important announcements.", "char_len": 1707, "id": 6, "source": "Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://business.wisc.edu/centers/weinert/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::0", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu\n\n![Aerial view of downtown Madison and the isthmus with the Wisconsin State Capitol Building in the center.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2024/11/aerial-madison-2.jpg)\n\nEvery day at our university, we acquire and impart knowledge, gain inspiration, and form ideas—ideas that could change lives. What if we could do more to foster the pursuit of these ideas?\n\n## Nurturing ideas across our campus and bringing them to life is at the heart of the Wisconsin Idea\n\nEntrepreneurship involves improving our world outside the boundaries of the classroom. It goes beyond discovery, beyond publication, beyond a patent, and transforms ideas into action.\n\nOur 21st century economy is fast-moving, fueled by innovation and investment. Our vision is to be the premier university for students, staff, faculty, and alumni to pursue entrepreneurial endeavors and creatively solve problems to create a better world.\n\n## Tap into the potential. Strengthen the infrastructure. Chart a map. Empower the changemakers.\n\nEntrepreneurship is a key priority for UW–Madison. In 2024, an ad hoc working group comprised of entrepreneurial and innovation leaders from campus and industry came together to determine how the university can better support entrepreneurs and improve entrepreneurial outcomes.\n\nThe findings and recommendations outlined in this report, released in October of 2024, aim to transform UW–Madison into a premier university in which to pursue entrepreneurial endeavors and creatively solve problems to create a better world.\n\nRead the executive summary\n\nRead the full report\n\n![Cover of executive summary booklet titled, 'Empowering the Wisconsin Idea: The Future of Entrepreneurship at the University of Wisconsin–Madison.'](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/02/UWE-booklet-788x1024.png)", "char_len": 1895, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::1", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "the executive summary\n\nRead the full report\n\n![Cover of executive summary booklet titled, 'Empowering the Wisconsin Idea: The Future of Entrepreneurship at the University of Wisconsin–Madison.'](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/02/UWE-booklet-788x1024.png)\n\n![Portrait of Lewis Sheats](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/02/Lewis-Sheats-400x400-1.jpg)\n\nquotation mark\n> Universities are powerful places for ideas to grow, and UW–Madison has a remarkable history of bringing big ideas to life. I’m looking forward to building partnerships on campus and across the state to help foster an environment where more people can confidently pursue entrepreneurial paths.\n\n**Lewis Sheats**, associate vice chancellor and executive director, Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub\n\n## Harnessing the power of Wisconsin innovation\n\nEntrepreneurs revolutionize, solve problems, and serve needs across all aspects of society. Supporting and enabling all campus entrepreneurs—faculty, staff, and students—fosters a culture of innovation and facilitates services that empower individuals to transform ideas into impactful ventures, thereby driving economic growth and social change. The potential for growth is enormous.\n\nThe entrepreneurship hub intends to serve the entire campus by fulfilling the recommendations laid out in the report:\n\n* Commit to excellence in entrepreneurship with a focus on founders\n* Establish campus leadership and structure to bolster entrepreneurship\n* Create a culture to promote and celebrate entrepreneurship\n* Expand access to capital\n\n## Impacts that affect everyone\n\nSince 1990, more than 400 companies across Wisconsin started at UW–Madison.\n\nBetween 1997 and 2021, 33 UW–Madison alumni founded 28 companies that each individually achieved a valuation of over $1 billion.\n\nThese companies have generated an annual economic impact of $10 billion, 42,855 jobs, and $320,224,874 in state and local tax revenue.\n\nThe potential for growth is enormous once future entrepreneurs are given a clear path forward.\n\n## The Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub in the News\n\n![Portrait of Lewis Sheats.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/01/Lewis_Sheats_1200x800.jpg)", "char_len": 2264, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::2", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 2, "text": "and local tax revenue.\n\nThe potential for growth is enormous once future entrepreneurs are given a clear path forward.\n\n## The Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub in the News\n\n![Portrait of Lewis Sheats.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/01/Lewis_Sheats_1200x800.jpg)\n\n### Lewis Sheats named inaugural leader of UW’s Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub\n\n![A person sits at a table in a lab working on a small electrical motor.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/11/WEMPEC-Ludois-lab-scaled.jpg)\n\n### Badger Tech Foundry, first “spoke” in the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub, focused on helping early-career researchers become serial entrepreneurs\n\n![Aerial view of campus buildings and downtown Madison set between the isthmus.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/08/Drone-Lakeshore-2025-07-02TW-11-1600x1065-1.jpg)\n\n### UW–Madison launching new hub to accelerate entrepreneurship\n\nRead more news\n\n## This initiative is more successful with you\n\nGet involved\n\nAsk a question\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/news\n\n# News\n\n![Portrait of Lewis Sheats.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/01/Lewis_Sheats_1200x800.jpg)\n\n## Lewis Sheats named inaugural leader of UW’s Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub\n\n![A person sits at a table in a lab working on a small electrical motor.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/11/WEMPEC-Ludois-lab-scaled.jpg)\n\n## Badger Tech Foundry, first “spoke” in the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub, focused on helping early-career researchers become serial entrepreneurs\n\n![Aerial view of campus buildings and downtown Madison set between the isthmus.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/08/Drone-Lakeshore-2025-07-02TW-11-1600x1065-1.jpg)\n\n## UW–Madison launching new hub to accelerate entrepreneurship\n\n![Aerial view of downtown Madison set between the isthmus on a clear day with blue skies.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/02/UWE-news-itemArtboard-1.jpg)\n\n## UW–Madison unveils strategic vision to boost entrepreneurship", "char_len": 2180, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::3", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 3, "text": "new hub to accelerate entrepreneurship\n\n![Aerial view of downtown Madison set between the isthmus on a clear day with blue skies.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/02/UWE-news-itemArtboard-1.jpg)\n\n## UW–Madison unveils strategic vision to boost entrepreneurship\n\n![Group of people seated at a long table having a discussion.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/02/UWE-news-itemArtboard-2.jpg)\n\n## Panel: UW to focus on founders in entrepreneurship push\n\n![Jon Eckhardt looking off camera with arms crossed in front of a glass window.](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/04/badger-talks-1.jpg)\n\n## Badger Talks: Jon Eckhardt discusses opportunities for entrepreneurship\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/awards\n\n# Chancellor’s Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards\n\nThe University of Wisconsin–Madison’s vibrant culture encourages innovation among faculty, staff, students and alumni. Established in 2011, the Chancellor’s Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards recognize innovators and UW alumni who further the Wisconsin Idea through outstanding accomplishments in entrepreneurship. Honorees have achieved great entrepreneurial success that contributes to economic growth and welfare, serve as models for the UW entrepreneurial community, or inspire a campus culture of entrepreneurship. The annual awards event is presented by the Office of the Chancellor in partnership with the Wisconsin Foundation and Alumni Association and produced by the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub.\n\nFor information on how to nominate individuals for this award, please see our Nominations page.\n\n**Nominations for the 2026 awards have now closed.**\n\n## Past Award Recipients", "char_len": 1759, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::4", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 4, "text": "in partnership with the Wisconsin Foundation and Alumni Association and produced by the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub.\n\nFor information on how to nominate individuals for this award, please see our Nominations page.\n\n**Nominations for the 2026 awards have now closed.**\n\n## Past Award Recipients\n\n| **Date** | **Honorees** | **Stories and Videos** |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **April 2025** | Marcus Carpenter ’00, Founder, Route 1 Heather Hasson ’04, CEO & Co-Founder, OOG.Health, Co-Founder & Executive Chairman, FIGS  Greg Piefer ’99, MS’04, PhD’06, Founder & CEO, SHINE Technologies  View Photo Gallery | Entrepreneur award winners turn ideas into impact — from farming to fashion to fusion |\n| **April 2024** | Mark Bakken ’89, Founder and Managing Partner HealthX Ventures James Dahlberg, Professor Emeritus of Biomolecular Chemistry, University of Wisconsin–Madison; Co-Founder, Third Wave Technologies and Cambridge BioTech Corp.\n\nDorri McWhorter ’95, President and CEO, YMCA of Metropolitan Chicago  View Photo Gallery | Three honored for innovation, entrepreneurial excellence |\n| **April 2023** | Tyler Kennedy ’13, Senior Vice President-Operations and Co-Founder, Fetch Winslow L.\n\nSargeant PhD’95, Chair, International Council for Small Business  Wesley Schroll, CEO and Founder, Fetch  Anne Smith JD’83, Co-Founder, Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic, University of Wisconsin Law School | UW entrepreneurial awardees model innovation, shape Wisconsin’s entrepreneurial ecosystem |\n| **March 2022** | Lynn Allen-Hoffmann, Stratatech Corporation Jim Bakke ’77, Sub-Zero Group, Inc.", "char_len": 1585, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::5", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 5, "text": "Fetch  Anne Smith JD’83, Co-Founder, Law & Entrepreneurship Clinic, University of Wisconsin Law School | UW entrepreneurial awardees model innovation, shape Wisconsin’s entrepreneurial ecosystem |\n| **March 2022** | Lynn Allen-Hoffmann, Stratatech Corporation Jim Bakke ’77, Sub-Zero Group, Inc.\n\nValarie King-Bailey ’82, OnShore Technology Group  Scott Resnick ’09, Hardin Design & Development, StartingBlock Madison | Four honored with UW Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards |\n| **November 2018** | Matt Howard ’11, Eric Martell ’12 and Alex Wyler, EatStreet | EatStreet snaps up campus award for entrepreneurship |\n| **May 2017** | Michele Boal ’91, Quotient Technology (formerly Coupons.com) Troy Vosseller ’06, MBA’09, JD’10, gener8tor and Sconnie | Alumni honored with Entrepreneurial Achievement Award |\n| **April 2016** | Christopher Salm ’75, Salm Partners LLC Andrew Ziegler ’83, JD’86, Artisan Partners LLC | UW honors noted entrepreneurs with achievement awards |\n| **May 2015** | Mark Cook, Aova Technologies and Isomark LLC Pavan Nigam MS’82, Cendura Corp and WebMD (formerly Healtheon) | UW honors noted entrepreneurs with achievement awards |\n| **May 2014** | Elisa All ’90, 30Second Mobile and iParenting Media Mike Shannon ’80, KSL Capital Partners | UW–Madison honors leading entrepreneurs with achievement awards |\n| **April 2013** | Laurie Benson ’75, LSB Unlimited and CORE BTS (formerly Inacom Information Services) Richard Burgess, ConjuGon  Brian Raffel ’86, Raven Software  Eric Sheinkop ’04, Music Dealers | UW honors four with Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards |\n| **April 2012** | Rajiv Batra MS’83, Palo Alto Networks Jon Hammes MS’74, Hammes Company  Sheldon B.\n\nLubar ’51, LLB ’53, Lubar & Co  Thomas Rockwell “Rock” Mackie, TomoTherapy Inc.\n\nStephen Siegele ’84, Advanced Delivery & Chemical Systems  Toni Sikes MS ’83, The Guild, Inc.\n\nMatthew Younkle ’97, Y Innovation LLC and Laminar Technologies | Seven receive entrepreneurial achievement awards |\n| **April 2011** | Jim Berbee ’85, MS’87, MBA’89, Berbee Information Networks Judy Faulkner MS’67, Epic Systems  Hector DeLuca MS’53, PhD’55, Deltanoid Pharmaceuticals Inc.", "char_len": 2158, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::6", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 6, "text": "Inc.\n\nMatthew Younkle ’97, Y Innovation LLC and Laminar Technologies | Seven receive entrepreneurial achievement awards |\n| **April 2011** | Jim Berbee ’85, MS’87, MBA’89, Berbee Information Networks Judy Faulkner MS’67, Epic Systems  Hector DeLuca MS’53, PhD’55, Deltanoid Pharmaceuticals Inc.\n\nChad Sorenson ’99, MS’01, MBA’02, Sologear LLC  James Weinert ’67, MBA’69 Weinert Applied Ventures in Entrepreneurship and the Weinert Center for Entrepreneurship | Five receive Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards |\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/funding\n\n# Funding\n\nThe Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub administers two funding opportunities that support entrepreneurs and innovators: Draper TIF and SEED. We also have relationships and connections to help projects access other sources of funding in the region and beyond. Need help deciding which grant is right for you? Scroll down for more information.\n\n## The Draper Technology Innovation Fund (TIF)\n\nThis fund supports the additional research necessary to bring new concepts and inventions to the patent and licensing stage. The program goal is to help get new products and processes out of the lab and into people’s hands where they can impact change. Funds can be used to support efforts to enhance the scope or patentability of inventions and assist with their potential licensing to the commercial sector. Examples of research activities include prototype development, preparation of samples for evaluation, and application testing. The Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub administers this program in partnership with the Wisconsin Alumni Research Foundation. TIF funding is made available on a quarterly basis throughout the calendar year. **The next deadline is Friday, August 14, 2026.**\n\nLearn more and apply\n\n## The State Economic Engagement & Development Research (SEED) Grant", "char_len": 1844, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::7", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 7, "text": "this program in partnership with the Wisconsin Alumni Research Foundation. TIF funding is made available on a quarterly basis throughout the calendar year. **The next deadline is Friday, August 14, 2026.**\n\nLearn more and apply\n\n## The State Economic Engagement & Development Research (SEED) Grant\n\nThis grant allows UW–Madison faculty and academic staff with ownership in a Wisconsin company to engage in innovative research designed to facilitate commercialization of their company’s technology. The State Economic Engagement & Development (SEED) research funding is designed to generate additional private and public sector support for innovator research programs that take place on the UW–Madison campus and promote technology transfer between the University and industry.\n\nLearn more about SEED funding\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/contact-us\n\n# Contact Us\n\n## The Hub Team\n\n![Abram Becker](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/01/Abram400x400.jpg)\n\n### Abram Becker\n\nInnovation and Commercialization Specialist\n\nabram.becker@wisc.edu\n\n![Cecily Brose](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/01/CecilyBrose400x400.jpeg)\n\n### Cecily Brose\n\nInnovation and Commercialization Specialist\n\ncecily.brose@wisc.edu\n\n![Tim Dalby](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/Dalby_Tim_434.jpg)\n\n### Tim Dalby\n\nChief of Staff\n\ntim.dalby@wisc.edu\n\n![Jon Eckhardt](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/02/Jon-eckhardt.jpg)\n\n### Jon Eckhardt\n\nSpecial Advisor to the Chancellor for Entrepreneurship | Pyle Bascom Professor in Business Leadership Discovery Fellow, Wisconsin Institute for Discovery\n\njon.eckhardt@wisc.edu\n\n![Samantha Nash](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/04/Sam-Nash-Headshot-670x800.jpg)\n\n### Samantha Nash\n\nAdministrative Manager\n\nsmnash@wisc.edu\n\n![Sarah Perdue](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/05/sarah-perdue-profile-picture.jpg)\n\n### Sarah Perdue\n\nCommunications Manager\n\nsaperdue@wisc.edu\n\n![Lewis Sheats](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/02/Lewis-Sheats-400x400-1.jpg)\n\n### Lewis Sheats", "char_len": 2239, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::8", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 8, "text": "Sarah Perdue\n\nCommunications Manager\n\nsaperdue@wisc.edu\n\n![Lewis Sheats](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2026/02/Lewis-Sheats-400x400-1.jpg)\n\n### Lewis Sheats\n\nAssociate Vice Chancellor for Entrepreneurship and Executive Director, Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub\n\nlsheats@wisc.edu\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/awards/nominations\n\n# Nominations for the Chancellor’s Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards\n\nThe University of Wisconsin–Madison’s vibrant culture encourages innovation among faculty, staff, students and alumni.\n\nEstablished in 2011, the Chancellor’s Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards recognize innovators and UW alumni who further the Wisconsin Idea through outstanding accomplishments in entrepreneurship. Held each spring, the awards event is presented by the Office of the Chancellor in partnership with the Wisconsin Foundation and Alumni Association and produced by the Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub.\n\nHonorees have achieved great entrepreneurial success that contributes to economic growth and welfare, serve as models for the UW entrepreneurial community, or inspires a campus culture of entrepreneurship. Honorees can come from a variety of backgrounds. Examples include (but are not limited to) startup founders, serial entrepreneurs, intrapreneurs, educators, leaders of entrepreneurial support organizations, venture investors, and social entrepreneurs. The honorees have changed lives through their entrepreneurial activities, furthering the Wisconsin Idea, our university’s pledge to benefit citizens beyond the boundaries of the campus. Honorees have also demonstrated leadership by giving back to the university and community, helping others to learn, grow and achieve.\n\nSee past nominees\n​\n\n​\n\nNominations of innovators and entrepreneurs are considered in two broad categories:\n\n* Leadership/career achievement\n* Early/mid-career achievement\n\nDiversity is a source of strength, creativity, and innovation for UW–Madison. Nominations of innovators and entrepreneurs from every background are encouraged.\n\n**Nominations for the 2026 awards have now closed.**", "char_len": 2129, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::9", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 9, "text": "broad categories:\n\n* Leadership/career achievement\n* Early/mid-career achievement\n\nDiversity is a source of strength, creativity, and innovation for UW–Madison. Nominations of innovators and entrepreneurs from every background are encouraged.\n\n**Nominations for the 2026 awards have now closed.**\n\n**Nominations must be received by October 1st, 2026 for consideration for the annual awards event held in spring 2027.** Nominations may be considered for the upcoming or future awards events. Self-nominations are accepted. Past award recipients may not be nominated again.\n\nFor questions, please email entrepreneurship.hub@wisc.edu.\n\n## Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards Nomination Form\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/awards/2025-award-recipients\n\n# 2025 Award Recipients", "char_len": 785, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
{"chunk_id": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub::10", "doc_slug": "wisconsin-entrepreneurship-hub", "chunk_index": 10, "text": "Self-nominations are accepted. Past award recipients may not be nominated again.\n\nFor questions, please email entrepreneurship.hub@wisc.edu.\n\n## Entrepreneurial Achievement Awards Nomination Form\n\n## [page] https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/awards/2025-award-recipients\n\n# 2025 Award Recipients\n\n![Greg Piefer with his award and three other guests at the Chancellor's awards](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/RCT09243-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x683.jpg)![Jennifer Mnookin with Marcus Carpenter and his family](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/RCT09233-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x683.jpg)![Greg Piefer speaks at podium at the Chancellor's Awards](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/RCT09188-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x683.jpg)![Abram Becker, Interim Director at Discovery to Product](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/RCT09031-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x683.jpg)![Chancellor Jennifer Mnookin shakes hands with Heather Hasson](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/DSC09744-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x683.jpg)![Chancellor Jennifer Mnookin presents Marcus Carpenter with an award](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/DSC09739-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x657.jpg)![Auditorium filled with people at the Entrepreneurial Awards](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/DSC09711-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x586.jpg)![Michael Falk and two other guests at the Chancellor's Awards](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/DSC09673-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x641.jpg)![Cynthia Czajkowski and Jeanine Burmania](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/DSC09666-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1024x715.jpg)![Three guests at the 2025 Chancellor's Awards](https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/214/2025/10/DSC09664-Enhanced-NR-20250423-Med-1536x1001-1-1024x667.jpg)![Jennifer Mnookin with Vice Chancellor of University Relations, Craig Thompson, Madison mayor, Satya", "char_len": 2196, "id": 1, "source": "Wisconsin Entrepreneurship Hub", "type": "static_html", "category": "campus-portal", "url": "https://entrepreneurship.wisc.edu/"}
